{[%evp 0,143,19,31,19,-16,-9,-9,0,-40,-5,20,17,3,13,22,48,47,41,33,54,40,61,34,
28,39,33,21,20,24,25,24,37,39,15,15,68,71,91,73,87,67,111,109,117,103,101,93,
98,95,88,79,83,78,88,86,81,84,83,55,69,83,83,75,90,75,90,82,76,89,117,113,125,
116,121,118,115,117,119,119,119,108,110,90,121,81,93,99,98,109,108,109,131,120,
117,119,129,115,107,78,79,87,95,84,65,62,58,85,56,56,56,48,57,40,41,20,76,40,
75,73,98,30,152,92,9,0,0,0,42,207,217,221,219,219,234,234,256,315,388,497,497,
507,507,507,507,527] The minority's attack has been known for more than a
century already. Here is a very old example, featuring quite modern play on
White's side. Napier's name may be completely unknown to modern readers. He
was actually a very strong master and Lasker played one of his most famous
games against him, in Cambridge Springs 1904. That game was a fascinating
tactical struggle and Napier was the last to go wrong. Lasker said afterwards
to his young opponent: "It is your brilliancy, even though I won it." Mainly a
tactical and attacking player, he will display refined positional
understanding in our minority's attack game.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4.
Bg5 Nbd7 5. Nf3 c6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 Be7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 {
We can notice that this tabiya, one of the most important in the Queen's
Gambit Exchange variation modern theory, has quite a long history. In fact,
this is just the second game where this position occurred. After a few mutual
hesitations in the range of the 14th and 15th moves, White will carry out his
queenside attack very consequently, making the game relevant for the typical
plans with this structure.} 11. Ne5 {A straightforward continuation, hoping to
reach the Pillsburry attacking setup with f2-f4.} Ng4 $1 {This is considered
to be the most accurate reaction up to today. By exchanging the active white
knight in a moment when f2-f4 is impossible, Black somewhat frees his position.
} 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxg4 Bxg4 14. Rae1 Qf6 $6 {This move has several drawbacks.
It wastes a tempo, gives up the control over b4 and prevents the bishop's
retreat to f7 after ...f7-f6.} (14... Bh5 $5 15. f4 f6) (14... Rad8 $5) 15. a4
{White's only questionable move in the whole game. I would have written
"clumsy" if there was not something prophetic in it (see the later game
Karpov-Kharitonov).} ({I don't exclude the possibility that the game went} 15.
b4 Re7 16. a4 {, meaning that a mouse slip generated the move order given in
the database.}) (15. f4 $14 {is also strong, since the bishop does not have a
quick retreat to f7.}) 15... Re7 ({With the actual move order,} 15... a5 {
is called for, even though White can switch to the kingside plan with} 16. f4
$14) 16. b4 {Everything back to normal now.} Rae8 ({Black usually tries to rid
himself of superfluous queenside weaknesses with} 16... a6) 17. b5 {Here it is,
the queenside pawn impact. No matter what he does, Black will have a weakness
somewhere in that area.} Qd6 {Curiously, a novelty with respect to an even
older game.} (17... Qg5 {Curiously, a game played in the third Millenium ended
in a draw here, Agabekian-Arhipov, Kazan City-ch 2007..} 18. f4 {Pillsburry
remains consequent to "his" attacking plan.} (18. bxc6 Bf3 19. g3 bxc6 {
yields Black certain counterplay.}) (18. Ne2 $14 {as played by Napier slightly
later would have taken measures against Black's initiative.}) (18. Kh1 $14)
18... Qf6 19. Qd2 Bf5 {At this stage, Black has excellent play on light
squares, Pillsbury,H-Showalter,J New York 1898 (1-0, 54). It is also curious
that in all these games, White first played a2-a4 and only next b2-b4.}) 18.
bxc6 bxc6 {The standard reaction.} ({In general,} 18... Qxc6 {would weaken d5,
which is especially important with the knight far from f6, but in this
concrete case, it also loses an exchange to} 19. Bb5 $18) 19. Rb1 $1 {After
opening the queenside, the rooks do not have much to do on the opposite wing.
White has got the b- and c-files for setting up his pressure, a target on c6
and a good square for the knight on c5. These circumstances will dictate
Napier's play.} Bc8 20. Rfc1 Re6 {The only reasonable plan. On the sixth rank,
the rook not only defends the weakness on c6, but also prepares a kingside
attack.} 21. Ne2 $1 {As we will see later, a move Karpov would be proud of.
White immediately takes measures against Black's attack while clearing the
c-file for his major pieces.} (21. a5 Rh6 {yields Black good play} 22. h3 $2 (
22. g3 {is better, but Black has good counterplay after} Bg4) 22... Bxh3 $1 23.
gxh3 Rxh3 24. Ne2 Qh6 {with a decisive attack.}) 21... Rh6 22. Ng3 {Black's
attack has reached a dead end.} Nd7 {If Black could transfer his knight to h4,
White would have to count with the potential threats of ...Nxg2 and ...Bh3.
However, the knight cannot cross the sixth rank because the pawn on c6 is
hanging.} (22... Qe7 23. Rb3 Qh4 {leads nowehere after} 24. h3 ({The
ultra-cautious} 24. Nf1 {is also good.}) 24... Bxh3 25. gxh3 Qxh3 26. Bf5 Qh2+
27. Kf1 $18) (22... Bd7 {defends c6 in order to prepare the knight's
activation, but loses ground on the queenside.} 23. Rb7 Ng6 24. Rxa7 Nh4 25.
Rb1 $18 {Combinations are not working yet and Black's backside is vulnerable
already.}) 23. Qc3 Qc7 24. Rb2 {A good, though slightly shy move.} (24. Rb5 $5
{[%cal Gb5d5,Gb5a5] attacking d5 and preparing Ra5.}) (24. Bb5 $5 {forcing the
knight to retreat to b8.}) 24... Rd6 25. Qb4 g6 26. a5 Rde6 {White seems to
have increased his queenside pressure to the maximum. There still is one
element missing, though.} 27. Ne2 $3 {Once again typical for Karpov. After the
danger of ...Rh6 has disappeared, the knight will navigate towards c5. In his
comments to the s3econd game of the Merano 1981 World Championship match with
Kortschnoj, where he carried out a similar manoeuvre  (Nc3-e2-g3-e2-c1-d3)
Karpov writes: "The knight has fulfilled his kingside job and is heading for
the d3-square."} Kg7 28. Nf4 Rd6 29. Be2 Nf6 30. Bd3 (30. Nd3 {is premature
due to} Ba6) 30... h5 31. h4 Ng4 32. Rbc2 Nh6 33. g3 Ng8 34. Qc5 Ne7 35. Rb2
Red8 36. Rcb1 R6d7 37. Rb8 {[%cal Gb8a8]} Qd6 38. Qxd6 Rxd6 39. Ra8 R6d7 40.
Bf1 Rc7 41. Nd3 Rg8 42. Nc5 {AFter the knight has reached this square, the
game is practically over.} Bf5 43. Rxg8+ Nxg8 44. Rb8 Nf6 45. a6 Bc8 46. f3 $1
Ne8 47. e4 Kf8 48. e5 Ke7 49. Be2 Ng7 50. g4 hxg4 51. fxg4 Ne6 52. Nxe6 Kxe6
53. h5 gxh5 54. gxh5 Kf5 55. Kf2 c5 56. dxc5 d4 57. Rb1 Kxe5 58. h6 Bf5 59. Rb7
Rxc5 60. Rxa7 d3 61. Bf3 Kf4 62. Rxf7 Rc2+ 63. Kg1 Kg3 64. Rxf5 Rc1+ 65. Bd1
Rxd1+ 66. Rf1 Rd2 67. Ra1 Rg2+ 68. Kf1 d2 69. Ra3+ Kf4 70. Rd3 Ke4 71. Rd7 Rg6
72. a7 1-0

