{Here is a successful modern interpretation of the minority's attack.} 1. d4 d5
2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 c6 8. Qc2 Nbd7 9.
Bd3 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. h3 g6 12. Bh6 Bd6 $5 {A relatively unexplored move.
Once the pin along the h4-d8 diagonal is released, Black places his bishop on
a more active square.} 13. Rab1 {The most natural reaction. Until the moment
Black defines his intentions on the queenside, White proceeds with his
standard queen side plan.} Ne6 {Black seems to regroup harmoniously, but he
does not take any measures against White's plan, while his kingside
counterplay will not take concrete contours.} 14. b4 a6 15. Rfe1 $5 {An
interesting prophylactic move. Black's main idea is to play ...Kh8 and ...Ng8,
endangering the white bishop. In doing so, he needs to consider that with the
pawn on f7 vulnerable, ...Kh8 can run into Ng5, solving White's kingside
problems and maintaining an edge. Therefore, Black should prepare ... Kh8 with
...Qe7. Anticipating all these, White's next move prepares to open the centre
with e3-e4, if the queen goes to e7.} (15. a4 Qe7 (15... Kh8 16. Ng5) 16. b5
axb5 17. axb5 Kh8 18. bxc6 bxc6) 15... Ng7 (15... Kh8 {[%cal Yf6g8]} 16. Ng5 $1
$14) (15... Qe7 16. Qb2 $14 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb2h8]} Kh8 $2 17. e4 $1 $18 dxe4
18. Bxe4 $18 {Threatening d4-d5} Nxe4 19. Nxe4 {renewing the threat with
increased effect.}) 16. Bg5 {Maintaining the light kingside pressure.} Be7 {
The losses of time of both sides compensate each other.} (16... Ne6 17. Bh4 $14
) 17. a4 Bf5 18. Bxf5 Nxf5 {Black has managed to exchange his "bad" bishop,
but White has made important progress on the queenside.} 19. b5 axb5 20. axb5
Nd7 21. bxc6 bxc6 22. Bf4 Bd6 23. Ne2 {A familiar regrouping. The opening has
been a success for White. Black faces a difficult defensive task.} Rc8 24. Rec1
{An interesting moment. There are two main arguments to the favour of this
move. It completes White's development and it is the engines' favourite.
Despite all these, I would strongly consider the following alternative:} (24.
Bxd6 $5 Nxd6 25. Nf4 {This wastes a bit of time concerning the game
continuation, but it inhibits ...c6-c5, which is Black's only chance for
getting some relief.} c5 (25... Nc4 26. Ra1 Ra8 27. Rec1 Qc7 28. Nd3 c5 $6 29.
Rxa8 Rxa8 30. Nf4 {and Black is hanging in the centre.}) 26. Nxd5 cxd4 27. Qa4
$1 $16 {The threat Qxd7! followed by Nf6+ gains an important tempo for
grabbing the pawn on d4.}) 24... Bxf4 $6 {This practically offers White two
extra tempi with respect to the variation above.} (24... c5 $5 {was the only
chance to free Black's position a bit. Of course, the Isolani looks vulnerable,
but the pawn on c6 will be an even bigger source of worries.} 25. dxc5 (25.
Bxd6 Nxd6 26. dxc5 Nxc5 $14) 25... Nxc5 (25... Bxf4 26. Nxf4 Nxc5 27. Nxd5 Qxd5
28. Rb5 $16) 26. Qd1 Bxf4 (26... Bf8 27. Rc2 $16 {followed by Rd2.}) 27. Nxf4
Ne7 $14 28. g4 $5 (28. Nd4 h5 $5 {yields Black more freedom.}) 28... Qd6 29.
Nd4 {White's position looks pleasant, but I doubt that he has realistic
winning chances.} Ne4 30. Rxc8 Rxc8 31. Rb7 Qf6) 25. Nxf4 Nd6 26. Nd2 {This is
the kind of position where one cannot indicate a crystal-clear winning plan,
but one also knows that White's chances to win are higher than Black's
possibilities to draw.} Nb6 (26... c5 {loses a pawn to} 27. Qa4 cxd4 28. Qxd4
$16) 27. Qc5 Nb5 {Black tries to set up a fortress, but his queenside remains
vulnerable.} 28. Ra1 Nd7 29. Qb4 Qb6 30. Rab1 Rb8 31. Nf3 Rb7 32. Nd3 f6 $6 {
Black should not have hurried to weaken his kingside. He will now be in danger
on both wings.} (32... Kg7 33. Nfe5 Nxe5 34. Nxe5 Rc8 35. Qc5 Qxc5 36. Rxc5
Rbc7 37. g4 {Planning to block the kingside with g4-g5.} f6 38. Nd3 $16 {
This does not look rosy for Black, but without queens the kingside weaknesses
are less relevant.}) 33. Rb2 {Still not finding a clear plan, but not
releasing the pressure any single bit, either.} (33. Nf4 Nf8 34. Ne1 Ne6 35.
Nxe6 Rxe6 36. Nd3 Re8 37. Rb2 $16) 33... Nb8 34. Qd2 Qd8 35. Ra1 Ree7 36. Qc2
Ra7 37. Rc1 Ra3 38. Rb3 Rea7 39. Nf4 Kf7 40. h4 Ra2 $6 {Black does not have
chances for counterplay, so avoiding the exchange does not make sense.} (40...
Rxb3 41. Qxb3 Ra3 $16) 41. Qb1 Kg8 42. h5 $1 {Black is in trouble on both
wings.} g5 43. Ne6 Qe8 (43... Qd7 44. Qf5 $18) 44. Nc7 $1 {A "petite
combinaison" to finish the game.} Qd7 (44... Nxc7 45. Rxb8 $18) (44... Rxc7 45.
Qxa2 $18) 45. Nxb5 cxb5 46. Rxb5 Nc6 47. Rb6 Ra1 48. Qxa1 Rxa1 49. Rxa1 Qc7 50.
Ra8+ Kf7 51. Raa6 1-0

