{[%evp 0,43,20,27,13,13,30,-5,-1,-8,9,26,29,29,25,33,53,43,65,48,38,50,44,39,
75,62,63,75,75,55,60,39,43,33,94,70,61,61,103,94,104,81,124,116,122,122] In
the previous examples, Black did not come even close to creating kingside
counterplay. In the next game, played a few decades after Napier's, Black did
somewhat better, despite the final result.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Bg5
Nbd7 5. e3 Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Rc1 Re8 8. a3 a6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 c6 11. O-O
Nf8 12. Qc2 Nh5 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. b4 Be6 15. Qb2 Rad8 $6 {There was no need to
waste a tempo on "completing the development". In fact, the rook could be
useful on a8 after a3-a4 followed by b4-b5, ...axb5.} ({Black should have
started his kingside attack at once:} 15... Ng6 $1 16. a4 Bg4 17. Nd2 (17. Ne1
Nh4 $132) 17... Qg5 18. Rfe1 (18. Kh1 $2 Ngf4 $1 19. exf4 Nxf4 20. Bb1 Bf3 $19
{wins}) (18. g3 Re6 {also yields Black counterplay.}) 18... Bh3 19. g3 Nh4 {
with excellent play.}) 16. a4 g5 $5 {Rubinstein intends to make his attack
global. Eventually, he will manage that, but at this stage his plan is too
time consuming.} 17. b5 axb5 18. axb5 g4 19. Nd2 (19. Ne1 $1 {was a better way
of anticipating} c5 {, by defending the bishop on d3 and staying safe from a
possible ...dxe3..} 20. dxc5 Qxc5 (20... d4 21. Ne4 $1 dxe3 22. Nd6 exf2+ 23.
Qxf2 {with overwhelming pressure.}) 21. Nc2 {The knight reaches d4 anyway,
yielding White a stable advantage.}) 19... Bc8 {Too slow.} (19... c5 $1 20.
dxc5 d4 $1 21. exd4 (21. Nce4 $2 {is impossible due to} dxe3 $19 {, when
White's minor pieces are hanging.}) 21... Rxd4 22. Bb1 Qxc5 23. Nce4 Qb4 $11)
20. Rfe1 f5 21. Na2 {The knight is heading for b4, aiming at winning the weak
pawn on c6.} (21. Ne2 $1 {as played by Napier would have been more accurate,
maintaining the balance between attack and defence even.}) 21... Rd6 22. bxc6
bxc6 23. Qb6 {Once again, too straightforward.} ({White should have maintained
his overall harmobny with} 23. Nb4 Bd7 24. g3 Nf6 25. Bf1 $14) 23... Bd7 24.
Nb4 Nf6 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gh4h3] Typical for Rubinstein. He usually
carried out his plans slowly, but consistently. He intends to advance his
h-pawn as far as possible and install his knight on e4. However, on this
occasion this is too slow.} ({The position was ripe for} 24... f4 $1 $11 25.
exf4 $6 Qxe1+ 26. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 27. Bf1 Nxf4 $15) 25. Rc2 Ne4 26. Bxe4 {
Bogoljubow writes that he needed the d2-knight to defend h2 from f1.} fxe4 27.
Rec1 Qf6 28. Qb7 Re7 29. Qa8 Rf7 30. Nf1 {Finally some defensive manoeuvres.
The knight is heading for f4.} h5 31. Ng3 {[%csl Gf4]} h4 32. Nh5 {Since the
knight cannot obstruct the second rank, this is the only way of reaching f4.}
Qg5 $2 {This natural move is not the best.} (32... Qh6 $2 {would not work,
either:} 33. Nf4 g3 34. Nxc6 $16) (32... Qh8 $3 {was the strongest m0ve. The
idea is that after sacrificing the exchange on f4, Black needs to take on d4
with his queen.} 33. Qb8 (33. Nf4 g3 34. Nxc6 Rxf4 $1 35. exf4 Bxc6 36. Rxc6
gxf2+ 37. Kf1 Qxd4 $44 {with fantastic play for the exchange.} 38. Rxd6 Qd3+
39. Kxf2 Qd2+ 40. Kf1 Qxc1+ 41. Ke2 {The king has to calculate his steps in
such a way that Black does not get to take on f4 with check.} Qc2+ 42. Ke1 $1
$11) 33... Qh6 $3 {Another fine move, defending the rook and the c6-pawn,
while keeping the white queen isolated from the kingside.} (33... Rh6 34. Nf4
g3 35. Nxc6 Rxf4 36. Qxf4 $18) 34. Nf4 (34. Rf1 g3 $1 35. hxg3 $2 h3 $1 $19 {
[%cal Gd7g4,Gg4f3] followed by ...Bg4-f3 soon}) 34... g3 35. fxg3 hxg3 36. hxg3
Rh7 37. Kf2 Rf6) 33. Qb8 $2 (33. Nf4 $1 Rxf4 (33... g3 34. fxg3 hxg3 35. Nxc6
gxh2+ 36. Kh1 $18) 34. exf4 Qxf4 35. Qa3 $16) 33... Rh6 $2 (33... Qh6 $1 {
transposes above.}) 34. Nf4 g3 (34... Rff6 $5) 35. Nxc6 $1 {Bogoljubov
evaluated the consequences of the pawn grabbing correctly.} gxf2+ 36. Kxf2 Bxc6
37. Rxc6 Rxc6 38. Rxc6 h3 39. gxh3 $1 (39. g3 Qg4 $11 {yields Black enough
counterplay.}) 39... Qh5 40. Ke1 $1 {The only move maintaining an advantage.
White gets ready to regroup with Kd2 and if necessary, Ne2. But he also has an
additional idea in mind.} Qf3 41. Rg6+ $5 {The most active way of eluding the
threats. One move earlier, this manoeuvre was not possible.} (41. Kd2 Qf2+ 42.
Ne2 {also wins, for instance} Rf3 43. Qb3 {Threatening Qxd5+.} Kh8 44. h4 $18)
41... Kh7 42. Rg3 Qh1+ 43. Kd2 {Things have almost calmed down and White is
winning. But a game is a game...} Qa1 (43... Qxh2+ 44. Rg2 Qh1 45. Qe8 {
wins, for instance:} Rg7 (45... Rf6 46. Qe7+ {mates soon.}) 46. Rxg7+ (46. Qh5+
Kg8 47. Qxd5+ {is convincing, too.}) 46... Kxg7 47. Qe7+ Kg8 48. Nh5 Qg2+ 49.
Kc3 Nh7 {The only way of parrying Nf6+.} 50. Qe8+ Nf8 51. Nf6+ Kg7 52. Qe7+ {
winning the knight and the game.}) 44. Qc8 Qa2+ 45. Ke1 Qa1+ 46. Ke2 $6 (46.
Kf2 $1 Ng6 47. Qg4 Rxf4+ 48. exf4 Qxd4+ (48... Qb2+ 49. Ke1 Qb1+ 50. Qd1 $18)
49. Kg2 Qb2+ 50. Kh1 Qf6 51. Qh5+ Kg7 52. f5 $18) 46... Qb2+ 47. Kf1 Ng6 48.
Qg4 Rxf4+ 49. exf4 Qc1+ 50. Kf2 Qd2+ 51. Kg1 Qc1+ 52. Kf2 Qd2+ 53. Qe2 Qxd4+
54. Qe3 Qb2+ 55. Kf1 Qa1+ 56. Ke2 Qb2+ 57. Kd1 Qb1+ 58. Qc1 Qxc1+ (58... Qb5 {
keeps the game going, even though Black would have feeble hopes to save.}) 59.
Kxc1 Nxf4 60. Rg4 Ne6 61. Kd2 Kh6 62. Ke3 Kh5 63. Rg8 Kh4 64. Rg6 Nc7 65. Rc6
Ne8 66. Rc8 Nd6 67. Rd8 Nc4+ 68. Kf4 Kxh3 69. Rxd5 e3 70. Kf3 Kxh2 {Black has
eliminated the last white pawn, but his knight is isolated from the king.} 71.
Rc5 Nd2+ 72. Kxe3 $18 Nf1+ 73. Kf2 Ng3 {Not the most favourable way of
coordinating Black's pieces, but Black did not have anything else.} 74. Re5
Nh1+ 75. Kf3 Ng3 76. Rg5 Nf1 77. Kf2 1-0

