{[%evp 0,75,26,16,16,0,37,38,75,54,67,29,30,40,30,30,59,2,8,4,-2,-24,-8,-21,
-21,-21,-14,-21,0,0,24,24,24,8,0,0,0,0,16,0,7,0,10,6,18,18,11,25,19,26,30,34,
37,37,61,61,70,79,74,69,96,96,101,123,140,145,102,73,204,161,240,215,269,227,
340,489,29995,29996] There were a couple of moments when Black's plan based on
...g7-g5-g4 looked a bit clumsy. However, we know already that Black could
have handled it better in two important moments. To get a full picture, we
will examine a modern top level game, in which this plan was absolutely
correct, even though Black missed the best continuation at the critical moment.
} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 Bg7 5. Bg5 Ne4 6. cxd5 Nxg5 7. Nxg5 e6 8.
Nf3 exd5 9. e3 O-O 10. b4 Be6 11. Be2 Nd7 12. O-O f5 13. Re1 g5 {As we will
see, the main idea is to reduce White's control on d4.} (13... f4 14. e4 $14 {
Karpov.}) ({The more solid} 13... c6 $5 {was also playable.} 14. Rc1 Kh8 15.
Bd3 a5 16. b5 c5 {Even though the knight defends d4, the bishop's pressure in
the centre maintains the chances even.}) 14. Rc1 Kh8 15. Bd3 c6 {Kortschnoj
does well to keep ...g5-g4 until the centre opens.} (15... g4 16. Nd2 Nf6 (
16... f4 17. exf4 $16) 17. Ne2 $16 {Karpov Now is the first moment when we get
acquainted with Karpov's mysterious knight moves in this structure, even
though this time they happened only in a comment and not in the game yet.}) (
15... a6 $5) 16. b5 (16. Ne2 {makes less sense now.} f4 17. exf4 gxf4 {Marin})
16... g4 $1 {Now is a good moment for this move.} (16... c5 $6 17. dxc5 Nxc5
18. Nd4 $14) 17. Nd2 ({Karpov gives} 17. bxc6 {as a worthy alternative.
Objectively, it should lead to equality, the same as the game continuation,
but abstractly it is a small concession. White exchanges the pawn that had
cost him two tempi, while also opening the b-file for Black's counterplay.}
bxc6 $1 {is simple and strong.} (17... gxf3 $2 18. cxd7 fxg2 19. Qf3 (19. f4
Qxd7 20. Re2 $14 {Karpov}) 19... Qxd7 20. Ne2 $16 {Marin}) 18. Nd2 c5 {Same
idea as in the game.} 19. dxc5 (19. Bb5 {Karpov gives this as slightly better
for White, but this is just his usual display of optimism. In fact, Black's
position seems to be preferable.} cxd4 20. exd4 Bg8 21. Nf1 Nf6 $15 {Marin})
19... Nxc5 20. Nb3 Nxb3 21. axb3 ({With the b-file open,} 21. Qxb3 Bg8 {
is even less appealing than in the game.}) 21... d4 ({The simpler} 21... Qb6
22. Ne2 a5 {also offers Black a good counterplay.}) 22. exd4 Bg8 ({The only
positive consequence of the intermediate exchange on c6 is that} 22... Qxd4 $2
{loses to} 23. Nb5 {followed by Nc7.}) 23. Ne2 f4 {With obvious compensation
for the pawn. In fact, the pawn on d4 does not seem to be destined for a long
carrier.}) 17... c5 18. dxc5 (18. Ne2 c4 $15) 18... Nxc5 19. Nb3 (19. Bb1 d4
$15) 19... Nxb3 20. axb3 {Karpov hurries to evaluate the position as clearly
better for him.} (20. Qxb3 {would only yield a moderate advantage, he adds.
Both evaluations are over-optimistic since the position is about equal in both
cases.} Qd6 (20... Re8 $11) (20... Bg8 $11) 21. Ne2 d4 22. Bc4 Bxc4 23. Rxc4
dxe3 24. Qxe3 Rae8 $11) 20... Rc8 $2 {Only this hesitant move puts Black in
positional trouble.} ({It is hard to say why Kortschnoj refrained from
carrying out his idea until the end with} 20... d4 $1 21. exd4 Qxd4 ({The
familiar} 21... Bg8 22. Ne2 f4 {with adequate compensation is fine, too. While
the main line may be difficult to evaluate over the board, this one is just
natural.}) 22. Rxe6 Rad8 $1 {Kortschnoj might have missed this move,
completing the development and revealing that White is poorly coordinated.} 23.
Bf1 (23. Be2 Qxc3 $1 24. Rxc3 Rxd1+ 25. Bxd1 Bxc3 $11) (23. Re3 f4 24. Ne2 Qd6
25. Nxf4 Qxf4 26. Rc2 Bd4 $13 27. Ree2 $2 g3 28. hxg3 Qxg3 $19 {[%csl Gd3]
[%cal Gf8g8] The threat ...Rg8 is decisive, as the bishop is stuck on d3.})
23... Qxc3 24. Qxd8 Rxd8 25. Rxc3 Bxc3 26. Re7 {White seems to be more active,
but Black's kingside space advantage, the consequence of his global plan,
ensures him a relatively easy draw.} f4 (26... Rd2 27. Rf7 Bd4 28. Rxf5 Kg7 29.
g3 Bb6 30. Bc4 Kg6 31. Rf4 h5 $11 {White cannot make any progress.}) 27. Rf7 g3
28. hxg3 (28. Rxf4 gxh2+ 29. Kh1 Rd1 $19) 28... fxg3 29. fxg3 Rd6 {Threatening
...Bc5+ followed by ...Rh6 mate!} 30. Kf2 Rf6+ 31. Rxf6 Bxf6 $11 {with an
elementary draw.}) 21. Ne2 Rxc1 22. Qxc1 Qb6 23. Nf4 $1 {Starting with this
moment, Karpov plays a good game. Since this is not directly related with our
main theme, I will only make some additions to his lines, without verbal
comments.} Bg8 (23... Rc8 24. Qb1 {/\ Bf5}) 24. g3 $1 (24. Qc2 d4 $132) 24...
d4 25. Bc4 $1 (25. e4 fxe4 26. Rxe4 Bxb3 27. Qa3 Bf7 {[%cal Gf4h5]} 28. Qe7 $18
{Marin}) 25... Rc8 (25... dxe3 26. Rxe3 Bd4 27. Re2 $16 {/\ Qe1}) 26. Qb1 $1
dxe3 (26... Bxc4 27. bxc4 Rxc4 28. Qxf5 $18) 27. Rxe3 Qc5 28. Qe1 $1 (28. Qd3
$18 {Marin}) 28... Bd4 29. Re2 (29. Nd3 Qf8 30. Re7 $18 {Marin}) (29. Re7 Bxf2+
$19 {Marin}) 29... Bxc4 (29... Rf8 30. Bxg8 Rxg8 31. Ne6 $18) (29... Bg7 30.
Re8) 30. bxc4 Rg8 (30... Qxc4 31. Re8+ $18 Rxe8 32. Qxe8+ Kg7 (32... Qg8 33.
Qd7 Be5 34. Nd3 (34. Nd5 $16) 34... Bc3 35. Qxb7 $16 {Marin}) 33. Ne6+ Kf6 34.
Nxd4) 31. Qc1 $1 (31. Re7 $2 Bxf2+) (31. Re6 Qxc4 32. Re7 Qxb5 $13) 31... Rc8
32. Qc2 Bg7 (32... Qxc4 $2 33. Re8+ $18) 33. Qd3 $18 {[/\ Qd7]} Qd4 34. Qxf5
Qxc4 35. Re7 Rd8 36. Kg2 Qb3 37. Qxg4 Rg8 38. Ng6+ $1 1-0

