{[%evp 0,60,22,27,27,-5,1,0,0,9,47,13,25,7,10,26,57,20,66,57,54,52,43,42,42,35,
40,27,42,41,45,28,28,2,35,7,35,26,31,8,15,16,20,19,33,18,44,17,24,9,0,0,25,0,
25,31,20,15,20,11,45,37,45] The safest way of meeting the minority's attack
was discovered a few years after Napier's game. While keeping in mind the
possibility of a kingside conterplay, Black can prepare a solid reaction to
the advance of the b-pawn.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bg5 c6
6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 Be7 8. Qc2 Nh5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Be2 Nhf6 11. a3 Nb6 $1 {
Placing a knight on b6 is an important element in Black's global plan of
meeting the queenside attack.} 12. Ne5 {This will result into some waste of
time.} ({However,} 12. O-O O-O 13. b4 Bg4 {does not change much.}) 12... O-O
13. O-O Nfd7 14. Nf3 (14. Nxd7 Bxd7 {does not change the situation essentially.
It actually frees Black's position a bit.} 15. b4 Be6 16. Rab1 g6 {[%cal Gh7h4]
Preparing the resolute advance of the h-pawn but also threatening ...Bf5.} (
16... Rfe8 $5) (16... f5 $5) 17. Bd3 (17. b5 Bf5 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Qxa3 20.
bxc6 bxc6 21. Ra1 Qe7 22. Ra6 $11 {with just normal compensation for the pawn.}
) 17... a6 18. a4 Kg7 19. b5 (19. a5 {gains space and ensures the knight's
stability on c5, but freezes the queenside, leaving White short of
constructive plans.} Nc8 20. Na4 Nd6 21. Nc5 Bf5 $15 {As we will see later,
the positions with no other black minor piece than a knight on d6 are
auspicious for Black.}) 19... cxb5 20. axb5 a5 $1 $15 {The same structure as
in the main line. More about it later.} 21. Na4 Nxa4 22. Qxa4 Rfc8 23. Rfc1 h5
24. Rxc8 Bxc8 $15) 14... Rd8 {Clearing the f8-square for the knight and
preparing to over defend d5, which is essential if Black intends to play ...
cxb5 later.} 15. b4 a6 16. Qb3 Nf8 17. a4 Be6 {Maybe a bit too solid.} (17...
Bg4 $5) (17... Bf5 $5) 18. Rfc1 Ng6 {Black has displayed his forces
harmoniously, being ready to attack and defend on the respective wings.} 19.
Qb2 Bg4 ({Another merit of the knight's presence on b6 is that it can use the
relative weakness on c4.} 19... Nc4 20. Bxc4 dxc4 {Threatening to consolidate
the passed pawn with ...b7-b5.} 21. a5 Bd5 $1 22. Qe2 (22. Ne1 Rd6 {also
offers Black counterplay.}) 22... f5 {with a stable position and certain
kingside chances.}) 20. Nd2 Qg5 $6 {This seemingly active move slightly spoils
Black's coordination.} (20... Bxe2 {was simpler and better.} 21. Nxe2 Nh4 22.
b5 cxb5 23. axb5 a5 {with an improved version of the game continuation.}) 21.
b5 cxb5 $1 22. axb5 a5 $1 {Now is the moment to explain Black's defensive/
counter-attacking concept. The knight occupies a perfect blocking square on b6
and the a-pawn could become threatening in the endgame. The knight also
defends d5 and is ready for an intrusion to c4. With the queen on e7, as in
the recommended line above, Black would also be ready for ...Qb4 or ...
a5-a4-a3. In many cases, it is useful to keep the reserve knight close to b6 (.
..Ng6-f8-d7) to replace his colleague after an exchange with Na4.} 23. g3 $6 {
Returning the favour.} (23. Nb3 $5 {offers White chances to take advantage of
Black's spoiled coordination.} Bxe2 (23... Nh4 24. f4 Qg6 25. Bxg4 Qxg4 26. Qf2
a4 27. Nc5 $14) (23... a4 24. Nc5 Nh4 25. f4 Qg6 26. Bd3 Bf5 27. Bf1 $14 {
In these lines White wins a pawn with only partial black compensation.}) 24.
Qxe2 Nc4 (24... Nh4 25. g3 $16 {[%csl Gf3] and the square on f3 is defended.})
25. Nxd5 Rxd5 26. Qxc4 Rxb5 27. Nc5 $14 {with very active white play.}) 23...
Bxe2 24. Nxe2 Qg4 {Things re-enter the typical paths now, but not for too long.
..} 25. Nc3 Rd6 $2 {A thematical rook lift but also a heavy mistake. Black had
several ways of continuing his kingside plan.} (25... Nh4 26. h3 (26. Na4 Rd6
27. Nxb6 $2 Qh3 $19 {wins}) 26... Nf3+ 27. Kg2 (27. Nxf3 Qxf3 28. Qe2 Qf5 $5
$11 {with pleasant play for Black.}) 27... Nh4+ 28. Kg1 $11) (25... h5 $5) (
25... Rdc8 26. Qa2 Ne7 $11 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge7c8,Gc8b6] getting ready to
bring the reserve knight to b6 (via c8) if needed.}) 26. Qb3 ({Missing the
ombination} 26. Rxa5 $1 Rxa5 27. Qb4 {True, Black's coordination is so good
that White would have practical problems converting his material advantage.}
Rf6 28. Qxa5 Qf5 29. f4 h5 $14 {and things are far from clear yet.}) 26... Nh4
27. Qd1 (27. h3 $2 Qxh3 $1 28. gxh4 $2 Rg6#) 27... Qh3 28. Qf1 Qg4 29. Qd1 Qh3
30. Qf1 Qg4 1/2-1/2

