{I will not hide that this whole plan based on ...Nb6 was one of the reasons I
was induced to play the Queen's Gambit with Black. The exchange variation has
since always been prevalent and I enjoyed the thought of having this structure
frequently. Here is one of the games in which I managed to apply Black's main
ideas.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Nbd7 6. e3 h6 7. Bf4 {
White transposes to the Bf4 system after having induced a minor kingside
weakening. In modern chess (and not only) this sometimes happens without the
previous exchange on d5.} c6 8. Bd3 Nb6 {Of course.} 9. h3 Bd6 10. Nge2 O-O 11.
O-O Re8 12. Qc2 Bxf4 13. Nxf4 Qd6 14. Rab1 Bd7 {Black has comfortable
development and a clear plan of improving his position, based on .. .Re7, ...
Rae8 and a slow kingside pawn expansion.} 15. Rfd1 {Still preparing the
minority's attack.} (15. b4 {may run into} Nc4 $5 ({The standard} 15... a6 {
is also possible, of course.}) 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. b5 b6 18. a4 g6 $5 $11 19. Rb2
(19. Nxg6 fxg6 20. Qxg6+ Kf8 21. Qxh6+ $2 Kf7 $17) 19... Bf5 20. Qd1 g5 21.
Nfe2 (21. Nh5 $2 Nxh5 22. Qxh5 Qa3 $19 {wins material.}) 21... Bd3 $11) 15...
Rac8 16. Nfe2 (16. b4 {may once again be premature.} Nc4 $5 17. Bxc4 dxc4 18.
b5 (18. d5 Qe5 $11) (18. Nfe2 Nd5 $11) 18... b6 19. bxc6 (19. a4 Nd5 20. bxc6
$2 {runs into the unexpected} Bf5 $3 $17) 19... Bxc6 $11) 16... h5 {With
little going on on the queenside, Black starts the kingside expansion.} 17. Ng3
{Still trying to find a good square for the knight.} (17. h4 Bg4 $132 {yields
Black could counterplay. I was dreaming of} 18. f3 $2 Rxe3 $1 19. fxg4 Nxg4 {
with a massive attack, even though I could not calculate the lines below in
advance.} 20. g3 Rce8 (20... Rxg3+ {is good, but not best.} 21. Nxg3 Qxg3+ 22.
Qg2 Qe3+ 23. Kf1 Qf4+ 24. Ke1 Re8+ 25. Ne2 Nc4 $15) 21. Kh1 (21. Kg2 Rxe2+ $1
22. Nxe2 Ne3+ {wins the queen.}) 21... Rxg3 $1 {Now everything is ready for
this.} 22. Nxg3 Qxg3) ({No matter how long White has been preparing for} 17. b4
{, Black could still answer with} Nc4 ({At this stage, I might have chosen} 
17... a6 {, though.}) 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. e4 Qe7 20. f3 b5 21. a4 a6 {with
normal play for Black, who has a potential target on h3.}) 17... h4 18. Nf5 {
I do not think Axel overestimated his bishop's strength when forcing this
exchange. He probably feared my own bishop, which causes some permanent latent
danger on h3.} (18. Nf1 {was more flexible (and maybe in Karpov's style) , but
Black could try} g5 $5 19. f3 Nh5 {with good counterplay.}) 18... Bxf5 19. Bxf5
Rc7 20. Bd3 (20. Rdc1 {fails to create serious tactical threats.} g6 {It
appears that Black can ignore the threat.} (20... Rce7 $5 $11) (20... a6 $5 $11
) 21. Bd3 (21. Nb5 cxb5 22. Qxc7 Qxc7 23. Rxc7 gxf5 24. Rxb7 f4 {yields Black
at least equal play.}) 21... Rce7 22. b4 a6 23. a4 Kg7 24. b5 cxb5 25. axb5 a5
{with similar play as in the game.}) 20... g6 (20... Rce7 {is possible, of
course, but I preferred to improve my kingside position with the rook on c7,
anticipating that White would try something on the queenside.}) 21. b4 a6 22.
a4 Kg7 23. Rdc1 Rec8 {By doubling rooks on the (for me, closed) c-file, I
bought some time for improving my knights' placement. The optimal setup
consists of having the knights on b6 and e6.} 24. Ne2 Nbd7 25. Rb3 Nf8 {
Continuing my plan.} ({As a curiosity,} 25... Nb6 {is possible despite} 26. Qc5
{when, Black is not forced to improve White's structure by exchanging the
queens.} Qd8 $1 27. Qxb6 Nd7 28. Qa5 b6 29. Qxa6 Ra8 30. Qxa8 Qxa8 31. Ra1 {
with just good compensation for the queen.}) ({I briefly considered} 25... b5 {
, threatening ...Nb6-c5,} 26. a5 Nf8 {, but paraphrasing Petrosian, I said to
myself: "If your opponent wants to carry out the minority's attack, you should
not prevent him!" Of course, this applies only under certain circumstances.})
26. Qb1 Ne6 27. Rbc3 Nd7 {Getting close to the optimal regrouping.} 28. b5 $6 {
Finally!} (28. Qb2 {was more solid when Black had a relatively wide choice.}
Nb6 ({This is the thematical continuation, but during the game I thought that
now was a good moment for abandoning the neutral strategy:} 28... b5 29. a5 f5
30. Kh1 Nf6 31. Ng1 Ne4 32. R3c2 N6g5 $11 {with active kingside play and
absolutely queenside safety. However, White's position is solid enough.}) (
28... f5 $5 $11) 29. Ra1 Ra8 {Maintaining the possibility of a later ...a6-a5.}
(29... Kg8 $5 30. b5 axb5 31. axb5 c5 {is another possibility I was aware of.
The main point is that the knight on e6 prevents White from reaching a safe
blockade on d4. Besides, the other knight is very stable, too.} 32. dxc5 Rxc5
33. Rxc5 Rxc5 $11 34. Nd4 Qe5) 30. b5 cxb5 31. axb5 a5 {reaching the usual
structure.}) 28... cxb5 $1 (28... axb5 29. axb5 c5 {was once again a safe
alternative, but the game continuation is more promising.} 30. dxc5 Rxc5 31.
Rxc5 Rxc5 $11) 29. axb5 a5 $1 {In view of the inevitable simplifications, the
a-pawn is likely to become dangerous.} 30. Rxc7 {This and the next move are
some sort of concession.} ({In the event of} 30. Qa2 $5 {I planned to keep the
b6-square available for the knight(s).} Rxc3 ({In fact,} 30... b6 $11 {is also
good, since White cannot intrude to c6.}) 31. Rxc3 Ra8 32. Ra3 Qb4 {
Threatening ...Qe1+.} 33. Nc3 Nb6 34. Rb3 Qd6 35. Na4 (35. Ra3 $6 Rc8 $5 36.
Qb2 Qb4 37. Rb3 Na4 $1 $17 38. Nxa4 Qe1+ $1 39. Kh2 Rc1 $19 {Now is when the
pawn on h4 is useful.}) 35... Nxa4 36. Qxa4 Nf8 $11 {[%cal Gf8d7,Gd7b6]
Followed by ...Nd7-b6.}) 30... Rxc7 31. Rxc7 Nxc7 32. Nc3 (32. Qa2 Qb4 $17)
32... Nb6 33. Qc2 $6 ({I planned to meet} 33. Qb2 $6 {with} Qb4 34. Qxb4 axb4
35. Na2 b3 36. Nc3 b2 37. Kf1 Nc4 38. Ke2 b6 39. Kd1 Na3 {White cannot do
anything against the b-pawn. Black's best plan is to start a pawn attack on
the kingside and after achieving certain results, to take on b5. For instance:}
40. Kd2 f5 41. Kd1 Kf6 42. Kd2 g5 43. Kd1 f4 44. Kd2 Ke6 45. Kd1 (45. Ke2 Ncxb5
$19) 45... fxe3 46. fxe3 Ncxb5 47. Nxb5 Nxb5 48. Kc2 Nc3 49. Kxb2 Nd1+ {wins.})
(33. Qb3 Qb4 34. Bc2 {was the last chance to stay close to equality.}) 33...
Qb4 $17 {Black's middlegame plan was crowned by success and I eventually won.}
34. Kf1 (34. Na4 Qe1+ 35. Bf1 Nc4 $19) (34. Na2 Qe1+ 35. Kh2 Ne6 $17) 34... Ne8
(34... Nc4 35. Nxd5 Nd2+ 36. Ke2 Nxd5 37. Qxd2 Nc3+ 38. Kf3 a4 $19) 35. f4 Nd6
36. f5 gxf5 37. Bxf5 Nxb5 (37... Nbc4 38. Kf2 (38. Nxd5 Qxb5 $19) 38... Nxe3
39. Kxe3 Nxf5+ 40. Qxf5 Qxc3+ 41. Ke2 Qb2+ 42. Kf3 Qb3+ 43. Kf2 Qg3+ 44. Kg1 a4
$19) (37... a4 38. Bd3 a3 $19) 38. Nxb5 Qxb5+ 39. Kg1 Qc6 40. Qd1 Kf8 (40...
Qh6 41. Qg4+ Kf8 42. Kf2 a4 $19) 41. Qe1 Qh6 42. Qxa5 Qxe3+ 43. Kh1 Qc1+ 44.
Kh2 Qf4+ 45. Kh1 Qf1+ 46. Kh2 Qf4+ 47. Kh1 Qxd4 48. Qa7 Qf6 49. Qxb7 Qa1+ (
49... Qxf5 $19) 50. Kh2 Qe5+ 51. Kh1 Qa1+ 52. Kh2 Qe5+ 53. Kh1 Nc4 54. Qb1 Ne3
55. Bg4 Qg3 56. Bf3 Kg8 57. Qc1 d4 58. Kg1 Kg7 59. Qd2 Kh6 60. Qa5 f6 61. Qb4
Kg5 62. Qa5+ Qe5 63. Qd8 Nf5 64. Qg8+ Kf4 65. Qc4 Qe1+ 66. Kh2 Qg3+ 67. Kg1
Qe1+ 68. Kh2 Qc3 69. Qe6 Qc7 70. Qxf6 {The benefits of having advanced the
pawn to h4 are visible in the endgame, too. The white king is under pressure
and White cannot create a kingsid epassed pawn. Conceptually, I played well
the last phase of the game, but the permanent time trouble (30 seconds per
move) prevented me from ending the game faster.} d3 $2 (70... Ke3+ $1 71. Kg1
Qc1+ 72. Kh2 Kf2 $19) 71. Bg4 (71. Qb2 $5) 71... Qe5 72. Qd8 (72. Qg6 d2 73.
Bd1 Ke3+ 74. Kg1 $11) 72... Ke3+ 73. Kg1 Qa1+ 74. Kh2 Qe5+ (74... Kf2 75. Qb6+
Ne3 $19 {Checks are over since the black queen controls f6.}) 75. Kg1 Ng3 76.
Qa8 Ne2+ 77. Bxe2 Kxe2 78. Qa2+ d2 79. Qc4+ Kd1 80. Qa4+ Kc1 81. Qc4+ Kb2 82.
Qb4+ Kc2 83. Qa4+ Kd3 84. Qa6+ Ke3 85. Qa3+ Ke4 86. Qf3+ Kd4 87. Qg4+ Kd3 88.
Qg6+ Qe4 89. Qa6+ Qc4 90. Qg6+ Kc3 91. Qb1 Qd4+ 92. Kh2 Qd6+ 93. g3 Qxg3+ 94.
Kh1 Qe1+ 95. Qxe1 dxe1=Q+ 96. Kg2 Qe2+ 97. Kh1 Kd4 98. Kg1 Ke5 99. Kh1 Kf4 100.
Kg1 Kg3 101. Kh1 Qd1# 0-1

[Event "World Cup"]
