{[%evp 0,124,27,28,27,20,27,-5,-5,-16,-17,-8,12,10,13,9,16,-4,33,33,31,28,28,
26,19,19,36,1,-4,-7,-9,-15,-15,-16,-18,-22,-22,-22,-22,-11,-19,-26,-12,-16,-11,
-22,-5,-14,-14,-20,-14,-22,-9,-21,-2,-10,-9,-9,-17,-10,-18,-14,-11,-17,2,-93,
-97,-117,-118,-95,-109,-143,-108,-145,-156,-188,-184,-185,-178,-180,-183,-188,
-188,-179,-194,-205,-184,-180,-197,-221,-200,-219,-201,-220,-271,-305,-329,
-347,-360,-361,-237,-252,-240,-271,-271,-271,-265,-276,-303,-307,-211,-240,
-260,-260,-263,-256,-260,-311,-311,-311,-325,-309,-352,-362,-362,-367,-324] We
will now illustrate Black's absolute dream position in the Carlsbad structure.
I had published the game with my Queen's Gambit repertoire for Black, but the
game is an absolute classic and this material would not be complete without it.
} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Qc2 Na6 7. a3 Nc7 8.
Bg5 g6 $1 9. e3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. b4 {Even in the
absence of the light-squared bishops, the minority's attack can be consistent.
Strictly speaking, Black has gained a tempo with his knight manoeuvre, as
a2-a3 would not be very useful after ...a7-a6, when White would have to spend
time on preparing a2-a4. But the knight on c7 fulfills a purely defensive task
yet, by controlling b5, being far from c4 or even b6.} Ne4 {The correct
decision, aiming at exchanging the knight on c3 and thus slowing down b4-b5.}
14. Bf4 {Portisch rightly decides to target the knight on c7 to keep his main
plan possible.} ({If} 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Rfb1 {Precisely this rook, in
anticipation of ...a7-a5.} Nd6 16. a4 a6 {Now is the right moment to mention
that in the Carlsbad structure d6 is an optimal square for the knight. It
controls c4 and e4 while also taking measures against b4-b5. More about it
later in the game. White does not have constructive plans while Black can
prepare the same kind of kingside expansion as in the game. If} 17. Nd2 Rae8
18. Nb3 {, trying to reinforce the queenside pressure (although this has no
practical effects), Black could even speed up his attack with} f5 $5 {as the
knight is far from e5.}) 14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 $6 {Rather inconsequent.} ({
White should have carried out his plan until its logical end with} 15. Bxc7 $1
Qxc7 16. Qxc3 {, keeping his queenside attack alive. A possible continuation is
} a6 17. a4 Rfc8 18. Rab1 Bd6 19. Rfc1 Kg7 20. Qb3 {With b4-b5 in the air,
Black could stabilize the queenside with} a5 $5 21. b5 (21. bxa5 Rcb8 $15 {
leaves White with weaknesses.}) 21... Rab8 {with static equality, since} 22.
bxc6 bxc6 23. Qc2 Rb4 {would offer Black a certain counterplay. This is
another structure to remember. The presence of the a-pawns helps Black.}) 15...
Bd6 {Black uses the given chance to keep his knight. When agreeing to that,
Portisch must have thought that the knight is passive on c7, overlooking a
small tactical detail.} 16. Bxd6 $6 {Going all the way.} ({Better was} 16. a4
Bxf4 ({If} 16... Ne8 {Black cannot bring his knight to d6 in time to stop} 17.
b5) 17. exf4 $11 {True, WHite's structure is imperfect, but he is safe against
any kingside attack. He could play Ne5 (and if ...f7-f6, then Nd3.}) 16... Nb5
$1 {The move missed by Portisch. The knight reaches d6 in time.} 17. Qb3 Nxd6
$15 {Black has achieved a dream position, the best he might dream of. The
knight on d6 controls all important squares and Black is ready to launch a
slow positional attack based on ...f7-f6, ...g6-g5 and ...h7-h5-h4.} 18. a4 a6
19. Ne5 {White will play without a plan until the end of the game.} ({But
preparing b4-b5 is not easy, but it was all White had to put up some
resistance. Here is an illustrative line that transfers the knight to c3:} 19.
Nd2 Qe7 20. Nb1 a5 $5 {A logical counterplay, taking advantage of White's
temporary lack of coordination.} 21. b5 cxb5 22. axb5 (22. Qxd5 b4 $17 {
followed by ...b7-b5 soon creates two dangerous queenside passers.}) 22... Nc4
23. Rc1 Rfc8 24. Nc3 Qb4 $5 (24... Nxe3 25. fxe3 Qxe3+ 26. Kh1 Rc4 {offers
Black good compensation for the knight, but hardly an advantage.}) 25. Qa2 ({
Relatively best.} 25. Rab1 $2 {loses to} Nd2 26. Qxb4 axb4 27. Rxb4 Rxc3 $1) ({
Or if} 25. Qxb4 axb4 26. Nxd5 b3 $1 $17 {and the b-pawn is very molesting. For
instance} 27. Ne7+ $2 Kf8 28. Nxc8 b2 $1 {wins a knight.}) 25... Nxe3 26. Nxd5
Rxc1+ 27. Rxc1 Nxd5 28. Qxd5 Qa3 $5 29. Rf1 Qe7 {Black's position remains
preferable because of his outside passed pawn, but white is very much in the
game.}) 19... Re8 20. Rfe1 Qg5 21. h3 Kg7 22. Qc2 Re6 23. Rac1 Rae8 24. Qb1 Qh5
$1 25. Qb3 f6 26. Nd3 g5 27. Qd1 Qg6 28. Qc2 R6e7 29. Red1 h5 30. Qb1 ({
Now or in other moments, White could have considered} 30. Nc5 {to offer the
queen exchange before Black's kingside pressure becomes too strong.}) 30... h4
{Black has carried out his plan with a brilliant consequence, while White has
been mainly waiting.} 31. Qc2 g4 $6 {This premature break will be crowned by
success only because of White's lack of resolution.} ({Black should have
prepared it with} 31... Kh6 $5 {planning to transfer his rooks to the g-file.}
32. Kh2 ({The attempt at evacuation} 32. Kf1 {can be met with} Nc4 {
threatening ...Rxe3.}) 32... Rg7 33. Rg1 Reg8 34. Nc5 Qxc2 35. Rxc2 f5 36. Nd3
g4 37. hxg4 fxg4 38. Rh1 Kg5 $15 {with a very unpleasant position for White.})
32. Nf4 $2 ({Hard to say why did Portisch refrain from stabilizing his
position with} 32. hxg4 Qxg4 33. Nf4 {The only active attempt is} h3 $5 34.
Nxh3 Nf5 35. Nf4 Re4 ({Preparing ...Nh4 followed by ...Rxf4} 35... Nh4 {
is ineffective due to} 36. Kf1) 36. f3 Nxe3 37. Qxe4 Rxe4 38. fxg4 Nxd1 39.
Nh5+ Kg6 40. Rxd1 Rxg4 41. Nxf6 Kxf6 42. Kf2 {and White should reach a draw
with a well-timed b4-b5  (finally! possible).}) 32... Qxc2 33. Rxc2 g3 $1 {
The weakness on e3 is decisive.} 34. Rd3 (34. fxg3 Nf5 $1 $19) 34... Kh6 35.
Kf1 Kg5 36. Ne2 Nc4 37. Rcc3 Nb2 38. Rd2 Nxa4 39. Rb3 Nb6 40. Ng1 Nc4 41. Nf3+
Kh5 42. Rdd3 a5 $1 43. bxa5 Ra8 44. Rd1 Rxa5 45. Re1 b5 46. Re2 Ra1+ 47. Re1
Rea7 48. fxg3 Rxe1+ (48... hxg3 $19) 49. Kxe1 Ra1+ 50. Ke2 hxg3 51. Ne1 Ra2+
52. Kd1 Rd2+ 53. Kc1 Re2 54. Kd1 Rxe3 55. Rxe3 Nxe3+ 56. Ke2 Nf5 57. Nc2 Nh4
58. Nb4 Nxg2 59. Kf3 Nh4+ 60. Kxg3 Nf5+ 61. Kf4 Nxd4 62. Ke3 Nf5+ 0-1

