{So far, we have reviewed three main aspects. 1) The potential queenside
danger (or, if you wish, White's dream achievement) 2) Black's kingside
counterplay 3) Black's optimal queenside regrouping. The time has come to take
a step further. It cannot be that White has no chances for an advantage, is it
not? In his best days, Karpov used to treat these positions in a very
instructive way. He actually was the absolute master in positions with static
structures, and this one is no exception. I find this game Karpov's gem in the
Carlsbad structure.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3
Nbd7 7. Nf3 c6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. h3 Be6 12. Rfc1 $5 {
At that moment, a novelty. Karpov starts messing up his pieces on the
queenside, without defining his intentions with respect to the pawns yet.} N6d7
13. Bf4 Nb6 {As we notice, Kharitonov was aware of the best defensive setup.
There were things that anybody would know in the Soviet Union...} 14. Rab1 Bd6
15. Ne2 {A familiar retreat. In the long run, this knight may land on c5.} Ng6
16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. a4 $3 {You surely remember that I had expressed some doubts
with respect to Napier's move order. Did he really start his queenside attack
with a2-a4? If this is true, did he have prophetic abilities? In this position,
this is the right thing to do. White needs to cause Black some discomfort
without weakening the c4-square too soon.} ({Karpov gives the following line
in order to justify his move order:} 17. b4 Nc4 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Nc3 b5 20. a4
a6 {with normal play for Black.}) ({He could have defended c4 before playing
b2-b4, but we know that the standard plan is not that dangerous.} 17. Nd2 Qe7
18. b4 a6 19. a4 Rec8 $5 {is entirely possible, with similar ideas as in my
game with Smith.} (19... Qg5 {Trying to take advantage of the fact that the
knight has retreated actually spoils Black's coordination a bit (we are
familiar with that, too).} 20. Ng3 (20. Nf3 Qf6 {[%cal Gb6c4,Ge6h3]
threatening both ...Nc4 and ...Bxh3, does not achieve much for White.}) 20...
Rec8 $2 {This generally desirable move loses.} 21. a5 $1 Nd7 22. Ndf1 $18 {
[%cal Gf2f5] Due to the poor coordination (or, if you wish, piece congestion)
Black loses material after f2-f4.}) 20. a5 $6 Nd7 21. f4 $6 {does not work
because of} Bxh3 $1 22. gxh3 Qxe3+ 23. Kh2 Nxf4 {with excellent compensation
for the piece.}) 17... Rac8 {Continuing to inhibit b4-b5, a move that was not
part of Karpov's plans soon.} ({Karpov gives two lines after} 17... a5 {
, the reaction that preoccupied us in Napier's game. Karpov is right that the
simplest would be} 18. b3 {, planning Qd2 and Rc5} (18. Qc5 Nc8 $5 {According
to Karpov, this is unclear, but in fact White is better.} (18... Qxc5 19. dxc5
Nd7 20. Ned4 Nge5 21. Bf1 Nxf3+ 22. gxf3 $14 {Karpov. White's position remains
more pleasant, but Black is doing better than after Karpov's recommendation.})
19. b4 axb4 20. Rxb4 Ra7 21. Rcb1 Re7 22. Nc1 {[%cal Gc1b3,Ga4a5] followed by
Nb3 and a4-a5, with similar play as later in the game.})) 18. Qc5 {Karpov
still does not wish to commit himself.} ({However, this might have been a good
moment to use the a-pawn for weakening Black's queenside:} 18. a5 Nd7 19. a6 b6
20. b4 b5 {Hoping for ...Nb6-c4.} 21. Ng5 h6 22. Nxe6 Qxe6 23. Bf5 Qd6 24. Bxd7
Qxd7 25. Rb3 Rc7 26. Rc3 Rec8 27. Rc5 {[%cal Ge2c3] Threatening Nc3, when the
pawns on b5 and d5 would be under attack.} Ne7 28. Nf4 $1 $14 {[%cal Gh3h4,
Gc1e1,Gf4d3,Gh4h5] /+/- After this square has become available, White has
several pleasant ideas. He can transfer his knight to c5, consolidate his
knight with h4-h5, or else find a good moment to open the centre with Re1 and
e3-e4.}) 18... Qb8 {Karpov analyses several alternatives to this somewhat
passive move.} (18... Qxc5 $6 19. dxc5 Nd7 (19... Nxa4 $4 20. b3 $18) 20. b4 ({
Actually I would prefer} 20. Ned4 Nge5 21. Nxe5 Nxe5 22. Be2 $16 {, placing
the bishop on a better square than in Karpov's line.}) 20... Nge5 21. Nxe5 Nxe5
22. Bc2 $16 {Karpov. Maybe "slight advantage" is a better evaluation.}) (18...
Qc7 $5 19. Qa3 Qd8 {Karpov obviously considered this to be slightly more
flexible than the game continuation.}) (18... Qf8 $5 19. b3 (19. a5 Nd7 20.
Qxa7 $2 Rc7 $1 {/\ Ra8-+}) 19... Rc7 $14) 19. Qa3 {We can understand now that
by Keeping the pawn on b2, Karpov intended to provide the queen with the
highest mobility.} a6 $5 {Kharitonov finally takes measures against the
advance of the a-pawn.} (19... Nc4 20. Qa2 {[%cal Gb2b3] followed by b2-b3}) (
19... Nf8 {may run into} 20. a5 Nbd7 21. a6 b6 22. Nf4 {with similar play as
in a line above.}) 20. Rc3 Qc7 21. Rbc1 Ra8 {Continuing to take measures
against b4-b5.} ({Black cannot organize the exchange of the
light-squaredbishops yet.} 21... Ne7 $6 22. Nf4 $1 Ng6 (22... Bf5 $2 23. a5 $1
$18 Nd7 24. Bxf5 Nxf5 25. Nxd5 {winning an essential pawn.}) 23. Nxe6 $16 fxe6
(23... Rxe6 $2 24. Bf5 $18) 24. Bxg6 hxg6 25. Ne5 $16 {with a crushing
advantage.}) 22. Nd2 {According to Karpov, he played this intending to finally
advance his b-pawn. But I suspect that he would have considered transferring
his knight to c5 before anything.} a5 {Maybe His opponent's reaction inspired
Karpov's comment.} (22... Qd8 {is more flexible.}) 23. Rb1 {Under the changed
circumstances, b2-b3 is the main plan.} Nc8 (23... Ra7 {would not prevent
b2-b4 for long, for instance} 24. Qc5 Rea8 25. Ra3 {In the meantime, the rooks
do not stand well on the a-file.}) 24. b4 $1 axb4 25. Qxb4 Nd6 {Black has
managed to transfer the knight to the dream square, but the circumstances are
not optimal for him. The b-file is open and the pawn on b7 is vulnerable.
Besides, Black has not exchanged the bishops yet.} 26. Nb3 Bc8 {It is hard to
say whether this is solid or passive. Black ensures the b7-pawn is well
defended, but stays a bit passive.} ({Black could free his position a bit with
} 26... Bf5 {at the cost of making b7 more vulnerable.} 27. Bxf5 Nxf5 28. Nc5
Nd6 29. Qb6 ({The similar line like recommended below does not work:} 29. Rcb3
Reb8 30. Qb6 Qe7 {The point is that White cannot play} 31. a5 {because of} Nc4)
29... Re7 (29... Qe7 30. a5 $16 {followed by a5-a6 is very strong.}) 30. Qxc7
Rxc7 31. Rcb3 Ra7 32. f3 $5 $14 {This may be close to equality, but in the
long run, White is not without chances, since Black has to stay passive.}) 27.
a5 {In the later lines with ... Bf5, the pawn's presence on a5 (in other words,
the extra tempo) will be very relevant.} Ne7 {Trying to exchange the bishops
with some delay.} (27... Bf5 {is by far less favorable than a few moves
earlier.} 28. Bxf5 Nxf5 29. Nc5 Nd6 30. Rcb3 Reb8 (30... Rxa5 31. Nxb7 $16) 31.
Qb6 $16 Qe7 $2 32. a6) 28. Ng3 g6 {Black prepares the familiar to us advance
of the h-pawn.} ({Karpov gives the following line, which I have tried to
improve in two moments.} 28... Nef5 29. Nxf5 (29. Nh5 $1 Ne7 30. Ra1 Bf5 31.
Bf1 Ne4 32. Rcc1 Ra7 33. Nf4 {and the knight may be heading for d3-c5 Marin})
29... Bxf5 30. Bxf5 Nxf5 31. Nc5 Nd6 32. Qb6 Qxb6 33. Rxb6 Nc4 (33... Ra7 34.
a6 $16) 34. Rxb7 Nxa5 35. Rc7 Rec8 36. Na6 (36. Rxc8+ Rxc8 37. g4 $5 $16 {
is more convincing. Black will struggle for a long time.}) 36... Kf8 37. Rxc8+
Rxc8 38. Nb4 Rb8 $14 {(Karpov). Actually this is less promising for White than
the similar position in my last line, since Black is more active.}) 29. Rcc1 $1
{Many say that chess thinking has advanced a lot because of computers. I will
not embark a long discussion now, but just mention that Karpov's slightly
mysterious move is the engines' favourite!} ({Their other candidate is} 29. Ra1
h5 30. Rcc1 {, transposing to the game. For Karpov, such regrouping moves were
just natural. The rooks had achieved their aim and now was the time to restore
the natural coordination. The rook gets away from the d6-knight's range, it
over-defends the rook on a1 in order to prepare Nc5 without allowing ...b7-b6
and clear the queen's retreat for emergency cases.}) 29... h5 {Strangely
enough, Karpov criticizes this natural and good move.} ({He analyzes} 29...
Nef5 30. Nxf5 Bxf5 31. Bxf5 Nxf5 32. Nc5 Reb8 $14 {(Karpov) We can continue
the line with} 33. Qb6 Qxb6 34. Rxb6 Rxa5 35. Rxb7 Rxb7 36. Nxb7 $16 {with the
usual unpleasant ending for Black.}) 30. Ra1 h4 31. Nf1 {Planning to attack
the pawn on h4 with Nd2-f3, according to Karpov.} Bf5 32. Be2 Ne4 33. Nc5 Nxc5
$2 {Unnoticed by Karpov, this is a serious mistake.} (33... Ra7 $1 {would have
been the correct answer, preparing ...R8a8.} 34. Nxe4 Bxe4 35. Nd2 Rea8 {
With the pawn hanging, White has to make a decision.} 36. a6 (36. Nb3 Bf5 {
possibly followed by ...Bc8 and .. .Nf5-d6 is passive but solid.}) 36... bxa6
37. Qc5 a5 38. Nxe4 dxe4 39. Qg5 Kg7 40. Qxh4 f5 {White's structure is more
compact, but the a-pawn may become threatening. The position is not clear at
all.}) 34. Qxc5 $16 {The rook regrouping is not possible anymore since the
queen controls a7.} Be6 (34... Nc8 $2 35. Qxd5 $18) 35. Nd2 ({Karpov rejected} 
35. Nh2 {because of} g5 {, but this was just an abstract worry.} 36. Bg4 $1 ({
Karpov only gives} 36. Nf3 g4 {, with certain counterplay, indeed.}) 36... f5 (
36... Bxg4 37. Nxg4 Kg7 38. e4 $18) 37. Bh5 Rf8 38. Nf3 $18) 35... Nf5 ({
In the event of} 35... g5 {Karpov intended to play} 36. Nb3 {.}) 36. Nf3 {
White has achieved an optimal regrouping and Black is vulnerable on both wings.
} Qd8 $6 (36... Kg7 37. a6 bxa6 38. Bxa6 $16) 37. a6 $1 bxa6 38. Rxa6 Rxa6 39.
Bxa6 Qa8 $2 (39... Bd7 40. Bd3 Ng7 41. Ne5 Re6 42. Qa7 Be8 43. Rb1 $18 {Karpov}
) 40. Qxc6 Qxc6 41. Rxc6 Ra8 42. Bd3 Ra1+ 43. Kh2 Ra2 44. Rc2 $1 1-0

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "THE ISOLANI"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/pp3ppp/4p3/8/3P4/8/PP3PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]

{The Isolani is one of the most controversial structures. Is the isolated pawn
weak or strong? Countless games disputed over the decades and centuries
suggest a simple answer: "It depends". Since from a structural point of view,
the Isolani is a weakness. We will start by investigating a few typical
endings where the player with an isolated pawn has a "bad bishop". We will see
that these endings are not that dangerous in the absence of additional
weaknesses. When playing against an Isolani, the most promising situation is
when no minor pieces are left and all major pieces are on board. In the vast
majority of the cases, this ensures a practically decisive advantage. In
complex middlegame positions, with many (or all) pieces on board, the Isolani
provides to its owner (we will refer to him as "White", based on the
exemplifying diagram above) considerable space advantage. There are several
possible favourable situations. 1) Being better developed, White plays d4-d5,
grabbing the initiative. 2) White starts a (possibly sacrificial) kingside
attack, often helped by a knight on e5. 3) If Black manages to install a minor
piece (usually a knight) on d5, but does not have a backup minor piece, the
exchange Nxd5 or Bxd5, forcing ...exd5 would transpose to the Mutual Isolanis
structure, examined separately. White would do that only if his mobilization
were superior. Otherwise, this would lead to equality. 4) Due to the pressure
on d5, Black is forced to play ...Nd5xc3, allowing White to strengthen his
centre with bxc3. This transposes to the Semi-Hanging pawns structure,
examined in a later section. As we will see, White should be heading for such
a structure only if Black could not establish a safe blockade on c4 and d5.
The latent tension is not always resolved in the early middlegame, though. The
most consistent games feature long manoeuvres, without an obvious or immediate
outcome. All the abovementioned situations are worth keeping in mind in those
cases permanently.}  *

[Event "Ivan Parcetic Memorial-04"]
[Site "Sombor"]
[Date "1970.08.14"]
[Round "11"]
[White "Cudina, Ivan"]
[Black "Andersson, Ulf"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "E55"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "102"]
[EventDate "1970.08.03"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "15"]
[EventCountry "YUG"]
[SourceTitle "EXT 1999"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "1998.11.16"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "1998.11.16"]
[SourceQuality "1"]

{When we try to dream of a perfect scenario in the fight against the Isolani,
I feel that most of us would mention the good knight versus bad bishop ending.
Aesthetically, it is hard to think of something more pleasing indeed. From a
practical point of view, things are not one-sided. The player with a good
knight may count on a win only if the player with an Isolani has additional
weaknesses. Even then, things are not easy to handle. Here is a typical
example.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e3 O-O 5. Nf3 d5 6. Bd3 c5 7. O-O
dxc4 8. Bxc4 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Qe7 10. Ne4 Rd8 11. Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. a3 Ba5 13. dxc5
Qxc5 14. Qc2 Qxc2 15. Bxc2 Bd7 16. b4 Bb6 17. Bb2 Rac8 18. Rfc1 Bc6 19. Nd4 Be4
20. Bb3 Bd5 21. Bxd5 Nxd5 {Black does not have ways of intruding, but with his
two next moves White allows him to reach the type mentioned above of ending.}
22. Rxc8 $6 (22. Kf1 $11) 22... Rxc8 23. Rc1 $2 (23. Kf1 $15) 23... Rxc1+ 24.
Bxc1 Bxd4 $1 25. exd4 {Apart from the beautiful central square, Black also has
chances to get control over a4, b5 and/or c4.} Kf8 26. Kf1 {Centralization is
the highest priority.} ({Now and in the next phase, White cannot create a
barrier in the black king's way with} 26. b5 {, since} Nc3 {would win a pawn.})
({Preparing it with} 26. Bd2 {is too time-consuming, practically excluding the
white king from the fight.} Ke7 27. b5 Kd6 28. Kf1 {Black has even two winning
plans now.} e5 {Using Black's advance in development.} ({The static approach
is also possible:} 28... Nc7 29. Bf4+ Kd7 30. a4 {The pawn ending is lost for
White.} Nd5 31. Bd2 Nb6 32. a5 Nd5 33. Ke2 Nc7 34. b6 axb6 35. axb6 Nd5 {
winning the b-pawn soon.}) 29. dxe5+ Kxe5 30. Ke2 Kd4 {The queenside pawns are
doomed.}) 26... Ke7 27. Ke2 Kd6 28. Kd3 Kc6 {Now is the right moment to
highlight an important aspect. Black's winning chances are connected with his
pieces (the king and the knight) having enough light squares to fight for.
This way, they can mutually complete (or complement) their actions. If Black
had only the square on d5, we would see a "competition" between his pieces,
which would stand in each other' way. More about this in the next example.
White faces a tough choice regarding both wings. Should he leave the kingside
pawns on their initial squares, avoiding creating new weaknesses, or advance
them as far as possible? Should he fight against the black king's intrusion to
b5 and e4, or keep his own king in the centre? As far as I understand, there
is no saving combination between the possible plans, but Black's strategy may
vary from one case to another.} 29. g4 $5 {It may seem that the pawns are not
getting anywhere, but this plan is exciting. Sooner or later, the white king
will find a way to advance, while the black one will destroy the queenside.
For this eventuality, having the kingside pawns as close as possible to the
promotion squares is useful.} ({Passive policy on both wings makes things
easiest for Black:} 29. Bd2 Kb5 30. Bc1 Ka4 31. Kc4 ({The counterplay started
with} 31. Ke4 {is too slow.} Kb3 32. Ke5 Kc2 33. Be3 Kb2 34. a4 Ka3 35. a5 Kxb4
36. Bd2+ Kb5 37. Kd6 Kc4 38. Kd7 b5 39. axb6 axb6 40. Ke8 f5 41. Kf7 g6 42. Kg7
Kd3 {We can now feel the term "bad bishop." means. It cannot retreat to e1
because of ...Ke2 and cannot control the b-pawn along the long diagonal
because of the Isolani!} 43. Bc1 b5 44. Kxh7 b4 45. Kxg6 Kc2 46. Bh6 b3 $19 {
and the pawn promotes.}) 31... b6 {Preventing Kc5.} 32. f4 Nc7 33. g4 (33. d5 {
fails to offer counterplay:} Nxd5 34. Kd4 Nc7 35. Ke5 Nb5 {and the king cannot
advance.}) 33... Nb5 34. d5 Nxa3+ 35. Bxa3 exd5+ 36. Kxd5 Kxa3 $19 {wins.}) (
29. Kc4 {is the most natural continuation, of course, since it prevents the
kingțs access to a4.} a6 $5 {Preventing b4-b5.} 30. g4 {Together with the
game plan, the most consistent setup.} (30. a4 {only weakens the pawn on b4.}
b5+ 31. axb5+ axb5+ 32. Kb3 Ne7 33. Kc3 Kd5 {In view of the simultaneous
threats ...Nf5 and ...Nc6, Black wins.} 34. Bg5 (34. g4 {weakens the kingside,
allowing} Ke4 $19) (34. Kd3 Nc6 $19 {wins one of the pawns.}) (34. Be3 Ke4 {
does not change anything:} 35. Kd2 Nf5 36. f3+ Kd5 37. Kd3 Nxe3 38. Kxe3 Kc4
$19) 34... Nf5 35. Be3 Nxe3 (35... Ke4 {also wins.}) 36. fxe3 Ke4 37. Kd2 f5
$19 {with a won pawn ending.}) (30. Bd2 {In this line, we will examine the
case when White maintains his structure intact on both wings.} Ne7 {Clearing
the d5-square for the king.} 31. Bc1 b5+ 32. Kd3 Kd5 33. Bd2 Nf5 34. Bc3 (34.
Be3 {once again leads to a lost pawn ending:} Nxe3 35. fxe3 f5 36. g3 e5 37.
dxe5 Kxe5 38. Kd2 Ke4 39. Ke2 g5 40. h3 g4 $19) 34... h5 {The start of a pawn
attack, resulting into additional weakness on light squares in White's camp.}
35. Bb2 g5 36. Bc3 (36. g3 g4 {yields Black a complete blockade.} 37. Bc3 Nd6
38. Bd2 Nc4 39. Bc1 f6 {Zugzwang!} 40. Kc3 Ke4 $19 {wins.}) 36... Nh4 37. g3
Nf3 38. h3 Ng1 $19 {wins.}) 30... Ne7 31. h4 b5+ 32. Kd3 Kd5 33. h5 f6 $1 {
Black has to be careful.} ({In the event of} 33... Nc8 34. Bf4 Nb6 {Otherwise,
Bc7 would cause problems with the knight's transfer to c4.} 35. Be5 g6 36. hxg6
hxg6 37. g5 Nc4 38. Bg3 Nxa3 39. f4 {It is hard to see how Black can break
White's fortress. If he organizes ...a6-a5, this would most likely allow the
white king's invasion on the kingside.}) 34. Bd2 Nc8 35. Be3 Nb6 36. f3 {
Defending g4 is necessary.} (36. Bd2 Nc4 37. Bc1 {runs into} e5 38. dxe5 Nxe5+
$19 {winning an important pawn.}) 36... Nc4 37. Bc1 h6 {Zugzwang.} 38. f4 (38.
Kc3 {takes the king too far from the kingside.} e5 39. dxe5 Nxe5 $19 {wins the
pawn on f3.}) 38... f5 39. g5 (39. gxf5 exf5 $19 {followed by the knight's
transfer to f6 wins the pawn on h5.}) 39... Nd6 40. Bd2 Ne4 {Black wins a
kingside pawn.} 41. Bc1 (41. Be1 hxg5 $19) (41. gxh6 gxh6 42. Be1 Nf6 $19)
41... Ng3 $19) 29... a6 {In this position, this seems like a half-waiting move,
inviting White to display his cards.} ({The kingside invasion starting with} 
29... Kb5 {allows White to reveal the merits of his plan:} 30. h4 Ka4 $2 (30...
f5 $1 31. f3 Kc6 $1 {more or less transposes to a line below.}) 31. Ke4 Kb3 (
31... f6 32. f4 $11 {undermines the knight soon.}) 32. Ke5 Kc2 33. Bg5 Kb2 34.
f4 Kxa3 35. f5 Kxb4 {Black has won two pawns, but White's counterplay is
strong.} 36. fxe6 fxe6 37. Kxe6 Kc4 38. Kf7 a5 39. Kxg7 a4 40. Bc1 b5 41. g5 b4
42. h5 a3 43. g6 hxg6 44. h6 $1 Kc3 45. Bxa3 (45. h7 a2 46. h8=Q a1=Q $15 {
ofers Black some symbolic chances.}) 45... bxa3 46. h7 a2 47. h8=Q a1=Q 48.
Kxg6 $11 {drawn. In this line, it becomes clear why White used the available
time for advancing his kingside pawns.}) ({The immediate} 29... f5 {would lead
to similar play as in the game.}) 30. h4 {In the light of the following
comment, we should also consider a neutral move.} (30. Bd2 Kb5 {gains a tempo
concerning the drawing line above, since after ...Ka4 the bishop will have to
return to c1.}) ({In the event of} 30. h3 {, Black can make another half
waiting move,} f6 {, when} 31. h4 f5 {transposes to the game.}) 30... f5 $1 {
I assume that Andersson waited with this move until White weakened his
kingside to the maximum. The idea is to create a barrier in front of the white
king, preventing his advance to e5.} 31. gxf5 {This yields White a passed 
(though blocked) pawn in the center, but creates a potentially mobile black
kingside majority. From a practical point of view, creating some dynamic
unbalance is the best chance.} ({The solid} 31. f3 {allows} Kb5 $1 32. Bd2 (32.
gxf5 exf5 33. Bd2 Kc6 $1 {transposes to a similar position as in the game,
with the negative difference for White that the f3-square is not available
anymore.}) (32. h5 h6 $1 $19 {creates potential kingside weaknesses in White's
structure.}) 32... g6 $1 {This move consolidates the knight, making the plan
of the queenside invasion real.} 33. gxf5 (33. Bc1 h5 {does not change much.}
34. g5 {The only move that does not transpose below.} b6 35. f4 a5 $1 {The
last reserve tempo, setting up the Zugzwang.} 36. bxa5 Kxa5 37. Kc2 {The only
way of preventing ...Kb3 in the near future.} Ka4 38. Kb2 b5 39. Bd2 Nb6 40.
Ka2 Nc4 41. Bc1 {Otherwise, the knight gets to g2, winning one of the pawns.}
b4 {The decisive break.} 42. axb4 Kxb4 43. Kb1 Kc3 $19 {wins.}) 33... gxf5 34.
h5 (34. Bc1 h5 {is similar.}) 34... Nf6 35. h6 Nd5 36. Bc1 ({Forced, since} 36.
Bg5 Ka4 37. Bc1 {gives Black a tempo for} Kb3 $19) 36... b6 $1 {The only
winning move, putting White in Zugzwang.} (36... Ka4 37. Kc4 b6 38. f4 $11 {
puts Black in ZUgzwang.} Nf6 39. Bb2 Ng4 40. d5 $1 {with enough counterplay.})
37. f4 (37. Bd2 {once again offers Black the needed tempo.} Ka4 38. Bc1 Kb3 $19
) 37... Kc6 $1 {After f3-f4, Black's plan becomes simpler. He will just grab
the pawn on h6 with the knight and install his king on d5.} 38. Bd2 Nf6) 31...
exf5 32. Bd2 b5 ({I would also mention the following regrouping, which might
have been the quickest way to a win.} 32... Ne7 33. Bg5 Ng6 34. h5 Nf8 35. Bd2
Ne6 36. Kc4 b5+ 37. Kd3 Kd5 {This is one of the optimal situations when both
the knight and the king have perfect squares, not competing with each other.}
38. Be3 h6 39. f3 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8h7,Gh7f6,Gf8d7,Gd7f6]} 40. Bf4 Nd7 {followed
by ...Nf6, winning the pawn on h5.}) 33. Bc1 ({If White speeds up his
counterplay with} 33. Ke2 {, Black can react with} Ne7 34. Kf3 Kd5 35. Be3 ({
Alternatively,} 35. Kf4 h6 36. Bc1 Ng6+ {The pawn exchange favours Black, while
} 37. Kg3 h5 $19 {is just lost, since the white king is very passive.}) 35...
Ke6 36. Bc1 Ng6 37. h5 Ne7 38. Kf4 h6 $19 {and the h5-pawn is doomed.}) 33...
Kd6 (33... Ne7 {was again possible, of course.}) 34. Ke2 Ke6 35. Kf3 {
Andersson's failure to activate both his pieces with, for instance, the
regrouping mentioned above has brought him in a situation where he needs to be
careful in order to win. White threatens Bf4-e5, when suddenly his bishop will
cease looking "bad".} Kf6 $2 {This throws the win away.} (35... h6 $1 {The
fact that Black needed to discover the only winning idea in the last available
moment speaks of his inaccuracy in the previous phase. Such endings should be
won at leisure and not on edge. Let us reveal the idea behind the modest pawn
move.} 36. Bf4 Nf6 37. Be5 Nh5 38. Ke3 {[%cal Gf2f4] If White manages to block
the kingside with f2-f4, the game would be drawn. Now is when the pawn is
useful on h6.} g5 $1 39. hxg5 hxg5 $19 {For instance:} 40. Kd3 Nf6 41. Bb8 Kd5
42. Bc7 Ne4 43. f3 Nd6 44. Bd8 g4 45. fxg4 fxg4 46. Bc7 Nc4 $19 {with an easy
win.}) (35... Nf6 $1 {could transpose after} 36. Bf4 (36. Kf4 h6 {is no
improvement for White.}) 36... h6) 36. Bg5+ (36. Bf4 {is more direct.} g6 37.
Be5+ Ke6 38. Bg7 {Black's kingside pawns are immobile. Black needs to free the
d5-square for the king  (there is a competition now), allowing the white king
to advance.} Nb6 39. Kf4 Nc4 40. Kg5 $11) 36... Kg6 37. Bf4 Kf7 (37... Kh5 {
does not promise much, either.} 38. Be5 g6 39. Kg3 h6 40. f4 $1 $11) 38. Bd2 $2
{Hesitating in a favourable moment.} (38. Be5 $1 $11) 38... Ke6 39. Kg3 h6 {
Finally!} 40. Kf3 Nf6 41. Bf4 Ne4 $2 {We already know this is not the right
trajectory for the knight.} (41... Kd5 $1 42. Be5 Nh5 $19) 42. Be5 g5 43. h5 $1
{This is the point! The knight does not block the h-pawn; now the h6-pawn is a
target.} Nf6 44. Bxf6 $1 Kxf6 45. Ke3 Ke6 {The pawn ending is drawn, but White
makes the fatal mistake now.} 46. f3 $2 (46. Ke2 Kd5 47. Kd3 $11 Ke6 $11 (47...
g4 $2 48. Ke3 Kc4 49. Kf4 $18) (47... f4 48. f3 Ke6 49. Ke4 Kd6 $11)) 46... Kd5
47. Kd3 g4 {It is all over now.} 48. fxg4 fxg4 49. Ke3 g3 50. Kf3 Kxd4 51. Kxg3
Ke3 {I assume that you as surprised as I am by the fact that a win under such
favorable circumstances may be so challenging to achieve. One important point
is that the bishop is a long-range piece and the pawn on d4 alone is not
restricting it much. The time has come to examine the situation when the
Isolani is the only weakness of the player with a supposedly bad bishop.} 0-1

