{[%evp 0,104,19,31,19,-16,-9,-1,1,6,31,15,30,43,43,8,48,58,28,28,22,40,22,37,
39,43,55,42,42,33,33,33,29,29,48,39,39,36,36,30,29,30,40,32,25,10,17,12,12,13,
9,10,17,0,0,0,0,-10,-8,-10,11,2,0,5,5,9,5,13,8,29,15,0,4,16,17,28,16,7,8,8,9,
12,39,37,27,27,16,12,12,5,12,5,56,7,7,6,144,144,41,35,7,0,0,0,0,0,0] The final
part of this famous game is examined in all the important endgame books.} 1. d4
d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Nbd7 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Qc2 c5 8. cxd5 Nxd5
9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qb4+ 13. Qd2 Nc5 14. Bb5 Qxd2+
15. Kxd2 a6 16. Bd3 Be6 17. Rac1 Rfc8 {White's position is very pleasant, of
course. In fact, I am not sure whether I would mind getting something similar
once in, say, three games! Flohr proobably overestimated the knight's strength,
since with his few next moves he went straight to the knight versus bishop
endgame.} 18. Rc2 (18. Bb1 Ne4+ 19. Ke2 $14 {, maintaining a bit of tension,
is worth considering. It could transpose to the same type of ending as in the
next game}) 18... Nxd3 19. Kxd3 Rxc2 20. Kxc2 Kf8 21. Kd2 Rc8 22. Rc1 $6 {
The way I see it, this throws away the last symbolic chance for an advantage.
In such one-sided positions, exchanging one rook is a known method of avoiding
Black's counterplay. The same rule says that the active player should keep the
other rook in order to be able to create threats.} ({The plan of a kingside
expansion is just a bit more promising.} 22. h4 $5 h5 $1 {The sad thing is
that this seems to be playable, even though it places another pawn on a light
square.} (22... Ke7 23. h5 h6 24. Rh4 a5 25. a3 b6 26. f3 $14 {leaves White
room for improvising still}) 23. Ne2 $5 {A more effective way of exchanging
the rooks than in the game.} (23. Ke2 Ke7 24. Kf3 Kd6 25. Kf4 f6 26. f3 Bd7)
23... Ke7 24. Rc1 Rxc1 25. Nxc1 Kd6 26. Kc3 {One important point is that the
white king reaches d4 without the need to play f2-f4.} f6 (26... Ke5 $2 27.
Nd3+ {With the b7-pawn one step forward, the king could advance, but the way
it is it cannot allow Nc5+.} Kd6 28. Nf4 g6 29. Kd4 {Black will soon lose a
pawn due to Zugzwang.}) 27. Kd4 b6 28. Nd3 a5 29. Nf4 Bf7 {Optically, White
has achieved much more than in the game. Concretely, I do not see how to make
progress or put Black in Zugzwang.}) 22... Rxc1 23. Kxc1 {All the endgame
books I know examine the game from this moment.} Ke7 24. Kd2 Kd6 25. Kc3 b6 $1
{The priority is placing the queenside pawns on dark squares.} (25... b5 $4 {
would more or less transpose to the mirrored version of the previous game.})
26. f4 {Otherwise, the king could not advance to d4.} Bd7 27. Nf3 f6 28. Kd4 a5
29. Nd2 Bc8 30. Nb1 Be6 31. Nc3 Kc6 32. a3 h6 ({Iliya Rabinovich explains
White's plan if Black does not undertake anything concrete. I have
"translated" his words to moves, with a few commentaries in between.} 32... Kd6
33. Ne2 {Heading for h4.} Kc6 34. Ng1 Kd6 35. Nf3 Kc6 36. Nh4 Kd6 37. f5 Bd7
38. g4 Be8 ({In fact,} 38... h5 {is also good. Now h2-h3 leaves White with a
weakness on g4,while} 39. gxh5 Bc8 $11 {is also drawn.}) 39. Ng2 Bf7 40. Nf4
Kc6 $2 ({The bishop has to defend h5 and 5, but now is the last moment when
Black can display activity:} 40... g5 $1 41. fxg6 hxg6 42. h4 g5 43. hxg5 fxg5
44. Nh3 Be6 45. Nxg5 Bxg4 $11) (40... g6 $11) 41. Ne6 $1 {Rabinovich is right
when stating that this ending is won.} Bxe6 (41... g6 42. Nd8+ {wins the
bishop, but apart from this casualty, Nf8 also wins..}) 42. fxe6 Kd6 43. e7
Kxe7 44. Kxd5 Kd7 45. b4 $18) 33. g3 h5 34. b4 axb4 35. axb4 Kd6 36. b5 {
Restricting the king's mobility, but creating a target on b5.} g6 $1 {Engines
agree that this is the only way of maintaining absolute equality. Other moves
lose a pawn, but not necessarily the game.} (36... Bg8 37. f5 Bf7 38. h4 Bg8
39. Ne2 $1 {With the bishop far from e8, now is the right moment to transfer
the knight to f4.} Bf7 40. Nf4 Be8 41. Nxd5 Bxb5 42. Nxb6 $14) (36... f5 37.
Na4 Bd7 (37... Kc7 $2 38. Ke5 $18) 38. Nxb6 Bxb5 39. Nxd5 $14 {In both cases,
White's win is problematic because of his imperfect structure, but an extra
pawn and a knight versus a bishop with all the pawns on one wing still yield
some practical chances.}) 37. Na4 Kc7 38. Nc3 Kd6 39. f5 {The last try.} gxf5 {
Again the most convincing.} (39... Bxf5 40. Nxd5 Bd7 41. Nxf6 Bxb5 42. Nd5 Kc6
43. Ne7+ Kd6 44. Nxg6 $14) 40. Ne2 Bd7 41. Nf4 Be8 42. Nxd5 Bxb5 43. Nxb6 Bc6 {
In the next phase, Capablanca will consequently prevent the knight from
reaching f4.} ({However, that would be only a symbolic achievement for White:} 
43... Be8 44. Nd5 Bb5 45. Nf4 Be8 $11) 44. Nc4+ Ke6 45. Nb2 Bb5 46. Nd1 Be2 47.
Nf2 Bf1 48. Nd3 Bxd3 49. Kxd3 Ke5 ({Paradoxically, even} 49... Kf7 {draws.} 50.
Ke2 (50. Kd4 Ke6 $11) 50... Kg6 51. Kf3 Kg5 52. h3 (52. h4+ Kh6 53. Ke2 Kg6 54.
Kd3 f4 $5 {One of the drawing variations, with an elegant end.} 55. exf4 Kf5
56. Ke3 Kg4 57. Kf2 f5 58. Kg2 $11 {Stalemate!}) 52... h4 53. gxh4+ Kxh4 54.
Kf4 Kxh3 55. Kxf5 Kg3 56. Kxf6 Kf3 $11) 50. Ke2 Ke4 51. h3 Kd5 52. Kf3 Ke5 (
52... Ke5 53. h4 Kd5 54. Kf4 Ke6 {and White does not have reserve moves to
create a Zugzwang.}) 1/2-1/2

