{When evaluating the different possible endings and middlegames with the
Isolani blocked and weak, I came to a paradoxical conclusion. I could not find
games where the "good" knight could win against the "bad" bishop if the
passive side does not have additional weaknesses! I also discovered that a
"good bishop" versus "bad bishop" situation is more promising. Abstractly,
this is easy to explain. In the absence of other weaknesses (as those in
Andersson's game), the knight is optimally placed on the blocking square. This
means that other pieces do not have access to it and also that the pressure
along the d-file is not easy to organize. Things are different with a "good
bishop". The d4-square is available to the major pieces or the king, while the
bishop can simply keep the weakness under pressure. We will start by examining
a classical endgame.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. e3 d5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. d4
Nc6 7. Be2 Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 a6 11. Na4 Be7 12. Bb2 Ne4 13.
Rc1 Bf6 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15. Nd4 Ne5 16. Nc5 Qe7 17. Nd3 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Be6 19. Rc2
Rac8 20. Rfc1 Qd7 21. f3 Rxc2 22. Qxc2 Rc8 23. Qxc8+ Qxc8 24. Rxc8+ Bxc8 25.
Kf2 Kf8 26. Ke1 Ke7 27. Kd2 Kd6 {The endgame is only slightly better for White,
but with two minor pieces each, it is easier for White to generate chances and
provoke the opponent's mistakes. As a level of difficulty, it is not far from
a technical middlegame.} 28. b4 {An important move, causing Black problems
with reaching the optimal queenside setup based on ...a6-a5 and ...b7-b6.} Ne8
29. Bd3 g6 {The first questionable move. Black places another pawn on a light
square, weakening the kingside dark squares a bit.} ({With knights on board,
he might have thought that} 29... h6 30. h4 {followed by h4-h5 and Bf5 would
be unpleasant. I can understand that. This detail explains why one should keep
additional material on board until reaching certain progress and only after
that exchange the superfluous pieces.}) ({At this stage,} 29... Bd7 {Black
could ignore the threat on h7 with, say} 30. h4 {, he would sooner or later
choose a way of defending the pawn.} (30. Bxh7 $2 g6 $19)) 30. Kc3 Nc7 {
Another important moment.} ({At first sight, it looks impossible to fight
against the queenside blockade.} 30... b6 31. a4 a5 32. Nb5+ Ke7 (32... Ke5 33.
f4+ Ke6 34. bxa5 bxa5 35. Kd4 $18 {followed by the king's advance wins easily.}
Nf6 36. Kc5 Nd7+ {does not save because after} 37. Kc6 {there is no check on
e5.}) (32... Kc6 33. bxa5 bxa5 34. Na7+ Kc7 35. Nxc8 Kxc8 36. Kd4 Nc7 37. Kc5
$18 {also wins.}) 33. bxa5 bxa5 34. Kd4 {Black seems lost as the white king
threatens to advance.} Nf6 $1 {The only defence.} 35. Bb1 ({In the event of} 
35. Kc5 Nd7+ {theking has to return to d4 in avoidance of double attacks on b6
or e5.}) 35... Bb7 36. Ba2 {Black seems to be getting close to Zugzwang.
However, things are not that simple.} h6 $3 {I assume that this is an
impossible move to find over the board. Its idea is to prepare ...g6-g5
without leaving the pawn vulnerable on h7. Why vulnerable? you may ask. The
pawn is defended and not attacked. The answer will come below. But first let
us show that Black can only move with his pawns.} (36... Kd7 37. Kc5 $18) (
36... Nd7 37. Nc7 Nb6 38. Bxd5 Bc8 39. Bb3 Bd7 40. Nb5 $18) (36... Ba8 37. Nc7
$18) (36... g5 {runs into} 37. Bb1 $3 {The idea is to play Bf5 followed by Kc5.
Unfortunately, ...Nd7 loses the pawn on h7. Now we can get the point behind ...
h7-h6.} Bc8 38. Kc5 Nd7+ 39. Kc6 $18) (36... h5 37. h4 $18 {reaches a
favorable kingside configuration and puts Black in real Zugzwang.}) 37. Bb3 (
37. h4 g5 38. hxg5 hxg5 39. Bb3 Nd7 {is similar to the main line, since Black
will have kingside counterplay.}) 37... g5 $1 (37... Nd7 38. Nc3 ({With the
bishop on b3,} 38. Nc7 Kd6 39. Nxd5 $2 {loses to} Nc5 40. Ba2 Ne6+ 41. Ke4 Nc7
$19) 38... Kd6 (38... Nb6 39. Bxd5 $1) 39. Bxd5 $18) 38. Ba2 (38. Bc2 Nd7 {
allows Black to fight on.}) 38... h5 39. Bb3 h4 40. h3 {Black has exhausted
his pawn moves and needs to move with a piece already.} Nd7 $1 41. Nc3 Nb6 42.
Bxd5 (42. Kc5 Nd7+ 43. Kb5 Kd6 44. Kxa5 Kc5 {threatens ...Ne5-c6 mate, forcing}
45. Nxd5 Bxd5 46. Bxd5 Kxd5 47. Kb5 $11) 42... Nxd5 43. Nxd5+ Ke6 44. Nc3 f5 {
Due to his kingside space advantage, Black has every right to count on a draw.}
) 31. a4 b6 32. a5 $1 bxa5 33. bxa5 {White has made some progress already.} Kc5
34. Nb3+ Kd6 35. Kb4 {For the time being, the king has to content himself with
this square.} (35. Kd4 {runs into} Ne6+) 35... Ne6 36. g3 {This might have
been meant as a half-waiting move, inviting Black to go wrong under the
feeling that he is in Zugzwang.} Nd8 (36... Kc6 {was possible, since after} 37.
Nd4+ Nxd4 38. exd4 Kd6 {, WHite cannot make progress despite his huge "visual"
advantage.}) 37. Nd4 Nc6+ $2 {The decisive mistake. Botvinnik once said that
if you have pawn weaknesses (such as an Isolani) you should keep a knight on
board. Given its ability to jump on squares of both colours, the knight is
suitable for both defending and unblocking such a pawn.} 38. Nxc6 Kxc6 {
In his endgame monograph,, Averbakh considers this position to be drawn still,
but he underestimates White's ideas. It may seem that White's main problem is
transferring the king to d4, but he can overcome it.} 39. f4 $1 {One of the
two good moves.} (39. Kc3 $1 {is a worthy alternative.} Kc5 40. h4 {Preparing
to block the kingside on light squares.} h6 (40... f6 41. g4 Bb7 42. g5 f5 43.
f4 Bc8 44. Be2 Bb7 45. h5 Bc8 46. h6 Bb7 47. Bh5 $1 {and the h-pawn promotes
soon.}) 41. f4 h5 (41... Bb7 {allows WHite to continue his expansion.} 42. g4
Bc8 43. g5 hxg5 44. fxg5 $1 {The key move.} Bb7 45. Bf1 Bc8 46. Be2 {Zugzwang.
The king cannot retreat and the bishop has to move further from the f7-pawn.}
Bb7 47. h5 gxh5 48. Bxh5 $18) 42. f5 $1 Bxf5 (42... gxf5 43. Be2 $18 {wins the
pawn on h5.}) 43. Bxa6 $18) 39... f5 {Averbakh considers this the decisive
mistake. Matanovic hoped to block the position and reach a fortress.} ({
Averbakh recommends} 39... h6 {and analyses two lines to prove that Black can
defend.} 40. e4 (40. Be2 f6 {Averbakh}) (40. h4 Kd6 41. g4 Bxg4 42. Bxa6 f6 43.
Bb7 g5 44. a6 Kc7 45. Bxd5 Kb6 46. hxg5 hxg5 47. fxg5 fxg5 48. Bc4 Bc8 $11 {
Averbakh}) (40. Kc3 $1 Kc5 41. h4 {transposes above}) 40... dxe4 41. Bxe4+ Kd6
42. Kc3 $3 {Overlooked by Averbakh.} (42. Kc4 {allows} Bg4 43. Kd4 Be2 44. h4
Bg4 45. Bd3 Bc8 46. g4 Bxg4 47. Bxa6 f6 $11 {Averbakh}) 42... Kc5 43. Bd3 Bb7
44. h3 Bg2 (44... Bc8 45. h4 h5 46. Bc4 f6 47. Bd3 f5 48. Bc4 $18 {followed by
Bf7.}) 45. h4 Bb7 46. g4 Kd5 47. g5 hxg5 (47... h5 48. Bc4+ Ke4 49. Bxf7 Kxf4
50. Bxg6 Kg4 51. Bd3 Kxh4 52. g6 $18 {promotes the pawn.}) 48. Bc4+ $1 Ke4 49.
fxg5 Kf4 50. Kd4 Kg4 51. Ke5 Kxh4 52. Kf6 $18 {followed by Bxf7 and winning
either the f7 or the a6-pawn afterward.}) (39... Bb7 40. g4 {is simple.}) (
39... f6 40. h4 Bb7 41. g4 {leads to a familiar scenario.}) 40. h4 $1 {In the
old times, there was an unwritten rule among Soviet players: "Do not force
matters before adjourning the game!" In this case, Averbakh feels that
delaying concrete action may spoil the win, so he made his committal move
right before the control. White needs to create a kingside target and now is
the moment to achieve that.} Kd6 ({The poihnt is that} 40... h5 {runs into} 41.
Bc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2a4,Ga4e8] (Averbakh). It is the only winning move. Had Black
got a tempo for '''Kd6 earlier, the game would have ended in a draw.}) 41. h5 {
What else?} gxh5 (41... Kc6 42. h6 Kd6 43. Kc3 Kc5 44. Be2 Bb7 45. g4 fxg4 (
45... Bc8 46. g5 Bb7 47. Bh5 {leads to a familiar scenario.}) 46. Bxg4 Kb5 47.
f5 $18 {Averbakh}) 42. Kc3 $1 {Home analysis convinced Matanovic that further
resistance is useless.} (42. Kc3 Kc5 43. Bf1 Bb7 44. Be2 Bc8 45. Bd3 {Zugzwang.
} d4+ {A desperate try.} (45... Kc6 46. Kd4 Kd6 47. Be2 Bb7 48. Bf1 Bc8 49. Bd3
h6 50. Be2 Bb7 51. Bf1 Bc8 52. Bd3 $18 {wins by using a series of Zugzwang
setups. - Marin}) 46. exd4+ Kd5 47. Bc4+ Kd6 (47... Ke4 48. d5 $18 Kf3 49. d6
Kxg3 50. Bxa6 Bd7 51. Bb7 $18) 48. d5 Kc5 49. d6 $1 {White needs the d4-square
for the king.} Kxd6 50. Kd4 {Finally!} Bb7 51. Bf1 Bc8 52. Bd3 $18 {Averbakh})
1-0

