{[%evp 0,83,19,29,27,-5,1,-26,-21,-20,-7,-4,-2,-3,-12,-5,29,9,7,7,0,10,12,11,
11,23,37,32,37,28,36,48,53,50,68,50,67,59,72,53,70,73,63,64,55,53,55,53,53,53,
58,48,51,60,57,54,58,49,43,47,74,53,95,54,59,82,69,78,123,172,132,133,253,252,
311,257,311,195,429,414,652,602,855,884,1251,1327] In the middlegame, too, a
good versus a bad bishop is a promising situation when playing against an
Isolani. Here is a classical example, perfectly illustrating the typical ideas.
} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. b3 Nf6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8.
Nxd5 exd5 9. d4 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Bf6 11. Qd2 Nc6 12. Be2 Be6 13. O-O Bxb2 14. Qxb2
Qa5 15. Rfd1 Rad8 16. Rd2 Rd7 17. Rad1 Rfd8 18. h3 h6 {Both sides are well
regrouped, but the excellent control over d4 makes it clear that only White
can fight for an advantage.} 19. Ne5 $1 {As mentioned in the previous game's
comments, a knight's presence helps the player with an Isolani. This is the
most active way to provoke the knights' exchange.} (19. Nd4 Nxd4 20. Qxd4 {
would also be good, but as we will see, the queen stands better on e5.}) 19...
Nxe5 {Maintaining the tension does not help Black.} (19... Re7 {allows White
to transpose to a favourable version of a different typical structure, the
semi-hanging pawns.} 20. Nxc6 (20. Nd3 {is less effective than in the line
below, since the rook on d8 is well defended and so is the bishop on e6.} d4 $1
21. Nf4 dxe3 22. Rxd8+ Nxd8 23. fxe3 Nc6 $11) 20... bxc6 21. Rc2 Rc7 (21... c5
{loses the pawn to} 22. Rdc1 Rc7 23. b4 $18) 22. b4 $16 {with a fantastic
blockade. Compare with Rubinstein-Salwe.}) (19... Rc7 {needs to be answered
differently.} 20. Nd3 {[%cal Gd3f4,Ge2f3] Planning to increase the pressure on
d5 with Nf4 and Bf3} ({With the rook on c7, Black is better prepared for the
structure arising after} 20. Nxc6 bxc6) 20... d4 21. Nf4 $16 {The rook on d8
is hanging and the threat of Nxe6, spoiling Black's structure, is annoying.})
20. Qxe5 Qc5 21. Bf3 {All White's pieces attack on d5 and due to the pin along
the fifth rank, White threatens e3-e4, winning a pawn.} b6 {Defending the
queen.} 22. Qb2 {Just a move repetition before switching to the main plan.} Rc8
23. Qe5 {Botvinnik writes: "White's advantage is obvious, but he did not find
the correct, slightly paradoxical plan immediately."} Rcd8 24. Rd4 a5 25. g4 $1
{This simple attacking move is justified by the fact that Black's pieces are
tied up to the defence of the isolated pawn. It is as if the board would be
cut into two halves.} Qc6 {The queen on e5 can be neither attacked nor
exchanged.} (25... Qd6 26. Qxd6 Rxd6 {loses a pawn to} 27. e4 {. We should
remember this issue. An isolated pawn faces the risk of perishing due to the
pin along the d-file in the presence of major pieces and with few or no light
pieces left.}) (25... Rd6 26. e4 f6 {is no improvement:} 27. Qf4 Bf7 28. exd5
$16 Bxd5 $2 29. Qf5 $18 {wins at least an exchange.}) 26. g5 {Botvinnik does
not comment on this move, probably considering it natural. I would praise him
for his deep understanding. Strictly speaking, White spoils his structure, but
the important thing is that he opens the g-file for the attack, eventually
forcing Black to create new weaknesses.} ({Botvinnik probably refrained from
the seemingly more constructive} 26. h4 {, because Black's last move had
prepared} f6 {. However,} 27. Qg3 {folowed by g4-g5 still yields White a large
advantage.}) 26... hxg5 (26... Bxh3 {runs into} 27. Rh4 Qe6 28. Qg3 Bf5 29.
gxh6 Qg6 30. Qxg6 Bxg6 31. hxg7 Kxg7 32. Rhd4 $16 {winning the pawn on d5 soon.
}) 27. Qxg5 {White has a series of serious threats, such as Rh4 followed by
Qh5 or Kh1 followed by Rg1.} f6 {The first consequence of WHite's brutal
attack. Black weakens his kingside a bit. However, this is only a partial
success since the kingside pawns are on dark squares, going in harmony with
the bishop.} ({Both players must have discarded this because of} 27... Bxh3 28.
Rh4 {but Black can try to fight with} Rd6 $5 (28... Be6 $2 29. Qh5 f6 30. Qh8+
Kf7 31. Bh5+ g6 32. Bxg6+ $1 $18 {mates soon.}) 29. Kh2 $1 {is the correct
answer, for reasons explained in the following lines.} (29. Kh1 {is
ineffective due to} Bc8 {or 29...Be6.}) (29. Be4 $5 $14 {is interesting but
not decisive.} f5 $1 (29... dxe4 $2 {leads to mate after} 30. Qxd8+ $1 Rxd8 31.
Rxd8+) 30. Bxf5 Bxf5 31. Qxf5 Rg6+ 32. Kf1 $14 {WHite stands a bit better, but
the situation is not entirely clear.}) 29... Be6 (29... Bc8 {does not help now,
since White has} 30. Rh1 $18 {followed by Kg2 with a decisive attack along the
h-file.}) 30. e4 (30. Rh1 {is less convincing with the bishop on e6, since
Black can defend with} f6) (30. Rg1 $5 {is interesting, though.}) 30... Qc7 (
30... dxe4 31. Qxd8+ {leads to a familiar mate.}) 31. e5 $1 {With the bishop
on c8, Black could answer ...Rg6, but here he is just helpless against White's
attack.}) 28. Qg6 Bf7 29. Qg3 f5 {THis immediately puts Black in a
strategically lost position. We can recognize the "bad bishop" pattern already.
On the other hand, Black faced a series of dangers, inducing him to play his
last move.} (29... Qd6 30. e4 $16) (29... g6 30. h4 $16) (29... Be6 30. h4 $16
{with a promising attack.}) 30. Qg5 Qe6 31. Kh1 Qe5 32. Rg1 Rf8 33. Qh6 {
White's pieces feel at ease on dark squares.} Rb8 34. Rh4 Kf8 35. Qh8+ Bg8 36.
Rf4 Rbb7 37. Rg5 {With a perfect blockade and... winning a pawn soon.} Rf7 38.
Qh5 Qa1+ 39. Kg2 g6 40. Qxg6 Bh7 41. Qd6+ Rfe7 42. Qd8+ 1-0

