{[%evp 0,86,40,-12,4,4,-5,-5,18,5,24,40,31,-2,18,-4,19,17,25,25,21,21,21,9,58,
49,49,31,44,25,38,16,27,5,-7,-6,-13,-15,-8,-28,-4,-14,-25,-29,-16,-52,-4,-40,
-51,-54,-52,-45,-42,-58,-46,-44,-44,-72,-67,-93,-76,-72,-55,-54,-64,-95,-59,
-101,-72,-78,-77,-172,-160,-125,-125,-309,-367,-367,-296,-446,-572,-579,-581,
-594,-576,-586,-588,-586,-581] This famous classical game reveals a few
important aspects of the fight against the Isolani. 1) The more minor pieces
are exchanged, the weaker the isolated pawn becomes. 2) For the player with an
Isolani, what could seem to be a "good" bishop, is by far less useful than the
"bad" one (as in the games examined above). 3) The most favourable situation
when fighting against the Isolani consists of the presence of all major pieces
and no minor pieces.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4
O-O 7. Rc1 dxc4 8. e3 c5 9. Bxc4 cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6 11. O-O Nh5 $1 {Karpov
takes advantage of the concrete circumstances. Had Black played ...h7-h6 with
the Isolani on board already, White would have retreated with his bishop to f4
or e3, in order to create the potential threat Bxh6 and avoid minor piece
exchanges. The way this game developed in the opening, White did not have this
possibility. The last move provokes the exchange of White's dark-squared
bishop.} 12. Bxe7 (12. Bg3 Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bf6 $11) 12... Nxe7 13. Bb3 ({If
Kortschnoj anticipated the danger. He might have chosen the modest.} 13. d5 $1
$11 exd5 14. Bxd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 {White's initiative is temporary.} Nf6 $5 $11)
13... Nf6 14. Ne5 Bd7 15. Qe2 Rc8 16. Ne4 $6 {Continuing to exchange minor
pieces in the illusory hope of getting attacking chances.} Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bc6
18. Nxc6 $6 {Another exchange that helps Black.} Rxc6 19. Rc3 ({Kortschnoj
might have noticed i the last moment that} 19. Rxc6 {runs into} bxc6 $1 $15 {
Maintain control over d5.} (19... Nxc6 20. d5 $14)) 19... Qd6 20. g3 Rd8 21.
Rd1 Rb6 $1 {After completing the development, Black keeps the rook safe from
any exchange. The b6-square is only transitory, of course.} 22. Qe1 Qd7 23.
Rcd3 Rd6 24. Qe4 Qc6 25. Qf4 Nd5 26. Qd2 {We have reached a typical position
with a knight versus a presumably "good" bishop. In fact, such a bishop is
almost useless, since it can neither defend the weak pawn (as the "bad" bishop
would do), nor fight against the blockade.} Qb6 27. Bxd5 {An obvious
concession as Black will have more freedom in organizing the siege of the
d-pawn..} ({Karpov recommends} 27. a3 {This does not save the pawn, but White
might have better chances to hold the position with minor pieces on board.} Ne7
{In the following lines, we can notice the knight's versatility and the
relative bishop's passiveness.} 28. Ba2 (28. Kg2 Nc6 29. d5 Ne7 (29... Ne5 30.
Re3 Ng4 31. Rf3 Nf6 32. Qf4 exd5 33. Rd4 {offers White some activity for the
pawn.}) 30. Qe2 Nxd5 31. Bxd5 exd5 $17 {Blacvk has won a pawn since} 32. Rxd5
$2 {loses to} Qc6 $19) 28... Nc6 29. d5 Ne5 $1 (29... Ne7 {allows White to
equalize completely.} 30. Qe2 Nxd5 31. Bxd5 exd5 32. Rxd5 $1 Rxd5 33. Rxd5 Rxd5
34. Qe8+ Kh7 35. Qe4+ $11 {with a probable draw.}) 30. Re3 Ng4 31. Rd3 Nf6 {
followed by ...Nxd5. True, the converting process might be difficult.}) 27...
Rxd5 {[%cal Ge6e5] We have reached the typical position with major pieces only,
which should be the dream of any player fighting against the Isolani. Suddenly,
White faces the familiar threat ...e6-e5.} 28. Rb3 (28. f4 Qd6 29. Kg2 Qd7 30.
Kg1 f6 $17 {renews the threat ...e6-e5.}) 28... Qc6 29. Qc3 Qd7 30. f4 {
White cannot do without this move, which seriously weakens the king.} b6 $5 ({
Very typical for Karpov. He tries avoiding any shadow of white counterplay. Of
course,} 30... f6 {would have won the pawn soon, but he prefers refraining
from such weakening moves.}) 31. Rb4 b5 $5 32. a4 (32. Qd2 a5 33. Rb3 b4 34.
Rd3 f6 $17) 32... bxa4 33. Qa3 a5 34. Rxa4 Qb5 35. Rd2 {In his desperate
attempts to create some chances for counterplay, White has spoiled his
coordination, allowing a decisive blow.} e5 $1 {It appears that Black does not
need to play ...f7-f6. Nor to win the pawn. Karpov's last move weakens the
white king's defence, while keeping his own king absolutely safe.} (35... f6
36. Rf2 Qb6 37. Rc4 Rxd4 38. Qc5 $17) 36. fxe5 Rxe5 37. Qa1 Qe8 $1 $19 {
A nice regrouping move.} 38. dxe5 Rxd2 39. Rxa5 Qc6 40. Ra8+ Kh7 41. Qb1+ g6
42. Qf1 Qc5+ 43. Kh1 Qd5+ 0-1

