{[%evp 0,49,27,27,27,6,6,6,28,28,31,11,19,19,21,27,27,14,16,-15,31,25,39,34,34,
33,63,27,17,17,9,9,26,24,30,30,22,19,36,36,36,36,37,0,32,23,605,627,633,633,
628,636] Everything is relative in chess. Starting with ...Nh5, the previous
game was so convincing that we could think that the Isolani with a bishop on
h4 is always in danger. One single tempo can change the evaluation, though.
Here is an almost twin example.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 O-O 5.
Bg5 c5 6. e3 cxd4 7. exd4 h6 8. Bh4 d5 9. Rc1 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nc6 11. O-O Be7 12.
Re1 {Due to the fact that Black's bishop needed two tempi for reaching e7,
White has an extra tempo, which he spent on Re1.} b6 {This time, Karpov
switches to slow development.} ({Why did he not play in the same way as
against Kortschnoj? The point is that the extra tempo can make a difference:} 
12... Nh5 13. Bxe7 Nxe7 14. d5 exd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Be6 ({With the rook
on e1,} 16... Nf6 {runs into} 17. Ne7+ Kh8 18. Qb3 {and Black has serious
problems with completing his development.}) 17. Nc7 Qxd1 18. Rcxd1 Rac8 19.
Nxe6 fxe6 20. Rxe6 Rc2 21. Rb1 Nf4 22. Re3 $14 {It is hard to evaluate how big
White's chances are, but Black is struggling a bit, for sure.}) 13. a3 Bb7 14.
Bg3 $6 {A bit passive.} ({White should have started regrouping for the attack.
One possible continuation is} 14. Qd3 Rc8 15. Ba2 Nh5 16. Bg3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 Bf6
18. Bb1 g6 19. Rxe6 Bg7 $14) 14... Rc8 15. Ba2 Bd6 16. d5 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Bxg3
18. hxg3 exd5 19. Bxd5 Qf6 20. Qa4 Rfd8 21. Rcd1 {White has only an optical
advantage and the game should end in a draw, but Karpov soon blundered.} Rd7 (
21... Rc7 22. Qg4 g6 $11 {[%cal Gg8g7] followed by ...Kg7}) 22. Qg4 Rcd8 $4 (
22... Rd6 $11) (22... Rdd8 $11) 23. Qxd7 $1 Rxd7 24. Re8+ Kh7 25. Be4+ 1-0

