{[%evp 0,60,26,-16,25,30,18,19,16,16,23,16,16,21,38,34,34,28,38,42,42,20,24,14,
14,10,10,10,24,15,50,18,46,48,51,39,29,29,27,-6,-6,0,0,3,-7,-7,-2,-3,-3,-3,0,0,
9,6,11,11,17,14,21,19,19,10,10] Time has come to look at the Isolani positions
from the opposite perspective. We are aware now of the potential weakness of
the Isolani, but now we will ilustrate its possible strength. In fact, the
last game marked a transition between the two opposite angles. We will
maintain the connection with the previous section by examining another game in
which Black lost a tempo with his king's bishop.} 1. c4 c6 2. e4 d5 3. exd5
cxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nf3 Bb4 7. Bd3 dxc4 8. Bxc4 O-O 9. O-O Nc6 {
In my opinion, a risky setup.} ({More common (and solid) are} 9... b6) ({and} 
9... Nbd7 {, both usually followed by ...Bxc3.}) 10. Bg5 Be7 11. a3 {An
important move in such positions. White prevents Black from consolidating his
blockade on d5 with ...Nb4-d5 and allows the bishop's safe retreat to a2, far
from the c6-knight's range.} b6 12. Qd3 {A good square for the queen, since in
the long run White could play Ba2-b1, threatening something similar to mate.}
Bb7 13. Rad1 Rc8 14. Rfe1 {As mentioned earlier, this is the right way of
placing the rooks if White plays for a win. There is nothing to do on the
c-file. White would play Rc1 only if wishing to exchange rooks and absolve
himself of technical problems, because otherwise this would lower his
attacking potential. The rook on d1 sustains the central break d4-d5 (any
unblocked pawn has the natural tendency to advance, as Nimzowitsch wrote),
while that on e1 contributes to tactical ideas around e6.} Re8 {a good
half-waiting move.} ({The standard simplifying move} 14... Nd5 {is not
sufficient for equality.} 15. Bxd5 $1 (15. Bxe7 {would allow Black consolidate
with} Ncxe7 $1) 15... Bxg5 (15... exd5 {is somewhat safer, but leaves Black in
a passive position after, say,} 16. Qf5 $14 {Pinter,J (2540)-Olafsson,H (2515)/
Copenhagen 1985/MCD (½-½, 34) This structure will be examined separately.})
16. Be4 {The white bishop has been activated radically, keeping two important
diagonals under observation and winning an essential tempo for the development
of the initiative. At the same time, the g5-bishop is somewhat hanging.}) 15.
Bb3 $5 $146 {The theoretical reason for preferring this move to 15.Ba2 is that
the bishop has more squares available, although on a2 it looks less vulnerable.
Sometimes, the intermediate Ba4 would change quite a lot in the dynamic
balance of the position.} g6 $5 {Another prophylactic move.} ({The concrete
idea behind my last move is revealed after} 15... Na5 16. Ba4 $1 Bc6 17. Bc2 g6
18. Ne5 $14 {[%csl Rc6] when the bishop on c6 is exposed.}) (15... h6 {is not
to be recommended, because it weakens the kingside.} 16. Bh4 $5 $14 ({The
standard answer is} 16. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Rh6] ><h6}) {White's superior
development makes the generally desirable} 16... Nh5 $6 {impossible because of}
17. d5 $1 $16 Bxh4 (17... exd5 18. Bxd5 Bxh4 19. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 20. Qc4+ $16)
18. dxe6 $1 fxe6 19. Qf5 $1 $16) 16. h4 $1 {In my initial analysis after the
game, I considered that this was the moment when I let my advantage slip away.
Modern engines think differently, considering my last move the best. Before
continuing concrete analysis we should evaluate the position in general. Black
is solid and has normal development, but his coordination is poor. The knights
stand in the bishops' way and the queen does not have a safe square except for
the initial one. On top, d4-d5 is a permanent threat. The last move over
defends the bishop for the eventuality. Black moves with his knight on f6 and
also prepares h4-h5 under certain circumstances. Because he wasted a tempo
with his bishop, Black does not have a way of freeing himself.} ({After the
game, I thought that} 16. Qe3 $1 {would be stronger. It is a good move,
maintaining White's advantage, but not necessarily better than my move.} Na5 ({
Maybe} 16... Nd5 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Qf4 $14 {is safer, but not really appealing
for Black.}) 17. Bxe6 $1 fxe6 (17... Bd6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Bxc8 Rxe3 20. Rxe3
Bxc8 21. Re8+ Kg7 22. Rxc8 $16) (17... Bf8 18. Qf4 $18) 18. Qxe6+ Kg7 19. Ne5
$40 Ng8 (19... Rf8 20. Nd7 $1 {Marin 2007}) 20. Qf7+ Kh8 21. Bxe7 Rxe7 22. Rd3
{[%cal Ge5g6]} Rxf7 23. Nxf7+ Kg7 24. Nxd8 Rxd8 25. d5 $14 {White has a rook
and two pawns for two minor pieces and the better coordination.}) ({But the
funny thing is that the position is ripe for two different combinations
already.} 16. Rxe6 $1 {is one of them.} fxe6 (16... Na5 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Rxe8+
Qxe8 19. Ba2 Bxf3 20. Qxf3 $16 Bxd4 $6 {White would have an extra pawn in the
endgame after taking twice on f7, but even stronger is} 21. Ne4 $18 {followed
by Ng5.}) 17. Bxe6+ Kg7 18. d5 Nb8 19. Ne5 Ng8 20. Bf4 Rf8 21. Qe3 $16 {
[%cal Gd5d6,Ge5c6,Ge6c8] White is a rook down, but has huge pressure. His main
threats are Bxc8, d5-d6 and Nc6.}) (16. Bxe6 $1 {is simpler from practical
point oif view, since it sacrifices less material, achieving similar results.}
fxe6 17. Rxe6 {[%cal Gd4d5] Threatening d4-d5-d6.} Nd5 18. Rxg6+ $5 (18. Rde1 {
is also strong. Black succumbs under the pressure.} Nxc3 19. Rxg6+ $1 hxg6 20.
Qxg6+ Kh8 21. Re6 $18) 18... hxg6 19. Qxg6+ Kh8 20. Qh5+ Kg8 21. Bh6 Bf8 22.
Ng5 {Despite his seeming good development, Black does not have adequate ways
of defending.} Re7 (22... Rc7 23. Nxd5 Qxd5 24. Qxe8 $18) 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. Bxf8
Qxf8 25. Nxd5 {White will most likely retrieve an exchange, leaving him with
four pawns for a minor piece and a continuing attack. Black cannot afford to
move with the rook.} Rd7 (25... Rg7 26. Qh6+ Kg8 27. Nf6+ $18 {wins the queen.}
) 26. Rd3 $18) 16... Na5 {The only way Black can try to breathe a bit.} 17. Ba4
$6 {This "consequent" move throws a part of White's considerable (maybe
decisive) advantage away.} ({Even though} 17. Ba2 {It looks like a loss of
time, it maintains White's huge pressure. The main threat is b2-b4, when all
the previous ideas and threats would be valid again.} Nd5 18. Ne4 {[%cal Gb2b4]
Renewing the threat b2-b4 and allowing other ideas, such as h4-h5.} Nf6 {
There is not much that Black can do.} 19. d5 $1 {Finally the dreaded central
break.} Nxe4 (19... Nxd5 20. b4 Nc6 21. Qb1 $1 {Preparing Qb2 followed by Bxd5
and a decisive attack on dark squares.} Nb8 22. Qb2 Nd7 23. Nd6 $1 $18) 20.
Bxe7 Rxe7 21. Qxe4 {With crushing pressure.} Rec7 22. dxe6 $1 Bxe4 23. Rxd8+
Rxd8 24. exf7+ Kf8 25. Rxe4 Re7 26. Rf4 {Threatening Ng5.} h6 27. h5 $5 gxh5 (
27... g5 28. Rf6 $18) 28. Nd4 $18) 17... Bc6 18. Bxc6 (18. Bc2 $6 Nc4 $1 $15)
18... Nxc6 19. d5 {After this move, the position will simplify quickly and
White's advantage will be more symbolic.} ({I spent a long time investigating
the consequences of} 19. Ne5 Nd5 (19... Nxe5 20. dxe5 $14 {[%csl Rf6]}) 20. Qf3
{My conclusion that White has absolutely nothing seems to be correct.} f6 $5 (
20... Nxe5 21. dxe5 Bxg5 22. hxg5 Qxg5 23. Ne4 Qe7 24. Nd6 $16) 21. Ng4 $1 {
This move did not come to my mind.} ({I only analyzed} 21. Nxg6 $5 hxg6 22.
Rxe6 Nxc3 23. bxc3 Qd7 24. Qd3 {In avoidance of R1e1, with very strong
pressure, Black should play} Qxe6 $11 {forcing White to deliver a perpetual.})
21... fxg5 ({In the event of} 21... Nxc3 {White has a choice between bxc3,
transposi9ng to the main line and} 22. Nxf6+ $5 Bxf6 23. Bxf6 Rf8 24. Bxd8 Rxf3
25. bxc3 Rxc3 26. Bg5 Kf7 27. d5 exd5 28. Rxd5 Rc7 29. Rd6 $16 {with strong
initiative in the endgame.} Rxa3 $2 30. h5 gxh5 31. Rf6+ Kg7 32. Ree6 Nd4 33.
Bh6+ Kg8 34. Re8#) 22. Rxe6 Nxc3 23. bxc3 Rf8 24. Qe2 Bd6 (24... Bf6 25. d5 $16
Nb8 26. d6) 25. hxg5 $14) 19... Nxd5 20. Nxd5 exd5 (20... Qxd5 21. Qa6 Qf5 22.
Qb7 $44 {Sergeev}) 21. Qxd5 Qxd5 (21... Bxg5 22. Rxe8+ Qxe8 23. Qxg5 $14) 22.
Rxd5 Bxg5 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. hxg5 Kg7 (24... Kf8 $5) 25. Kf1 Re7 26. b4 {פc6}
Rc7 27. Rd6 h6 $1 $11 (27... Ne7 28. Ne5 Nf5 29. Rc6 Re7 30. Ng4 (30. f4 Ng3+
31. Kf2 Ne4+ 32. Ke3 Nxg5) 30... Nd4 31. Rc8 Ne6 32. f4 Rc7 $1 $11 (32... Nxf4
$4 33. Nf6 $18) (32... Rd7 33. Nf6 Rd8 34. Rxd8 Nxd8 35. Ke2 $14) 33. Rxc7 Nxc7
34. Ke2 $2 Nb5 $1) 28. gxh6+ Kxh6 29. g4 Kg7 30. Ke2 Kf8 {Despite its peaceful
result, I have selected this game because the analysis reveals plenty of
attacking ideas, being almost an attacking manual in the positions with an
Isolani. It also gives us a fair warning that when having an Isolani, you can
rarely win by moving the pieces around. You must find the right moment for
decisive action and go for it!} 1/2-1/2

