{In the previous game, the focus was on sacrifices in the immediate king's
neighborhood, but the central break d4-d5 was also a recurring theme.
Unblocked pawns have the natural tendency to advance, said Nimzovitsch. The
isolated pawns are among the most typical cases.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 Nf6
4. d4 cxd4 5. exd4 d5 6. Nc3 e6 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bd3 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Nf6
11. a3 b6 12. Bc2 Bb7 13. Qd3 g6 {This move, allowing White to develop his
bishop on the best square without waste of time, is more or less forced.} ({
The point is that} 13... Rc8 {runs into} 14. d5 $1 {The first moment when this
pawn break comes to light.} exd5 {Forced, since the knight has to defend h7.}
15. Bg5 $1 Ne4 {Again forced.} (15... g6 $2 16. Rxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxd5 $18 {wins})
16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Qxe4 g6 18. Qh4 $18 {with a decisive advance in development
and initiative.}) 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Rad1 Qc7 $6 {Dieter tries to get out of the
"Isolani pattern shell" and treat the position according to general rules.
This used to be part of Kortschnoj's strength (I refer to several typical
structures), but the experiment is unjustified in this case. Black intends to
complete his development harmoniously with ...Rad8. The harmony is only
optical, though, since the rook's presence on d8 will not cross White's plans.}
({The main line goes} 15... Rc8 16. Bb3 Na5 17. Ba2 Nd5 18. Ne4 $14) 16. Bb3
Rad8 {The consequent continuation. Black should not fight against the bishop
on h6:} (16... Ng4 $2 17. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 (17... Nxh6 18. Rxg6+ $1 $18) 18. Bxe6+
Kh8 19. Bxg4 $18 {with two pawns for the exchange and a dominating position.})
(16... Na5 17. Ba2 Ng4 18. Rxe6 $1 Kh8 (18... fxe6 19. Bxe6+ Kh8 20. Bxg4 $18)
19. Rxe7 Rxe7 20. d5 $1 {Threatening both d5-d6 and Qd4+.} Qc5 (20... Nxh6 21.
d6 Qd7 22. dxe7 Qxe7 23. Qd4+ f6 24. Nd5 $18) 21. Qd2 Nc4 22. Bxc4 Qxc4 23. Bf4
Rae8 24. h3 Nf6 25. Bg5 Kg7 26. Bxf6+ Kxf6 27. b3 $1 $18 {followed by either
Qd4+ or Qb2.}) 17. d5 $5 {A strong and tempting move, but as we will see later,
maybe not the very strongest.} Ng4 $2 {Typical for Dieter. Instead of trying
to defend in a symmetrical position, he adds tension to the fight. But despite
his seemingly p[erfect development, Black is not prepared for that.} (17... Na5
$2 {runs into} 18. Nb5 $1 {Defending the bishop with a gain of time.} (18. dxe6
$2 {is premature due to} Nxb3) 18... Qb8 19. dxe6 $1 Nxb3 {This White a
decisive attack, requiring some accuracy, though.} (19... Rxd3 {is no
improvement, though.} 20. exf7+ Kh8 21. fxe8=Q+ Qxe8 22. Rxd3 Qxb5 23. Rxe7 $18
) 20. exf7+ Kxf7 21. Qxb3+ Bd5 22. Rxd5 Nxd5 23. Rd1 Qb7 24. Nc3 Ke6 {White
has a pawn for the exchange and the pin is impossible to remove.} 25. h4 $1 {
One of the winning moves, removing any back rank problem and taking g5 under
control.} Bf6 26. Ng5+ Bxg5 27. Bxg5 Rd7 28. Nxd5 Rxd5 29. Re1+ Kd7 30. Qa4+ {
With the pawn on h2, Black could simply cover the check with the queen. And
with the pawn on h3, this would have yielded White just an extra pawn in the
rook ending since the bishop would be hanging.} b5 (30... Qc6 31. Qxc6+ Kxc6
32. Rxe8 $18) 31. Qg4+ Rf5 32. Qd4+ Qd5 (32... Rd5 33. Qg7+ $18) 33. Qxa7+ $18)
(17... Nxd5 $2 18. Bxd5 $18 {is crushing.}) (17... exd5 {might have been a bit
safer, but not satisfactory either.} 18. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Ge1e7] Even though it
implies losing a tempo, this familiar idea is effective.} (18. Nxd5 {is the
natural reaction, yielding White a minimal advantage only. True, there are
some hidden dangers for Black on the way.} Nxd5 19. Bxd5 Bf8 $1 (19... Nb4 $2
20. Qd4 Bf8 21. Rxe8 Rxe8 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. Bxb7 $18) (19... Na5 $2 20. Qd4 Bf8
21. Bxf7+ $1 Qxf7 (21... Kxf7 22. Qh8 Bxh6 23. Ng5+ $1 Bxg5 24. Qxh7+ $18 {
wins the queen.}) 22. Qxd8 Rxd8 23. Rxd8 $18 {White will soon be an exchange
and a pawn up.}) (19... Bf6 $6 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Qc4 $16 {with strong
pressure.}) 20. Bxf8 Rxe1+ 21. Rxe1 Rxf8 22. Ba2 $14 {[%cal Gh2h4] followed by
h2-h4.}) 18... Na5 19. Nb5 Qc5 {Keeping e7 defended.} 20. Ba4 $1 {Threatening
Rxe7.} Ne4 21. Nbd4 Nxg5 22. Bxe8 Nxf3+ 23. Qxf3 Rxe8 24. b4 $16 {Black will
not have full compensation for the exchange.}) {While pondering over my next
move, an amusing but disturbing incident happened on the next board. Suba met
Bologan's draw offer with explosive laughter, which he repeated after a few
minutes. This made me lose my focus to such an extent that I made a losing
move in a practically won position.} 18. Bc1 $4 ({As far as I remember, I was
calculating the consequences of} 18. Qd2 $1 Bc5 19. dxe6 $1 Rxe6 (19... Rxd2 {
leads to mate:} 20. exf7+ Qxf7 21. Rxe8+ Bf8 22. Rxf8#) 20. Rxe6 fxe6 (20...
Rxd2 21. Re8+ Bf8 22. Rxf8#) 21. Bxe6+ Kh8 22. Bxg4 Rxd2 23. Rxd2 {[%cal Gd2d7]
White has overwhelming compensation for the queen. The immediate threat is Rd7.
} Bc8 24. Nb5 Qb7 25. Nxa7 $1 Qxa7 (25... Bxg4 26. Nxc6 Be7 27. Nfe5 Be6 28. h3
$5 $16) 26. Bxc8 Qf7 27. b4 $16 {I surely did not reach so far with my
calculation, but I thought the queen's sacrifice was promising. Disturbed by
the incidence, I must have thought there was no difference between the played
move and Qd2. Or was it a Lspsus Manus?}) (18. Nb5 {also yields White an
advantage, but I considered it only briefly since the following lines are not
easy to systematize. For this reason, I will not investigate it further.}) ({
The strongest move was} 18. dxe6 $1 {I do not remember calculating it, but if
the idea had come to my mind, I might have played it.} Nxh6 (18... Rxd3 19.
exf7+ Kh8 20. fxe8=Q+ {mating next.}) (18... f6 19. Qd7 Qb8 20. Bf4 Qxf4 21.
Qxb7 $18) 19. Nd5 {White throws all his pieces into the fight.} Qc8 (19... Rxd5
20. exf7+ Nxf7 21. Qxd5 Ncd8 22. Qd7 {The material is equal and White
maintains the initiative.} Qxd7 23. Rxd7 Bxf3 24. Rdxe7 Rxe7 25. Rxe7 Bc6 26.
Rxa7 $18) 20. exf7+ Nxf7 21. Qc4 Kg7 (21... Rf8 22. Nxe7+ Nxe7 23. Qxc8 Nxc8
24. Ng5 Ncd6 25. Re7 $18) 22. Nc7 Qxc7 23. Qxf7+ Kh6 {requires a bit more of
an effort from White.} (23... Kh8 {loses quicker.} 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 (24... Qxd8
25. Ng5 $18) 25. Ng5 $18 {In this lines, the pin along either the e-file or
the seventh rank is decisive.}) 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 (24... Qxd8 25. Ng5 $1 Kxg5 26.
Qxh7 Qd4 27. g3 $18 {mating soon.}) 25. g4 {Threatening g4-g5, based on the
pin along the seventh rank.} Qc8 {One way to remove the pin.} (25... Rc8 26.
Rxe7 $1 Qxe7 27. g5+ Kh5 28. Qf4 $18 {wins.}) ({AFter} 25... Qb8 26. h4 $18 {
the threat g4-g5+ is decisive.}) 26. Be6 $1 Rf8 27. g5+ $1 Bxg5 28. Nxg5 Qd8 (
28... Rxf7 29. Nxf7+ Kg7 30. Bxc8 $18) 29. Qxh7+ Kxg5 30. h4+ Kf6 31. Qxb7 Qd6
32. Ba2 Ne5 33. Qe4 $18 {Black does not have compensation for the pawn. In
fact, his king remains exposed.}) 18... Bc5 $1 {This is very strong now.} 19.
dxe6 {The same combination as in the line with Qd2 does not work, since there
is no bishop on h6. This is what I must have overlooked.} (19. Re2 Nd4 $19) (
19. Rf1 Nd4 $19) (19. Ne4 exd5 20. Nxc5 bxc5 21. Bxd5 Nd4 $19) (19. Be3 Bxe3
20. fxe3 Nce5 $19 {In all these lines, the attack on h2 is decisive.}) 19...
Rxe6 20. Rxe6 Rxd3 21. Re8+ Kg7 22. Rxd3 Bxf2+ 23. Kh1 Nd4 0-1

