{[%evp 0,51,21,6,10,19,10,20,28,14,27,14,36,31,40,26,18,18,37,22,24,30,56,37,
24,21,38,38,45,48,48,50,34,-36,77,54,80,80,118,124,124,185,241,246,255,265,266,
267,268,268,268,268,269,269] The previous game was never published,
encouraging Dieter to repeat his experiment a few years later.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3
c5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. d4 cxd4 6. exd4 d5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O
O-O 10. Re1 Nf6 11. a3 b6 12. Bc2 Bb7 13. Qd3 g6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Rad1 Qc7 16.
Bb3 Rad8 17. h3 $1 {The organic drawbacks of Black's setup are so big that
White can spent a tempo on preventing ...Ng4, without releasing the pressure
any single bit.} (17. d5 {was my move, as you surely remember.}) 17... Rd7 {
An over confident move, preparing ...Red8.} (17... Nd5 {might have been the
best chance, when the game would transpose to a structure examined in a
different section.} 18. Nxd5 exd5 19. Qc3 $16 {followed by Ne5.}) (17... Na5
18. Ba2 Nd5 19. Nb5 Qb8 20. Ne5 {also yields White huge pressure.} a6 21. Nc3
b5 $6 22. Qf3 f6 $6 23. Nxg6 hxg6 24. Qg4 $18 {wins.}) 18. d5 $1 {The same
issue. Unblocked pawns must advance.} Rc8 {Probably aimed at removing the
potential pin along the e-file, while keeping the square on d8 clear for the
queen.} (18... Red8 19. Nb5 Qc8 20. Qc3 exd5 21. Rxe7 Rxe7 22. Qxf6 $18) (18...
exd5 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 {[%cal Gd5f7,Gd3c3] Threatening Bxf7.} Na5 21. Qd4
$18) 19. Qe3 {The simplest. White wins without unnecessary complications.
However, it is worth mentioning two powerfull queen sacrifices.} (19. Nb5 $1
Qd8 20. dxc6 $1 Rxd3 21. cxb7 Rb8 22. Ne5 Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Qxd1+ (23... Nd5 24.
Bxd5 exd5 25. Nc6 Qe8 26. Nxb8 Qxb8 27. Rc1 Qxb7 28. Rc7 Qb8 29. Rxe7 $18) (
23... Qe8 24. Nc7 $18 {traps the queen.}) 24. Bxd1 Rxb7 25. Bf3 Nd5 26. Nc3 Bf6
27. Nxd5 exd5 28. Nd3 $18) (19. dxe6 $1 Rxd3 20. exf7+ Kh8 21. Rxd3 $18) 19...
exd5 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. Bxd5 {[%cal Ge3c3,Gd5f7]} Bc5 (21... Bf8 22. Bxf8 Rxf8
23. Qh6 {[%cal Gf3g5] Black can parry the threat Ng5 followed by mate only
with the obviously insufficient} Rxd5 24. Rxd5 $18) 22. Qe8+ Bf8 23. Bxf8 Rxe8
24. Rxe8 Qb8 25. Rxb8 Nxb8 {It may seem that Black has got dry out of muddy
waters.} 26. Bd6 $3 {This and only this retains the material advantage.} (26.
Bd6 Rxd6 27. Bxf7+ Kxf7 28. Rxd6) 1-0

