{[%evp 0,84,80,27,29,27,27,4,6,6,37,44,61,21,35,22,22,28,28,28,32,32,22,40,33,
29,83,47,59,47,54,47,47,48,57,48,67,87,110,47,60,36,184,43,61,-23,0,-96,39,
-215,35,53,67,51,85,66,66,66,100,105,145,252,252,252,252,133,66,248,252,252,
252,195,654,997,1162,1162,1162,1162,1231,516,521,563,563,634,655,653,655] The
following game stands apart from all the others examined in this section. The
material balance seems to favour Black starting with the critical moment, but
White's anterior positional achievements were more important. I have used this
game in my attacking trilogy for Modern Chess. Now I have added some comments
that make the connection with our current theme.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 d5
4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. a3 cxd4 10. exd4 Bf6
11. Be4 Nce7 12. Ne5 $5 {A small psychological experiment.} ({Even at the time
when this game took place, the main line was} 12. Qd3 {, inviting Black to
advance one of the kingside pawns, each possibility having its pros and cons.})
12... g6 {Ribli falls into the small trap and answers in the same way as he
would have probably done against Qd3.} (12... Bd7 $5) (12... b6 $5) 13. Bh6 Bg7
14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Rc1 $1 {White has spared the tempo Qd3 and is ready to take
over the control of the c-file. Besides, he has effortlessly weakened Black's
kingside dark squares.} b6 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bxd5 {At first sight a
paradoxical exchange. Isn't the player with an Isolani supposed to avoid
exchanging the minor pieces? Now is the moment when Smyslov's refined
positional understanding tells. Since Black has weakened his dark squares, the
exchange is absolutely logical. At the same time, the Isolani will not be weak,
because Black will be busy defending f7.} Qxd5 ({Ribli's desire to keep the
blockade on d5 is understandable, but with hindsight, it would have been
better to keep c7 defended with} 17... exd5 $14 {offering White just very
pleasant play. This would actually transpose to a different structure examined
in this database.}) 18. Rc7 $1 {This is by far more than fighting for the
c-file. In fact, White will not transfer any other piece to the queenside,
they will all flow closer to the enemy king. At first sight it may seem that
the rook is unstable on c7 without the direct support of its colleagues. And
also that White's kingside attack would not have enough force. But the
combined pressure along the seventh rank and the g-file will gradually acquire
overwhelming force.} Bb7 ({A first tactical moment relevant for the rook's
relative stability arises after} 18... Qd6 $2 19. Rxf7+ Rxf7 20. Nxf7 Kxf7 21.
Qf3+) 19. Qg4 Rad8 {For the time being it is essential to control d7 to
maintain central stability. But this offers White another tempo for building
up his attack.} (19... Rac8 20. Rd7 Qe4 21. Qxe4 Bxe4 22. f3 Bd5 23. Rxa7 Rc2
24. b4 $16 {White has won a pawn while the pressure on f7 prevents Black from
generating enough counterplay.}) 20. Rd1 a5 {After removing the pawn from the
vulnerable square, Black seems ready to expel the molesting rook.} 21. h4 $3
$16 {This is a natural move, of course, but my enthusiastic evaluation refers
to the fact that it makes the communication between the wings effective and
not just theoretical. The threat is h4-h5 followed by hxg6 and Qxg6+, based on
the pin along the seventh rank. But if we examine the second line below and
the course of the game we can see that the seventh rank pressure ensures the
queen's stability while the pressure on g6 helps the rook maintain the control
over the seventh rank!} Rc8 (21... h5 $2 22. Qxg6+) (21... Qe4 {allows a very
elegant tactical solution:} 22. h5 Qxg4 23. h6+ $1 Kxh6 24. Nxg4+ Kg5 25. Ne5
$16 {winning an exchange.}) 22. Rd7 Qe4 23. Qg5 {We notice this is not a
typical Isolani position. White has only one minor piece, but what a piece it
is! The isolated pawn prevents Black's counterplay along the d-file and
sustains the knight rather well.} Bc6 ({Another nice illustrative line is} 
23... h6 24. Qxg6+ Qxg6 25. Nxg6 Kxg6 26. Rxb7 $16) 24. f3 $6 {This principled
intermediate move is somewhat inaccurate due to a hidden tactical nuance.} ({
SImpler and better was} 24. Ra7 {with possible transposition to the game.})
24... Qf5 $6 {Missing his chance.} ({Attacking the second rook would not
molest White:} 24... Qe2 $2 25. Ng4 $3 Qxd1+ 26. Kh2 Kg8 (26... Bxd7 27. Qf6+
Kg8 28. Nh6#) 27. Qh6 {with the decisive threat Nf6+.}) ({Black's best chance
for reaching a draw in an inferior ending was} 24... h6 $5 25. fxe4 (25. Qc1
Qe2 26. Nxc6 Rxc6 27. Qxc6 Qxd1+ 28. Kh2 {and Black has every chance to reach
a draw by perpetual.}) 25... hxg5 26. Nxc6 Rxc6 27. hxg5 $14) 25. Ra7 Ba4 26.
Re1 $1 {Planning Re4-g4, continuing the slow invasion. Compared with
Grischuk's Rxe4-g4. Paradoxically, Black has no adequate defences.} Rc2 27. b4
Bb3 28. bxa5 bxa5 29. Re4 h6 (29... Qxg5 30. hxg5 a4 31. Rf4 $18) 30. Qe3 Rb2
31. Rg4 $1 {Smyslov carries out his plan with calm and precision. There is no
adequate defence against Rxg6+ any more.} ({He did not let himself decoyed by
the f7-pawn with} 31. Rf4 Qc2 32. Rfxf7+ $2 ({Actually} 32. Rg4 $1 {still wins.
}) 32... Rxf7 33. Rxf7+ Kg8 34. Rf8+ Kxf8 35. Qxh6+ Kg8 $1 {and the best White
can hope for is perpetual.}) 31... g5 {Ribli launches a desperate
counterattack, but his 63-year-old opponent displays remarkable tactical
accuracy until the end.} 32. hxg5 h5 33. Rg3 h4 34. Rg4 h3 $1 35. g6 h2+ (35...
Rxg2+ 36. Rxg2 Qb1+ 37. Kh2 hxg2 38. Kxg2 Rh8 39. Rxf7+ Kg8 40. Rf8+ Kxf8 41.
g7+ Kxg7 42. Qg5+ Kh7 43. Qh5+ Kg7 44. Qf7+ Kh6 45. Ng4+ Kg5 46. Qf6+ Kh5 47.
Qxh8+ Kg6 48. Qf6+ Kh7 49. Qf7+ Kh8 50. Nf6 $18) 36. Kxh2 Rh8+ 37. Kg3 Rxg2+
38. Kxg2 Qc2+ 39. Qf2 $1 Rh2+ 40. Kxh2 Qxf2+ 41. Kh3 Qf1+ 42. Rg2 Qh1+ (42...
Qh1+ 43. Kg3 Qe1+ 44. Kg4 Qh1 45. Rg3 Bc2 46. Rxf7+ Kg8 47. Kg5 Qe1 48. Rg4 Bf5
49. Kf6 $18 Bxg4 50. Rg7+ Kf8 51. Rh7 Kg8 52. Nf7 {(Smyslov)}) 1-0

