{[%evp 0,53,23,15,49,-1,7,7,7,-23,4,4,8,9,39,38,30,30,55,27,38,27,34,26,34,19,
16,16,29,35,35,26,17,13,11,-37,-13,-33,-3,-46,-30,-81,-41,-27,-95,-98,-98,-98,
-17,-81,-76,-85,-22,-76,-76,-75] We will end this section by examining two
examples with slightly unusual play. He has seen the two extremes, featuring
the Isolani as a weakness and as a strength. The next games belong somewhere
in between.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 {Many years ago, when trying to find a reliable
system against the Alapin variation, I was curious to check the way Gheorghiu
used to meet it and came across this original game.} d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6
5. Nf3 e6 6. Be3 cxd4 7. cxd4 Nc6 8. Nc3 Qd8 9. a3 Be7 10. Bd3 O-O 11. Qc2 {
The queen does not belong here, but this move is meant to inhibit...b7-b6.} (
11. O-O b6 12. Qe2 Bb7 13. Rad1 {is a slightly improved version for Black of
Nisipeanu's game above. The bishop is on e3 and White does not have induced
the weakening of the kingside yet.}) 11... Bd7 {An apparently modest move,
initiating a coherent global plan.} (11... b6 {runs into} 12. Ne4 $1) 12. O-O
Rc8 13. Rad1 {A natural move, completing the development.} ({Had White
anticipated Black's intentions, he would have chosen a different move order.} 
13. Rfe1 $5 {By keeping the queen's rook on a1, White intends to meet} Qa5 {
with} 14. b4 Qh5 (14... Qd8 {may be better. At the cost of two tempi, Black
has weakened White's queenside.}) 15. b5 Na5 16. Ne5 $16 {, causing strong
discomfort to the queen.}) 13... Qa5 {The queen is stable on this square now.
The main idea is to clear the d8-square for the rook in order to continue the
planned regrouping.} 14. Rfe1 Rfd8 15. Qe2 Be8 {This is only the first part of
the regrouping. There are certain openings where Black retreats with the
bishop to e8 in order to consolidate the kingside and clear the path for the
rook on d8. However, the regrouping will continue since Black has the tempting
square on d5.} 16. Bc4 h6 $1 {Preparing ...Bf8 without fearing Bg5. We should
also notice that if necessary, Black could restrict the queen plus bishop
battery along the b1-h7 diagonal with ...g7-g6, without fearing sacrifices on
g6, since the bishop on g8 defends everything.} 17. Bd2 Qh5 {With the white
queen on e2, the black one is out of danger on h5.} 18. Bc1 Bf8 19. Ba2 Ne7 $1
{This is the final part of Black's plan. The last move consolidates his
control over d5 and prepares the activation of the bishop with ...Bc6. When
playing over this game, I was sure that I had never seen such a plan before.}
20. Qf1 {Trying to molest the queen with Ne5.} Qa5 $1 {Maintaining Black's
flexibility. It has become obvious that White is nowhere with his active plans,
while Black's regrouping is optimal.} 21. Ne5 Nc6 $1 {The most convincing
among several good moves.} ({The knight jump to e5 was probably aimed at
inhibiting} 21... Bc6 $2 {, which would run into} 22. Nxf7 $1 $18 {, with the
possible insertion of b2-b4.}) (21... Ned5 $5 $15) (21... b5 $5 $15 {followed
by ...b5-b4.}) 22. Nxc6 {Sad necessity. White exchanges his most active piece 
(which happens to be a minor piece!)} (22. Nf3 {allows} Bxa3 $1 $17) 22... Bxc6
$17 {All Black's pieces are active now, ensuring him a clear advantage at no
risk.} 23. Bb1 Bd5 {Not a bad move, but the over-cautious Gheorghiu meant it
as a way of preparing the move repetition.} (23... Bxa3 $5 {is objectively
strong but may lead to unnecessary complications.} 24. Re5 Qb4 25. Qe2 Ba4 26.
Nxa4 Qxd4 27. Rf1 Bd6 28. Ra5 Bc7 29. Be3 Qd6 30. Rh5 Nxh5 31. Qxh5 Qb4 32. Nc3
Qxb2 $17) ({Black can maintain his advantage by continuing to improve his
piece placement. For instance} 23... Rd7 24. Qe2 Rcd8 $17) ({Alternatively,} 
23... g6 24. Ba2 Bg7 $17) 24. Qd3 (24. Nxd5 Rxd5 25. Qe2 (25. Ba2 Rd7 $15)
25... Qd8 $15) 24... Bc4 25. Qf3 Bd5 (25... Qb6 $15) 26. Qd3 Bc4 27. Qf3
1/2-1/2

