{No matter how original Black's play was in this game, there is nothing really
new on Earth. This ancient game proves this truth once more.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 c5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. a3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. exd4 Be7 9. O-O O-O
10. Be3 $6 {In the previous game, the bishop landed on this square in order to
provoke the exchange on d4.} (10. Re1 {or}) (10. Qd3 {are more to the point.})
10... Bd7 {The first step along Gheorghiu's plan (if we can call it so after
seeing the current game).} 11. Qd3 (11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Bxd5 $10)
11... Rc8 12. Rac1 Qa5 13. Ba2 (13. d5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Rfd8 $11)
13... Rfd8 14. Rfe1 {White did not display his rooks on the optimal squares,
but he did not play badly. In fact, so far he did a lot better than
Rooozentalis, as the analysis of the next phase shows.} Be8 {The first part of
the standard regrouping is over.} 15. Bb1 g6 $6 {People of those times were so
impressed about Steinitz's general regrouping that some of the commentators
evaluated the position as clearly better for Black after his last move. In
fact, it is an inaccuracy.} ({True, is the only modern game reaching this
position, Black did worse:} 15... e5 $2 16. Bg5 (16. d5 $18 {is crushing})
16... Nxd4 {Mammadov,Z (2417)-Araujo Sanchez,J (2337) Chess.com INT 2020 (1-0,
36)}) ({Steinitz must have noticed that} 15... h6 $2 {, preparing the familiar
...Bf8 and ...Ne7, runs into} 16. Ne4 $16 {, since the exchange on e4 followed
by ...g7-g6 loses the pawn on h6.}) (15... Qa6 $1 {was the solution to this
problem.} 16. Qc2 (16. Qxa6 bxa6 {yields Black free play, since White no
longer has attacking chances.} 17. Bd3 a5 18. h3 h6 $11 {followed by ...Bf8 or
...Bd6.}) 16... h6 {Now this is playable.} 17. Ne4 {This leads to interesting
complications, but not to an advantage for White.} Nxd4 18. Nxf6+ (18. Qxc8
Rxc8 19. Rxc8 Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 Kf8 {may transpose. If White deviates with} 21.
Nc5 Bxc5 22. Bxc5+ {, Black is safe after} Kg8 $11) 18... Bxf6 19. Qxc8 Nxf3+
20. gxf3 Rxc8 21. Rxc8 Kf8 22. Ra8 Bg5 $5 {In anticipation of the threat
Rc1-c8, Black weakens White's kingside.} 23. f4 Be7 24. Rc1 f5 25. Rcc8 Qe2 26.
Rxe8+ Kf7 $11 {Black threatens both retrieving the bishop and delivering a
perpetual.}) 16. Qe2 {This slow move offers Black the tempo he needs for
completing his regrouping.} (16. Ba2 $1 {was much stronger.} Bf8 $6 17. Bg5 Bg7
18. d5 $16) 16... Bf8 17. Red1 (17. Bg5 $2 {runs into} Nxd4 $1 $17) 17... Bg7
18. Ba2 Ne7 {Optically, Black has reached an even more ambitious setup than
Gheorghiu. However, the slight weakening of the kingside squares may play a
part, while Black will not have the ideas with ...Bxa3 anymore. As a general
evaluation, we can say that Black has solved all the opening problems and it
is White's turn to think of a way to maintain equality.} 19. Qd2 {This move
was called "planless" by the commentators of that time. They only saw the
mini-threat Nd5, which is not even real due to ...Rxd5. However, this is a
constructive way of preparing Bg5.} (19. Bg5 {was recommended, but this runs
into} h6 $1 {[%cal Ge7f5]} (19... Nf5 20. d5 $1 $18 {Horowitz}) 20. Bxf6 Bxf6
21. Ne4 Bg7 $17 {Marin.}) 19... Qa6 (19... Bc6 $5 $15) 20. Bg5 {White has
achieved something that was denied to Rozentalis: install the bishop on g5.
The constant pin along the h4-d8 diagonal allows him to maintain the equality.}
(20. Qe1 $5 {/\ d5 Lasker} Nf5 $1 21. d5 Nxe3 22. Qxe3 exd5 23. Nxd5 Nxd5 24.
Bxd5 Bxb2 $17 {Neistadt}) 20... Nf5 21. g4 $5 {Embarking big adventures.} (21.
Qe1 $5 {/\ d5 Lasker} h6 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. d5 exd5 24. Bxd5 Kg7 $15) (21. d5 h6
$1 (21... Bc6 $2 {is the old recommendation, but it loses material to} 22. g4
$1 Ne7 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. Qf4 $18) 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 $11) (21. Qf4 {/\ Rd2, Rcd1
Minckwitz} h6 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Rd2 Bc6 24. d5 Bxc3 25. Rxc3 Bxd5 $17) (21.
Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Ne4 Bg7 23. Rxc8 Rxc8 $17 {Neistadt} 24. d5 $11 {Marin}) 21...
Nxd4 $1 (21... Nxg4 22. Bxd8 Rxd8 23. Qf4 Nf6 24. d5 $14 {maintains Black
under pressure, even though he has ... Bh6 in reserve.}) 22. Nxd4 e5 {The game
enters a phase that is no longer related to our main theme. My point when
showing this game was to prove that such old games can be inspiring for modern
players, too.} 23. Nd5 (23. Qe2 exd4 24. Qxa6 bxa6 25. Nd5 Nxd5 (25... Rxc1 26.
Rxc1 Rxd5 $1 $17 {Steinitz}) 26. Rxc8 (26. Bxd8 Rxd8 $19) 26... Rxc8 27. Bxd5
Rc5 $19) 23... Rxc1 24. Qxc1 (24. Nxf6+ Bxf6 25. Qxc1 exd4 $19 {Minckwitz})
24... exd4 25. Rxd4 (25. Re1 $1 $44) 25... Nxd5 26. Rxd5 (26. Bxd8 Bxd4 27.
Bxd5 Qd6 $19 {Steinitz, 27...Qe2-+ Horowitz}) 26... Rxd5 27. Bxd5 Qe2 $1 28. h3
(28. f3 Bd4+ 29. Kh1 Bc6 30. Bxc6 bxc6 $19) 28... h6 $5 (28... Bxb2 $1 29. Qc8
(29. Qc5 $6 Qd1+ 30. Kh2 Be5+ 31. Kg2 (31. f4 Bd4 $1 $19 {/\ Qg1#}) 31... Qxd5+
32. Qxd5 Bc6 $19) 29... Qd1+ 30. Kh2 Be5+ $1 (30... Qxd5 31. Qxe8+ Kg7 32. Be7
Be5+ 33. Kg1 $10 h6 $19) 31. f4 Qd2+ 32. Kg3 $10 {Steinitz} Qe3+ 33. Kg2 (33.
Bf3 Bd4 {/\ 34.Qc2 Qe1 then Qf2# or 34.f5 Qe1 and then Be5# or Qg1# /\ 34.Qc2
Qe1 nebst Qf2# oder 34.f5 Qe1 nebst Be5# oder Qg1#} 34. h4 Qf2+ 35. Kh3 Qxf3+
36. Kh2 Qf2+ 37. Kh3 Qf1+ 38. Kg3 (38. Kh2 Bg1+ 39. Kg3 Qf2+ 40. Kh3 Qh2#)
38... Bf2+ 39. Kf3 Bg1+ 40. Ke4 Qe2+ 41. Kd5 Qd3+ 42. Ke5 Qd4#) 33... Qe2+ 34.
Kg3 Bd4 35. h4 (35. Bxf7+ Kg7 $19) 35... Bf2+ 36. Kh3 Qf1+ 37. Bg2 Qd3+ 38. Kh2
Bg3+ 39. Kg1 Qe3+ 40. Kh1 Qe1+ 41. Bf1 Qxf1# {von Kockelkorn}) 29. Bc4 $2 (29.
Bxh6 $2 Bxh6 30. Qxh6 Qd1+ $19) (29. Qd2 Qb5 30. Be3 Bxb2 $19 {Steinitz} 31. a4
Qxa4 32. Qxb2 Qd1+ 33. Kh2 Qxd5 34. Bxh6 Qd6+ $11) (29. Be3 {! Neistadt} Bxb2
30. Qb1 Kh7 31. Bxb7 Bb5 {/\ Bd3 Steinitz} 32. Be4 $17 {Horowitz =}) 29... Qf3
30. Qe3 (30. Qe1 Bc6 $19) 30... Qd1+ 31. Kh2 Bc6 32. Be7 {2h} (32. Bxh6 Bxh6
33. Qxh6 Qh1+ 34. Kg3 Qg1+ $19 {Minckwitz}) 32... Be5+ $1 33. f4 (33. Qxe5 Qh1+
34. Kg3 Qg2+ 35. Kh4 Qxf2+ 36. Qg3 g5+ $19 {Steinitz}) 33... Bxf4+ (33... g5 $3
$19 {/\ Qg1, Qg2#}) 34. Qxf4 Qh1+ 35. Kg3 Qg1+ 0-1

