{[%evp 0,65,42,27,30,-7,18,9,9,14,10,14,14,4,4,-28,-18,-17,-17,-24,-16,-9,-1,
-2,-3,2,19,31,58,57,67,36,48,35,35,56,56,54,62,64,64,64,63,67,81,84,97,111,100,
101,110,137,137,98,405,134,131,124,204,232,223,247,322,244,1255,1280,29995,
29996] The paradox signalled when examining the weak Isolani only partly
applies to this structure. A good knight versus a bad bishop is likely to
ensure a big advantage, if everything is fine from structural point of view.
The problem is that achieving such a situation is not easy in practice and any
minor weakness may offer chances to the passive side. Here is an example:
Everything was perfect for the player with a knight.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3.
Nc3 e6 4. e3 d5 5. d4 Nc6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 a6 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 9. h3 Qc7 10.
O-O Bd6 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 Qe7 14. Rc1 Bd7 15. Na4 Ba7 16. Bd4
Ne4 17. Bxa7 Rxa7 18. Qd4 Rb7 19. Nc5 Nxc5 20. Rxc5 $16 {This is White's best
dream. He has a perfect blockade and the knight will land on d4 soon, while
his structure has no weakness.} f6 $2 {Exosing the king and wasting a tempo in
order to prevent Ne5.} ({True, a neutral move such as} 20... h6 {allows} 21.
Ne5 $1 Rc8 22. Rfc1 Qd6 23. Nxd7 $1 Qxd7 24. Qa4 Rb6 25. Qg4 f5 (25... Qxg4 26.
hxg4 {threatening Rxd5 wins a pawn, maintaining the better structure..}) 26.
Qg6 $18) (20... Re8 {would have served better the purpose of preventing Ne5.}
21. Rfc1 h6 $5 22. Qd3 {Clearing the d4-square for the knight.} (22. Ra5 {
does not necessarily yield concrete results.} Ra8 23. Qa4 Be8 $5 {Defending
the queen and clearing the seventh rank.} (23... c5 24. Qa3 {wins a pawn.}) 24.
Rcc5 (24. Rxa6 {runs into} Rba7 $1 $11) 24... Bd7 25. Nd4 Rb6 {White's
advantage is beyond doubt, but a clear win is not in sight yet.}) 22... Rb5 (
22... Rb6 23. Nd4 Rc8 24. a4 a5 25. Qc3 $18 {wins the a-pawn with all the
comfort.}) 23. R5c3 Rb6 24. Nd4 Qg5 25. Kh2 Qe5+ 26. Kh1 Qf6 $16 {Black is
still kicking a bit.}) 21. Rfc1 Rfb8 (21... Rc8 22. Qa4 Rb6 23. Nd4 Qe8 24. Qa5
Rcb8 25. Qc3 Rc8 26. a4 $18) 22. Qf4 $5 {Clearing the d4-square and tending a
small trap.} Rb5 $2 {A flawed attempt to reduce the rpessure.} (22... Rc8 23.
Nd4 Rb6 24. Qf3 {followed by the queen's transfer to the central dark squares
is joyless for Black, too.}) 23. Nd4 $1 $18 {Suddenly, Black is poorly
coordinated.} Rxc5 (23... R5b6 24. Nxc6 $18) 24. Qxb8+ Kf7 25. Rxc5 Qxc5 26. b4
Qc4 (26... Qe7 27. Qb7 $18) 27. Qd6 Ke8 28. Nb3 Bf5 29. Na5 Qxa2 30. Nxc6 Kf7
31. Qc7+ Kg6 32. Ne7+ Kg5 33. Qf4+ 1-0

