{In games between stronger players, achieving such a dream position is
virtually impossible. We will examine two almost twin games, in which the
player with a knight had to weaken his structure just a bit.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nc3
Nc6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. d4 d5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bb5 Bd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O
O-O 10. b3 Bg4 11. Bb2 a6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. Rc1 Bd6 14. Ne2 Rc8 15. Ne5 Bxe5
16. Bxe5 Qe7 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 {In view of the threat ...Bxe2 followed by ...c6-c5,
equalizing, White needs to play} 18. f3 {The relative weakness on e3 will
cause White big problems in reaching optimal coordination.} Bd7 19. Qd4 Qe7 (
19... Qxd4 20. exd4 a5 21. Nf4 f6 22. Nd3 $16 {The weaknesses along the c-file
leave Black struggling.}) 20. Nc3 {White does not make any effort to reach the
optimal regrouping with the knight on d4. On c5, the knight will be nicely
placed but will not attack anything!} (20. Qc5 $5 Qg5 21. Rc3 Rfe8 22. Re1 h5
23. Nd4 h4 24. b4 Rb8 $5 {Truth said, this is not clear since the weakness on
e3 restricts White's possibilities. More about it in the next example.}) 20...
Rfe8 21. Rfe1 h5 22. Na4 Rb8 23. Nc5 a5 {The best way of displaying the
queenside forces. White has to count with ...Rb4.} (23... Bc8 24. e4 $16 {
yields White strong initiative.}) 24. Qc3 Rb5 25. e4 {The logical consequence
of White's previous play. The knight on c5 plays an active part, allowing
White to gain space. However, this does not yield him a substantial advantage.}
(25. Nxd7 Qxd7 26. Qxc6 Qxc6 27. Rxc6 a4 {yields Black enough counterplay.} 28.
Rc3 d4 29. Rd3 axb3 30. axb3 (30. Rxb3 Rxb3 31. axb3 dxe3 32. Kf1 g5 33. Ke2 f5
$11) 30... Kh7 31. Kf2 dxe3+ 32. Rdxe3 Reb8 33. Rb1 h4 $5 $11) 25... Qd6 {
Black is not prepared for opening the position.} (25... dxe4 $2 {leads to
disaster.} 26. Rxe4 Qd8 (26... Be6 27. Nxe6 fxe6 28. Qxc6 $18) 27. Rd4 $18) 26.
e5 Qe7 {The game has entered a new phase. Apart from the blockade on dark
squares, White also has a kingside majority. On the other hand, he has
weakened his control over d4. Black has the potential threat of .. .Rb4
followed by ...d5-d4.} 27. a3 {Leaving Black without counterplay, but creating
a weakness on b3. The knight is bound to stay on c5 now.} Bf5 {The bishop is
not such a bad piece. It helps Black to maintain his kingside stability.} 28.
Qd4 Qg5 29. Kf2 Qg6 (29... h4 $5) 30. Re3 (30. h4 $5) 30... Qg5 {In the next
phase, White will move his pieces around, without a clear plan, while Black
will sit and wait.} 31. Rce1 Qe7 32. Rc1 Qg5 33. Rcc3 Qe7 34. Kg1 Qg5 35. Kf1
Qe7 36. Kf2 Qg5 37. g3 Qe7 38. Kg2 Be6 39. h3 {White finally shows his
intentions to start a kingside attack with g3-g4. His regrouping looks
impressive, but it is known that the queen is not the best-suited piece for a
blockade, especially that of a passed pawn.} g6 $6 {At this stage, Black did
not need to weaken his kingside dark squares and the king's residence in
general. He might have considered only g3-g4 ...hxg4, hxg4, when. ..Kg7
followed by ...Rh8 would offer him excellent counterplay. If this is true, he
underestimated ...fxg4.} ({Black should have maintained his neutral policy.} 
39... Qg5 $5 40. Kh2 Qe7 41. Re2 Qg5 42. Rg2 {The same regrouping as in the
game.} Qe7 43. g4 hxg4 44. fxg4 Qh4 45. Rf2 Qg5 46. Rcf3 Qh4 $5 47. Nxe6 Rxe6
$5 (47... fxe6 {is also good, of course}) 48. Rxf7 Rxb3 {With the pawn on g7,
the black king is safe, despite the neighborhood with the rook.}) 40. Re1 Kg7
41. Rec1 Bc8 42. Re3 Be6 43. Re2 Kg8 44. Rd2 Bc8 45. Re2 Be6 46. Kh2 Kg7 47.
Qc3 Kg8 48. Qd4 Kg7 49. Ree1 Kg8 50. Re3 Kg7 51. Re2 Kg8 52. Rc3 Kg7 53. Rg2
Kg8 54. g4 hxg4 $6 {Still not feeling the danger.} (54... Qh4 $5) 55. fxg4 $1
$16 {Black will soon have problems along the f-file.} (55. hxg4 $2 {would
justify ...g7-g6, at least partly:} Qh4+ 56. Kg1 Qe1+ 57. Kh2 Kg7 $1 ({More
ambitious than} 57... Qh4+ {with a draw.}) 58. Nxe6+ Rxe6 (58... fxe6 59. Qa7+
$1 {maintains the balance even.}) 59. f4 (59. g5 Rb8 {wins}) 59... g5 $1 {
with a decisive attack.}) 55... Kg7 56. Rf2 Qg5 (56... Qh4 57. Rcf3 $18) 57. b4
$6 {This natural move, consolidating the knight, actually gives Black counter
chances along the a- and b- files.} (57. Rcf3 {is ineffective.} Kg8 (57... Rxc5
58. Qxc5 Qxe5+ $16 {does not yield enough compensation for the exchange.}) 58.
Nxe6 $2 Rxe6 59. Rxf7 Rb8 $1 $44 {Black's king is defended, while White's is
exposed. Besides, the pawn on e5 is hanging.}) (57. Rf6 Reb8 $16) (57. Kg3 Reb8
$16) (57. Kg2 $3 {would have been strongest. It would have put Black almost in
Zugzwang while preparing h2-h4!. The main idea is to play Kg3 in a moment when
Black cannot double rooks on the b-file.} Reb8 (57... Kg8 58. Rf6 Kg7 59. Kg3
Re7 60. h4 $18) (57... Re7 58. Kg3 $18 {[%cal Re7b7] Black cannot double rooks
along the b-file.}) 58. Nxe6+ fxe6 59. h4 $1 Qe7 (59... Qxh4 $2 60. Qf4 $18)
60. Rf6 $18 Rxb3 61. Rxb3 Rxb3 62. h5 {with a decisive attack.}) 57... axb4 58.
axb4 Kg8 {Too passive.} (58... Reb8 $1 59. Rb2 Qh4 60. Rf3 Qg5 $14) 59. Nd3 Bd7
60. Ra3 {White is on the top again.} Rbb8 61. Ra7 Be6 62. Ra6 Bd7 63. Ra7 $2 {
White obviously wanted to prevent .. .Ra8, but he should have done it by
indirect means.} (63. Kg3 $1 $16 Ra8 $2 64. b5 cxb5 65. Rxa8 Rxa8 66. Qxd5 $18)
63... Be6 64. Kg3 Ra8 65. h4 Qh6 66. Nf4 g5 {Suddenly, the position has become
double-edged. White cannot keep both wings under control.} 67. Nh5 Rxa7 68.
Qxa7 gxh4+ 69. Kxh4 Kh8 $11 70. g5 $2 Qh7 71. Qd4 Qe4+ $2 {Playing for a draw
in a better position.} (71... Ra8 $1 $17 {is suddenly bad for White, whose
king is too advanced.}) 72. Qxe4 dxe4 73. Nf6 Rb8 74. g6 fxg6 75. Kg5 Kg7 76.
Rh2 Rb5 77. Ne8+ Kf8 $2 {The decisive mistake.} (77... Kg8 $1 78. Nc7 Rxe5+ 79.
Kf6 Rh5 $11 80. Rxh5 $2 gxh5 81. Nxe6 h4 $19) 78. Nc7 Bc4 (78... Rxe5+ 79. Kf6
Rh5 80. Nxe6+ Kg8 81. Ra2 $18) 1-0

