{[%evp 0,36,28,9,46,-39,24,-6,-1,1,0,11,0,-41,-10,-4,-9,-79,-17,-64,-54,-66,
-81,-89,-93,-95,-72,-85,-55,-50,-50,-50,-50,-50,-50,-53,-53,-53,-56] The
positions with a good versus a bad bishop are as promising as the similar ones
with an Isolani. The essence remains the same. The good bishop does not stand
in the major pieces' way in their attempt to block the enemy's weaknesses
while contributing to increasing the pressure on them. We will start with a
classic example in which White had an additional weakness. This was not a 1.d4
game, but we are mainly interested in the structure.} 1. e4 Nf6 2. d3 c5 3. f4
Nc6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. Nbd2 d5 {We can now state that this could be a
reversed 1.d4 position.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Kh1 b6 $15 9. exd5 Qxd5 10. Qe1 Bb7 11.
Nc4 Nd4 12. Ne3 Qc6 13. Bd1 Nd5 $1 14. Nxd4 cxd4 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Bf3 Qd7 17.
Bxb7 Qxb7 18. c4 dxc3 19. bxc3 Rac8 20. Bb2 Rfd8 21. Rf3 Bf6 22. d4 Qd5 23. Qe3
Qb5 $1 24. Qd2 Rd5 25. h3 e6 26. Re1 Qa4 27. Ra1 b5 {Black has established a
firm blockade on light squares, and the white bishop is very passive. Whitețs
reaction is natural. He intends to mend the queenside structure by placing the
queen on b3. The pawn on f4 is the aforementioned additional weakness. We
should notice, though, that with the pawn on f2, Black could play ...e6-e5,
endangering Whitețs central pawns.} 28. Qd1 Rc4 29. Qb3 Rd6 {Alekhine
understands that the static pressure would not yield concrete. Therefore, he
starts maneuvering to induce White to exchange the queens.} 30. Kh2 Ra6 31.
Rff1 Be7 32. Kh1 Rcc6 33. Rfe1 Bh4 34. Rf1 {White has to take care of both his
wings.} (34. Re2 $2 {runs into} Bg3 $1 35. Rf1 ({In the event of} 35. Re4 {
, Black can do even better than winning the pawn on f4 with ...f7-f5:} Qxb3 36.
axb3 Rxa1+ 37. Bxa1 Ra6 38. Bb2 Ra2 39. Re2 a5 $1 $19 {Even better than taking
on f4. White is helpless against the advance of the a-pawn, winning the bishop
soon.}) 35... Qxa2 36. Qxb5 Rab6 37. Bc1 (37. Ba1 Qxa1 $1 $19 {wins apiece.})
37... Rxb5 38. Rxa2 Rxc3 $19 {Black has won an important pawn and White cannot
retrieve it because of losing the bishop:} 39. Rxa7 $6 Rb1) 34... Qc4 {
Planning ...Ra4 followed by ...R6a6.} 35. Qxc4 {WHite could not refrain from
this exchange for too long.} (35. Kh2 Ra4 36. Kh1 Rca6 37. Qxc4 {Obviously
forced.} bxc4 ({Even better than} 37... Rxc4) 38. a3 Be7 $19 {Black will win
the pawn on a3, maintaining a target on c3 in the rook ending.}) 35... Rxc4 36.
a3 Be7 37. Rfb1 Bd6 $1 {Making the best out of the superiority of the black
bishop over the white one.} ({Winning the pawn on a3 is likely to absolve
White of most of his problems.} 37... Rca4 38. Kh2 Bxa3 39. Bxa3 Rxa3 40. Rxa3
Rxa3 41. Rxb5 Rxc3 42. Ra5 Rc7 43. d5 exd5 44. Rxd5 $15 {With every chance to
hold.}) 38. g3 {The position is difficult for White. At this stage, we can
notice that Black has more good light squares than active pieces that can
occupy them. He needs his king on d5 to fix that problem.} Kf8 $6 {Alekhine
misses a good moment for increasing his positional advantage.} (38... h5 $1 {
would cause White serious strategic damage.} 39. Rf1 (39. h4 {leads to the
same structure as later in the game.} Kf8 $19) 39... Rca4 40. Rfb1 h4 $19 {
With a decisive weakening of White's kingside structure.}) 39. Kg2 $1 {White
will be in time now for over-defending f4.} Ke7 (39... h5 {is parried with} 40.
Kf3) 40. Kf2 {White does not try to prevent the black king from reaching d5.} (
40. Kf3 {does not solve his problems, though.} Kd7 (40... Rca4 {does not
threaten anything yet, since the king is far from the hanging pawn on b5.}) 41.
Ke4 Kc6 42. Ra2 Rca4 43. Rba1 f6 44. Bc1 e5 $17 {White's structure is under
pressure and his king exposed.}) 40... Kd7 41. Ke2 Kc6 42. Ra2 Rca4 43. Rba1
Kd5 {The king has finally reached this dominating square.} 44. Kd3 R6a5 {
Alekhine continues to improve his position. His last move prepares ... a7-a6,
absolving him of the worries connected with the b5-pawn. However, this move
deprives the rook of the possibility of a quick switch to other board sectors.}
(44... f6 45. Bc1 Rc6 {might have been a better way of regrouping.} 46. Rb1 a6
47. Rd2 {White needs to anticipate the central break.} (47. Rb3 e5 48. dxe5
fxe5 49. fxe5 Bxe5 50. g4 Rf6 $19 {White cannot defend both his wings anymore.}
) 47... Rc7 {Still postponing the break until the moment when his rooks will
be ready for an intervention on the other wing.} (47... e5 $5) 48. Rd1 Rac4 49.
Rb3 e5 50. dxe5 fxe5 51. fxe5 Bxe5 52. Kc2+ Kc6 53. Rd8 Rf7 $17 {White has
managed to activate one rook, but his position remains difficult.}) 45. Bc1 a6
46. Bb2 h5 47. h4 $2 {This positional concession was not necessary. We have
reached now the same structure as that mentioned in the comments after the
recommended 38...h5 above.} (47. Bc1 {was a flexible way of defending f4.} f6
48. Kc2 Kc4 ({Or if} 48... Rc4 49. Kb3 Raa4 50. Re2 $15 {with acceptable
coordination.}) 49. Bb2 e5 50. dxe5 fxe5 51. Re1 $1 exf4 52. gxf4 Bxf4 53. Raa1
$15 {With the black roks stuck on the queenside, White has realistic drawing
chances despite the missing pawn.}) 47... f6 48. Bc1 e5 {The player
controlling the light squares should eventually break on dark squares! Due to
the newly createdweakness on g3, WHite is lost.} 49. fxe5 fxe5 50. Bb2 (50.
dxe5 Bxe5 51. Rg2 Rg4 $19) 50... exd4 (50... Rc4 $5 51. Re1 (51. Rg1 e4+ 52.
Ke2 b4 53. cxb4 Bxb4 $19) 51... Raa4 52. Raa1 exd4 53. cxd4 Rc8 $19) 51. cxd4
b4 52. axb4 (52. Rg1 {[%cal Gg3g4] , preparing g3-g4 fails to yield sufficient
counterplay.} Kc6 {Clearing the fifth rank for the rook.} 53. g4 hxg4 54. Rxg4
Rf5 55. Rxg6 Rf3+ 56. Ke2 Rh3 $19 {White's queenside pieces are in a desperate
situation.}) 52... Rxa2 53. bxa5 Rxb2 0-1

