{[%evp 0,75,26,20,20,21,60,35,35,35,37,32,32,21,22,22,15,27,27,-12,14,-2,49,1,
1,4,4,-14,19,27,37,-1,7,-10,19,5,25,23,24,20,46,48,57,46,58,56,71,73,82,61,110,
84,98,143,188,190,195,183,184,204,237,216,231,204,201,194,203,222,249,265,277,
232,255,251,330,386,779,879] It is worth mentioning that in the positions with
bishops, the weakness induced by f2-f3 does not restrict White's possibilities
to the same extent as with a knight on board. Here is another famous classic.} 
1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. g3 Nc6 7. Bg2 cxd4 8.
Nxd4 Qb6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. O-O Be7 11. Na4 Qb5 {A good square for the queen,
keeping the knight under pressure and the c5-square well defended.} 12. Be3 O-O
13. Rc1 Bg4 {A very modern approach. Black fights against the blockade by
dynamic means.} 14. f3 $3 {If played by a player of a lesser category, this
would look like a clumsy and impatient way of evading the threats on e2. It is
the continuation of a long plan, speeding up the following regrouping. The
fluence of White's play in the next phase is such that it does not require any
comments.} (14. Bc5 Bxe2 $1) (14. Re1 Rfe8 15. Bc5 (15. Bd4 Nd7) 15... Bxc5 16.
Rxc5 Bxe2 17. Qc2 Bd3 $1 {with little or no compensation for the pawn in both
cases.}) 14... Be6 15. Bc5 Rfe8 16. Rf2 $1 Nd7 17. Bxe7 Rxe7 18. Qd4 Ree8 19.
Bf1 $1 {Preparing to include the last remaining pieces into the fight for the
queenside.} Rec8 $6 {We have seen this symptom in Howell-Houriez. Black
resigns himself to passive defense. He could have displayed particular
activity on the wings, yielding reasonable chances.} (19... a5 $5 {Taking
measures against b2-b4.} 20. e3 Qb7 21. Rfc2 Bf5 22. Rc3 Ne5 {We can notice
that the rook is useful on e8. After the game continuation, Black will not
have the same possibility again.} 23. Be2 Qe7 $11 {with a harmonious
regrouping and certain counterplay.}) (19... h5 $5 {Just a familiar useful
move.} 20. e3 Qb7 21. Rfc2 Bf5 22. Rc3 (22. Rxc6 $2 Ne5 $19) 22... Ne5 $11 {
with the same evaluation as above. We can conclude that Black had to search
for counterplay while still having a knight. Now is a good moment to remember
what Botvinnik said about the necessity of keeping a knight if one has pawn
weaknesses.}) 20. e3 Qb7 {Again passive.} (20... Qa5 {requires a bit of
accuracy from White.} 21. Rc3 {Removing the rook from an exposed square.} (21.
a3 $6 c5 $1 22. Nxc5 Nxc5 23. b4 Qxa3 $11 24. Rxc5 a5 $5) 21... h5 (21... c5
22. Nxc5 $1 Nxc5 23. b4 $16) 22. a3 $14 {followed by Nc5.}) 21. Nc5 ({White
could have still prepared the invasion on c5.} 21. Rfc2 $5 a5 (21... Bf5 22.
Rc3 $16 {and there is no ...Ne5 in view.}) 22. b3 h5 23. Rc3 $16) 21... Nxc5
22. Rxc5 {While the previous phase was instructive in general. The game only
now becomes 100% relevant for the good bishop versus bad bishop issue.} Rc7 $6
(22... a5 $14) 23. Rfc2 Qb6 24. b4 $1 {White has reached a perfect blockade.
This must have been the position Rubinstein dreamed of when playing the
unexpected f2-f3.} a6 {This exposes the pawn and weakens the square on b6,
making the queen unstable. Black wanted to insure himself against b4-b5. True,
the alternatives did not offer reasons for joy, either.} (24... Rb7 25. a3 Bd7
26. Kg2 $16 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gf1d3,Gh2h4] Planning to start a slow kingside attack
with Bd3, g3-g4, and h2-h4. In the long run, this should provoke the weakening
of Black's kingside, with possible decisive implications deep in the endgame.}
a5 {This fails to equalize.} 27. Rxa5 Rxa5 28. Qxb6 Rxb6 29. bxa5 $18 {Due to
the support provided by the bishop, the a-pawn has a decisive strength.}) (
24... Rcc8 25. Bd3 $16) 25. Ra5 Rb8 $6 {Making things easier.} (25... Qxd4 26.
exd4 {transposes to a structure examined in the next example. As explained
there, the exchange of all rooks is likely to yield White a won bishop ending.}
) 26. a3 $1 {After defending b4, White wins the a6-pawn.} Ra7 27. Rxc6 $1 Qxc6
28. Qxa7 $18 Ra8 29. Qc5 Qb7 30. Kf2 h5 31. Be2 g6 32. Qd6 Qc8 33. Rc5 Qb7 34.
h4 a5 35. Rc7 Qb8 36. b5 a4 37. b6 Ra5 38. b7 1-0

