{[%evp 0,167,24,-16,32,21,25,20,14,12,28,14,16,4,4,13,5,3,14,-2,27,25,20,12,11,
-2,17,17,19,19,12,14,48,48,51,38,40,41,30,14,13,9,-7,1,16,1,5,3,15,18,28,31,38,
34,34,9,37,35,54,31,61,48,41,28,54,7,0,0,41,40,44,37,44,47,46,51,51,49,44,42,
42,45,50,51,45,40,37,49,50,59,56,56,62,62,62,71,77,77,77,75,71,71,63,68,63,63,
63,41,68,70,68,70,85,89,80,89,76,76,76,76,97,69,65,76,97,63,76,65,78,15,24,15,
24,0,0,0,54,0,13,0,0,0,0,0,0,43,165,179,394,422,435,487,691,728,701,811,851,
907,888,961,1157,1002,992,1014,2137,2246,29177,29974,29975,28935] As announced
earlier, we will examine a game that is relevant for ths endgame arising after
a queen exchange on d4.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. e3 e6 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. d4 d5 6.
cxd5 exd5 7. Be2 Bd6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. O-O O-O 10. b3 a6 11. Na4 Bd6 12. Bb2 Ne4
13. Rc1 Re8 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 Bc7 16. Qd3 Be6 17. Rfd1 Rc8 18. Qb1 Qe7 19.
Qa1 f6 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Bd6 22. Bf3 Rc6 23. Bb2 Rec8 24. g3 Ba3 25. Rxc6
bxc6 26. Bxa3 Qxa3 {At first sight, Black has an active version of this
structure. However, the weaknesses induced by ...a7-a6 and ...f7-f6 cause him
some problems. With his next few moves, Averbakh will take over the control of
the position.} 27. Rd4 $1 {Threatening Ra4, winning the pawn on a6.} Qa5 28.
Ra4 $1 Qb6 29. Qf1 $1 {The most effective way of preparing the queen's
centralization.} Ra8 ({Now is a case when} 29... a5 {does not work so well:}
30. Qe1 Ra8 31. b4 $18 {winning a pawn.}) 30. Qd3 Bf7 31. b4 {Getting closer
to the complete blockade.} Be6 32. Qd4 $2 {Averbakh correctly evaluated the
pure bishop ending as favorable for White but missed a small detail of the
position with rooks on board.} ({If he wanted to offer the queen exchange, he
should have prepared it with} 32. h4 {, taking measures against ...Bh3.} Bf7
33. Qd4 Qxd4 34. exd4 {We have reached the same ending as in the game.}) ({
However, White could have also continued increasing his pressure in the
middlegame.} 32. a3 Ra7 {Due to the weaknesses induced by ...f7-f6, Black has
to care about tactical dangers.} (32... Bf7 33. Ra5 Be6 34. Be2 Bc8 35. Rxd5 $1
$18) 33. Ra5 Bf7 34. h4 (34. Be2 {fails to win the pawn on a6 due to} Bg6)
34... Bg6 35. Qc3 h6 36. Rc5 Be8 37. e4 $18 {With queens on board, Black
cannot defend both his wings properly.}) 32... Qxd4 33. exd4 Kf8 $2 {Black
misses his chance to equalize.} (33... Bh3 $1 {Threatening ...Re8-e1 mate!} 34.
Ra3 (34. Bg2 $11) 34... Re8 35. Re3 Rb8 (35... Rxe3 36. fxe3 {Even this ending
is less dangerous than the game since White's structure is less flexible.}) 36.
a3 (36. Rb3 Re8 $11) 36... a5 37. Rb3 axb4 38. axb4 Ra8 $11) 34. Be2 {White is
in control again, but the technical process will be long.} Bc8 35. f3 Ke7 36.
Kf2 Kd6 {The king is hurrying to b6 to free one of the pieces from the task of
defending a6. In the next phase, Black might have done better by advancing his
kingside pawns, but that would not be complete without risk.} 37. Ra5 Bb7 38.
Ke3 Kc7 39. Kd2 Kb6 40. a3 Re8 41. Rc5 Bc8 42. a4 Bd7 43. Bd3 h6 44. a5+ Kb7
45. Rc1 Bc8 $6 {Now was the last moment Black could have advanced one of his
kingside pawns.} (45... g5 $5 46. h4 $16) (45... f5 $5 46. h4 g6 47. Rg1 $16 {
[%cal Gg3g4] preparing g2-g4. In both lines, White's advantage is indisputable,
but after the game continuation, Black will be simply lost.}) 46. Bg6 $1 $18 {
Averbakh proves to be aware of the danger. Before exchanging rooks, he makes
sure that his king will have a path for intruding.} (46. Re1 $2 Rxe1 47. Kxe1
g5 $11 {would reach a reliable fortress.}) 46... Re7 47. Re1 $1 Rxe1 48. Kxe1
Kc7 49. g4 $1 {A curious position. White has a blockade on dark squares on the
queenside and on light squares on the opposite wing. The pawns on f3 and g4 do
not count as weaknesses since they are not blocked and restrict the black
bishop. Moreover, the last move clears the path on dark squares for the king.}
Kd6 50. Kf2 Ke7 51. Kg3 Kf8 52. Kh4 Be6 53. Kh5 Bc8 ({Averbakh analyzes the
pawn ending arising after} 53... Bf7 {[%cal Gg6f5,Gf5c8] extensively. Black is
absolved of his queenside worries now, but due to White's numerous reserve
tempi (such as h2-h3), the endgame is hopeless anyway.} 54. Bxf7 Kxf7 {[%csl
Gf3,Gh2]} 55. f4 (55. h4 $1 {is an improved move order concerning Averbakh's
analysis as if} g5 {White wins easily with} 56. hxg5 hxg5 57. Kh6 Ke8 58. Kg6
Ke7 59. Kg7 Ke6 60. Kf8 f5 61. Kg7 $18) 55... Kf8 (55... g5 56. fxg5 (56. f5 $2
Kg7 57. h4 Kh7 58. hxg5 hxg5 59. b5 cxb5 {leads to stalemate!}) 56... hxg5 57.
Kh6 Kf8 58. Kg6 Ke7 59. Kg7 Ke6 60. Kf8 f5 61. gxf5+ Kxf5 62. Ke7 Ke4 63. Kd6
Kxd4 64. Kxc6 Kc4 65. b5 d4 66. bxa6 d3 67. a7 d2 68. a8=Q d1=Q 69. Qg8+ Kb4
70. Qb8+ Kc3 (70... Ka3 71. Qd6+) 71. Qe5+ Kc2 72. Qc5+ Kb1 73. a6 $18 {Marin})
(55... f5 56. g5 hxg5 57. Kxg5 g6 58. h4 Kg7 59. h5 gxh5 60. Kxh5 Kf6 61. Kh6
Kf7 62. Kg5 Ke6 63. Kg6 $18) 56. Kg6 Kg8 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gh2h4] White has to
count the tempi when carying out h2-h4 followed by g4-g5. He could play either
h2-h4 or h2-h3-h4.} 57. h4 $1 {As we will see later, the correct way.} Kf8 58.
Kh7 Kf7 59. g5 hxg5 60. hxg5 f5 (60... fxg5 61. fxg5 g6 62. Kh6 $18) 61. Kh8
Kg6 (61... Kf8 62. g6) 62. Kg8 $18) (53... Bg8 {runs into} 54. Bd3 Bf7+ 55. Kh4
{[%csl Ga6][%cal Ga6b7,Ga5a8] , when Black cannot prevent Bxa6 followed by Bb7
and the advance of the a-pawn.}) (53... Bd7 54. Bd3 Bc8 55. Kg6 {is similar to
the game continuation.}) 54. Bd3 Kf7 55. h3 Kf8 ({Black does not have reserve
moves, since} 55... Bb7 56. Bf5 Ba8 57. Bc8 {cages the bishop.}) 56. Kg6 Kg8
57. Bf1 Kf8 58. Be2 $1 {"Losing" a tempo with the bishop, in order to put
Black in Zugzwang.} (58. Kh7 $2 f5 $1 {frees Black.}) 58... Kg8 (58... Bb7 59.
Bd3 {threatening Bf5} Bc8 {transposes.}) 59. Bd3 Kf8 60. Kh7 Kf7 61. Bg6+ {
The bishop returns to the blocking square.} Kf8 62. Kh8 ({Averbakh indicates a
simpler winning plan.} 62. h4 Bd7 63. Bd3 Bc8 64. Be2 Kf7 65. f4 Kf8 66. g5
hxg5 67. hxg5 fxg5 68. fxg5 Kf7 69. Bh5+ Kf8 70. g6 Bd7 71. Be2 Bc8 72. Bf1 {
Black is in Zugzwang and will lose the pawn on g7 soon.} Bb7 73. Bh3 Ba8 74.
Bc8 $18) 62... Bd7 63. f4 {Gaining more space and restricting the enemy bishop
even more, for purposes revealed a bit later.} Bc8 64. f5 Bd7 65. Bh5 {A
waiting move, putting Black in Zugzwang.} Bc8 66. Be8 $1 {The key to White's
plan.} Kxe8 (66... Bb7 67. Bd7 Ba8 68. Bc8 $18) 67. Kxg7 {Remarkably, the
bishop is weaker than two pawns now.} h5 (67... Ke7 68. h4 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gf5f8]}
(68. Kxh6 $2 Kf7 $1 $11) 68... Bd7 69. g5 hxg5 70. hxg5 Be8 71. gxf6+ {[%cal
Gf5e6] Unfortunately, e6 is unavailable to the black king.} Kd6 72. f7 $18) 68.
Kxf6 hxg4 69. hxg4 Kf8 70. g5 Kg8 71. g6 Kf8 72. Kg5 Bd7 73. f6 Be8 (73... Kg8
74. g7 Kf7 75. Kf4 Be6 76. Ke5 {[%cal Gf7g6,Ge6f7] Black is not in time to
regroup with ...Kg6 and ...Bf7.} Bg4 77. Kd6 Bf5 78. Kxc6 Bh7 (78... Bd3 79.
Kxd5 $18 {[%csl Gd3,Gf6,Gg7][%cal Gd5c6,Gd4d5] followed by the decisive
advance of the d-pawn.}) 79. b5 $18) 74. Kf5 Kg8 75. g7 Bf7 76. Ke5 Bg6 77. Kd6
Bd3 (77... Be8 78. Ke7 Bg6 79. Kd7 $18) 78. Kxc6 (78. Kd7 Bb5 79. Ke7 $18)
78... Kf7 (78... Bc4 79. Kd6 {[%cal Gc4g8] The pawn on d5 prevents Black from
maintaining the blockade of the far advanced pawns.} Kf7 80. g8=Q+ Kxg8 81. Ke7
$18) 79. Kd6 Bf5 80. b5 axb5 81. a6 Bc8 82. a7 Bb7 83. g8=Q+ Kxg8 84. Ke7 {
[%cal Gb7d5,Gf6f7,Ga7a8]} 1-0

