{In the absence of minor pieces, the defensive task of the player with
semi-hanging pawns is easier. This does not mean that the position is equal if
he cannot put his pawns into motion. Here is a classical rook ending with this
structure.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Nf3 Nbd7 7.
Qc2 c5 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Bd3 g6 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. O-O
Bg4 14. Nd4 Rac8 15. Qd2 a6 16. Bc2 Qg5 17. f3 Bd7 18. Rfe1 Rfd8 19. Rad1 Qf6
20. Bb3 Ba4 21. Bxa4 Nxa4 22. Rc1 Nc5 23. Red1 Qb6 24. Ne2 Nd7 25. Qd4 Qxd4 26.
Nxd4 Ne5 27. b3 Kf8 28. Kf1 Rxc1 29. Rxc1 Nc6 30. Nxc6 {Finally, the exchange
leads to the familiar structure.} Rc8 31. Rc5 $6 {Despite White's hopes, this
does not force Black to capture the pawn.} (31. Ke2 $1 {was the way of
achieving that.} Rxc6 $2 (31... bxc6 32. Rc5 {transposes to the game.}) 32.
Rxc6 bxc6 $18 {With this occasion, we can also get acquainted with Black's
problems in the pawn ending with this structure.} 33. b4 ({Not the only move
order. White can also start with} 33. Kd3 {, since} c5 $2 34. e4 d4 35. b4 cxb4
36. Kxd4 Ke7 37. Kc4 a5 38. Kb5 {wins.}) 33... Ke7 34. Kd3 Ke6 (34... Kd6 35.
Kd4 f5 {fails to build up a fortress.} 36. g4 fxg4 37. fxg4 g5 38. e4 $18) 35.
Kd4 Kd6 36. e4 dxe4 37. fxe4 {Threatening to gain space with e4-e5.} f6 38. a4
h5 {WHite has to display certain accuracy now.} 39. g3 $1 {is correct,
maintaining the possibility of h2-h3-h4.} (39. h4 $2 {unnecessarily wastes a
reserve tempo. The pawn should reach h4 in two moves.} g5 $1 40. g3 g4 41. a5
Kd7 42. e5 (42. Kc5 Kc7 $11 {and White does not have reserve tempi.}) 42... f5
43. Ke3 Ke7 $11) (39. h3 h4 {deprives White of several reserve moves.}) 39...
g5 40. h3 g4 41. h4 Kd7 42. Kc5 Kc7 43. a5 $18 {The needed reserve tempo.})
31... bxc6 (31... Rxc6 $1 {would have ensured a much easier draw.} 32. Rxc6 (
32. Rxd5 Rc2 {offers Black}) 32... bxc6 {Due to the tempo wasted by White with
his rook, the king cannot reach d4.} 33. b4 Ke7 34. Ke2 Kd6 35. Kd3 c5 36. Kc3
h5 $5 $11) 32. Ke2 Ke7 33. Kd3 Kd6 34. Ra5 Ra8 35. Kd4 f5 {Taking measures
against e3-e4.} 36. b4 Rb8 37. a3 {White has a perfect blockade, but his rook
is stuck on a5. To create chances, he needs to clear the fifth rank with e3-e4.
} Ra8 $1 {The rook maintains some mobility only along the a-file.} (37... Rb6
$2 {is too passive.} 38. h4 $5 ({Putting Black in some sort of Zugzwang and
being even better than the immediate.} 38. e4) 38... Kd7 39. e4 fxe4 40. fxe4
dxe4 41. Kxe4 $18 {This is a great improvement over the game continuation.
With the rook immobile on b6, without chances for a quick activation even at
the cost of the a6-pawn, Black is lost.}) 38. e4 fxe4 39. fxe4 dxe4 40. Kxe4
Ra7 (40... Kc7 41. Kf4 Kb6 {is also good but requires certain accuracy.} 42.
Kg5 Rd8 $1 {Black needs to prepare ...Rd5.} (42... Re8 $2 43. Kh6 Re7 44. g4
Rd7 45. g5 Re7 (45... Rd5 46. Kxh7 {wins, because White was in time to bring
his candidate to promotion to g5.}) 46. h4 Kb7 47. Rc5 Kb6 48. a4 Kb7 49. a5
Kc7 50. Rc4 Kd6 51. Rd4+ Kc7 52. Rf4 Kd6 53. Rf8 $18) (42... Ra7 43. Kh6 Rd7
$11 {is the other way of reaching d7.}) 43. Kh6 Rd5 (43... Rd7 44. g4 Rd5 $11 {
still raws, but it makes no sense to lose a tempo.}) 44. Kxh7 Rxa5 45. bxa5+
Kxa5 46. Kxg6 c5 47. h4 $11) 41. Kf4 h6 (41... Kc7 42. Kg5 Kb6 43. Kh6 Rd7 $1
$11 {Of course, this idea is not easy to spot in the game}) 42. h4 {White
needs to clear a path for the king's intrusion.} Ke6 $6 {This offers White
some hope.} (42... Kc7 $2 {is bad due to} 43. Ke5 $18) ({It would have made
sense to keep the king close to the queenside with} 42... Ra8 $1 43. Kg4 Kd7 $1
{In the absence of the threat Ke5, this works.} (43... Ra7 $6 44. g3 Ra8 45. h5
Rg8 46. hxg6 Rxg6+ 47. Kh4 $14 {is less simple for Black.}) 44. h5 (44. g3 Kc7)
44... Rg8 $11 45. hxg6 Rxg6+ 46. Kh3 Rd6 47. Rxa6 Rd3+ 48. Kh4 Kc7 $1 49. g4
Kb7 50. Ra5 Kb6 51. Kh5 Rh3+ 52. Kg6 Rh4 $11) 43. Kg4 Ra8 44. h5 g5 $2 {
The losing move. Black should not agree on having such a weakness on h6.
Vidmar might huave hoped that this was a fortress, but it is not.} (44... gxh5+
$2 45. Kxh5 Rg8 46. g4 $18) (44... Kf7 $5 45. hxg6+ Kxg6 46. Kh4 Kg7 (46... Ra7
$2 47. Rc5 Rc7 48. a4 $1 $18 {threatening b4-b5} Rb7 $6 49. Rxc6+ {with check!}
) 47. Kh5 (47. Rc5 Rc8 48. a4 Rb8 $11) (47. g4 Re8 48. Rxa6 Re3 $11) 47... Ra7
48. Kg4 Ra8 49. Kh4 Ra7 50. Kh5 {The position remains difficult for Black.} Ra8
$1 (50... Kh7 $2 51. a4 Rb7 52. Rxa6 Rxb4 53. Ra7+ Kg8 54. Kxh6 Rg4 (54... c5
55. a5 Ra4 56. a6 c4 57. g4 c3 58. g5 c2 59. Ra8+ Kf7 60. g6+ Kf6 61. Rf8+ Ke5
62. Rc8 $18) 55. a5 Rxg2 56. a6 Ra2 57. Rg7+ Kf8 58. a7 $18) 51. Re5 Rb8 $1 {
The rook belongs to b6 now, providing h6 with indirect defense.} 52. Re7+ Kf8
53. Ra7 Rb6 54. g3 $5 {Creating some sort of Zugzwang.} Kg8 (54... Ke8 55. g4
Kf8 56. Kxh6 c5+ 57. Kh7 c4 58. g5 $18) 55. Re7 (55. g4 Kh8 56. Kxh6 c5+ 57.
Kh5 cxb4 58. axb4 Rxb4 $11) 55... Kf8 56. Re5 Kg7 $14 {There is no clear win
for White, but the position is no fun for Black.}) (44... Rg8 $1 {was still
the best chance, even though the black king is not optimally placed on e6.} 45.
hxg6 Rxg6+ 46. Kh3 Kd7 47. Rxa6 Rd6 (47... Kc7 48. b5 $18) (47... Rg5 $14) 48.
Ra7+ Ke6 49. g4 $14 {The difference concerning a line above is that the black
king does not restrict the white rook.}) 45. g3 Ra7 46. Kf3 Ra8 47. Ke4 Ra7 48.
Kd4 Kd6 49. Ke4 Ke6 50. Re5+ $1 {The black king cannot keep both wings
defended.} Kd6 (50... Kf6 51. g4 Ra8 52. Rc5 Rc8 53. Ra5 Ra8 54. Kd4 Ke6 55.
Kc5 Kd7 56. Kb6 $18) 51. Re8 (51. Kf5 Rf7+ 52. Kg6 {also wins.} Kxe5 53. Kxf7
Kf5 (53... g4 54. Kg6 Ke4 55. Kxh6 Kf3 56. Kg5 Kxg3 57. h6 Kf3 58. h7 g3 59.
h8=Q g2 60. Qd4 $18) 54. Kg7 Kg4 55. Kxh6 $18) 51... c5 52. Rd8+ Kc6 (52... Ke7
53. Rh8 $18) 53. Rc8+ Kb6 54. Rxc5 Rh7 55. Re5 Kc6 56. Re6+ Kb5 57. Kf5 Rf7+
58. Rf6 1-0

