{[%evp 0,56,38,28,28,6,6,6,44,44,53,42,44,-17,-14,8,8,18,37,5,31,31,28,28,41,
45,49,-2,46,21,32,-14,-8,-6,15,-32,-33,-45,-32,-53,-27,-47,-18,-55,-37,-21,-38,
-43,-130,-161,-120,-111,-74,-82,-101,-59,0,-20,-11] If the opponent fails to
submit the semi-hanging pawns to pressure and blockading, they are likely to
ensure enough central stability to their owner for starting a kingside attack.
Here is a typical example, played next board to mine by my team colleague Marc
Narciso.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. g3 Nf6 7. Bg2
Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 h6 11. Be3 Re8 12. Rc1 Bg4 13. Na4 Qd7 14.
Nxc6 bxc6 15. Qd3 Qb7 16. a3 Nd7 17. h3 Bh5 18. Rfe1 Bf6 {Black has displayed
his pieces actively and White still needs some effort to establish the
blockade.} 19. Qc2 (19. b4 Ne5 20. Qb3 a5 {yields Black excellent counterplay.}
) 19... Re6 20. b4 Qa6 21. g4 Bg6 22. Qb3 $2 {White delays his thematic action
too much.} (22. Nc5 $1 {was called for, even though this implies a pawn
sacrifice.} Nxc5 23. Qxc5 Qxa3 (23... Bb2 {is another good possibility.} 24.
Rcd1 Qxa3 25. b5 Rxe3 $1 {It is better to give up the rook for this bishop and
not for the other one, as after ...cxb5 Bxd5..} 26. Qxe3 Qxe3 27. fxe3 cxb5 28.
Bxd5 Rb8 $44) 24. b5 Qb2 25. bxc6 d4 26. Bf4 d3 $1 {The position is almost
irrational.} 27. Qc4 (27. exd3 $2 Bd4 $19) 27... d2 28. Bxd2 Qxd2 29. c7 Rc8
30. Bb7 {The tension does not get lower any single bit.} Bd4 31. Qxd4 (31. Bxc8
Bxf2+ 32. Kxf2 Qe3+ 33. Kg2 Be4+ 34. Qxe4 Qxe4+ 35. Kg1 Qe3+ {with a draw by
perpetual.}) 31... Qxd4 32. Bxc8 Re8 $13) 22... Rae8 23. Bf1 {Defending e2 in
anticipation of ...d5-d4.} ({It was too late for} 23. Nc5 Nxc5 24. Bxc5 (24.
Rxc5 d4 $19) 24... Rxe2 $17) 23... Rxe3 $1 {With the white knight on a4, the
black centre is still solid and stable. This positional sacrifice weakens the
white kingside decisively.} 24. fxe3 Bg5 25. Rc3 Qb7 {Transferring the queen
closer to the dark squares connected with the white kingside.} 26. Bg2 Qc7 27.
Rf1 Nf6 28. Nc5 {Offering White only platonic consolation. The knight does not
threaten anything and cannot contribute to the defence, either.} h5 29. gxh5
Nxh5 30. b5 {Under different circumstances, this would have yielded White a
clear positional advantage, but his king is too weak now.} Ng3 31. Rf2 d4 32.
exd4 Nxe2+ 33. Rxe2 Rxe2 34. Rf3 Re1+ 35. Bf1 Qd6 36. Qc3 Rc1 37. Qb4 Qd5 38.
Rg3 cxb5 39. Nd3 Bxd3 40. Rxd3 Qf5 0-1

