{Black's attack in the previous example has been a bit unusual and, for many,
unexpected. We will now examine a more specific position of this kind.} 1. e4 {
This time, we should not complain that the game did not start with 1.d4.} ({
The game is rightly classified under a 1.d4 ECO code, since the standard move
order is} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 cxd4 7.
exd4 Nc6 8. Bc4 Be7 {transposing.}) 1... c6 2. c4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. cxd5 Nf6
5. Nc3 Nxd5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. d4 e6 8. Bc4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Nxc3 11. bxc3 b6
12. Bd3 Bb7 {This is in fact, a theoretical position. Black is well developed,
but his minor pieces are passive yet. White's central pawns ensure him enough
stability to think of active operations on the wings. Sadly, Black is far from
establishing a blockade yet.} 13. h4 $1 {A dangerous positional pawn sacrifice.
White threatens Ng5.} Bxh4 (13... Rc8 14. Ng5 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 Qd5 16. Qg4 {
forces the weakening move} f5 17. Qg3 $16 {Poluljahov,A (2530)-Balashov,Y  
(2580) St Petersburg 1998 (½- ½ 26)}) (13... h6 14. Bc2 $5 {Threatening Qd3.}
Ba6 15. Ng5 $1 {with a huge attack.} hxg5 $2 16. Qh5 g6 (16... f5 17. hxg5 $5
$18 {threatening g5-g6.}) 17. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 18. Qxg6+ Kh8 19. hxg5 Qe8 20. Qh6+
Kg8 21. Rxe6 $18) 14. Nxh4 Qxh4 15. Re3 {White gains a few tempi for his
attack. Please note that the black minor pieces did not make any progress with
the blocking process.} g6 (15... Qe7 16. d5 Nd8 17. c4 $18) ({Another game went
} 15... Qd8 16. Qh5 g6 17. Rg3 (17. Qh6 $5 Qd7 18. Ba3 Rfe8 19. Rh3 f5 20. Re1
$18) 17... Qd7 18. Bh6 Rfe8 19. Re1 {AT this stage, it becomes obvious that
the black kingside cannot stand the combined pressure of all White's pieces.}
Qc7 20. Ree3 Ne7 21. Qg5 Nd5 22. c4 f6 23. Qh4 $18 {Poluljahov,A (2502)-Volkov,
S (2558) Tomsk 2001 (1-0, 42)}) 16. Rg3 {Threatening Bg5.} Qe7 17. Bg5 f6 (
17... Qd6 18. Qg4 $1 (18. Bf6 e5 19. Qf3 e4 (19... Na5 20. dxe5 $18) 20. Bxe4
$16) 18... f5 19. Qh4 Rf7 20. Re1 $18) 18. Bh6 Rf7 19. Qh5 f5 {Sad necessity.}
(19... Rd8 {allows White displaying his threat.} 20. Bxg6 $1 hxg6 21. Rxg6+ Kh8
22. Bg7+ Kg8 23. Qh8#) 20. Re1 Qd7 21. Qe2 $6 $16 {Starting with this moment,
White loses control bit by bit.} (21. Rxg6+ $6 {is premature and leads only to
equality.} hxg6 22. Qxg6+ Kh8 23. Bg5 (23. Qh5 $2 Rh7 $19) 23... Rg8 24. Bf6+
Rxf6 25. Qxf6+ Qg7 26. Qh4+ Qh7 27. Qf6+ Qg7 $11) (21. d5 $1 {was the
necessary preliminary step to the winning combination. The pawns stand nicely
on c3 and d4, but White needs to consider their potential mobility.} exd5 (
21... Nd8 22. c4 exd5 23. Bxf5 $1 Qxf5 24. Re8+ $18) 22. Rxg6+ $1 {With the
f5-pawn vulnerable and the e-file open, this wins.} hxg6 23. Qxg6+ Kh8 (23...
Rg7 24. Bxg7 Qxg7 25. Qxf5 {followed by a decisive rook lift soon.} Rf8 26. Qh5
Qf7 27. Qh4 $18 {with the unstoppable threat Re3-g3.}) 24. Qh5 $1 Rh7 (24...
Re8 25. Bg5+ Kg8 26. Qg6+ Kh8 27. Rxe8+ Qxe8 28. Bf6+ Rxf6 29. Qxe8+ {wins})
25. Bxf5 $1 {The point behind d4-d5!} Qf7 26. Bg6 Qd7 27. Bxh7 Qxh7 28. Qg5 $18
) 21... Nd8 22. Bb5 $6 (22. Qh5 Rc8 23. Qh4 $16 Rxc3 $2 24. Bb5 $18) 22... Bc6
23. Bxc6 $6 Qxc6 24. Re3 (24. c4 Qd6 25. d5 e5 $1 $14) 24... Re7 25. c4 Nf7 26.
Bf4 Rc8 $13 {Black does not have reasons for worry anymore.} 27. Rc1 Ree8 28.
Be5 Nxe5 29. Rxe5 Kf7 30. Qe3 Qd7 31. Re1 Rxc4 32. d5 Re4 33. Rxe4 fxe4 34.
Qf4+ Kg8 35. Qxe4 e5 36. f4 Rd8 37. fxe5 Qxd5 38. Qe2 Qd4+ 39. Kh1 Rd5 40. a3
Kg7 41. g3 Qc3 42. Qe4 Rd4 43. Qb7+ Kh6 44. Re2 Qxg3 45. Rh2+ Rh4 46. Rxh4+
Qxh4+ 47. Kg2 Qg5+ 48. Kf3 Qf5+ 49. Kg2 Qxe5 50. Qxa7 b5 51. Qd7 Qf5 52. Qb7
Qc2+ 53. Kg1 Qc5+ 54. Kg2 Kg5 55. Qxh7 Qxa3 56. Qd7 Qb2+ 57. Kf1 Qb1+ 58. Ke2
Qe4+ 59. Kd2 b4 60. Kc1 Kh4 61. Qd8+ g5 62. Kb2 Qe5+ 63. Kb1 b3 64. Qd3 Qe1+
65. Kb2 Qf2+ 66. Ka3 b2 67. Ka2 g4 68. Qh7+ Kg3 69. Qd3+ Kh2 70. Qh7+ Kg1 71.
Qd7 Qe2 72. Qd4+ Kh2 73. Qh8+ Kg2 74. Qh5 Kg1 75. Qc5+ Qf2 76. Qh5 Qd4 77. Qg6
Kg2 78. Qc2+ Kg3 79. Qc7+ Kf3 80. Qc6+ Kf2 81. Qc2+ Ke3 82. Qc7 Kd2 83. Qh2+
Kd1 84. Qh1+ Ke2 85. Qg2+ Ke1 86. Qh1+ Kf2 87. Qh2+ Kf3 88. Qh1+ Kg3 89. Qe1+
Kf4 90. Qf1+ Kg5 91. Qe1 Qf6 92. Qe3+ Kh5 93. Qe2 Qc3 94. Qe8+ Kh4 95. Qe7+ Kg3
96. Qd6+ Kh3 97. Qh6+ Kg2 98. Qe6 g3 99. Qe4+ Kg1 100. Qe6 g2 101. Qb6+ Kf1
102. Qb5+ Ke1 103. Qe8+ Kd2 104. Qd8+ Kc2 0-1

