{[%evp 0,64,28,28,30,23,24,13,6,20,22,18,68,21,21,21,27,27,27,30,30,38,47,47,
60,58,49,24,65,17,50,-2,-10,-31,15,-33,-30,-68,-68,-90,-90,-154,-193,-202,-205,
-228,-212,-195,-178,-178,-178,-220,-220,-218,-188,-276,-211,-231,-211,-244,
-250,-250,-250,-261,-213,-1432,-512] The section dedicated to strong
semi-hanging pawns cannot be too rich, since in such cases their owner usually
finds a good moment for advancing the c-pawn, reaching the hanging pawns
structure (examined separately). I would end this section with a piece of
warning. Even when unblocked and not submitted to the pressure of the major
pieces, such pawns can be vulnerable tactically. Here is a great example.} 1.
d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 d5 4. Nc3 c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bc4 cxd4 8. exd4
Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Nxc3 11. bxc3 b6 12. Bd3 Bb7 {The same tabyia as before.
The plan corresponding to the next moves had been designed and successfully
tested by Bent Larsen 8 years earlier and was considered to lead to a
promising attacking position.} 13. Qc2 g6 14. Qd2 {After having provoked a
slight weakening of the kingside, White re-directs his queen towards that area.
Looking at the position without calculating anything, it is obvious that
placing the queen in front of the (undeveloped) bishop is far from natural and
possibly bad. Larsen may have thought that White could afford such extravagant
play, because his central pawns are defending him against early black
counterplay and the temporary lack of harmony in his camp cannot be taken
advantage of.} Bf6 15. h4 {Another thematic move, aimed to weaken the
g6-square with h5xg6. This will lead to another loss of two tempos.} Rc8 $1 16.
h5 {Everything seems to be running according to the plan. White needs one or
two more tempos to start creating dangerous kingside threats.} Nxd4 $3 $146 {
What a shock! Remarkably, such an original thinker and dynamic player like
Larsen has overlooked the possibility of this tactical blow. It appears that
the white centre only apparently keeps him well defended. The sacrifice is
justified by the huge difference in coordination between the enemy armies.
However, we should mention in advance that White should not lose.} ({Larsen's
game went:} 16... Na5 $6 {(This move makes part of the general plan but is too
slow under the concrete circumstances and allows White to carry out his plan.)}
17. Ne5 {Immediately taking advantage of the fact that Black has somewhat
reduced his pressure against the central squares.} Bxe5 18. Rxe5 Nc4 19. Bxc4
Rxc4 20. Qd3 {With opposite colored bishops on board, the weakness of the
kingside dark squares eventually led Black to defeat in Larsen,B-Unzicker,W
Lugano 1968 (1-0, 36). And yet, this hardly is a logical outcome of the
opening since White has repeatedly violated the simple rules of development
during the first 16 moves.}) 17. Nxd4 {Forcing Black to sacrifice even more
material but he is ready to do it.} (17. cxd4 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Bxd4 {also leaves
White's pieces hanging.} 19. Ba3 $1 ({After} 19. Rb1 Bc3 {White loses material.
}) (19. hxg6 fxg6 $1 {helps the f8-rook come into play.}) 19... Bc3 {Under the
given circumstances, the queen occupies an optimal position on d2, keeping
both wings under control. Therefore, before deciding what to capture, it is
useful to force it away.} 20. Qe3 (20. Qe2 {allows} Qg5+ 21. Kf1 Qxh5 {with a
devastating attack, according to Ermenkov. A possible continuation is} 22. Kg2
Qg5+ 23. Kf1 Rfd8 {At some point, Black will capture one of the enemy rooks
and then insert one of his own into attack along the fifth rank.}) 20... Bxe1
21. hxg6 $3 {The only saving move.} (21. Rxe1 {leaves the bishops hanging after
} Rc3 22. Qh6 Rxa3 23. hxg6 fxg6 $1 24. Bxg6 Qd7 $19) (21. Bxf8 Bc3 22. Rc1
Qxf8 {Black is two pawns up, but White has not exhausted his resources yet.}
23. Ba6 {Is Black in trouble? two of his pieces are hanging.} Qb4 $1 24. Bxc8
Bd2 {A striking example of bad coordination. White has no intermediate move 
(or check) to avoid being left in an ending with two pawns down.}) 21... Bc3 (
21... hxg6 22. Rxe1 Rc3 23. Qh6 $18 {The threats Bb2 and Bxg6 are decisive.})
22. gxh7+ Kh8 23. Rc1 Bg7 24. Rxc8 Qxc8 25. Bxf8 Qxf8 $11) 17... Rxc3 $3 {
The point of the combination. Black sacrifices two of his pieces on
consecutive moves to remove each of the central pawns.} 18. Qxc3 (18. Be4 $5
Qxd4 19. Qxd4 Bxd4 20. Bb2 (20. Bxb7 Rc7 $17 {, with a double attack, leaves
Black with two extra pawns.}) 20... Rc4 21. Bxd4 Bxe4 22. Rxe4 e5 $1 {Black
will have an extra sound pawn in the double rook ending, but this will not
guarantee a win..} 23. Rxe5 Rxd4 24. Re7 Ra4 25. h6 {White has just enough
compensation for the material deficit.} Ra8 (25... Rxa2 26. Rc1 $11 {followed
by R1c7.}) 26. Rae1 Kf8 27. R1e3 Rxa2 28. Rb7 {Threatening Ree7 or Rf3.} Ra5
29. g4 $11) 18... Bxd4 19. Qc2 ({The slightly changed for setting the double
attack with} 19. Qd2 Bxa1 20. Ba3 {is ineffective because of} Qd5 {(Ermenkov)})
19... Bxa1 20. Ba3 $2 {Finally the mistake.} (20. Bh6 $1 Bg7 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22.
Qc3+ Kg8 23. h6 f6 24. Rxe6 Bd5 25. Re2 Bf7 26. Bc4 $5 $11 {Once again, White
has normal compensation for the pawn.}) 20... Qg5 (20... Qd5 {is slightly less
effective than in the previous line. With the bishop not pinned, White can
answer with} 21. Be4 {although Black remains on the top with} Qa5 $1) 21. Be4
Rc8 {Black has removed his pieces from the attacked squares and retains his
material advantage. White struggled for about ten more moves, but could not
avoid defeat. The complications generated by 16...Nxd4!! are not easy to
exhaust analytically, even if assisted by a computer. We can imagine how much
more difficult the task was more than 430 years ago.} 22. Qe2 Bxe4 23. Qxe4 Bg7
24. Qb7 Qd8 25. hxg6 hxg6 26. Qxa7 Qd2 27. Re3 Qd1+ 28. Kh2 Qh5+ 29. Kg1 Be5
30. g3 Rd8 31. Re1 Bd4 32. Qb7 Qa5 0-1

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "MUTUAL ISOLANIS"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "6k1/pp3ppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PP3PPP/6K1 w - - 0 1"]
[PlyCount "0"]

{Without being entirely sure about it, I feel that I have invented this term
myself. "Blocked central pawns" would be another denomination, but that would
not specify "the quantity" of pawns involved. In the introduction to the
Isolani, I have mentioned one typical way of reaching this structure. After
one of the players gets an Isolani, he forces his opponent to get one, too.
This gives some sense to the definition used here (irrespective of whether I
had actually read or heard this term somewhere). The structure is completely
symmetrical, but things can be exciting depending on the pieces left on board
and their activity. Maintaining the general structure of the previous sections,
I have started by examining a few typical endings, in which one of the players
has a "bad bishop". The drawish margin is quite wide objectively, but things
are not that simple for the defending player during an over-the-board fight.
With two open files available, the positions with major pieces only are
crucial. With minor pieces on board, the squares on e4/ e5 (and to a lesser
extent, on c4/c5) is important. I have examined games where maintaining (or
gradually increasing) the pressure for a long time proved successful. I have
also illustrated the opposite situation, when the active player makes too many
commitments, allowing to is opponent to organize effective counterplay.}  *

