{[%evp 0,113,40,25,38,9,10,27,27,23,23,11,13,13,13,27,59,31,45,29,32,32,49,49,
44,42,91,83,71,74,116,119,119,87,87,71,74,83,100,53,61,51,51,51,51,48,49,17,21,
-10,-10,-12,4,4,-1,3,0,0,0,0,1,0,0,0,0,-4,-1,-1,0,3,1,-5,0,0,0,0,8,22,22,6,22,
11,26,30,30,30,27,28,46,40,81,77,137,35,149,36,98,61,112,101,139,89,139,56,56,
56,56,38,41,53,55,55,56,0,126,126] We will follow the same pattern as with the
previously examined structures. We first of all need to find out the chances
yielded by having a good knight versus a bad bishop. Anticipating, I would say
that from practical point of view, the winning chances for the side with a
knight are bigger than against the Isolani or the semi-hanging pawns.
Objectively, these endgames should be drawn unless the player with a bishop
has too many additional weaknesses to take care of. I have analyzed the
endgame part in my book "Learn from the Legends". I have analyzed the whole
game for this electronic book and made many additions and corrections
concerning my old comments.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. d4 d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5
exd5 6. Bf4 O-O 7. e3 c5 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O cxd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. exd4 Be6 12.
Rc1 Ne8 13. Re1 Bd6 14. Be5 $1 {A strong practical move, inducing the
weakening of Black's kingside.} f6 (14... Bxe5 15. dxe5 $16 {yields White a
space advantage with chances for a kingside attack and pressure along the
d-file.}) (14... Rc8 $5 {might have been better, but it remains an open
question whether Black can maintain the tension forever.}) 15. Bxd6 Qxd6 16.
Qc2 $1 {Provoking another weakness. I feel Levenfish played the whole
middlegame with one thought: preparing for a favorable endgame.} g6 {From the
point of view of the endgame, this is bad, of course, since Black weakens the
dark squares. However, we are in the middlegame still and the alternative
would have been more dangerous.} (16... h6 $6 17. Nb5 (17. Re3 {is also good.})
17... Qd7 18. Re3 $18 {The difference concerning the game is that the black
knight is passive, not having the g7-square at its disposal.} Nd6 (18... a6 19.
Rce1 Rc8 20. Nc3 Rc6 21. Qb3 {[%cal Gc3a4] Threatening Na4-c5.} b5 22. a4 $18)
19. Nxd6 Qxd6 20. Qc7 Qxc7 21. Rxc7 Rac8 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23. Re7 Rf7 (23... f5 {
prevents Bg6, but weakens e5 and offers White a tempo.} 24. Rc7 $1 f4 25. f3
$18 {Black is completely paralyzed and the white king can march in to, say, c5.
}) 24. Re8+ Rf8 25. Bh7+ Kf7 26. Bg6+ Kg8 27. Re7 $18 {Black is once again
paralyzed.}) 17. Nb5 {Such moves are useful even when they do not yield
immediate results. Black will have to play. ..a7-a6 soon, after which White
will have the permanent threat of Na4-c5, taking advantage of the newly
created weaknesses.} (17. Re3 Ng7 $14) 17... Qd7 18. Qe2 (18. Re3 Ng7 $14) (18.
Qb3 $16) 18... Kf7 19. Qd2 a6 20. Qa5 {After wasting a few tempi with his
queen, Levenfish starts heading directly for the endgame. Objectively, this
throws away his considerable advantage.} (20. Nc3 Rc8 21. Bc2 {[%cal Gc3a4]
Threatening Na4.} b5 22. a4 $16) 20... Rc8 21. Rxc8 $6 (21. Nc3 Ng7 22. Na4 $16
) 21... Qxc8 22. Nc3 Qc7 23. Qxc7+ Nxc7 {WHite's position remains more
pleasant and in practice, Black's task is uneasy. However, the game should end
in a draw, objectively.} 24. Na4 Bd7 25. Nc5 Bc6 26. Rc1 Rc8 27. h4 Nb5 28.
Bxb5 Bxb5 29. Rc3 b6 30. Na4 Rxc3 31. Nxc3 Bc6 {We have finally reached the
endgame Levenfish had been aiming for. Black has a bad bishop and weaknesses
on both wings. However, the white king does not have clear possibilities of
intruding and Black's position is a fortress.} 32. Kf1 Ke6 33. Ke2 Kf5 34. Kf3
h5 {Abstractly, this is a small concession, placing another pawn on a light
square. Objectively, it does not spoil anything yet.} (34... a5 $5 35. Nd1 Ke6
36. Ne3 Bb5 {is more solid. The point is that} 37. g4 {, threatening g4-g5 in
a moment when the black king cannot advance, Black has} g5 $1 {We notice that
most of the black pawns are on "the right" squares.}) 35. Nd1 {In the next
phase of the game, White's maneuvers will be very instructive. Black can do
little else than sit and wait and White can coordinate his pieces the way he
likes.} Bb5 (35... g5 $5 36. Ne3+ Ke6 37. Kg3 Kf7 {is a safe alternative.} 38.
hxg5 fxg5 39. f4 Kf6 $11) 36. Ne3+ Ke6 37. Kf4 {The white king has advanced
with the help of the knight.} Be2 38. f3 Bd3 39. Nd1 {After doing its job on
e3, the knight returns to its previous location. As said, White is "playing
alone".} (39. g4 $5) 39... Bf1 40. g3 Bb5 41. Nc3 Bd7 42. g4 {White could not
hope to make progress without this move; tension is needed on the Kingside.}
Bc6 43. b3 $5 {This move, which aims to take the a4 square under control to
create the potential threat Na4, will provoke Black unjustified panic.} hxg4 $2
{A decisive concession.} (43... Bb7 $2 {runs into} 44. Na4 $18) ({From the
waiting moves,} 43... Ke7 $2 {is inadequate, too. True, the reasons are not
obvious yet.} 44. gxh5 gxh5 45. Na4 b5 (45... Bxa4 46. bxa4 Ke6 {The pawn
ending is won for White because he has enough reserve tempi.} 47. a5 $1 bxa5 (
47... b5 48. a3 $18 {does not change anything.}) 48. a4 Ke7 49. Kf5 Kf7 50. f4
$1 $18) 46. Nc5 a5 47. Kf5 Be8 (47... Kf7 48. a3 {is similar.} Ba8 {is the
only way of avoiding a transposition to the main line, but then} 49. Nd7 {
wins the pawn on f6 and the game.}) 48. a3 $3 {Curiously, Black is in Zugzwang.
} Bf7 (48... Kf7 49. Nb7 a4 50. bxa4 Bd7+ 51. Kf4 bxa4 52. Nc5 Bb5 53. Ke3 Kg6
54. Nd3 {Threatening Nf4 followed by the king's march to b4.} Bxd3 55. Kxd3 Kf5
{Otherwise, White will win on the queenside, which leads to disaster on the
kingside.} 56. Ke3 Kg6 57. Kf4 {with a familiar win.}) 49. Na6 {Black cannot
defend both his wings anymore.} Be8 50. Nc7 Bc6 51. Kg6 $18) (43... Kf7 {
is a much better king move. The interception of the diagonal h5-e8 is only
temporary} 44. gxh5 (44. Ne2 {planning Ng3} Ke6 45. Ng3 Be8 {and Black defends
successfully.}) 44... gxh5 45. Na4 b5 46. Nc5 a5 {We had something similar
before, but the evaluation is completely different.} 47. a3 (47. b4 $5 a4 $1
$14 {maintains the fortress.} (47... axb4 $2 48. Nd3 Ke6 49. Nxb4 Bb7 50. Ke3
Kf5 51. Nd3 Bc6 52. Kd2 Bb7 53. Kc3 b4+ 54. Kxb4 Ba6 55. Kc3 $18)) 47... Ke7 $1
{It turns out that this position, reached before with Black to move, is a
mutual Zugzwang.} 48. Kf5 Kf7 $11) (43... a5 {is another good move.} 44. Na4 b5
(44... Bxa4 $2 45. bxa4 {leaves Black with no reserve pawn moves.} hxg4 46.
Kxg4 $1 Kf7 47. f4 $18) 45. Nc5+ Kf7 46. b4 a4 $1 $14) 44. fxg4 Kf7 45. Nd1 (
45. Na4 Bxa4 $1 46. bxa4 {leads to a draw.} Ke6 $1 {is simplest.} (46... Kg7 {
loses, but this is wrong.} 47. h5 Kh6 48. hxg6 Kxg6 49. a5 bxa5 50. a4 {
The familiar Zugzwang patern. Black loses the pawn on d5, but this time not
the game.} Kg7 51. Kf5 Kf7 52. g5 fxg5 53. Kxg5 Ke6 54. Kg6 Kd6 55. Kf6 Kd7 56.
Ke5 {Now is a moment when Black n3eeds to be accurate.} Ke7 $1 (56... Kc6 $2
57. Ke6 Kc7 58. Ke7 Kc6 59. Kd8 $18 {wins.}) (56... Kc7 $1 $11) 57. Kxd5 Kd7
58. Kc5 Kc7 59. d5 Kd7 $11 {In the absence of the pawn on a6, White would win.
With two black pawns on the a-file, the time needed to eliminate them allows
Black to reach a drawn endgame.} 60. Kb6 Kd6 61. Kxa5 Kxd5 {Without the pawn
on a6, Kb6 would win now, but unfortunately} 62. Kxa6 {is necessary.} Kc6 $11)
47. a5 ({Black's idea is that after} 47. h5 {he can block the position with}
g5+) 47... bxa5 48. a4 Kf7 49. h5 Kg7 50. hxg6 Kxg6 {White misses one reserve
tempo to build the pseudo-Zugzwang from the previous line.}) 45... Bd7 46. Ne3
{The nice thing about White's position is that he can try to determine a small
concession on both wings without hurrying or caring too much about a
counterplay.} Be6 47. Nc2 (47. g5 $1) 47... Bc8 ({I am not sure why Kotov
refrained from} 47... a5 $5 {which would not have meant a weakness; on the
contrary, Black would have improved his structure. It would not change much,
though, as we will see later.}) 48. Nb4 Bb7 49. g5 {An important move: the g6
Pawn is fixed and the dark squares are put under pressure.} Kg7 50. Nd3 {
Levenfish plans to invert the roles of his figures: the Knight will be
transferred to f4, keeping Black's pieces passive, while the King will migrate
to the right to create some weaknesses.} (50. Nc2 {was the start of a simpler
winning plan.} Bc8 51. Ne3 Be6 52. gxf6+ Kxf6 53. a3 $1 {Zugzwang! Not later
than after one move, White will make kingside progress.} a5 54. a4 Bf7 55. Ng4+
Ke6 56. Kg5 $18) 50... Bc8 51. Ke3 Kf7 (51... a5 52. Nf4 {also wins.} Bb7 (
52... fxg5 53. hxg5 Bb7 54. Ne6+ Kg8 {The king has to avoid the fork Nc8+.} 55.
Kf4 $18) 53. Ne6+ {Same issue as in the previous line.} Kg8 54. gxf6 $18) 52.
Nf4 Bb7 53. Kd2 (53. b4 $5) 53... Bc6 54. Kc3 Bb7 (54... a5 {does not save:}
55. b4 a4 (55... axb4+ 56. Kxb4 {with zugzwang}) 56. b5 $1 {In my old comments,
I overlooked this resource.} Bxb5 57. Nxd5 fxg5 58. hxg5 $18 {[%cal Rf7e6,
Rd5c7]} Ke6 $2 59. Nc7+) 55. b4 Ba8 56. b5 $2 {This pawn break will turn out
well after Black's wrong answer, but he should have thrown the win away.} (56.
a4 $1 {was the right way of attacking.} a5 (56... Bb7 57. a5 b5 {leads to a
perfect structure for White.} 58. Kd2 Bc6 59. Ke3 Bb7 60. Nd3 Bc8 61. Nc5 Ke7
62. gxf6+ Kxf6 63. Kf4 $18 {Zugzwang.}) 57. b5 $1 Bb7 58. Kd2 Ba8 59. Ke3 Bb7
60. Kf2 {The simplest.} (60. Kf3 {allows Black to activate his bishop with} Bc8
{, even though this should not save, either.}) 60... Ba8 (60... Kg7 61. Ne6+
$18) (60... fxg5 61. hxg5 Kg7 62. Ne6+ Kg8 63. Ke3 $18) 61. Ng2 $1 {An
effective regrouping.} fxg5 (61... Ke6 62. gxf6 Kxf6 63. Ne3 {planning to
transfer the king to f4, followed by Ng4+ and Ke5.} g5 64. h5 $18) 62. hxg5 Ke6
63. Nh4 $1 {One of the ideas behind Ng2.} Bb7 64. Kg3 $18) 56... a5 $2 (56...
axb5 $1 57. Kb4 Bc6 58. a3 fxg5 $1 {Once again, this apparent concession is
necessary to offer some freedom for the black King. Other continuations would
have failed to save the game:} 59. hxg5 Kg7 {This is the difference; the check
on e6 is no longer dangerous: (60. Ne6+ Kg8 $11 (and I cannot see how White
can make progress; he has to take care of his g5 Pawn permanently...}) 57. Kd3
{"His Majesty successfully ended his mission on the Queen side; the signal of
the retreat was already heard. What are the concrete achievements? The b6 pawn
is weak now and the a4 square became available for the Knight. At the same
time, the c6 square is denied to the Bishop, who has only b7 and a8 left. This
creates additional possibilities of Zugzwang." (Learn from the Legends)} Bb7
58. Ke3 {"Black cannot improve the position of either of his pieces, because
his Pawns need permanent protection."} Ba8 59. Nd3 $1 {The knight is heading
for a4. Placed on the worse possible square, the bishop will fail to capture
the b5-pawn and defend the own d5-pawn by just one tempo.} Bb7 60. Nb2 $1 Bc8
61. Na4 Bd7 62. Nxb6 Bxb5 63. Nxd5 fxg5 64. hxg5 {White managed to win a pawn,
without allowing the slightest shadow of counterplay. The game is over.} Bc4 (
64... Ke6 65. Nc7+ $18 {winning the bishop}) 65. Nc3 Ke6 66. Ke4 Kd6 67. d5 Kc5
(67... Bf1 68. Kd4 $18 {followed by Ne4}) 68. Ke5 Ba6 69. d6 Bc8 70. Nd5 Bf5 (
70... Bd7 71. Ne7 $18) 71. Ne7 Bd7 72. Nxg6 Kb4 73. Nf8 1-0

