1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Ndb5 Bb4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8.
Nxc3 d5 9. e3 O-O 10. cxd5 exd5 11. Be2 Bf5 12. Nb5 Qb6 13. O-O a6 14. Nd4 Nxd4
15. Qxd4 Qxd4 16. exd4 Rac8 17. Bd1 Bc2 18. Be3 Bxd1 19. Rfxd1 Rc2 20. Rd2 Rfc8
21. Rxc2 Rxc2 22. Rc1 Rxc1+ 23. Bxc1 Nd7 24. Kf1 Nf8 25. Ke2 Ne6 {Compared to
the previous examples, White's situation seems less dangerous because his
Kingside has no weakness. However, we shall soon be surprised.} 26. Kd3 h5 27.
Be3 Kh7 28. f3 {From a theoretical point of view, the correct arrangement of
Pawns.} Kg6 29. a4 Kf5 30. Ke2 g5 31. Kf2 Nd8 32. Bd2 Kg6 33. Ke3 Ne6 34. Kd3
Kf5 35. Be3 f6 36. Ke2 Kg6 37. Kd3 f5 {During the last moves, Black has
systematically improved his position. Saidy limited himself to waiting moves,
relying on the lack of weaknesses. Little by little will become clear that the
huge space advantage is at least as dangerous for White as the disposition of
the h and g pawns on dark squares.} 38. Ke2 (38. g3 g4 39. f4 (39. fxg4 fxg4
40. b3 Kf5 41. Bd2 Nd8 42. Be3 Nf7 43. Bd2 Nd6 44. Bf4 Ne4 45. Bb8) 39... h4
40. Bd2 h3 41. Be3 Kf7 42. Bd2 Ke7 43. Be3 Kd7 44. Bd2 Kc6 45. b4 (45. Be1 b5
46. a5 b4 47. Bxb4 Kb5 48. Bd2 Ka4 49. Kc3 Kxa5) 45... Ng7 46. Bc3 Nh5 47. Be1
Nf6 48. Kc2 Ne4 49. Kb3) 38... f4 {***! As can be seen from the following
comment, this is a favorable moment for Black to declare his intentions
because the necessity of defending the d-pawn restricts the possibilities of
the white bishop.} 39. Bf2 {***Diagrama [#]} Ng7 {[#]} ({***} 39... g4 $1 40.
Kd3 (40. fxg4 hxg4 $19) (40. g3 Kf5 $19) (40. Kd2 Kg5) 40... Kg5 {><h4, /
\Ng7-f5, g3} 41. h4+ (41. Be1 Ng7 42. Ba5 (42. Bf2 Nf5 43. Kc3 g3 44. hxg3 fxg3
45. Be1 h4) 42... gxf3 43. gxf3 Kh4) 41... Kg6 (41... Kf5 42. Be1 Nf8 43. Ba5
Ng6 44. Bd8) 42. Be1 Ng7 43. Bd2 gxf3 (43... Nf5 44. fxg4 hxg4 45. Bxf4) 44.
gxf3 Nf5 45. Be1 (45. Bxf4 Nxh4 46. Ke2 Nf5)) 40. h3 ({Hard to believe, but
this is the decisive mistake; or, if we put it another way, this was the last
moment when I managed to find a draw for White. Saidy should have continued
his waiting tactic:} 40. Kd3 Nf5 41. Kc3 (41. Ke2 g4) 41... b6 42. Kb4) ({
*** In their "Winning endgame technique", Beliavsky and Mikhalchishin recommend
} 40. g4 fxg3 41. Bxg3 ({Remarkably,} 41. hxg3 $19 {would transpose to the
game Levenfish-Kotov}) 41... Ne6 {42.h3 (??) "building a fortress." The
fortress would break down after the rather uncomplicated 42...Nxd4+ and this
might be the reason why the comment was not taken seriously so far.  The
authors must have had in mind something like} (41... g4 {doesn't offer more
chances because after} 42. fxg4 hxg4 43. Ke3 {there is no way to make further
progress.}) 42. Ke3 Kf5 {(threatening g4)} 43. h3 {when it is hard to see how
Black can make any progress. White is coordinated well enough to control the
f4-square, while the general exchanges generated by an eventual ...g4 would
not offer winning chances because, unlike in the game Karpov-Kasparov, the
queenside is not blocked and the White king can generate adequate counterplay
if pushed away little by little from the d4-pawn.}) 40... Nf5 {(This is a real
zugzwang!)} 41. Kd3 g4 {Once the white King stepped to the left, this move
became possible.} 42. hxg4 ({You will probably be not surprised that after} 42.
Ke2 g3 43. Bg1 {the total (and ridiculous, I would say) passivity of the white
Bishop will lead White to catastrophe:} Kf7 44. Ke1 Ke6 45. Ke2 Kd6 46. Ke1 Kc6
47. Ke2 Kb6 48. b4 Nh4 49. Kf1 Kc6 {again zugzwang: White has to advance one
of his Queen side PAwns, opening the door to the black King.}) 42... hxg4 43.
fxg4 Nh6 44. Be1 $2 (44. Ke2 Nxg4 45. Bg1 (45. Be1 Kf5 46. Kf3 Nh2+) 45... Kf5
46. Kf3 Nf6 (46... b6 47. g3 fxg3 48. Kxg3 Nf6 49. Kf3) 47. Bh2 (47. b4 Ne4 48.
Bh2 Ng5+ 49. Ke2 Ke4 50. Bg1 Ne6) 47... Nh5 48. a5 $5 Kg5 49. g4 fxg3 50. Bxg3
$11) 44... Nxg4 {The ending has reached familiar contours: the position was
opened on the Kingside. The Queen side configuration favors White: a
counterplay is possible there. This is why Black has to win the g2 pawn, not
just to exchange it!} 45. Bd2 Kf5 46. Be1 Nf6 47. Bh4 Ne4 48. Be1 Kg4 49. Ke2 (
49. b3 Ng3 50. Bf2 Nf5 51. Ke2 Nd6 52. Be1 Ne4 53. Kd3 Kg5 54. Ke2 (54. Kc2 Kf5
55. Kd1 Kg4 56. Ke2) 54... Kf5 55. Kd3 (55. Bh4 Kg4 56. Be1 Ng3+) 55... Kg4 56.
Ke2 Ng3+ 57. Kd3 (57. Bxg3 Kxg3 58. Kf1 f3) 57... Nf5 58. Bf2 Nh4 59. Bxh4 Kxh4
60. Ke2 Kg3 61. Kf1 f3) 49... Ng3+ 50. Kd3 Nf5 {(This is the difference!
Because the Bishop doesn't defend Pd4, the King cannot return to the help of
Pg2)} 51. Bf2 Nh4 52. a5 (52. Bxh4 Kxh4 53. Ke2 Kg3 54. Kf1 f3 $19 {is easily
winning}) 52... Nxg2 53. Kc3 Kf3 54. Bg1 Ke2 55. Bh2 f3 56. Bg3 Ne3 {and
facing the threat Nf5 White decided to call it a day. There is a paradox in
this article. We have analyzed 3 drawish endings, won by the side with a
Knight every time. Were these games instructive at all? I believe so. All the
games were played very high, meaning mistakes were not casual. I am sure that
the reader will find more than 1-2 mistakes in my annotations as well. Those
acquainted with Botvinnik's writing, a monument of clarity and concision, will
have the sensation that the whole exposure could have occupied only one-third
of the space I used. The patriarch might have said with a brief smile: "Not
bad, kid, for your age". My main hope, however, is that I have passed the
reader the pleasure of examining this kind of position, which is much more
complex than they seem. As a last and decisive argument, I have also included
the game played by Botvinnik himself.} 0-1

