{[%evp 0,81,28,-11,18,16,21,30,30,16,13,-6,38,11,12,23,26,21,32,30,23,21,40,20,
21,13,43,28,46,59,59,30,46,37,39,16,10,27,45,30,30,31,30,68,62,21,28,0,40,127,
-15,-63,-43,-19,-90,-62,-90,-40,81,89,77,62,58,58,51,65,63,86,126,163,161,94,
150,75,139,125,245,229,265,267,237,245,237,299] Under certain circumstances,
the good knight versus a bad bishop duel can have decisive shapes in the
middlegame, too.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. e3 d5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. d4
cxd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. Bd3 Nc6 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Nf6 11. a3 b6 12. Bc2 Bb7 13.
Qd3 g6 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Rad1 Rc8 16. Bb3 Na5 17. Ba2 Nd5 18. Ne4 Rc7 19. Ne5 Bf8
20. Bg5 Be7 21. Bxe7 Rexe7 {In this Isolani position, Black seems to be well
regrouped, but his dark squares are weak. The next move, exchanging Black's
most active pieces, increases the significance of this detail} 22. Bxd5 $1 exd5
{The best chance. Black creates the possibility of displaying some activity by
means of ...Bc8 or ...Re6.} (22... Bxd5 {leaves Black with a beautiful but
completely useless bishop.} 23. Nf6+ Kg7 24. Qe3 $5 {One of the winning moves.
The main threat is Neg4.} Kxf6 (24... Nc4 25. Qf4 $18) 25. Ng4+ Kg7 (25... Kf5
26. Nh6+ Kf6 27. Qe5#) 26. Qe5+ {followed by the mate in two.} ({There is
nothing wrong with} 26. Qh6+ Kh8 27. Nf6 Qg8 $18 {, of course.})) 23. Nf6+ Kg7
{White needs to sustain his beautiful knights to prevent Black from pushing
them back.} 24. Qh3 $1 {After this strong move the f6-knight is taboo and
White already has serious kingside threats.} (24. Nfg4 {is too passive to
molest Black, who can equalize with a few accurate moves.} f6 25. Qf3 (25. Nf3
Nc4 $15) 25... Qd6 26. Qf4 g5 $1 (26... fxe5 $2 27. dxe5 Qe6 28. Qf6+ Qxf6 29.
exf6+ $18 {[%cal Gf6e7] wins material.}) 27. Qf3 Bc8 $11) (24. Qd2 $5 {is
another strong move, but only the second best. The knight is taboo, but the
queen will need a different tempo to join the attack concerning the game
continuation.} Nc4 (24... Kxf6 {leads to a beautiful mating end.} 25. Ng4+ Kf5
26. g3 $3 {A quiet move, typical for the mate in three problems. The threat is
Qf4, mate.} g5 {Black parries the threat, but blocks the square on g5 and
clears the b1-h7 diagonal.} 27. Qd3+ Kxg4 28. f3+ Kh5 29. Qxh7#) 25. Qg5 h6 26.
Qh4 Bc8 $14 {WHite's position remains more pleasant, but Black has achieved
certain progress.}) (24. Qf3 {fails to maintain the knights on attacking
positions.} Qd6 25. Nfg4 h5 26. Ne3 Nc4 $132 {with adequate play for Black.}) (
{The same move as against ...Bxd5 is ineffective now on account of} 24. Qe3 Re6
$1 25. Nfg4 Bc8 $11) 24... h5 $6 {This weakens the kingside too much.} (24...
Kxf6 $2 {remains impossible.} 25. Ng4+ Kg5 (25... Kg7 26. Qh6+ Kh8 27. Nf6 $18)
26. f4+ Kf5 (26... Kxf4 27. Rf1+ Kg5 28. Qh6+ Kxg4 29. Rf4#) 27. Re5+ Rxe5 28.
Nxe5+ Kf6 29. Qh4+ Kg7 30. Qxd8 $18 {Revealing one hidden drawback of Black's
regrouping superficially evaluated on the move 21: the queen is loose.}) (24...
h6 $5 {might have offered better chances for survival.} 25. Qh4 Bc8 (25... Qd6
26. Neg4 h5 27. Ne8+ {wins the exchange as} Rxe8 28. Rxe8 hxg4 $2 {allows} 29.
Qh8#) 26. g4 Nc4 27. g5 $16 {consolidating White's control on dark squares and
keeping his attacking chances.}) 25. Nxh5+ $6 {This looks promising, but after
correct black defence it should only lead to equality.} (25. Qh4 $1 {was the
most effective continuation of the attack! Before undertaking anything
concrete WHite should place his queen on a dark square.} Qd6 (25... Nc6 26. Qg5
{[%cal Gf6h5] threatening Nxh5+.} Qh8 27. Nxd5 $5 $18) 26. Nxh5+ $1 gxh5 27.
Re3 Qh6 28. Rg3+ Kf8 29. Rg5 $18 {with a decisive attack.}) 25... gxh5 26. Rd3
Qh8 27. Rg3+ Kf8 28. Rg5 Re6 $2 {This move loses for many reasons.} (28... h4
$1 {was the only defence ensuring approximate equality.} 29. Qf5 ({One
important point is that the white rook cannot leave the fifth rank:} 29. Rg4 $2
Rxe5 $1 30. dxe5 Qxe5 $1 $19) 29... Qh6 30. Qg4 Qh8 31. Rh5 Qf6 32. Rf5 Bc8 $1
33. Rxf6 Bxg4 34. Ng6+ Kg7 35. Nxe7 Be6 36. Nxd5 Bxd5 $13 {with roughly equal
chances in a complex position.}) (28... Bc8 $2 {fails to provide Black with
adequate defence.} 29. Rxh5 $1 Bxh3 30. Rxh8+ Kg7 31. Rxh3 f6 32. Nd3 {Black
has compensation for one pawn, but not for both missing ones.} Rxe1+ 33. Nxe1
Rc1 34. Kf1 Nc4 35. Rh5 Nxb2 36. Ke2 $16) 29. Qxe6 ({Even stronger would have
been} 29. Rxh5 Qf6 30. f4 Nc4 31. f5 $18) 29... fxe6 30. Ng6+ Kg7 31. Nxh8+
Kxh8 32. Rxh5+ $18 {This is good enough, of course. The connected passed pawns
are hard to stop.} Kg7 33. h4 Nc6 34. Rxe6 Nxd4 35. Rg5+ Kh7 36. Rd6 Rf7 37. f3
Nf5 38. Rxf5 Rxf5 39. Rd7+ Kg6 40. Rxb7 Rf4 41. Rxa7 1-0

