{[%evp 0,95,19,27,27,12,12,6,33,17,33,22,21,21,26,8,39,40,40,16,28,18,22,22,11,
-6,26,5,15,0,35,37,36,25,22,45,34,2,56,59,54,63,58,59,36,21,46,63,57,55,55,64,
63,57,62,51,87,87,83,88,83,95,93,91,156,185,173,165,183,166,174,173,214,194,
204,204,237,237,234,237,260,256,249,255,273,249,257,249,249,119,105,105,105,
107,107,107,107,149] The knight is not always stronger than the bishop in this
structure. Here is an example where the long-ranged bishop kept the knight
under domination, not without Black's help.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4.
e3 O-O 5. Bd3 c5 6. Nge2 d5 7. cxd5 cxd4 8. exd4 Nxd5 9. O-O Nc6 10. Nxd5 exd5
11. Nf4 Bd6 12. Be3 Bxf4 13. Bxf4 Qf6 14. Be3 {White has two bishops, but
being more active, Black can count on exchanging the light-squared one.} Nb4 $6
{The first step in the wrong direction. The knight was better placed on c6
than on b4.} (14... Bf5 $1 $11 {would have ensured easy equality.} 15. Be2 {
The bishop exchange would lead to Black's typical slightly more pleasant
position .} Nb4 16. Rc1 (16. Qb3 Nc2 17. Rad1 Nxe3 18. fxe3 Qe6 19. Bf3 Be4 $11
) 16... Nxa2 17. Rc7 Nb4 18. Rxb7 Nc2 $11) 15. Bb1 Bf5 16. Qb3 Bxb1 17. Raxb1
Qd6 {One gets the feeling that due to the sudden knight jump ahead, Black is
hanging a bit.} 18. a3 {A practical decision, but objectively not the
strongest move.} (18. Rbc1 $1 {would have offered better chances for a slight
advantage.} b6 19. Bd2 Nc6 20. Qa4 Rfc8 21. Rc3 $14 {with certain white
pressure.}) 18... Na6 $2 {This is a horrible and surprising move at this level.
The knight will never get back into play.} ({Black rejected the natural and
good} 18... Nc6 {because of} 19. Qxb7 {Instinctively, he should have felt that
losing this pawn is less important than maintaining the knight's activity. He
surely did not see the tactical resource} Nxd4 $1 {which is not the only
reasonable move, though.} (19... Rfb8 {is insufficient due to} 20. Qa6 $16) ({
But} 19... Na5 20. Qb5 Nc4 21. Qc5 Qd7 $44 {offers Black satisfactory
compensation for the pawn. The knight is stronger than the bishop and White's
queenside is under pressure.}) 20. Bxd4 Rfb8 {White must return the piece to
save the queen.} 21. Bc5 (21. Be5 $11 {is similar}) 21... Qxc5 22. Qa6 $11) 19.
Rbc1 $1 {Deliberately entering a lost position is one of the things not to do
against Carlsen. He rarely gives you a chance to escape in such situations.
This and the next moves aim to keep the knight isolated on a6.} (19. Qxb7 $2
Rfb8 20. Bf4 Qxf4 21. Qxa6 Qxd4 $11) 19... Qd7 20. Bf4 $1 Rac8 21. Qg3 $1 f6 {
Trying to restrict the bishop, but weakening the seventh rank.} (21... Nb8 $2
22. Rxc8 Qxc8 23. Bh6 $18 {wins the exchange.}) 22. h4 {Starting a positional
attack at his leisure, since Black cannot do much.} Rxc1 {Initiating a series
of exchanges, which only increase the significance of the knight's isolation.}
(22... Nb8 {loses to} 23. Bxb8 Rxb8 24. Rc7 $18 {as a direct consequence of ...
f7-f6.}) (22... h5 23. Rfe1 {leaves Black short of constructive moves and with
a vulnerable pawn on h5.}) (22... Rc4 23. h5 Rxd4 24. h6 g6 25. Rfe1 $18 {
Due to his poor coordination, Black will not be able to defend his seventh
rank and the king for too long.}) 23. Rxc1 Rc8 24. Rxc8+ Qxc8 {Earlier, White
was fighting with a queen, two rooks and a bishop versus a queen and two rooks.
Now it got to queen and bishop versus a queen. Perceptually, this is a clear
improvement for White.} 25. b4 b5 {Under different circumstances, for instance,
with the knight on c4, this might be just winning for Black. The way it is,
Black is helpless.} 26. h5 Qd7 27. Qf3 h6 28. Qc3 Qf5 29. g3 Qd7 30. Qc2 {
Black is in some sort of Zugzwang.} Kf8 {This loses a pawn, without promising
enough counterplay.} (30... Qe6 {, keeping c6, c8 and h7 defended, runs into}
31. Qg6 Kh8 32. Kg2 {, renewing the Zugzwang.} Qe4+ (32... Qd7 33. Bxh6 $1 gxh6
34. Qxf6+ Kg8 35. Qxa6 $18) 33. Qxe4 dxe4 34. f3 exf3+ 35. Kxf3 Kg8 36. Ke4 Kf7
37. Kd5 $18 {winning the knight soon.}) 31. Qh7 Nc7 32. Bxh6 Qg4 33. Be3 Ne6 {
The knight has reached a decent square, but the bishop controls his activity.
In the meantime, the white queen will cause damage to the opposite wing.} 34.
Qh8+ Kf7 35. Qc8 Qe4 36. Qd7+ Kg8 37. Qxa7 Ng5 38. Bxg5 Qe1+ 39. Kg2 Qe4+ 40.
Kh2 fxg5 41. Qb8+ Kf7 42. Qc7+ Kf6 43. Qd6+ Kf7 44. Qg6+ Qxg6 45. hxg6+ Kxg6
46. g4 Kf6 47. Kg3 Ke6 48. Kf3 1-0

