{Intuitively, I would say that a good bishop ensures fewer chances than a
knight in the fight with a bad bishop. The knight can confuse the opponent
with its unexpected jumping around, but the bishop's life is more "linear",
even though "diagonal". However, things are not always easy in practice for
the bad bishop player. Of course, one essential requirement is that the
defending side had additional weaknesses.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3
c5 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e3 Nc6 7. Bd3 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Qe2 b6 10. Rd1 cxd4 11. Nxd5
Qxd5 12. exd4 Bb7 13. Be4 Qd6 14. Ne5 Rad8 15. Be3 Ba8 16. Nc4 Qb8 17. a3 b5
18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. Bxa8 Ng4 20. Qxg4 Qxa8 21. Rac1 Qb7 22. h4 Rd5 23. Qg3 Bd6 24.
Qf3 Qd7 25. Rc3 Be5 26. Rc5 Rd8 27. Rxd5 Qxd5 28. Qxd5 Rxd5 29. Rc1 Bf6 30.
Rc8+ Rd8 31. Rc7 h6 32. g3 a6 33. Rc6 a5 34. Rc5 Rd5 35. Rxd5 exd5 {One brief
a glance at the position is enough to suggest that Black is not without
chances. All White's pawns are on dark squares, but except that on d4, they
are not blocked yet.} 36. Kf1 {White will constantly refrain from improving
his structure on the wings.} ({Now and later,} 36. h5 $5 {is natural and good.}
) (36. b3 $5 a4 37. b4 {secures the queenside, leaving Black short of
intruding plans.} h5 38. Kg2 Be7 (38... Kh7 39. Kf3 Kg6 40. Kf4) 39. Kf3) 36...
Kf8 (36... h5 $5) 37. Ke2 Ke7 38. Kd3 {Since the black king is heading for f5,
it is interesting to check whether White can prevent the manoeuvre. In the
following line, I will assume that White will not be willing to improve his
structure. The line is also relevant for the situations in which Black had
managed to block White's weaknesses in advance.} (38. Kf3 a4 39. Kf4 h5 {
White is in Zugzwang. He has to either retreat with his king or weaken his
kingside structure.} 40. f3 (40. Kf3 Ke6 41. Kf4 g6 {renews the Zugzwang.})
40... Ke6 41. Bf2 g6 42. Be3 Be7 43. Bf2 (43. Bd2 Bd6+ $19 {wins the pawn on
g3.}) 43... b4 $1 44. axb4 Bxb4 {[%cal Gb4c3] Threatening ...Bc3!} 45. Be3 {
The only way to evade the threat.} (45. Ke3 Bc3 46. bxc3 a3 $19) 45... f6 {
Threatening ...Bd6 mate!} 46. Bc1 Bd6+ 47. Ke3 Bxg3 $19 {It means that White
did not lose the game because he wasted time with his king. The main mistake
was that he did not care about the structure.}) 38... Kd7 39. Bd2 a4 {The
queenside pawns are blocked and White should have done something about the
kingside structure.} 40. Bb4 $2 {The decisive mistake.} (40. Ke3 $2 h5 41. Bc3
Ke6 42. Kf4 g6 43. f3 Bd8 $19 {leads to a familiar scenario.}) (40. h5 $15) (
40. Bf4 Ke6 (40... h5 41. Be5 $11) 41. h5 $15) 40... h5 $1 $19 41. Bc5 g6 42.
Bb4 Bd8 43. f4 {This looks like a horrible move, but White hoped he could
defend his fortress. Other moves fail to save anyway.} (43. Bc5 {allows} Ba5 $1
{, when White needs to care about the threat ...Be1.} 44. Bb4 ({Passive
defence does not help, either.} 44. Ke2 Ke6 45. f3 Kf5 46. Ba7 f6 47. Bc5 g5
48. Ba7 {The king has to defend the d2-square.} gxh4 49. gxh4 Bc7 {Threatening
...Bg3.} 50. Kf2 Bf4 $19 {followed by ...Bc1. In this line, it is obvious that
White has too many weaknesses on dark squares.}) 44... Bxb4 $1 {The pawn
ending is won, due to the superior activity of the black king..} 45. axb4 Ke6
46. Ke3 Kf5 47. Kf3 (47. f3 g5 48. hxg5 Kxg5 49. Kf2 f5 $19) 47... g5 48. hxg5
Kxg5 49. Kg2 Kg4 (49... h4 {also wins, due to the more advanced position of
the black king..} 50. Kh3 hxg3 51. Kxg3 Kf5 52. Kf3 f6 53. Ke3 Kg4 $19) 50. f3+
Kg5 51. Kh3 f6 $1 (51... f5 52. f4+ $1 $11) 52. f4+ (52. Kh2 f5 $19) 52... Kf5
53. Kh4 Ke4 $19) ({The king cannot get too much kingside activityȘ} 43. Ke3
Ke6 44. Kf4 Bb6 45. Bc3 f6 {Threatening ...Bc7+ followed by the kingțs
advance and ...g6-g5.} 46. g4 hxg4 47. Kxg4 f5+ 48. Kg5 {A desperate attempt
at getting counterplay.} ({Passive defence does not help.} 48. Kg3 Bc7+ 49. Kh3
Bd8 {Threatening ...Bf6 followed by the king's march to h5.} 50. Bd2 Bf6 51.
Be3 {The only way of crossing Black's intentions.} f4 52. Bxf4 Bxd4 53. Bc1
Bxf2 $19) 48... Kf7 49. h5 Bd8+ 50. Kf4 gxh5 51. Kxf5 Bf6 $19 {Zugzwang forces
White to retreat.} 52. f3 Kg7 53. Kf4 Kg6 54. Kg3 Kf5 $19) 43... Ke6 44. Ke3
Kf5 45. Kf3 Bb6 46. Bc3 (46. Bc5 {is most convincingly met with} Bxc5 47. dxc5
Ke6 48. Ke3 Kd7 {With such pawns as those on d5 and c5, reserve tempi are
essential.} 49. f5 $5 (49. Kd3 Kc6 50. Kd4 f5 $19) 49... gxf5 $1 {All other
moves lose, but this wins.} 50. Kd3 Kc6 51. Kd4 f6 $19) 46... Ba7 {Zugzwang!}
47. Ke3 Kg4 48. Kf2 Kh3 49. Kf3 f5 50. Kf2 Kh2 51. Kf3 Kg1 52. Ke3 Kg2 53. Be1
Bb6 (53... Bb6 54. Kd3 Kf3 {Zugzwang again. The only way of keeping the g3-
and d4-pawns defended is} 55. Kc3 {but it runs into} Ba5+ {winning the bishop.}
) 0-1

