{[%evp 0,79,17,-24,-12,-32,2,-4,14,2,8,-5,4,14,8,-1,24,24,24,39,52,39,44,35,38,
42,38,38,23,23,61,57,56,56,51,51,51,52,52,61,31,44,44,44,46,46,46,46,46,46,84,
64,74,21,17,20,52,26,89,60,77,77,93,93,93,89,96,93,94,94,94,0,7,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,
0,0] Due to the open c- and e-files, major pieces play an important part in
the fight with mutual Isolanis. This will be the case in this game, but the
preliminary part, transposing from a pure Isolani to our featured structure,
is also interesting.} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3 e4 4. Nd4 d5 5. cxd5 Qxd5 6. Nc2
Nf6 7. Nc3 Qe5 8. Bg2 Na6 9. O-O Be7 10. d4 exd3 11. exd3 Qd6 $6 {Too passive.}
({My opponent rejected} 11... Bg4 12. f3 Be6 {due to} 13. f4 {, but after} Qa5
{White's initiative is not easy to develop.}) 12. Bf4 Qd8 13. d4 {Black has to
fight with all his forces against the positional threat d4-d5.} Be6 14. Ne3 Nb4
15. Re1 {During the game, I thought that this developing move would be the
most precise move order, but I missed a hidden aspect. I overlooked a line
where the rook would not do much on e1.} ({The forcing} 15. a3 $1 {was much
stronger.} Nbd5 16. Nexd5 Nxd5 (16... cxd5 {runs into} 17. Nb5 O-O 18. Nc7 Rc8
19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Bh3 {with devastating initiative, for instance} Qd7 21. Re1
Rc6 22. Rc1 Rfc8 23. Qe2 Kf7 24. Rc3 $18 {followed by Re3.}) 17. Nxd5 Bxd5 (
17... cxd5 {is less effective than after the insertion of Re1 and ...0-0.} 18.
Qb3 Qd7 19. Rfc1 {Threatening Rc7.} Bd8 20. Rc5 Bb6 21. Rb5 O-O 22. Be3 Rfd8
23. a4 $16 {with overwhelming initiative.}) 18. Bxd5 Qxd5 (18... cxd5 19. Qb3
Qd7 20. Rac1 $18) 19. Re1 {I had reached this position in my calculation, but
underestimated my attacking potential.} Kf8 (19... f6 20. Qe2 Qf7 21. d5 cxd5
22. Qb5+ $18 {wins.}) (19... Rd8 20. Re3 Kf8 (20... Qxd4 {is as risky as it
looks.} 21. Qe2 Rd7 22. Re1 Qf6 23. Be5 Qg5 24. Bd6 $18) 21. Qe2 Bf6 22. Re1 g5
23. Be5 $18 {with decisive advance in development.}) 20. Re5 Qd7 21. d5 Bf6 22.
dxc6 $1 {The most convincing continuation.} Qxd1+ 23. Rxd1 bxc6 (23... Bxe5 24.
cxb7 Rb8 25. Bxe5 $18 Rxb7 $6 26. Rd8+) 24. Rc5 Bxb2 25. a4 Rc8 26. Rd7 h6 27.
Be3 $16 {Despite being a pawn down, White has a huge advantage. The a7-pawn is
doomed, turning my a-pawn into a dangerous candidate to promotion.}) 15... O-O
16. a3 Nbd5 17. Nexd5 Nxd5 (17... cxd5 18. Nb5 Ne8 19. Rc1 $16) 18. Nxd5 Bxd5
$2 {Returning the favour.} (18... cxd5 $1 19. Qb3 Qd7 20. Rac1 Rac8 $11 {
is only symbolically better for White.}) 19. Bxd5 cxd5 20. Rc1 {White has
advanced in developing at least two tempi, since he controls both open files
and the bishop on e7 is hanging. However, in symmetrical positions, this is
not always easy to convert into concrete.} Bf6 21. Be5 Bxe5 $6 {Offering White
another tempo.} ({While my opponent was thinking, I was more worried of} 21...
Re8 $1 22. Bxf6 ({I also calculated} 22. Qh5 Bg5 23. Rc7 g6 24. Qf3 Qxc7 $1 25.
Bxc7 Rxe1+ 26. Kg2 Rc8 27. Ba5 Re4 $13 {, without being thrilled.}) 22... Qxf6
23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Qa4 Qe7 (24... Ra8 $2 25. Qxa7 $1 $18) 25. Qxa7 {White has
won a pawn, but Black gets reasonable counterplay with} h5 $14) 22. Rxe5 f6 {
Black is forced to weaken his seventh rank, since otherwise, his pawn on d5
would be in danger.} 23. Re3 Qd7 24. Qf3 {Natural and good.} ({I overlooked
the merits of} 24. Qh5 $5 Rae8 (24... g6 25. Qf3 {is an improved version of
the game variation since Black's kingside has an additional weakness.}) 25. Rc7
$1 Qxc7 26. Rxe8 $16 {with a very unpleasant position for Black.}) 24... Rfe8 {
No matter which open file Black decides to fight for, White is prepared to
double his rooks on the other one.} (24... Rac8 25. Rce1 $16) 25. Rec3 Re7 {
Acknowledging that I do not have concrete threats yet, I gradually improved my
position.} 26. Kg2 Rd8 27. h4 Qe6 {Black loses his patience and tries to get
some activity. Truth be said, the neutral play would not have spared him
trouble, either.} (27... a5 {is ambitious strategically, but due to White's
superior activity is likely to turn this pawn into a weakness.} 28. Rc5 a4 29.
R1c3 Qe6 (29... b6 30. Rc6 b5 31. R6c5 $16) (29... Kf8 30. h5 $16) 30. Re3 Qd7
31. Rxe7 Qxe7 32. Rxd5 $16) ({Purely waiting play leads to similar
consequences.} 27... Kf7 28. b4 Kg8 29. Rc5 Kf7 30. R1c3 Kg8 31. b5 {followed
by a3-a4-a5 and either b5-b6 or a5-a6, with obvious progress for White. If
Black reacts with ...b7-b6, White's rooks get the c6-square for free use.}) 28.
Rc7 {It was hard to refrain from this active and good move. It more or less
wins a pawn by force.} (28. b4 $5 {was good, too. The point is that} Qe4 {
does not free Black.} 29. Re3 Qxf3+ 30. Kxf3 Kf7 31. b5 Rxe3+ 32. fxe3 Ke7 33.
g4 $16 {with a very pleasant ending.}) 28... Red7 29. Rxd7 Qxd7 30. Qf4 Rc8 31.
Rxc8+ Qxc8 32. Qd6 $1 {For Black, a painful invasion.} Qf5 (32... Qc6 33. Qb8+
Kf7 34. Qxa7 $18) 33. Qb8+ Kf7 34. Qxb7+ Kg6 35. Qb4 $4 ({Hard to say why I
did not see} 35. Qe7 $18 {, preventing the perpetual and retaining the extra
pawn.} Qc2 36. b4 Qc3 37. Qe3 $1) 35... Qe4+ 36. Kh2 Qc2 37. Kg2 Qe4+ 38. Kg1
Qb1+ 39. Kh2 Qc2 40. Kg2 1/2-1/2

