{So far, we have focused on positions with a reduced number of pieces, except
for Christiansen-Gheorghiu, which was a development of the theme of good
knight versus bad bishop. The time has come to investigate a few complex
middlegame examples. Much is decided by the mutual piecesț activity and the
active playerțs ability to restrict the enemy. Here is such an example.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 b6 4. Nc3 Bb7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 Be7 7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 c5 9.
O-O cxd4 10. exd4 d5 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Re1 Nc6 14. Bb5 Ne7 15.
Ne5 Bxe5 16. Rxe5 Ng6 17. Re3 {Here are a few elements defining White's
superior activity. Black's bishop is not only virtually "bad" in the
perspective of an ending, but also placed on a passive square, hitting onto
the own pawn. The knight's activity on g6 is relative and White will soon
restrict it with g2-g3. White controls the e-file. To play ...Re8, Black would
probably have to drive the enemy bishop away from the a4-e8 diagonal with ...
a7-a6 and ...b6-b5, but this would weaken the dark squares and turn the own
bishop even more passive than it was already. However, all these elements can
be transitory, so White has to play accurately to maintain some advantage.} Qg5
18. Rg3 Qf6 19. Qd2 Rad8 20. Re1 Bc8 {Black has progressed with his regrouping.
} 21. Qd1 {A somewhat mysterious move. In anticipation of Rge3, Spassky might
have wished to have free diagonals for his queen. Sometimes, the queen could
go to h5, a4 or b3.} Qf4 22. Rge3 Be6 23. g3 {Not only driving the queen away,
but also restricting the knight.} Qd6 24. Bd3 Ne7 {Black dreams of exchanging
the bishops after ...Bf5, but this is not easy to organize.} 25. Bb1 {Finally
a concrete plan. White prepares to set up the queen and bishop battery along
the b1-h7 diagonal.} Rfe8 $2 {This restricts Black's defensive possibilities
for some hidden tactical reasons.} (25... Rde8 $5 {is relatively best, for far
from obvious concrete reasons.} 26. Qc2 {Black has a choice now:} g6 (26... Bf5
$14 27. Qxf5 $2 Nxf5 28. Rxe8 {Without check!} Nxd4 $19) 27. Nb5 Qd7 28. Nc7
Rc8 $14 {and things are not that bad, as there is no rook hanging on e8.}) 26.
Qc2 Ng6 {Sad necessity. The knight returns to a passive square and does not
have any concrete ideas at all.} (26... Kf8 $2 27. Qh7 Ng8 28. Ne2 g5 29. Rf3
$16 {/+-}) ({If Black plays similarly as in the lines above, White wins by
force:} 26... g6 27. Nb5 Qd7 28. Nc7 Rc8 {and now the e8-rook is hanging:} 29.
Nxe8 Rxc2 30. Nf6+ $1 $18 {wins}) (26... Bf5 27. Qxf5 Nxf5 28. Rxe8+ {Unlike
in the similar line above, this capture comes with check.} Rxe8 (28... Kh7 29.
Bxf5+ g6 30. Rxd8 Qxd8 31. Bc2 $18) 29. Rxe8+ Kh7 30. Bxf5+ g6 31. Bc2 $18) 27.
Nb5 $1 {The threat Nc7 is stronger than it may seem.} Qb4 $6 (27... Qd7 28. Nc7
Rc8 29. Rc3 Re7 (29... Red8 30. Nxe6 Rxc3 31. Qxc3 $18 {wins material due to
the hanging knight on g6.}) 30. Nxd5 $1 Ree8 31. Nc7 Re7 32. Nxe6 Rxc3 33. bxc3
Rxe6 34. Rxe6 Qxe6 35. Qe4 $16) 28. Nc7 Nf8 {Equivalent to resignation.} (28...
Re7 {was no improvement, though.} 29. a3 $5 {[%csl Ge1] Forcing Black to
release the pressure on e1.} (29. Nxe6 Rxe6 30. Rxe6 fxe6 {[%csl Ge1] Due to
the hanging rook on e1, White does not have the time to take on g6. He can
take the pawn on e6, though.} 31. Rxe6 Nf8 $16) 29... Qd6 (29... Qa5 30. b4 {
traps the queen.}) 30. Nxe6 Rxe6 31. Rxe6 fxe6 32. Qxg6 $18) 29. Nxe8 $18 Rxe8
30. Qc3 Qb5 31. f4 Rc8 32. Qd2 Qd7 33. f5 Bxf5 34. Re7 Qxe7 35. Rxe7 Bxb1 36.
Rxa7 Ne6 37. h4 Be4 38. Qb4 Rc2 39. Qe7 Bg6 40. Ra4 Rd2 41. Qe8+ Kh7 42. Ra8
Bh5 43. Qg8+ Kg6 44. Ra7 Kf6 45. g4 Nxd4 46. Qd8+ Ke5 47. Qb8+ Ke4 48. gxh5
Rd1+ 49. Kf2 Rd2+ 50. Ke1 Nf3+ 51. Kf1 Nh2+ 52. Kg1 Nf3+ 53. Kh1 Ke3 54. Rxf7
Rd1+ 55. Kg2 Rg1+ 56. Kh3 Rh1+ 57. Kg4 Rg1+ 58. Qg3 Rxg3+ 59. Kxg3 Nd2 60. Re7+
Ne4+ 61. Kg4 1-0

