{A reliable way of restricting the enemy light pieces is displaying the
kingside pawns on f3 and, if allowed, g4 and h5. This is a committal plan,
requiring accuracy and alertness since the somewhat unusual development may
offer certain tactical possibilities to the opponent.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 7. g4 Be6 8. h4 Nd7 9. h5 Qb6 10. Rb1 Ngf6
11. f3 {So far, the game may seem irrelevant from our main theme's point of
view. But the structure will change soon.} h6 12. Bd3 c5 13. Nge2 Rc8 ({
It is a pity that Black did not transpose to our structure a bit earlier than
in the game, (} 13... cxd4 14. exd4) 14. Kf1 $1 {The rook belongs on h1, of
course.} O-O 15. g5 hxg5 16. Bxg5 Rfe8 17. Qe1 cxd4 18. exd4 {We have finally
reached our structure, but not before White has changed the kingside structure
a bit. Be it as it may, Black's minor pieces are passive and Black will have a
hard job providing them with some mobility.} Nh7 19. Bxe7 Rxe7 20. Qg3 Ndf8 {
Black concentrates his pieces around the king and seems to enjoy superior
mobility over his opponent whose king obstructs the rooks' communication. But
this can be solved very simply with:} 21. Kf2 $1 f6 {Everything is well
defended in Black's camp, including the g7- and the d5-pawn. At the same time
the queen's pressure on b2 and d4 seems to restrict White's active
possibilities.} 22. Bc2 $3 {The start of a great manoeuvre. The bishop is
heading for b3, increasing the pressure on d5 and freeing the b1-rook in order
to over-defend the d4-pawn with Rbd1, thus freeing the knight for Nf4. In
other lines, the rook could also go to g1, strengthening the attack along the
g-file. In other words, this plan removes all Black's reasons for the content
mentioned in the previous comment. I asked Rainer about his impressions of
this game, and he confessed that up to today he feels proud about his last
move. Improving the placement of an already well-positioned piece is a
difficult decision. Moreover, engines need some time to promote this move on
the top position of the available candidates.} Bf7 23. Bb3 Rce8 24. Rbd1 Ng5 ({
In his comments for the Chess Informant, Knaak analyses the following
instructive line, neutralizing Black's try to get counterplay:} 24... Re3 25.
Nf4 Qd6 26. Nfxd5 Re2+ 27. Nxe2 Rxe2+ 28. Kxe2 Qxg3 29. Ne7+ Kh8 30. Bxf7 $18 {
Despite losing his queen, White has a material advantage. On top, the threat
of Ng6+ is killing.}) 25. Nf4 Qd6 ({Once again the seeming active} 25... Re3 {
would be premature due to} 26. Nfxd5 {. The last move takes the black queen
out of the range of White's knights, thus making the threat of ...Re3 real.})
26. Rd3 $1 {Preventing the threat and leaving Black short of constructive
ideas. It can be felt that the d5-pawn will be doomed soon. This time engines
refuse to admit this is the best move, preferring Bb3-a4 with or without the
insertion of h5-h6, ...g7-g6, but this is mere misunderstanding since after ...
Rd8 they recommend Ba4-b3 and so on.} b5 {Black's activity has optically
reached a maximum, inducing Geller to start using his pawns for defence and
counterplay. This way of abstract thinking usually works out well, but only if
the position is objectively good. The game's ulterior course and analysis show
that despite his apparent harmony, Black has serious problems, making the last
move far from optimal.} ({Black would have retained better practical chances
to save the game by harassing White at least lightly. For instance:} 26... Qa6
{Attacking the rook and overloading the f4-knight.} 27. Rhd1 $1 Qd6 {After
having induced the rook to abandon the h-file the queen retreats to its most
natural square, creating the threat of simplifying with 28...Qxf4! 29.Qxf4
Nh3+.} 28. Kg2 a6 29. h6 {Before taking on d5 it makes sense to weaken the
f6-square.} g6 30. Ncxd5 Rd7 31. Re1 Rxe1 32. Qxe1 $16 {White is hanging a bit,
making the further progress a bit difficult. But Black cannot do more than
sitting and waiting.}) 27. Qg4 $1 {Removing the queen from an exposed square,
making the pressure against the black pawns real.. Against any knight capture
on d5 or b5, Black would dispose over the tactical trick ... Re2!+. When
playing the last move, Geller might have overlooked that White can neutralize
this idea before Black gets to play ...b5-b4.} Rd7 {No that the idea ...Re2+
is not available anymore, the rook moves on the d-file in the hope to
over-defend the d5-pawn.} 28. h6 {Rainer criticizes this move, recommending 28.
Ncxd5. That would be a good move, but there is nothing really wrong with
weakening the black kingside a bit, on the condition that White plays well
after that.} g6 29. Ncxd5 $6 ({But this is an inaccuracy, indeed, since the
d5-pawn was not running away. It would have been simpler to eliminate Black's
main source of counterplay with} 29. Nxb5 $1 {, for instance} Qa6 30. Nc3 {
and only later think of the central weakness.}) 29... a5 {Suddenly, White is
somewhat hanging due to the threat ...a5-a4.} 30. h7+ $6 {Rainer's criticism
on 28.h6 should actually be transferred to the second advance of his rook pawn,
unnecessarily exposing it and helping Black get his king into safety.} ({
It would have been better to evacuate the unstable square with} 30. Ne3 {
even though Black can hope to defend his position after, say,} Kh7) 30... Ngxh7
$2 {Being in severe time trouble, Geller forgets about the basic principles.} (
{Under no circumstances should he have cleared the h-file for the attack. After
} 30... Kh8 31. Ne3 Bxb3 32. axb3 {Black could win the h-pawn with ...Rxh7 at
the most favorable moment. In this line, we feel that White should evaluate
pawn advances with care before sending them into missions far from their own
house.}) 31. Nxg6 $1 $138 {While looking for a way out of trouble, Geller lost
on time, but his position was close to losing. Knaak analysis the following
line:} Nxg6 32. Ne7+ $1 {Clearing the bishop's diagonal with gain of time.}
Rexe7 33. Qxg6+ Kf8 34. Qh6+ Ke8 35. Qxh7 Kd8 36. Bxf7 Rxf7 37. Qf5 $18 {
Black is a pawn down and his king is more vulnerable than White;s, for instance
} Rg7 38. f4 {and Black does not have any other idea for counter-attacking.}
1-0

