{[%evp 0,83,19,38,100,21,23,-24,-22,-15,0,-6,-7,7,39,42,51,40,43,29,33,20,38,
32,32,29,19,19,32,25,56,38,26,29,29,6,2,2,-6,-6,0,-18,-12,-39,-14,-22,-23,-15,
-2,-48,-4,-15,-23,-36,-10,1,-11,-2,-9,-31,-19,-14,43,4,3,0,0,83,83,104,104,113,
113,114,212,233,267,319,408,417,827,937,1103,1331,1684,29988] We will now
examine two games featuring a complex struggle. By contrast, in the first of
them, the more active side will eventually outplay the opponent from an almost
equal position, while in the second one, counterplay proved more effective
than positional pressure.} 1. e4 c5 2. c3 d5 3. exd5 Qxd5 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 Nc6
6. Be2 cxd4 7. cxd4 e6 8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 Qd6 10. Nb5 Qd8 11. Bf4 Nd5 12. Bg3 a6
13. Nc3 O-O 14. Rc1 Nf6 15. h3 b6 16. a3 Bb7 17. Bd3 Rc8 18. Bb1 b5 19. Qd3 Na5
20. Ne5 Nc4 21. Rc2 Nd6 22. f3 g6 23. Bf2 Re8 24. Ba2 Bf8 25. Re2 Bg7 26. Rfe1
Nd5 {After 20 moves of maneuvering with an Isolani, White decides to change
the structure.} 27. Nxd5 exd5 {An interesting moment.} (27... Bxd5 28. Bxd5
exd5 {may seem more natural and better since Black rids himself of the "bad."
bishop. However, bad bishops defend good pawns (as GM Mihai Suba used to say).
After this exchange,} 29. Qb3 {is very unpleasant.} Bxe5 {The only way of
saving the d5-pawn.} ({The point is that the natural} 29... Nc4 $2 {or any
other knight move runs into} 30. Nxf7 $1 $18) 30. dxe5 Nf5 {The best square
for the knight. It controls d4, may contribute to slowing down the white
majority and has the possibility of regrouping to the blocking square on e6.} (
30... Nc4 $6 31. f4 $16) 31. Rd2 $14 {Due to the vulnerable pawn on d5 and the
weakness of Black's kingside dark squares, White's position is preferable.}) {
White's position is more active, but Black is well regrouped and should not
fear anything.} 28. Qd1 $5 {We are familiar with this mysterious queen retreat
from the game Spassky-Portisch. In this case, it just places the queen on a
passive square. Judit intended to transfer the knight to c5, but she will
never carry out this maneuver.} ({The immediate} 28. h4 {might have been
better.}) 28... a5 {Black takes the a-pawn out of the enemy knight's range,
while preparing to set up a queenside blockade with ...a5-a4.} (28... Nc4 $2 {
remains impossible due to the familiar} 29. Nxf7 $1 $18) (28... Rc7 $5 {
connecting the rook with the kingside and clearing the square on c8 with the
bishop might have been more to the point.} 29. h4 ({Alternatively,} 29. Nd3
Rxe2 30. Rxe2 Re7 31. Nc5 Rxe2 32. Qxe2 Bc8 {The pawn on d5 is not too tasty,
since} 33. Bxd5 {can be answered with} Bxh3 $5 {or the simple33...Nf5.}) 29...
h5 30. Qd2 Nc4 31. Qf4 Re6 {Continuing to consolidate the kingside.} 32. Bb1
Bc8 $5 $11) 29. h4 $1 {There was no concrete way of gaining a concrete
advantage. Therefore, throwing the h-pawn into the fight is the best practical
idea.} (29. Nd3 {is effective.} Rxe2 30. Rxe2 a4 31. Nc5 Bc6 32. h4 h5 33. Qd2
Nc4 $11) 29... Qc7 $6 {Black's main mistake in this game. It spoils Black's
coordination and does not take measures against White's threats.} (29... h5 $1
{weakens the g6-square, but Black can live with it.} 30. Qd2 a4 (30... Nc4 31.
Qf4 Qc7 32. Bb1 $16) 31. Bb1 Rc7 {with a familiar scenario.}) 30. h5 {White
has realistic attacking chances already. One Idea is to open the h-line with
31.h5xg6 and to start an attack in the h-line with Kg2 and doubling in the
h-line. Additional the bishop on a2 can go to b1 with the theat to sacrifice
something on g6.} Nc4 $2 {This move has created additional tension, something
Black is not prepared for.} 31. h6 $1 {The best way of making use of the
tension. All Black's reasonable moves have drawbacks. The point is that the
bishop was optimally placed on g7.} (31. Bxc4 {This intermediate exchange
would make sense only if followed by the same move as in the game, but it is
better to delay this decision for the time being, as the tension could work
for White differently.} bxc4 32. h6 $16) 31... Bxh6 {This yields White strong
initiative, but there was no easy way out of the trouble.} (31... Bxe5 $2 32.
dxe5 $18 {is likely to yield White a decisive attack.}) (31... Bh8 $2 {runs
into} 32. Nxc4 Rxe2 33. Qxe2 bxc4 34. Qe8+ Rxe8 35. Rxe8#) (31... Bf8 {maybe
safest, but no entirely satisfactory, either.} 32. Bxc4 (32. Ng4 Rxe2 33. Qxe2
$16 {White has an advantage on the black squares.}) 32... bxc4 (32... dxc4 33.
d5 $18 {or Ng4 with decisive initiative.}) 33. Bg3 $16) 32. Ng4 $1 {This
obvious move yields White a huge advantage, even though things will settle
down a bit later.} Rxe2 33. Nxh6+ Kg7 {This is the last important moment. Only
one of three reasonable moves ensures White an overwhelming, maybe decisive,
advantage.} 34. Rxe2 $1 {Correctly anticipating the following phase.} (34. Nf5+
$5 {Judit mentions this as an interesting alternative, but it does not bother
Black that much.} gxf5 35. Qxe2 {White's position is more pleasant, but the
game is very much on.}) (34. Qxe2 {This natural move, immediately setting up
the battery along the e-file, is not too threatening.} Kxh6 35. Bh4 Kg7 $13 {
(Polgar)}) 34... Kxh6 35. Qe1 $1 {The most effective way of setting up the
battery along the e-file. The queen also cooperates with the bishop and the
threats Re7 and Bg3 are hard to meet. It may be not that obvious optically yet,
but Black is in big trouble despite his extra pawn.} Kg7 (35... Qd6 36. Re7 Rc7
37. Rxc7 Qxc7 38. Qc1+ {The queen's versatility is awesome.} Kg7 39. b3 $18)
36. Re7 Qb6 (36... Qc6 37. Bxc4 dxc4 38. Qe5+ Kg8 39. Be3 Qd5 (39... f6 40. Qh2
$1 h5 41. Qg3 $18) 40. Qf6 $18) 37. Bxc4 bxc4 38. Qe5+ Kg8 39. Be3 $18 {
Threatening Bh6} f6 40. Qf4 {Threatening Qh6.} Kf8 (40... g5 41. Qh2 $18) 41.
Rxh7 Ke8 42. Qh6 1-0

