{[%evp 0,70,19,31,14,30,28,9,34,0,19,25,12,3,10,0,21,-6,-3,-5,5,-11,-5,-50,-37,
-22,-13,-5,-3,-3,4,-17,16,4,10,27,66,-10,31,22,37,37,55,39,47,54,21,16,27,13,
22,0,16,31,35,6,26,13,21,-23,-30,-134,-95,-136,-143,-169,-169,-142,-150,-256,
-288,-278,-278] This game illustrates an important aspect. The active side
should handle structural expansion care, since this will likely leave him with
permanent weaknesses.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. e3 c5 4. b3 b6 5. Bd3 Bb7 6. O-O
Be7 7. Bb2 O-O 8. c4 cxd4 9. exd4 d5 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Qe2 $6 {Slightly careless.
} ({White should prefer, when after} 11. Rc1 Nb4 12. Bb1 {White does not need
to play a2-a3 too soon.}) 11... Nb4 $1 {I was playing on the next board, and
after the game, Suba's confessed to me that Alekhine described this method of
play: the knight provokes the weakening move a2-a3, in order to later jump to
a5 and put pressure on the white queenside. For didactic reasons, it would
have been better if this had happened after exd5, .. .cxd5. We had a similar
situation in Levenfish-Kotov (Nb5 provoking ...a7-a6).} 12. Bb1 Rc8 13. Rd1 Re8
14. Ne5 {As we will see, the advanced position of the knight will later force
White to weaken even more squares. However, at present this move is necessary.}
({Indeed, after} 14. a3 Nc6 {(planing ... Na5)} 15. cxd5 {Black can safely
answer} Nxd5) 14... Bf8 15. a3 Nc6 16. cxd5 {White needs to release the
tension.} ({If he consolidates his d4-pawn with} 16. Qe3 {, Black can develop
his initiative with} Na5 17. Ba2 Nd7 {when the b3- and c4-pawns would be under
strong pressure.}) 16... exd5 {We have fially reached our featured structure.}
({The point behind 14.Ne5 is that} 16... Nxd5 $2 {loses to} 17. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7
18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Qxf7+ Kh7 20. Qxb7 $18) 17. Bf5 Rc7 {The situation in the
centre has stabilized, but White needs a solution against ...Nc6-a5.} 18. b4 {
A convenient solution at this height of the game, but in the long run the
weakness of the c4-square may tell.} Rce7 {Forcing the weakening of the
e4-square as well.} 19. f4 {We can summarize the consequences of the knight
jump to b4. White's position looks more active, but he has no clear targets
yet. At the same time, the weakness of his light squares cannot be repaired in
any way and offers Black good prospects in the long run.} g6 20. Bc2 Qd6 21.
Bb3 Bg7 22. Qf3 Nd8 $5 {Heading for e6 and clearing the c-file for the rooks.}
23. Rac1 a6 24. b5 a5 25. a4 {White plays too mildly, probably thinking that
his space advantage ensures him against trouble.} ({He should have thought of
concrete action, for instance} 25. f5 $5 gxf5 26. Qxf5 Rxe5 27. dxe5 Rxe5 28.
Qh3 (28. Qf2 $2 Ng4 $19) (28. Qf3 d4 $19) 28... Rh5 29. Ne4 Rxh3 30. Nxd6 Rxb3
31. Nxb7 Rxb2 $44) 25... Rc7 26. Nb1 {A clear hint that White failed to find
an active plan. The last move signals simplifications, allowing Black to take
over the initiative.} Rxc1 27. Rxc1 Ne6 28. g3 {Yet another small weakness.}
Qb4 29. Qd3 Ne4 $1 $17 {Black has occupied one of the weak central squares
with all the comfort. White may have hoped that since the other knight cannot
get to c4 easily, his position would remain holdable.} 30. Rd1 $6 N6c5 $1 $19 {
This simple tactical operation is an even better plan than the one mentioned
above. It is instructive that the knight who had indirectly provoked the
gradual deterioration of the white structure delivers the decisive blow.} 31.
dxc5 Nxc5 32. Ba3 Nxd3 33. Bxb4 Nxb4 34. Nd7 Re3 35. Nd2 Bc3 0-1

