{[%evp 0,77,30,24,30,-1,6,4,29,25,30,17,19,15,24,10,19,17,19,19,19,19,19,-12,
33,-20,13,13,5,0,20,14,40,39,53,5,42,2,28,44,36,32,51,58,53,41,67,64,66,46,62,
47,47,-3,0,0,0,5,7,14,18,6,5,5,0,9,8,8,12,12,4,0,-1,0,206,197,231,236,310,279]
The hanging pawns structure does not feature completely open files, making the
exchange of all rooks difficult. Therefore, purely minor pieces endings with
this structure are extremely rare. The only realistic scenario is featured by
this game, in which White will get an optically promising position with a good
knight against an only theoretically bad bishop. This game will open the
section dedicated to the situations when the player with hanging pawns advance
the c-pawn, either being forced to, or in order to restrict the opponent's
pieces or start an attack.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O
6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Qa4 c5 12. Qa3
Be6 13. Rc1 Nd7 14. Bb5 Rfc8 15. O-O Kf8 16. dxc5 Rxc5 17. Bxd7 Bxd7 18. Rc3
Rxc3 19. Qxc3 Rc8 20. Qd2 Bb5 21. Rd1 Bc6 22. h3 Bb7 23. Nd4 a6 24. Rc1 Rxc1+
25. Qxc1 Qc5 26. Qxc5+ bxc5 {This is the aforementioned scenario: the players
first exchanged rooks and only then transposed to our featured structure.} 27.
Nb3 c4 {Forcing the advance of the c-pawn is an achievement for White in many
positions with hanging pawns, but here it does not offer him much.} 28. Nd4 {
It is worth knowing that this ending does not offer more winning chances for
the player with a knight than the Isolani endgame from the game
Flohr-Capablanca.} g6 29. Kf1 Ke7 30. Ke2 Kd6 31. Kd2 Bc8 32. Kc3 Kc5 {White
has reached maximum activity, with his pieces blocking the central pawns.
Unfortunately, the king cannot advance to d4 under favorable circumstances.}
33. Nf3 {The kingside diversion initiated by this move will eventually be
successful.} (33. b4+ cxb3 34. Nxb3+ (34. Kxb3 g5 $5 $11) 34... Kb5 {does not
offer chances for a white advantage. In the event of} 35. Kd4 {, Black can
start his queenside counterplay with} Kb4 $11) 33... g5 (33... Be6 $11) (33...
f6 $11) 34. Ne5 Be6 $1 {The only move.} (34... f6 35. Ng4 $1 {with a double
attack, wins, since after} Bxg4 36. hxg4 {White has more reserve tempi than
Black.} a5 37. a3 a4 38. f3 Kb5 39. Kd4 Kc6 40. e4 dxe4 41. fxe4 $1 (41. Kxe4 {
leads by force to a theoretical drawn ending:} Kc5 42. g3 c3 $1 43. bxc3 Kc4
44. Kf5 Kxc3 45. Kxf6 Kb3 46. f4 Kxa3 47. f5 Kb3 48. Kg6 a3 49. f6 a2 50. f7
a1=Q 51. f8=Q Qc3 52. Kxh6 Qxg3 53. Kxg5 Qe5+ {Black will be struggling for a
long time, of course, but the correct defense should yield him half a point.})
41... Kb5 42. Kd5 $18) 35. Ng4 h5 ({As we know} 35... Bxg4 $2 36. hxg4 $18 {
is bad for Black.}) 36. Nf6 g4 $2 {A huge mistake.} (36... h4 $1 {draws
without too many problems.} 37. Nh7 g4 38. hxg4 Bxg4 39. Ng5 f6 (39... a5 $5 {
is also possible, since} 40. Nxf7 $2 {runs into} Bf3 $1 $19) 40. Nh3 Bxh3 (
40... Be6 {is also possible.} 41. Nf4 Bf7 42. f3 a5 43. a3 a4 $11 {White
cannot put Black in Zugzwang to advance with the king to d4.}) 41. gxh3 {
It may seem that White is not without chances, but on the way to using his
reserve tempi, White will have to weaken his structure a bit.} a5 42. f3 f5 43.
f4 a4 44. a3 {It may seem that Black is in real trouble...} d4+ $1 {The only
saving move.} 45. exd4+ Kd5 46. Kb4 $1 {White, too has only moves to maintain
the equality.} Kxd4 47. Kxa4 Ke4 48. Kb4 Kxf4 49. a4 Kg3 50. a5 f4 51. a6 f3
52. a7 f2 53. a8=Q f1=Q $11) 37. h4 $1 $18 a5 38. Nxh5 f5 39. Ng7 1-0

