{[%evp 0,25,30,-6,-9,-9,0,0,21,21,18,21,21,14,29,1,29,28,21,20,20,28,28,28,31,
25,36,5] Things are more complicated in the fight of a good knight against a
potentially bad bishop if there are major pieces on board.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5
3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 b6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxe7 Qxe7
10. Nxd5 exd5 11. Rc1 Be6 12. Qa4 c5 13. Qa3 Rc8 14. Be2 a5 15. O-O Na6 16.
dxc5 bxc5 17. Nd4 Bd7 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 {White has reached a typical position with
major pieces and a knight versus the presumably "bad" bishop. At this stage,
the evaluation of the position greatly depends on whether White will be able
to force ...c5-c4 or Black will find a favorable way of advancing his other
hanging pawn. It is the kind of middlegame where White's play seems easier
since the central pawns are permanently "hanging" (this denomination must have
been invented for something). However, Black's dynamic resources are rich. For
instance, the recent rook lift, a consequence of the thematical exchange of
the bishop for the knight, casts some danger over White's kingside.} 19. Ne2 ({
White is not ready to go for the queenside pawns since after} 19. Nb3 Rg6 20.
Rxc5 Qe4 $1 21. g3 Bh3 22. Rxc8+ Kh7 $1 $19 {Black has a decisive attack.}) (
19. Rfd1 {does not yield much, either.} Rg6 20. Ne2 Bg4 (20... d4 {is possible,
but Black needs to continue accurately.} 21. Nf4 Rgc6 22. exd4 Qg5 23. d5 Rf6
24. Ne2 Bg4 $44 {White's imperfect coordination yields Black compensation for
the pawn.}) 21. Nf4 Bxd1 22. Nxg6 fxg6 23. Rxd1 d4 $5 24. exd4 Qe2 25. Qd3 Qxd3
26. Rxd3 cxd4 27. Kf1 Rc2 $11) 19... a4 {This typical move, gaining queenside
space and restricting the enemy queen, wastes a tempo, allowing White to
regroup. True, it does not yield him an advantage yet, but from a practical
point of view, his play becomes a bit easier.} (19... Bb5 $1 {would have
solved all Black's problems by exchanging the minor pieces.} 20. Rfe1 Bxe2 21.
Rxe2 d4 22. Rce1 Re6 $1 ({The Bulletin gives only} 22... Qd6 $14 {, but
White's advantage is not that obvious. Anyway, the main line is more active
for Black.}) 23. Qxa5 c4 $44 {with obvious compensation for the pawn.}) 20.
Rfd1 Qd6 (20... Bg4 {does not force the exchange of the minor pieces but
induces an important weakness.} 21. f3 Be6 22. Nf4 {The threats on d5 and c5 
(after Nd3), require certain accuracy from Black.} Qb7 $1 23. Nd3 (23. Rxc5 {
leads to simplification and full equality.} Rxc5 24. Qxc5 Qxb2 25. Nxe6 Rxe6
$11) 23... c4 $1 24. Nc5 Rxc5 $1 25. Qxc5 Qxb2 $44 {The bishop is stable on e6
and ensures the safety of the central pawns. The passed pawn on c5 yields
Black enough compensation for the exchange.}) 21. Rd2 $1 {White avoids any
danger connected with ...Bg4 and starts building up the pressure on d5.} ({
As indicated in the bulletin,} 21. Nc3 d4 22. Ne4 {runs into} Qg6 $1 {I would
continue the line with} 23. Nxc5 $2 Bh3 24. g3 Rxc5 $1 25. Qxc5 Qe4 $19) 21...
Be6 22. h3 Rc7 23. Nf4 c4 {Spassky must have understood that he could not keep
his c-pawn next to its hanging colleague.} (23... Rcc6 24. Rcd1 {more or less
forces} c4 {under slightly less favorable circumstances than in the game.} 25.
Qxd6 (25. Nxd5 Qxa3 26. bxa3 Bxd5 27. Rxd5 c3 $11) 25... Rxd6 26. Nxd5 Rxd5 27.
Rxd5 Bxd5 28. Rxd5 {White has won a pawn, but after} a3 $1 {Black should count
on a draw.} 29. Rb5 (29. bxa3 c3 30. Rd1 Rxa3 31. Rc1 Rxa2 32. Rxc3 h5 $11 {
In practice, White sometimes wins this endgame, but objectively it is drawn,
of course.}) 29... axb2 30. Rxb2 {With just symbolical winning chances. We can
conclude that Spassky's move was better. On the other hand, we also feel that
his neutral 19th and 20th move left him to struggle a bit.}) 24. Qxd6 (24. Nxd5
Qxa3 (24... Bxd5 25. Qxd6 Rxd6 26. e4 $14) 25. bxa3 Rd7 26. e4 Rc6 $11 {
White's extra pawn does not count for much.}) 24... Rxd6 25. Ne2 {We can
notice an abstractly similar situation as in the Mutual Isolanis structure,
when the knights jump to b4 or b5, to provoke weaknesses, which it will use
later. The knight's incursion to f4 has induced ...c5-c4 and the time has come
now to use the available blockading squares.} a3 $6 {This simply loses a pawn.
Spassky might have thought that he would retrieve it quickly or that the pawn
would not be too relevant. In either case, he was wrong.} ({Instead of
absolving White from his relative weakness on b2, Black should have put it
under pressure.} 25... Rb6 26. Nc3 Rcb7 (26... Ra7 27. a3 Ra5 {is a bit
passive. White could think of starting some kingside play with} 28. Kh2 $5 {
combining the advance of the king with that of the pawns.}) 27. Rcc2 d4 $5 {
One of the merits behind setting up pressure on b2 is that Black can fight
against the blockade.} (27... Bf5 {It is also playable but leaves Black
struggling a bit.} 28. Nxd5 Bxc2 29. Nxb6 Rxb6 30. Rxc2 c3 $3 {Another
anti-blockading move. Anything else loses.} 31. bxc3 (31. Rxc3 Rxb2 32. Ra3 Rb4
33. g4 h5 $5 $11) 31... Rb1+ 32. Kh2 a3 33. c4 Rb2 34. Rc3 Rxa2 35. Kg3 Kf8 {
with just symbolic advantage to White.}) 28. exd4 Bf5 29. Rc1 (29. Nd5 Rd6 $19)
29... Rxb2 30. Rxb2 Rxb2 31. Nxa4 Rxa2 32. Rxc4 Be6 33. Rb4 g5 $44 {Due to his
superior activity, Black has just enough compensation for the pawn.}) 26. bxa3
Bf5 ({In the event of} 26... Ra6 27. Nc3 $16 {the pawn is taboo due to Nb5.
White will play a3-a4 next.}) (26... Ra7 27. Nc3 Ra5 28. Rb1 $16 {is similar.})
27. Nc3 {For reasons explained in the next comment, the knight belongs to this
square.} Rcd7 28. Rd4 $1 {We can now understand why White's chances are better
with rooks on board. In the previous example, featuring only minor pieces, the
king could not get to d4, meaning that White could not get the best out of the
control of the central dark squares. In this position, the blockade is very
effective. The knight does not obstruct the d-file, while blocking the passed
pawn and attacking d5.} Kf8 29. f3 (29. Rcd1 $141 Bd3 30. Rd2 Ke7 31. Rb2 $16)
29... Ke7 30. Rcd1 Be6 31. Rb1 (31. Kf2 $5 Ra6 32. a4 $16) 31... Ra6 32. a4 Kd6
33. Kf2 ({The bulletin gives the following instructive variation:} 33. e4 $6
Kc5 $1 34. Rbd1 Kb4 $1 $10 {breaking the blockade.}) 33... Kc5 34. Rd2 Ra5 $5 {
Preparing ...Bf5-d3, something White might have overlooked.} (34... Bf5 $2 35.
Rxd5+ Rxd5 36. Rb5+ $18) 35. Ke2 $6 (35. Rb5+ $6 {is premature.} Rxb5 36. axb5
Kb4 $11) (35. g4 $5 $14) ({In fact, the worst thing behind White's last move
was exposing the king to the check on d3, yielding Black an important tempo.
It is worth mentioning that White could spend a tempo on} 35. a3 $5 {,
preventing ...Kb4 in the eventuality that White gives up the control of the
b-file and allows Rb4.} g5 (35... Bf5 36. Rb8 Bd3 37. Rdb2 $18 d4 38. Rc8+ Kd6
39. exd4 $18) 36. Rb4 (36. Rb5+ {remains unconvincing.} Rxb5 37. axb5 Ra7 38.
Ra2 f5 {The threat ..f5-f4, clearing the path for the d-pawn, faces White with
certain dangers.}) 36... Rda7 37. g4 $16) 35... Bf5 $1 36. e4 (36. Rb8 {
might have been a bit better, anyway.} Bd3+ 37. Kf2 d4 $1 {With the rook on b2
already, this does not work, as we have seen above.} 38. exd4+ (38. Rc8+ {
allows} Kb4 $11 {. Another consequence of the wasted time (Ke2-f2).}) 38...
Kxd4 39. Nb5+ Ke5 40. Re8+ Kf5 41. Nc3 Rb7 $14) 36... dxe4 37. fxe4 Rxd2+ 38.
Kxd2 Bd7 $1 $11 {Preventing Rb5.} 39. Rb7 Kc6 40. Rb8 Kc5 41. Rf8 Be6 42. Rb8
Bd7 43. Rb7 Kc6 44. Rb2 Kc5 45. Ke3 Ra7 $1 ({The bulletin gives} 45... Bxa4 {
as mistaken in view of} 46. Rb7 Be8 47. Rc7+ {White wins a pawn, indeed, but
Black's activity ensures him reasonable compensation.} Bc6 (47... Kd6 $5 48.
Rxc4 Bc6 $44) 48. Rxf7 Ra3 49. Kd2 g5 $44) 46. Rd2 Bc6 $1 (46... Bxa4 $2 47.
Rd5+ Kb4 48. Kd4 $16 {We know how important it is to prevent the king's
advance to d4, even if there is no pawn to block on d5.}) 47. g4 Rb7 48. Rf2 $1
Rd7 $1 49. Rd2 (49. Rf5+ Kb4 50. Nd5+ Bxd5 51. exd5 g6 52. Re5 f6 53. Re6 Rxd5
$10 {(Bulletin)}) 49... Rb7 50. h4 f6 $1 1/2-1/2

