{[%evp 0,115,19,-1,-1,-1,4,-3,14,14,14,13,13,21,34,-6,2,-43,-51,-14,-14,-51,47,
5,27,22,64,33,34,33,27,10,5,6,-9,-12,17,-4,7,-4,0,0,22,7,0,-9,-6,-12,1,1,-23,
-23,2,4,0,24,19,18,13,13,37,40,45,77,71,52,122,122,243,18,111,115,118,118,126,
123,137,128,124,128,124,42,112,153,153,163,249,234,229,256,255,263,232,232,247,
247,247,246,246,246,258,217,217,217,217,217,256,236,258,269,266,267,29983,
29984,29985,819,819,848] Even though the position was equal for a long time in
the previous game, we could feel that the player with a knight could find the
moves and plans easier than his opponent. The same happened in the next game.
Even though, Black had an excellent position objectively, Black did not use
his dynamic resources. In this game, Black will play ...d5-d4, but we keep the
connection with the previous games because...c5-c4 was a behind-the-scenes
possibility in several moments.} 1. c4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5.
cxd5 exd5 {Please do not hurry to draw any premature conclusion. We will see
the hanging pawns a bit later.} 6. Bg5 c6 7. Qc2 Na6 8. e3 Nb4 9. Qd1 Bf5 10.
Rc1 a5 11. Be2 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qb3 Rfb8 15. Na4 Na6 16. Bxa6
Rxa6 17. Nc5 Rb6 18. Qc3 Rb5 19. Rfe1 h6 20. b3 Be4 21. Nd2 Bg6 22. Nf1 Nxc5
23. dxc5 b6 24. cxb6 R8xb6 {Finally, the game steps away from the Carlsbad
structure. We got the semi-hanging pawns, with the obvious possibility of ...
c6-c5. The lines below show that switching from the semi-hanging pawns to the
hanging ones needs certain accuracy.} 25. Nd2 {White does not have an
advantage mainly because his knight is too far from the center. If White could
transfer it to d4, his position would become very promising.} Qa3 $1 {An
instructive moment. Karpov gives two lines showing that the queenside
situation needs to be handled with care.} (25... c5 $2 26. a4 Rb4 27. Qxc5 $18
{Karpov}) (25... Qb4 $2 26. a4 $1 Qxc3 27. Rxc3 Rb4 ({The anti-blockading} 
27... d4 {does not improve the situation dramatically.} 28. exd4 Rb4 29. f3
Rxd4 30. Nc4 Ra6 31. Ne5 Rd6 32. Rec1 $16) 28. Rec1 ({Better than Karpov's} 28.
Rc5 {"with a clear advantage", when after} Ra6 29. Rec1 Rbb6 $11 {the
weaknesses on b3 and c6 compensate for each other. Things would be different
with the knight on d4, of course.}) 28... d4 29. Rxc6 $5 dxe3 30. fxe3 $16) 26.
Nf3 c5 27. Qd2 {Karpov evaluates the position as slightly better for him, but
his innate optimism most likely generated this. He probably felt at home in
the position, knowing what he has to do to face Black with concrete problems.
That was enough for Karpov to believe that he was better.} Be4 28. Ne5 Re6 {
The most natural move, but not the only good one.} (28... c4 $5 {(Marin) is
somewhat paradoxical. Why does Black concede the control over d4 to White?
First of all, the knight does not have access to d4 now. Secondly, the pawn on
b3 is under pressure and the one on c4 becomes a passer.} 29. Qd4 (29. bxc4 $2
Rb2 30. Qd4 Rxf2 $1 31. Kxf2 Rb2+ {[%cal Ga3a2]} 32. Re2 Rxe2+ 33. Kxe2 Qxc1
$17) (29. f3 Bg6 $11) 29... Qxa2 30. bxc4 Rb1 $11) (28... Qb4 $5 {(Marin) is
less committal, but not for too long.} 29. Red1 c4 $1 30. bxc4 Qxd2 31. Rxd2
Rb1 32. Rdd1 Rxc1 33. Rxc1 dxc4 34. f3 (34. Nxc4 $2 Rc6 $19 {wins the knight
soon.}) 34... Bd5 35. e4 Be6 36. Rc2 g5 $11 {Black is well regrouped and
controls the b-file.}) 29. Nd3 g5 {Without being necessary, this weakening
move is not a real mistake. Black prevents Nf4, maintaining his centre compact.
The dynamic alternatives would have been  easier to handle in a practical game.
} (29... Bxd3 30. Qxd3 c4 {Karpov claims a small advantage for White, but this
is again too optimistic.} 31. Qd2 Qb4 $1 (31... cxb3 $2 32. Rc8+ Kh7 33. Qd3+
Rg6 34. Qxb5 $18) 32. Qxb4 Rxb4 33. bxc4 dxc4 $11) (29... c4 $5 30. Nf4 Rc6 31.
f3 Bf5 32. Nxd5 Rd6 33. e4 cxb3 34. axb3 Be6 $11 {Marin.}) 30. Rc3 {An
unpleasant move, threatening b3-b4. Black is a bit on edge now.} d4 $2 {
This principled move could have led to immediate trouble.} ({The same as
Spassky in the previous game, Jussupow was reluctant to the favourable exchange
} 30... Bxd3 31. Rxd3 {True, his reasons are easier to understand since this
wins a pawn for White, but Black has excellent drawing chances after} Qb4 32.
Rxd5 Qxd2 33. Rxd2 Re4 34. h3 a4 $11 {, most likely simplifying to the four
versus three pawns rook ending.}) 31. exd4 {Karpov was probably set up for
building up his advantage gradually. It is strange that he, who enjoyed giving
lines with queen trappings so much, failed to notice that there is such a
possibility here, too.} (31. Rc4 $1 Bxd3 32. Ra4 $18 {Marin}) 31... cxd4 32.
Rc8+ {The position is not easy to evaluate. White has a blocking knight, but
it is under the is that so important?bishop's pressure. He controls the c-file,
but} Kg7 $2 {Running into an unexpected trick.} ({Karpov intended to meet the
correct} 32... Kh7 $1 {with} 33. Rc7 {. Apparently, he thought that White
would be better, but this is not true.} Qd6 $1 {[%cal Ge4g6] Preparing ...Bg6.}
34. Rec1 (34. Rxf7+ $6 Kg8 {[%cal Ge4d3] threatening with the winning ...Bxd3
forces} 35. Rxe4 Kxf7 36. Rg4 $15) 34... Bg6 {Black has regrouped properly and
it is White who should think of equality.}) 33. Nf4 $1 {A very unpleasant
surprise.} gxf4 34. Qxd4+ Rbe5 35. Rxe4 Qd6 (35... Qxa2 36. Rxe5 Qb1+ 37. Re1+
$18 {Karpov}) 36. Qa1 (36. Qxd6 $2 Rxd6 37. f3 Rxe4 38. fxe4 Rd1+ 39. Kf2 Rd2+
$11 {Karpov}) (36. h3 Qxd4 37. Rxd4 Re1+ 38. Kh2 R1e2 $1 39. Rxf4 $16 {Karpov.
Maybe White's advantage is not that clear, though.} Rxa2 $14) 36... Kh7 37.
Rxe5 Rxe5 38. h3 (38. h4 $5 {Karpov. Indeed, this would have restricted
Black's possibilities:} f3 39. gxf3 $18 {Marin}) 38... f3 $1 39. Qb1+ (39. gxf3
Rg5+ 40. Kh1 Rg7 $11 {Marin}) 39... Kg7 40. Rc4 (40. g4 Rd5 $44 {Marin}) (40.
Qb2 Kh7 41. Qc2+ Kg7 42. Qc3 Kh7 43. g4 $18 {With the queen away from the back
rank and e1 defended, this is possible and strong. (Marin)}) 40... Qe6 $2 (
40... Qd2 $5 {Karpov}) (40... h5 {Karpov}) 41. Rg4+ $18 Kf8 42. Qd3 h5 (42...
Re1+ 43. Kh2 Qe5+ 44. Rg3 (44. g3 $4 Rh1+ 45. Kxh1 Qe1+ 46. Kh2 Qxf2+ $19)
44... fxg2 45. Qd8+ Qe8 46. Qd6+ Qe7 47. Qxh6+ $18 {Karpov}) 43. Qd8+ Qe8 44.
Qd6+ Qe7 45. Qb8+ Qe8 46. Qd6+ Qe7 47. Qh6+ Ke8 48. Rg8+ $1 Kd7 49. Qd2+ Kc7
50. Qf4 fxg2 51. Rg7 Kb6 52. Rxf7 Qg5 53. Rf6+ Kb7 (53... Kc7 54. Qc4+ Rc5 55.
Qf7+ $18 {Karpov}) 54. Qf3+ Ka7 55. Rf7+ Kb6 56. Rb7+ Kc5 57. Rc7+ Kb4 58. Qf8+
1-0

