{[%evp 0,58,26,13,30,-3,10,-3,-3,-3,14,14,18,29,54,18,63,63,41,36,36,31,31,29,
44,10,10,2,2,2,8,-26,24,12,19,9,22,-7,-7,-36,-34,-40,-39,-25,-27,-31,-58,-58,
-26,-45,-26,-56,-22,-46,-35,-290,-318,-521,-529,-548,-546] If the player with
hanging pawns has a king's bishop left after exchanging the other one, the
advance of the c-pawn ceases being a positional concession. Here is a famous
classical example.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3
Nbd7 7. Rc1 b6 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Qa4 Bb7 10. Ba6 Bxa6 11. Qxa6 c5 12. Bxf6 Nxf6
13. dxc5 bxc5 14. O-O Qb6 15. Qe2 {With his knight stable on f6, safely
defending d5, and enough room to ensure an optimal piece.' coordination, Black
does not have any problem. The next move is one of Capablanca's most famous
decisions.} c4 {[%csl Gb2,Gc3,Ge7] (!!) Black did not need to play this at
this stage, but the idea was in the air anyway. Black widens the bishop's
horizon and prepares to exchange the knight on c3, which exerts pressure on d5
and prevents the enemy knight's jump to e4. With the newly resulting structure,
Black has a "good bishop". The double exclaim inserted between parenthesis
refers to the depth of Capablanca's understanding in general and not to the
concrete moment he advanced his c-pawn.} (15... Rfd8 {was absolutely fine, of
course.}) 16. Rfd1 Rfd8 17. Nd4 Bb4 {Continuing the plan mentioned above.} 18.
b3 {This is risky  since White loses at least part of his queenside stability.}
({Here is a sample of neutral play:} 18. h3 Rac8 (18... Bxc3 19. Rxc3 Ne4 20.
Rc2 Rac8 21. b3 Rc5 $11) 19. Qc2 g6 $11 {Both players are well coordinated.
Black has more space, but the knights ensure White certain stability.}) 18...
Rac8 19. bxc4 dxc4 20. Rc2 Bxc3 $1 21. Rxc3 Nd5 22. Rc2 c3 {The knight on d4
ensures White against immediate troubles, but the far advanced pawn is a
permanent threat.} 23. Rdc1 Rc5 24. Nb3 Rc6 25. Nd4 Rc7 26. Nb5 Rc5 {Black has
made some progress, despite the irritating knight jumps.} 27. Nxc3 $2 {Based
on a heavy oversight.} ({True, the passive play would yield Black some lasting
advantage.} 27. Nd4 g6 28. g3 h5 $5 $15 {Trying to keep White busy on both
wings.}) 27... Nxc3 28. Rxc3 Rxc3 29. Rxc3 Qb2 $1 {One of Capablanca's "little
combinations".} 0-1

