{[%evp 0,69,19,19,25,10,10,10,35,23,27,27,40,-8,36,6,22,23,22,22,36,-12,28,-2,
48,-6,44,44,63,49,49,37,50,27,31,31,33,39,59,26,26,33,33,33,33,5,23,25,13,2,13,
6,6,6,56,27,27,18,18,33,33,-94,-80,-178,-161,-161,-176,-205,-133,-140,-113,
-348] Things are not always static when the c-pawn advances. Here is a dynamic
example. This was the fifteenth game of the match, which might cause some
confusion. Nowadays, World title matches last 12 games and even so some
players complain about being exhausted, resorting to several fightless draws.
The 1977 quarterfinals were programmed for 12 games. In the case of equality,
a series of two-game mini-matches (the KO World Cup standard nowadays) was
going to take place. Spassky won the third game and maintained his lead for a
long time. However, in the tenth game, Hort equalized in a game with rather
unusual structures. The match ended in a tie with two more draws in the final
games. At this moment, Spassky had an appendix crisis and urgently needed
surgery. He had the right to postpone four games, but that was not enough for
the recovery period. According to the rules, he should have resigned from the
match, but the FIDE president and former World Champion Max Euwe decided to
allow a postponement of three whole weeks. The sad thing is that the rules
were broken without consulting Hort... The first two pairs of additional games
ended with equal scores and this was the first game of the third mini-match.
It featured an instructive complicated fight that ended dramatically.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 b6 4. e3 Bb7 5. Bd3 d5 6. O-O Nbd7 7. b3 Be7 8. Bb2 O-O 9.
Nc3 c5 10. Qe2 Rc8 11. Rfd1 Qc7 12. Rac1 Rfe8 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Bf5 g6 15. Bh3
Rcd8 {Black has corrected the minor developing defect and has a harmonious
position. White's chances are mainly connected with the long diagonal's
relative weakness and the c5-square.} 16. Na4 Ne4 {Immediately taking the
offered space.} ({The intended tricky} 16... c4 17. bxc4 Ba6 {would fail to}
18. Nc3 $1 {Since 18...Bxc4 fails to 19.Nxd5! Black has to accept a worse
position with} dxc4 19. a4 $14) 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Bxd7 Qxd7 19. Ne5 Qc7 20. f3
Nf6 {The last moves are natural from the perspective of the fight around the
dark central squares. We should do justice to Spassky, who played the first
part of the game in an inspired way. The position is very tense, with
possibilities of becoming chaotic, one of Spassky's predilect territories.
There were times before July 1972 when specialists claimed that Fischer would
be helpless against Spassky's ability to create uncontrollable complications.
They proved wrong, but we will see that Hort was entirely up to this difficult
task five years later.} 21. Nd3 $6 {This voluntary retreat forces Black to
weaken the d4-square but offers him dynamic resources as compensation.} ({
The critical move was} 21. Bd4 {Spassky probably feared that after} Qb8 {
his minor pieces would be hanging, but there was a way to win the battle for
the dark squares.} 22. Rxc5 $1 {Rather in Petrosian's style.} Bxc5 23. Nxc5
Rxe5 24. Nxb7 $1 Rc8 25. Nc5 Ree8 26. Nd3 $44 {White has the better structure,
a perfect blockade and some attacking ideas along the dark diagonal.
Objectively, the position may be equal, but Whitețs play is very pleasant.})
21... c4 {The most natural answer.} (21... Ba6 $5 {was also possible. It would
have implied a pawn sacrifice.} 22. Qc2 Bxd3 23. Qxd3 c4 24. Bd4 $5 Nd7 25.
bxc4 Ne5 26. Bxe5 Qxe5 {Due to the edged knight and the weakness on e3, Black
has good compensation for the pawn(s).} 27. c5 (27. cxd5 Bd6 $1 28. g3 Qxe3+
$44) 27... Rc8 $44) 22. Ndc5 {This was Spassky's idea of exploiting the
hanging position of the f6-knight. However, even though the last move is not a
sacrifice, his knights will remain immobile and hanging.} Bc6 23. Bd4 ({
White could have won a pawn with} 23. bxc4 dxc4 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Qxc4 {
but this would not bring in any chances for an advantage.} Bxa4 26. Bxf6 (26.
Nxa4 {lads to an immediate draw after} Rd1+ 27. Kf2 Rd2+ {With the h2-pawn
hanging, White should rather return to g1, allowing perpetual check.}) 26...
Bxf6 27. Qxa4 Be5 28. f4 Bd6 29. Nd3 Qe7 30. Re1 Bc7 $44 {followed by ...Bb6
with excellent compensation for Black.}) 23... Bb5 24. Qf2 {Spassky plays
solidly.} (24. bxc4 dxc4 25. Nc3 {is likely to win a pawn, yielding good Black
compensation for it, though.} Bxc5 26. Nxb5 Qb6 27. Qxc4 Bxd4 28. exd4 Nd5 $44)
24... Nd7 $5 {In principle, the minor piece exchanges should favor White, but
Hort played this having the active 26th move in mind.} (24... Qc6 $1 $15 {
Might have been stronger. After all, White is hanging, so exchanging one of
his knights helps him a bit.}) 25. Nxd7 Bxd7 26. Nc3 Bf5 {Suddenly, things
seem to have become a bit problematic for White. If allowed to play ...Bd3,
Black would get complete control of the position and could start a slow attack
based on ...h5-h4, ...Bd6, etc.} 27. e4 $6 {Played out of premature panicking.}
(27. g4 $1 Be6 ({It appears that} 27... Bd3 $2 {is not a threat, since it runs
into} 28. Nxd5 $1 Rxd5 29. Rxd3 $18) 28. Qg3 $11 {With a stable position.})
27... dxe4 28. Nxe4 $6 {A serious mistake of principle. Ever since Nimzowitsch,
it has been known how dangerous it could be to unblock a pawn like that on c4,
even for just an instant.} ({White would have retained better chances for
equality with} 28. fxe4 Be6 29. bxc4 Bg5 ({Only not} 29... Bxc4 30. Nd5 $1) 30.
Be3 (30. Rc2 {leaves White hanging after} Qxc4 31. Nd5 Qa4 $1 32. Nf6+ $2 Bxf6
33. Qxf6 Rxd4 $19) 30... Bxe3 31. Qxe3 Bxc4 32. Nd5 Qe5 33. Rxc4 Rxd5 {with a
probable draw.}) 28... Bxe4 29. fxe4 {Spassky might have hoped to win the
c4-pawn rather than block it, but he must have overlooked the next move.} c3 $1
{Of course! Unblocked pawns have a natural tendency to advance. Since 30.Rxc3
loses to 30...Qxc3, White is in trouble. The pawn is even more dangerous than
Capablanca's since instead of a stable knight on d4, White has a vulnerable
bishop on the same square.} 30. Rf1 {Hitting f7 and c3 simultaneously...} Bb4 {
... and defending both pawns by one stroke. Besides, Black threatens 31...Rxd4.
} (30... Rxd4 $2 {would be premature due to} 31. Qxf7+ Kh8 32. Qxe8+) 31. Bxa7
$6 {parrying the threat, grabbing a pawn and.. allowing a decisive attack.} ({
White should have searched for saving chances with} 31. a3 Rxd4 32. axb4 Rdxe4
33. Qc5 Qb7 34. Rxc3 Rxb4 $17 {Black is a pawn up, but the technical process
is far from simple.}) 31... Rd2 32. Qe3 Ra8 {White has worries with his bishop
and cannot put up a serious defense of the second rank.} 33. Bb6 (33. Qxd2 {
fails to} Qxa7+ 34. Qf2 Bc5 $19) 33... Qd7 34. a4 c2 $1 {[#]Threatening ...Ba3.
} 35. Bc5 {After playing a wonderful game, Hort forgot about his clock and...
lost on time in a completely winning position.} (35. Bc5 {The game could have
continued:} Bxc5 36. Qxc5 Qg4 37. Rf2 (37. g3 Qh3 $19) 37... Rd1+ 38. Rf1 Rxc1
39. Rxc1 Qd1+ {with an extra rook for Black.}) 1-0

