{[%evp 0,79,27,0,0,0,0,-11,1,12,6,-26,-13,1,12,-1,2,-1,-12,-10,-10,-10,5,-38,
-19,-7,26,8,-6,20,38,20,4,9,65,25,15,-4,8,33,19,-30,-32,4,2,16,19,-41,29,-107,
49,20,52,42,95,71,126,55,120,112,178,102,117,100,119,108,111,156,156,160,161,
158,150,161,191,305,391,391,597,435,562,556] Abstractly speaking, for the
player with hanging pawns, things are simple. He needs to avoid losing the
pawns or advance them before the situation is ripe for it. When everything is
ready, the main plan would be advancing the d-pawn, in order to take advantage
of the (desirably) better coordination. Concretely, this is a lot more
complicated than it sounds, of course. We have seen Karpov fighting against
Jussupowțs hanging pawns. Now we will see him handling them with artistical
accuracy.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. e3 Be7 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. b3 c5 7. Bb2
Nc6 8. Bd3 cxd4 9. exd4 b6 10. O-O Bb7 11. Qe2 Re8 12. Rac1 Bf8 13. Rfd1 dxc4
14. bxc4 g6 {A relatively peaceful but complex Queen's Indian tabiya. The
dynamic force of the hanging pawns should not be underestimated, but White has
to be careful, too, in order to prevent them from becoming targets.} 15. Nf1 $5
{The black knight's transfer to e6 in the Queen's Indian or the Tartakover
Queen's Gambit is typical, but in this concrete position the plan was almost
new.} ({The usual setup is} 15. h3 Bg7 16. Qe3 Rc8 17. Ne5 $13) 15... Bg7 16.
Ne3 Rc8 {White has completed his mobilization and is ready to enter the
maneuvering phase.} 17. Bc2 {The start of a series of very subtle moves. In
this phase of the game Karpov aims to restrict Black's counterplay. White does
not need to prove an advantage at once. He has to maintain his pawns'
flexibility and slowly prepare their advance. The last move aims at inhibiting
...Ne7.} ({In a previous game White used a similar regrouping but with
reversed move order, offering Black counterplay:} 17. Bc3 Nb8 ({Karpov
recommends} 17... Ne7 {but White has} 18. d5 $1 exd5 19. Qb2 Rc6 20. Bc2 $16 {
with overwhelming pressure.}) 18. Bc2 Nd5 19. cxd5 Rxc3 20. dxe6 Rxe6 {
Kurajica,B (2585)-Dizdar,G (2510) Pula 1995 (1-0, 47)}) 17... Qe7 (17... Ne7 {
runs into} 18. Ba4 Bc6 19. Bb3 $1 $14 {White has regrouped for d4-d5 and is
likely to gain a tempo with Ne5.}) 18. Bc3 {Another prophylactic move, aiming
at securing the queenside.} (18. Ba4 Qb4 $1 19. Bb3 Ne7 (19... Na5 $6 20. Bc3
Qa3 21. Nc2 Qe7 22. Bxa5 bxa5 $14) 20. Nc2 Qa5 {Karpov}) 18... Red8 (18... Qa3
{reveals the idea of the previous move:} 19. Bb3 Na5 20. Nc2 $14 {Karpov}) 19.
Rb1 {Finally securing the queenside.} Rd7 (19... Qa3 20. Rb3 Qxa2 $2 21. Ra1
$18 {Karpov}) 20. Bd3 {Things have stabilized on the queenside and Black does
not have ...Ne7 anymore. Therefore the bishop returns to the kingside as if
anticipating the next move.} Nh5 21. Qb2 $1 Nf4 22. Bf1 {One may get the false
impression that Karpov is simply defending move by move. But as the game
advances, it will become clear that while parrying the one-move threats, he
constantly improved his position. In fact, Black already faces the threat of
g2-g3 followed by d4-d5.} Nb8 {Not a pleasant move to play, but Black has to
do something against the threat of a central expansion.} ({Clearing the square
on e7 for the knight with} 22... Qd8 $5 {looks more logical but is not
entirely satisfactory either.} 23. g3 Ne7 24. Ne5 Bxe5 25. dxe5 Nd3 26. Qc2 Nc5
27. Ng4 $14 {Black's kingside weaknesses are worrying.}) 23. Ne1 $1 {As we
will see, just the start of another regrouping. The knight is heading for c2
and the d4-c6.} Rcd8 (23... Qh4 {fails to maintain Black's outpost for too
long:} 24. Rbc1 (24. a4 $5 {Karpov}) 24... Rdc7 25. h3 $14 {Threatening 26.g3
and if 26...Nxh3+ then 27.Kh2 (Karpov).}) 24. a4 $5 {An auxiliary element. The
threat a4-a5 induces the knight to return to c6, obstructing the long diagonal.
} Nc6 25. g3 Nh5 (25... Nxd4 {fails to offer enough counterplay:} 26. gxf4 Qh4
27. Bxd4 Rxd4 28. Rxd4 Bxd4 29. N1g2 $16) 26. N1c2 $1 ({But now} 26. Bg2 {
is premature in view of} Rxd4 $1 (26... Bxd4 $6 27. Rxd4 $1 Nxd4 28. Bxb7 $18)
27. Bxd4 Nxd4 $44 {Karpov}) 26... Nf6 27. Bg2 {Nu rush!} ({But} 27. d5 $16 {
may transpose}) 27... Nb8 28. d5 $1 {After a long "defensive" phase, White is
suddenly close to winning! Black can do very little against Nd4-c6.} exd5 (
28... Na6 $2 29. d6 $1 $18 {Karpov}) 29. cxd5 Nh5 30. Nd4 (30. Bxg7 Nxg7 31.
Ng4 Rd6 32. Nh6+ Kf8 33. Ne3 $16 {Karpov (+-)}) 30... Na6 31. a5 Nc5 (31... Nc7
32. d6 $1 $18 {Karpov}) 32. Qc2 Nf6 (32... bxa5 33. Bxa5 Rc8 34. Nc6 $18 {
Karpov}) 33. Nc6 Bxc6 34. dxc6 Rxd1+ 35. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 36. Qxd1 Nfe4 (36... Ne8 $8
$16 {Karpov} 37. Nd5 Qd8 38. Bxg7 Kxg7 39. Qd4+ f6 40. Qe3 {[%cal Gd5b6]}) 37.
Nd5 $1 $18 Qe8 (37... Qe6 38. Bxe4 Nxe4 39. c7 Nxc3 40. Nf4 $18) 38. Bxg7 Kxg7
39. Qd4+ f6 40. c7 $18 1-0

