{[%evp 0,86,39,-20,-3,-3,-12,-3,11,-3,8,8,39,-7,24,32,30,23,26,-14,31,10,33,13,
19,16,25,31,40,32,17,-25,20,-19,-21,-48,-32,-32,-27,-43,-32,-51,-35,-36,-36,
-45,-42,-38,-35,-82,-149,-256,-250,-250,-250,-232,-219,-281,-235,-321,-221,
-221,-221,-221,-212,-229,-221,-401,-473,-502,-510,-502,-464,-600,-600,-704,
-596,-1039,-1039,-1039,-1053,-1054,-525,-898,-752,-752,-607,-29989,-492]} 1. c4
e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Rc1 Bb7 9.
Be2 Nbd7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O c5 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. Qc2 Rc8 14. Rfd1 {In this
game the exchange of the white bishop for the black knight will occur on
another square than f6.} Qb6 {In his comments, Karpov underlines the fact that
the b6- and e6-squares are very important for Black. In this game they will be
mainly used by the queen, but the queen's knight can also make good use of
them.} 15. Qb1 Rfd8 16. Rc2 Qe6 17. Bg3 $6 ({Kortschnoj's obvious intention
was to double rooks on the d-file and he meant his last move to prepare it. If
} 17. Rcd2 {White had to count with} Ne4 18. Nxe4 dxe4 {when he would be
hanging a bit. Karpov rightly considers this position to be a lesser evil for
White than the game continuation, but his analysis has some flaws.} 19. Bxe7
exf3 20. Bb5 (20. Bxf3 $2 {loses to} Bxf3 21. Bxd8 Qg4 22. g3 Qh3 $19) 20...
Be4 21. Qc1 c4 $1 ({Threatening ...Qg4 without allowing Bf1. Karpov only
analyses} 21... Qxe7 22. Rxd7 Rxd7 23. Rxd7 Qe6 24. Qc4 {with unclear play.})
22. Bh4 Bd3 $17 {With clear domination in the centre and kingside threats. But
White has several improvements on the way. In the actual position, he cannot
free himself with 23.b3 because the queen is hanging. This suggests 21.Qa1! is
a better move. But even earlier, the elegant 19.Ne5! would provoke mass
exchanges with approximate equality. But the main thing to retain from all
these lines is that the positions with hanging pawns are very dynamic and rich
in tactical resources for both players.}) 17... Nh5 18. Rcd2 Nxg3 19. hxg3 Nf6
$15 {We have reached a comfortable version of the hanging pawns with two
bishops, as the reserve knight reached f6, thus consolidating the neuralgic
d5-square. As the game reveals, White's plan to increase the pressure on d5
will only spoil his coordination. With the center firm in his hands, Black can
prepare either ...d5-d4 or ...c5-c4, but the most annoying scenario for White
is keeping the pawns as they are for a long time, thus maintaining both
possibilities move by move.} 20. Qc2 g6 21. Qa4 a6 {[%csl Gb6]} 22. Bd3 Kg7 23.
Bb1 Qb6 {Probably anticipating the next move.} 24. a3 $2 {Apparently, very
logical. After Ba2 the pawn on d5 would be in danger, while White controls d4
better than Black. And yet, the last move takes the a3-square away from the
white queen, allowing some simple tactics:} d4 $1 25. Ne2 {Equivalent to
resignation.} ({But} 25. exd4 {runs into} Bc6 $1 {winning material:} 26. Qc4 (
26. Qc2 Bxf3 27. gxf3 cxd4 {wins the knight, for instance} 28. Na4 Qb5) 26...
Bxf3 27. gxf3 ({Or if} 27. dxc5 Bxd1 28. cxb6 Rxc4 29. Rxd8 Bxd8 $19) 27...
cxd4 28. Na4 Qb5 $1 {and the knight is once again in lethal danger:} 29. Qe2 (
29. Qxb5 axb5 30. Nb6 Rc6 $19) 29... Rc7 30. Bc2 Rdc8 $19 {Due to his hanging
pieces, White cannot survive for too long.}) 25... dxe3 26. fxe3 c4 {Due to
the chronic kingside weaknesses, White is completely lost.} 27. Ned4 Qc7 28.
Nh4 Qe5 29. Kh1 Kg8 30. Ndf3 Qxg3 31. Rxd8+ Bxd8 32. Qb4 Be4 33. Bxe4 Nxe4 34.
Rd4 Nf2+ 35. Kg1 Nd3 36. Qb7 Rb8 37. Qd7 Bc7 38. Kh1 Rxb2 39. Rxd3 cxd3 40.
Qxd3 Qd6 41. Qe4 Qd1+ 42. Ng1 Qd6 43. Nhf3 Rb5 0-1

