{Things not always run that smoothly for the player with hanging pawns, of
course. A skilled opponent may exert lasting pressure against the centre,
inducing the advance of the d-pawn earlier than it would be desirable. After
that, one could think of either winning or blocking the daring pawn. Here are
two examples with Karpov on either side. After two hard-fought matches against
Kortschnoj in 1974 and 1978, which he won by just one point, Karpov did not
face problems in defending his crown in 1981. The result is 6-2 by 10 (not
counting) draws speaks for itself. However, Kortschnoj played a series of good
games. Since defecting from the Soviet Union until 1981, he only commented on
three of his games for the Chess Informant. The 1981 match marked the moment
when he became an active commentator again, just like in the '60s and the
early '70s. He annotated four games of the match, curiously not including his
win with Black in his beloved Open Spanish. His selection includes this game,
even though he never came close to winning it. This speaks about how he was
content with how he put pressure on Karpov's hanging pawns. Karpov, too,
annotates it in his book "Na shakhmatnom Olimpe" (on the chess Olympus), but
his comments are more superficial than Kortschnoj's.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4
Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. Rc1 b6 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Nxd5 exd5 10.
Bxe7 Qxe7 11. g3 Ba6 12. e3 c5 13. dxc5 Bb7 14. Bg2 bxc5 15. O-O Nd7 16. Qb3 {
Both sides have reasons to be content with the outcome of the opening. Black
is solid and has a natural development, while White can hope to organize
lasting pressure against the pawns, especially with his bishop developed on g2.
} Rfb8 {Karpov chooses a harmonious setup. Many of his pieces will exert
queenside pressure, while the queen will occupy the optimal square on e6,
ensuring the needed kingside and central stability.} ({Kortschnoj analyses} 
16... Nf6 17. Qa3 Ne4 18. Rc2 {"followed by either Nd4 or Nd2 with a clear
advantage". However, things are not that clear in this line since Black has
dynamic resources.} Rac8 (18... Rfe8 $5 {intrroduces a different plan, which
offers White a small edge:} 19. Nd2 d4 20. exd4 cxd4 21. Qxe7 Rxe7 22. Nxe4
Bxe4 23. Re2 Bxg2 24. Rxe7 Bxf1 25. Kxf1 a5 $14 {The most probable result is a
draw, but not without a bit of struggling for Black.}) 19. Nd4 $5 (19. Qxa7 $2
Ra8 20. Qb6 Ba6 {threatening ...Rfb8 wins material.}) ({With the pawn on c5
well defended,} 19. Nd2 {can be met with} Ng5 {, threatening ...d5-d4 with
initiative. Alternative, the knight could retreat to the optimal square on e6.}
) 19... Rfd8 20. Nb3 Rc6 {Black is keeping his own, since} 21. Bxe4 Qxe4 22.
Rxc5 d4 $1 {offers him dangerous initiative.}) (16... Nb6 {exposes the knight
to a4-a5, but even more importantly, provides the white queen with certain
safety on the queenside..} 17. Qb5 (17. Qa3 Nc4 18. Qc3 $16 {Kortschnoj} Rac8
$5 $11) (17. Rfd1 $5 $14 {[%cal Ga2a4] followed by a2-a4-a5 (Karpov).}) 17...
Rfc8 18. b3 $14 {The knight is slightly misplaced on b6.}) 17. Qa3 Qe6 {
Continuing the main plan.} (17... Kf8 $6 18. Nh4 c4 $2 19. Qxe7+ Kxe7 20. Nf5+
Kf6 21. Nd6 $16 {Kortschnoj}) 18. Rfd1 a5 {Both sides have completed the first
regrouping phase and White has to take a decision.} 19. Ne1 {A natural way of
clearing the bishop's diagonal.} ({Kortschnoj also analyses} 19. Nd2 $5 a4 (
19... c4 20. Nf3 $14 {Kortschnoj. Engines consider the position dead equal,
but this is not so relevant for the practical player. We know  this position
offers White better chances in the long run. Therefore, I prefer Kortschnoj's
evaluation. Here is a possible continuation:} a4 21. Nd4 Qf6 22. Ne2 Ne5 23.
Nf4 g5 24. Nxd5 Nf3+ 25. Bxf3 Qxf3 26. e4 $1 Qxa3 27. bxa3 $14 {White is not
without chances.}) 20. Nb1 d4 $5 (20... Rc8 21. Nc3 Nb6 22. Ne2 $16 {
Kortschnoj. Indeed, Black starts having problems with defending his pawns.})
21. Bxb7 Rxb7 22. exd4 cxd4 23. Rxd4 Ne5 24. Nd2 $14 {(Kortschnoj) Once again,
engines evaluate this as almost equal. A pawn is a pawn, though and White has
at least practical chances to convert it.}) 19... a4 {It turns out that Black
still had a neutral move.} 20. Nd3 {Facing the threats Nxc5 and Nf4xd5, Black
has to commit himself finally.} d4 $1 {So far, both sides' play has been
natural and (only apparently, of course) effortless. Things turned concrete
after this forced pawn break and both players will face choices between
apparently equivalent continuations. As a general evaluation, we can say that
Black gets a passed pawn in the centre, but White can think of either winning
or blocking it with the knight on the excellent d3-square. We had this in
Karpov-Jussupov, but here the knight will be stable on d3.} 21. Bxb7 $6 {
Kortschnoj rightly considers this an inaccuracy, but only one of the
alternatives suggested by him is an improvement.} (21. e4 $5 {more or less
wins a pawn but has the drawback of requiring the exchange of the excellent
blocking knight.} Rd8 $1 (21... Bxe4 $2 22. Re1 f5 23. f3 $16) 22. Rxc5 (22.
Nxc5 Nxc5 23. Rxc5 Bxe4 24. Re1 d3 25. Bxe4 d2 26. Rd1 Qxe4 27. Qe3 Qxe3 28.
fxe3 Rd3 $11 {Kors=tschnoj}) (22. f3 c4 $1 23. Nf4 Qb6 24. Rxc4 d3+ 25. Kh1 Ne5
26. Rc5 Rac8 $1 $44 27. Rxe5 $140 d2 {Kortschnoj}) 22... Nxc5 23. Nxc5 Qb6 24.
Nxb7 Qxb7 25. e5 Qb8 26. Bxa8 Qxa8 {Karpov also reaches this position, stating
that the central passed pawn ensures him a draw despite the small material
disadvantage. Kortschnoj gives one more move,} 27. f4 {, evaluating the
position as slightly better for White. Karpov's evaluation seems more accurate
after, say,} Qd5 $44) (21. Nf4 $1 {was the strongest.} Qb6 {Both Karpov and
Kortschnoj examine only this move. Quite understandably, since otherwise Black
loses the pawn on d4.} (21... Qe5 {runs into} 22. Bxb7 Rxb7 23. exd4 cxd4 24.
Rc4 $16) (21... Qa6 {is the engines' favorite, but they agree that Black does
not have enough compensation for the pawn after} 22. Bxb7 Qxb7 23. exd4 cxd4
24. Rxd4 Ne5 25. Rd5 $14) 22. Nd5 Bxd5 (22... Qd6 {allows both} 23. Rxd4 $18 {
and 23.exd4 Bxd5 24.dxc5!}) 23. Bxd5 Ra5 24. exd4 (24. Rc2 {given by
Kortschnoj as slightly better for White is not worrying for Black after the3
active} Ne5) 24... Qxb2 {This is indicated by Karpov, without any further
comment, apparently meaning that things are fine for Black. In fact, White
reaches a decisive advantage with} (24... cxd4 {allows} 25. Rc6 Qxb2 26. Rc8+
Kh7 27. Qd3+ g6 28. Rxb8 Qxb8 29. Qxd4 $18 {The difference of piece activity
is decisive to White's favor.}) 25. Qxb2 Rxb2 26. Bc6 Nf8 (26... Nb8 27. Be4
$18 cxd4 $2 28. Rc8#) 27. dxc5 Ne6 28. Be4 $18 {The pawn on c5 is taboo due to
back rank mate.}) 21... Rxb7 22. exd4 (22. Nxc5 $2 Nxc5 23. Rxc5 dxe3 24. fxe3
Rb3 $1 {Kortschnoj} 25. axb3 Qxe3+ 26. Kg2 Qe2+ 27. Kh3 Qxd1 28. bxa4 Rxa4 $19
{Karpov. According to the latter, this tactical variation justifies the
concept based on ..a5-a4 and ..d5-d4.}) 22... cxd4 23. Re1 $14 {White's
position remains preferable. The blocking knight defends b2 and neutralizes
the pawn on d4, while the rooks control the open files. Black's space
advantage partly compensates for these.} Qd5 24. Rc2 Nf8 25. Nf4 {The knight
must abandon the excellent square to force the queen to evacuate the central
square.} Qa5 {Kortschnoj unjustly criticizes this move.} ({He recommends} 25...
Qb5 {but refraining from attacking the rook on e1 offers White a tempo for
regrouping.} 26. Qf3 ({Karpov gives} 26. Qd3 {as slightly better for White.
This would be true if Black exchanged the queens, but he is not forced to do
that.}) 26... Rd8 27. Nd3 $14) 26. Rce2 ({Kortschnoj gives} 26. Rd1 {as an
important improvement. However, things are not entirely clear in some of his
lines.} Rd7 (26... Rb4 27. Nd5 $16 {Kortschnoj}) (26... g5 27. Ne2 Ne6 28. Nxd4
Rd7 29. Rcd2 {Kortschnoj} g4 $1 {followed by ...Ng5, with the normal
compensation for the pawn.}) 27. Rc4 {"With a clear advantage" (Kortschnoj).
That is too optimistic a comment.} g5 (27... Qa7 28. Qb4 Rad8 29. Nd3 $14) 28.
Nh5 (28. Rc5 Qd8 29. Nd3 Rd5 {and Black holds.}) 28... Qe5 {followed by ...Ne6
and keeping Black at least close to equality.}) 26... Qb5 27. Qf3 Rab8 28. h4
Qf5 {White has managed to control the d5-square with the queen, but needs to
find a way to restrore the blockade on d3.} 29. Re5 {Kortschnoj lets himself
charmed by an active operation, leading only to equality.} (29. Qd3 {Kotrschnoj
} Qc5 $1 $11) (29. Kg2 $5 {might have been best.} Ne6 (29... Rxb2 $2 30. Rxb2
Rxb2 31. Re8 $16 Qb5 (31... Rxa2 $2 32. Qa8 Qc5 33. Nd5 $18 {followed by Ne7+.}
) (31... Rb5 {defends d5, but is not satisfactory, either.} 32. Qa8 Qc5 33. h5
$5 $18 {Black is almost paralyzed.}) 32. Qe4 (32. Qa8 Qb7+ $11) 32... Rb1 (
32... Qb7 33. Nd5 $18) 33. Kf3) 30. Nd3 Qxf3+ (30... Qa5 31. Re5 Qa6 32. R1e2
$14) 31. Kxf3 $14 {with very pleasant play for White in both cases.}) 29... Qf6
30. Qd5 Rxb2 31. Rf5 (31. Rf5 Rd8 (31... R8b5 32. Rxf6 Rxd5 33. Ra6 Rd8 34.
Rxa4 $11) 32. Rxf6 (32. Nh5 $6 Qe6 $3 (32... Qg6 33. Qxd8 Qxf5 34. Qxd4 $18)
33. Qa5 Ra8 $1 $19) 32... Rxd5 33. Ra6 $11 {Tal}) 1/2-1/2

[Event "World-ch30-KK1 Karpov-Kasparov +5-3=40"]
[Site "Moscow"]
[Date "1984.12.07"]
[Round "31"]
[White "Karpov, Anatoly"]
[Black "Kasparov, Garry"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "D58"]
[WhiteElo "2700"]
[BlackElo "2710"]
[Annotator "GM Mihail Marin"]
[PlyCount "70"]
[EventDate "1984.09.10"]
[EventType "match"]
[EventRounds "48"]
[EventCountry "URS"]
[SourceTitle "MainBase"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "1999.07.01"]
[SourceVersion "2"]
