[SourceQuality "1"]

{Three years later, Karpov found himself on the other side of the board in a
similar position. This was the first Karpov-Kasparov match. Karpov was leading
by 5-0 and now is when he came closest to ending the match with a "dry score".
} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 b6 8. Rc1
Bb7 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. O-O c5 12. Qa4 a6 13. dxc5 bxc5 14. Rfd1 Qb6
15. Qb3 {This is the point behind provoking ...a7-a6.} Qa7 $6 {Too passive.} ({
In my repertoire database with the Tartakover system, I recommended} 15... Qxb3
$11) 16. Bg3 Rad8 {White has slightly better mobilization, partly due to the
passive black queen. There are more minor pieces on board than in the previous
game, which can mean two different things. The first impression is that, by
similarity to the Isolani positions, Black has more dynamic possibilities and
that the pawns are not easy to attack. At the same time, there could be
coordinating problems for Black.} 17. Ne1 {Karpov carries out the same
manoeuvre as Kortschnoj's. The main idea is to clear the f3-square for the
bishop and prepare a knight's transfer to f4. In other words, the same plan.
White had two important alternatives.} (17. Nh4 $5 {Probably not Karpov's
style, but the knight cannot be stopped from jumping to f5.} Rfe8 (17... g6 $2
18. Bf3 $18 c4 19. Qc2 Qa8 20. Nxg6 $1 fxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kh8 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23.
Qxh6+ Kg8 24. Qg6+ Kh8 25. Rxc4 $18) 18. Nf5 Bf8 19. Bc7 Rc8 20. Bd6 Re6 21.
Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Qa3 $14 {with certain pressure.}) (17. Ne5 $5 {may be the best
way of clearing the f3-square. White will not need to care about what to do
with his knight and if anything, exchanges a minor piece, slightly weakening
Black's defence.} Nxe5 (17... Rfe8 18. Bf3 Nb6 19. a4 $16) (17... Qa8 18. Nxd7
Rxd7 19. Na4 $16 {Black can't avoid ...c5-c4, since} Qa7 {runs into} 20. Qb6
Qxb6 21. Nxb6 Rdd8 22. Bc7 Rde8 23. Bf3 $18) 18. Bxe5 Qa8 19. Bf3 {White has
very strong pressure on d5.} Bc6 (19... Rfe8 20. Bxf6 $1 c4 21. Qa4 {It
appears that Black cannot avoid losing d5.} Bxf6 (21... Bc6 22. Qa5 {increases
the pressure on d5.}) 22. Nxd5 $1 $18 {It appears that the rook on e8 is
hanging.}) 20. Bxf6 c4 21. Qb6 Bxf6 22. Qc5 Bxc3 23. Rxc3 $14 {With a very
promising blockade.}) 17... d4 $6 {The young Kasparov chooses the dynamic way.}
(17... Rfe8 {yields White the more pleasant play, but possibly not an
objective advantage.} 18. Bf3 c4 19. Qc2 Qa8 20. Be2 (20. b3 $5) 20... Nc5 21.
Nf3 $14 {/=}) 18. exd4 cxd4 19. Na4 {This is not the best square for the
knight, but due to the weak square on b6, it is not the worst possible, either.
} Rc8 20. Rxc8 $1 Rxc8 21. Bc4 Rf8 {White has active play and the queen on a7
stands worse than ever. However, Black's dynamic resources should not be
neglected. Now is an important moment for White.} 22. Qd3 {This impatient move
wins a pawn but yields Black reasonable counterplay.} ({The main idea behind
Ne1 should be blocking the d4-pawn (compared with the previous game), but} 22.
Nd3 {is premature due to} Ne4 23. Nf4 (23. Bf4 g5 24. Bc7 Bc6 $11) 23... Nxg3
24. hxg3 Be4 25. Re1 Nf6 26. Bd3 Bc6 $11) (22. f3 $5 {is the right way of
preparing the blockading move.} Bc6 23. Nd3 a5 24. Rc1 $14) (22. Nf3 $1 {
was also worth considering. As Larsen once said, one should capture Isolated
pawns and not just block them! In this case, threatening to achieve that
without weakening the pressure on f7 would have been quite effective.} Ne4 {
Giving up the pawn and preparing to activate the bishop with ...Bf6.} (22...
Qa8 $2 23. Nxd4 $1 Bxg2 24. Nf5 Bc5 25. Rxd7 $1 Nxd7 26. Nxc5 Nxc5 27. Qc3 {
Suddenly, Black cannot avoid mate!!} Ne6 28. Bxe6 $18) (22... Nc5 23. Nxc5 Bxc5
24. Ne5 Be4 25. Rc1 $18 {The dark-squared bishop does not have good squares,
making the threat Nxf7 decisive.}) 23. Rxd4 Bc6 24. Rd1 Bf6 25. Bd5 Bxa4 26.
Qxa4 Nxg3 27. hxg3 Bxb2 28. Bc4 {White retains the strong initiative.} Nb6 29.
Qxa6 Qxa6 30. Bxa6 Ra8 31. Bb5 $14 {Despite the presence of opposite-coloured
bishops, White is not without chances. The square on f7 may prove weak.} Rxa2
$2 32. Rd8+ Kh7 33. Rb8 $18 {trapping the knight.}) 22... Bc6 23. Bb3 Ne4 $1 (
23... Bxa4 24. Bxa4 $16) 24. Qxd4 Qb7 25. Bd5 Ndf6 26. Bxc6 Qxc6 27. b3 Re8 {
White has won the pawn, but one knight is stuck on a4, the other on e1,
without anything to block on d3. Black has reasonable compensation.} 28. Qd3 ({
Karpov later wrote that} 28. Qc4 {would have won the game and the match, but
this is not that clear.} Qb7 29. Nc2 Bf8 30. Ne3 h5 {Black has reasonable
compensation for the pawn, even though White has an extra tempo concerning the
game.}) 28... h5 $1 $132 29. Qc4 Qb7 30. Nf3 Rc8 31. Qe2 Ng4 32. Ne5 Nxg3 33.
