{Black seems to have organized his queenside defence according to the
standards. Is that true?} 18. a5 $1 {In connection with the next move, the
most effective continuation of the attack.} (18. Qb2 {This standard way of
preparing the attack allows Black to correct the only problem in his position.}
Qe7 {Evacuating the c-file.} 19. b5 cxb5 20. axb5 a5 $11 {with a familiar
picture.}) (18. b5 {This is possible, but not the strongest.} axb5 19. Nxb5 Qb8
20. Nc3 Nc4 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. Ne5 Qc7 23. Rab1 b5 {White is somewhat better,
but the situation is not entirely clear.}) 18... Nc8 (18... Nc4 {more or less
loses a pawn, because of the specific queenside structure.} 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20.
Na4 {No ...b7-b5.} Ne4 21. Ne5 Nd6 22. Nb6 Rad8 23. Nexc4 $18) 19. b5 $1 {
The logical consequence of the previous move.} axb5 20. Nxb5 Qd8 21. Nc3 {
Just retreating before preparing to continue the attack. The structure
strongly resembles that in the game Karpov-Kharitonov, but you may agree that
the latter understood the process of coordinating better than the player with
Black in this game.} Nd6 22. Qb4 Qe7 23. a6 $1 {Dismnatling Black's fortress.}
bxa6 (23... b5 {leaves White with a dangerous passed pawn.} 24. Ne5 Bd7 25. Qc5
Nc4 (25... Rec8 26. a7 $18 {[%cal Ga1a6] followed by Ra6 is crushing.}) 26.
Nxd7 Qxd7 27. e4 $16 {Black's centre will soon crumble down.}) 24. Rxa6 (24.
Ne5 $16 {is also very strong.}) 24... Rxa6 25. Bxa6 Ra8 26. Bf1 $16 {A typical
Karpov retreat. The kingside is safe and White can organize his queenside play.
} (26. Bf1 $1 Nc8 27. Qb2 Nd7 (27... c5 28. dxc5 Qxc5 29. Ne4 Qa3 30. Nxf6+
gxf6 31. Qd2 $16) 28. Ne2 Rb8 29. Qc3 Rb6 30. Qa5 Qd6 31. Nf4 Ne7 (31... Bf5
32. Nxd5 $1 $18) 32. Nxe6 $5 (32. Rb1 Nc8 $16) 32... fxe6 (32... Qxe6 33. Ne5
Rb8 34. Qc7 $18) 33. Ne5 Rb8 34. Qa7 (34. Nxd7 Qxd7 35. Qc5 Ra8 (35... Rd8 36.
Ra1 $16) 36. g3 Kf7 37. h4 g6 38. Rb1 $16 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1g2] followed by Kg2
and Bd3, preparing h4-h5 and Rh1.}) 34... Nxe5 35. dxe5 Qd8 36. Be2 Kh8 $2 (
36... Kf7 $14) 37. Bg4 Ng6 38. f4 Ra8 39. Qc5 Qe8 40. Qxc6 Qxc6 41. Rxc6 d4 42.
exd4 Nxf4 43. g3 Nd3 44. Bxe6 Ra1+ 45. Kg2 g6 46. Bc4 Nb4 47. Rc8+ Kg7 48. d5 {
1-0 Carlsen,M (2863)-Caruana,F (2835) chess24.com INT 2020}) *

