{This is a slightly unusual version of the Carlsbad structure, arising from a
different opening than the Queen's Gambit. How should White organize his
queenside play?} 17. b4 $1 {In view of Black's plan based on ...Nf6-e4
followed by ...g6-g5 and ...f5-f4; White should not delay concrete action.} (
17. a4 {This move, unnecessarily preparing b3-b4 (which is possible at once),
offers Black an essential tempo for organizing his counterplay.} Nf6 18. b4 Ne4
19. Be1 axb4 20. Bxb4 Rf7 21. a5 g5 {Black has good counterplay.} 22. Qh5 (22.
Qd1 f4 {or}) (22. a6 f4 {are a bit dangerous for White.}) 22... Qe8 $1 {
Anticipating the next move.} 23. f3 (23. Kg2 $2 f4 24. exf4 gxf4 25. f3 Bxd4 $1
{with crushing initiative, partly based on the hanging rook.}) 23... Nxg3 24.
hxg3 Qxe3+ {with fantastic play for the piece.}) (17. a3 {The standard
minority's attack is slow and ineffective.} Nf6 18. b4 axb4 19. axb4 Ne4 20.
Be1 Rxa1 21. Rxa1 g5 {followed by ...f5-f4, with excellent counterplay.}) 17...
axb4 (17... a4 18. b5 $16 {keeps White's attack going, with his bishops
optimally placed.}) 18. Bxb4 Rf7 19. a4 {Planning to advance the pawn to a6.}
Nb8 {Solid but passive.} (19... Nf6 {works less well than in the line where
White wastes a tempo on a2-a4.} 20. a5 Ne4 21. Qd1 $5 (21. Bd3 {is also good.}
g5 22. Qh5 {In view of Bxe4 followed by Qxg5, Black is not ready for ...Qe8
yet.} h6 23. Ra2 Qe8 24. Kg2 f4 25. exf4 gxf4 26. f3 $16 {The bishop is on d3
already and the rook is not hanging after ...Bxd4, so White has a clear
advantage.}) 21... g5 22. a6 f4 23. f3 Nd6 24. Bh3 Kh8 25. exf4 gxf4 26. Be6
Re7 {Keeping b7 defended.} 27. Bg4 $16) 20. a5 Na6 21. Bd2 $16 {White has
stable queenside pressure and no worries on the opposite wing.} (21. Bd2 {
The game continued} Bf8 22. Rab1 Ra7 23. Bd3 Ba3 24. Rc2 Qf8 25. Rb6 Nb8 26.
Qd1 Be7 27. Qb1 Bd8 28. Rb3 Qg7 (28... Bxa5 $2 29. Bxa5 Rxa5 30. Rxb7 Rxb7 31.
Qxb7 $16) 29. Rcb2 Rd7 30. Kg2 Qf7 31. Bb4 $1 Be7 (31... Qg7 32. Bc5 $16) (
31... Na6 32. Bxa6 Rxa6 33. Bc5) 32. Bxe7 Qxe7 33. Rb6 Rc7 34. R2b3 Kg7 35. h4
$1 $16 h5 (35... Kg8 36. h5) 36. Qb2 Kf7 37. Kh2 Kg7 38. R3b4 Kf7 39. Qb3 Kg7
40. Qb1 Qf7 {Marin,M (2530)-Hebert,J (2435) Yerevan 1996 (1-0, 62) This is the
subject of the next test.}) *

