{Did Black manage to build up a reliable fortress?} 41. a6 $1 {Not really!
This pawn break weakens Black's queenside even more.} Nxa6 {What next?} 42. Ra4
$1 {It is best to delay Bxa6 in order to stay safe against ...g6-g5, Black's
only chance for counterplay.} (42. Bxa6 {is premature, allowing Black to get
kingside ciunterplay.} bxa6 43. Ra4 a5 44. Qa1 g5 45. hxg5 h4 46. gxh4 Qh5 $11)
42... Qf6 43. Qd1 {Removing the danger of ...g6-g5 for good.} Qe7 44. Qe2 {
Preparing to take on a6 with all the comfort.} Ra8 45. Bxa6 {Everything is
ready for this now.} bxa6 46. Raxa6 $16 {White has achieved a perfect version
of the minority's attack and eventually won.} (46. Raxa6 {The game continued}
Rac8 (46... Rxa6 47. Qxa6 Qe8 $16) 47. Qc2 Qd6 48. Qb1 Re7 49. Rb7 $1 {After
exchanging one rook, White will have better possibilities of combining the
threats against the king with the pressure on c6.} (49. Kg2 {[%csl Gg2] Marin
It is hard to say whether this improves White's position, as in some cases the
king could be vulnerable here.}) 49... Kf6 $6 (49... Rxb7 50. Qxb7+ Qc7 $5 {
Kharitonov} 51. Qb4 $18) 50. Raa7 Rce8 (50... Rec7 $2 51. Rxc7 Rxc7 52. Qb8 Rd7
53. Qh8+ $18) 51. Qb6 Rxb7 52. Rxb7 (52. Qxb7 $2 Re7 $10) 52... Re7 53. Rb8 {
Black starts having problems on both wings.} Qc7 54. Qb4 Kf7 55. Rb6 Kg7 $2 {
This speeds up the finish, but Black's position was lost anyway.} (55... Rd7
56. Qc5 Rd6 57. Ra6 Kf6 58. Ra7 Qb8 59. Qa3 $16 {Kharitonov} Qd8 60. Qa6 Qb8
61. Ra8 Qc7 62. Rc8 Qd7 63. Qa8 $18 {Marin}) 56. Rxc6 $1 $18 Qxc6 57. Qxe7+ Kg8
58. Kg2 Qb5 59. Kf3 Qf1 60. Kf4 $1 {1-0 Marin,M (2530)-Hebert,J (2435) Yerevan
1996} (60. Kf4 $1 Qxf2+ 61. Kg5 Qxg3+ 62. Kh6 $18)) *

