{Black has built up strong kingside pressure, which even a player with such a
subtle feel for the danger as Karpov underestimated when playing his next move.
Can you do better?} 25. f4 $1 {This is the best continuation, repealing
Black's attack and leaving the knight misplaced on h4.} (25. Bf1 $5 {This is
solid but fails to pose problems.} Nf5 26. Nxf5 Bxf5 $11) (25. Rg1 $5 {is too
passive to be dangerous for Black.}) (25. b5 $6 {was played in Karpov, A (2705)
-Beliavsky,A (2585) Tilburg 1986 (0-1, 36). You will have the occasion to
refute it yourself.}) (25. Qb2 {This prevents Black threat, but offers him a
tempo to activate his reserve knight.} Ne6 26. f4 Qf6 $11) 25... Qd8 (25... Qf6
26. Qf2 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4] exposes Black to an additional threat, e3-e4.} Nf5 $2
{This attempt to recycle or exchange the problem knight fails painfully.} 27.
Bxf5 Bxf5 28. e4 dxe4 29. Ngxe4 Bxe4 30. Nxe4 Qd8 31. Nf6+ $1 $18 {wins the
exchange.}) (25... Qe7 26. e4 $16) 26. Qf2 $14 {With the knight caged on h4,
Black is under constant pressure on both wings.} *

