{White's queenside attacks seem to develop normally, but Black's minor pieces
are close to the white king. White's last move, 17.Nd2, was a heavy mistake.
Why?} 17... Nxd2 $1 {Before launching his attack, Black eliminates an
important defender of the f3-square.} (17... f5 $6 {overexposes Black while
offering White a tempo.} 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. h3 $1 {An important intermediate
move.} Bh5 (19... Nxd2 {is a concession, allowing White to readjust his plans.}
20. Qxd2 Bh5 21. Be2 (21. Bxf5 {yields Black dangerous initiative.} Nh4 22. Bg4
Bxg4 23. hxg4 Qg5 24. Qe2 h5 25. g3 hxg4 $1 26. gxh4 Qxh4 {With the pawn on e3
vulnerable, ...g4-g3 is a serious threat.} 27. Rb2 g3 28. f3 Ra3 29. Nd1 Re6 {
with unclear play.}) 21... Qg5 22. Bxh5 Qxh5 23. Ne2) 20. Ncxe4 fxe4 {Did
something go wrong for White? You will have the occasion to answer the
question when solving another test.} (20... dxe4 21. Ba6 $1 $16 {[%csl Gc6]
[%cal Ga6b7] attacking c6 and threatening Bb7 is decisive.} Rxa6 $2 22. Qc4+))
(17... Nxc3 $6 {This knight is not as important as the knight on d2.} 18. Qxc3
Nh4 (18... Ra3 19. Rb3 Rxb3 20. Nxb3 Nh4 21. Ra1 $14 Qg5 22. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gf3]
safely defend9ing f3.}) 19. g3 $14) 18. Qxd2 {What next?} Nh4 {Indeed, Black
needs to increase the pressure on f3 and g2.} 19. f3 (19. Kh1 {White has
parried the threats ...Bf3 and ...Bh3, but has not saved the game. See a later
test.}) (19. Be2 {White has defended f3. How does Black win now? You will
explain that in another test.}) 19... Qxe3+ $1 {Black simply wins a pawn.} 20.
Qxe3 Rxe3 21. fxg4 Rxd3 $17 {Taimanov,M-Nezhmetdinov,R Kiev USSR ch 1954} *

