{You are playing with Black against a former World champion and still a
World's top two players. He is the absolute specialist in the Carlsbad
structure. Can you believe that he had done something wrong in the previous
phase? And would you dare to think that you could punish him?} 19... Bxh3 $1 {
The consequences of this sacrifice are impossible to calculate until the end,
but one HAS to play like this.} (19... Qh4 $2 {This timid move, played in
Karpov,A (2780) -Campora,D (2560) San Nicolas 1994 (1-0, 39), misses the
golden chance.}) 20. gxh3 Qh4 21. Kg2 Rxe3 $1 {White's light squares are
chronically weak now.} 22. Nf3 (22. Bf5 {allows} Rg3+ 23. Kh1 Ra3 {Gaining a
tempo by attacking the knight.} 24. Nc3 Qf4 25. Ng4 h5 26. Ne5 Qxd4 27. Nf3 Qf4
{Black has three pawns for the piece and a continuing attack. What is even
worse, White is hanging.} 28. Kg2 (28. Qd3 g6 $19 {Retrieving the piece.})
28... Bb4 {White cannot defend his minor pieces anymore.} 29. Qd3 Rxc3 30. Rxc3
Bxc3 31. Qxc3 Qxf5 $19) (22. fxe3 {leads to mate, of course.} Qg3+ 23. Kh1
Qxh2#) 22... Rxf3 $1 {Continuing the king's chase.} 23. Kxf3 Re7 $1 {The most
convincing. Black cuts the king's escape and threatens ...Qxh3 mate.} 24. Rh1 (
24. Kg2 {leads to a forced mate.} Qg5+ 25. Kh1 Qf4 26. Kg2 Qh2+ 27. Kf3 Qxh3#)
24... Re6 $19 {[%cal Ge6f6,Gf8e6] Planning ...Rf6 and possibly ...Ne6. Black
is a rook down, but the knight on a4 does not count for much and the attack
with opposite bishops practically yields Black another extra piece.} 25. Kg2
Rf6 26. Qb2 Qf4 {[%cal Gf4f3] Threatening ...Qf3+.} 27. Qe2 Qxd4 28. Nb2 Ne6
$19 {The game is still on and the position is impossible to analyze until a
logical end, but Black's attack is decisive.} *

