{[#] White is ahead in development and has some kingside threats already. How
would you continue with Black?} 19... Ne7 $1 {The highest priority was
securing the light squares with this regrouping move.} (19... Kg7 $2 {was
played in Rozentalis,E (2570)-Gheorghiu,F (2495) Suhr 1991 (0-1, 41) Gheorghiu
wanted to prevent Qh6, but his move fails to help the minor pieces.'
regrouping. You will have the occasion to punish it in a later test.}) (19...
Nh5 $2 {This way of preventing Qh6 is artificial, as you will be able to prove
yourself.}) 20. Qh6 {This was what Gheorghiu must have feared.} Nf5 (20... Re8
{may transpose to the main line after} 21. Re3 Nf5 22. Bxf5 exf5) 21. Bxf5 exf5
22. Re3 Re8 $1 {The rook clears the king's escape to f8, while also occupying
the open file.} 23. Nxh7 Nxh7 24. Rh3 {Black seems to be in trouble, but the
next move proves he is not.} Qxd4 $1 {Now is why the rook is useful on e8. The
queen defends the square on h8, yielding Black an equal game.} 25. Qxh7+ Kf8
26. Rhd3 (26. Qh8+ Qxh8 27. Rxh8+ Ke7 28. Re1+ Kd7 $11) 26... Qxd3 $5 {The
safest.} (26... Qg7 {is also playable, but keeping the queens on board may
offer White some hypothetical chances.} 27. Qh4 Kg8 {Black is in no immediate
danger, but his queen is a bit passive.}) 27. Qh8+ Ke7 28. Qxe8+ Rxe8 29. Rxd3
$11 *

