{White has a knight against a "not as good as it seems" bishop. The exchange
on d4 would lead to the king of position that should be impossible to save, at
least in practice. However, Black seems to be very active. Can White prove a
clear advantage?} 26. a4 $1 {This strong move shows that the bishop is much
worse than it seems.} (26. Rd2 $6 {slow maneuvering likely allows Black to get
counterplay.} h5 27. Rcd1 $6 g5 28. a4 $6 {Too late.} (28. h3 $5) 28... h4 29.
Qf1 hxg3 30. hxg3 Kg7 31. Qh3 Kg6 $11) 26... Qe7 (26... Rd6 {Does not help.
This position is the subject of a later test.}) 27. Nb3 $1 {This would have
been even stronger than the consequent game move. Provoking the exchange on d4
is good, but winning the Isolani by using the knight's superiority over the
bishop is even better.} (27. a5 {The game move is not bad at all, but White
could have done even better.} Bxd4 (27... Bc7 28. a6 $16) 28. Rxd4 f5 29. b4 {
It turns out that the advance of the a-pawn will also be useful for the global
plan with only major pieces on board.} Qe6 30. Qd3 a6 31. Rc5 g6 32. b5 $1 {
Khalifman goes straight for the main plan without trying to gain time and a
deeper understanding of the position with a series of null moves.} axb5 33.
Rxb5 Qc6 34. Qb3 Qc1+ 35. Kg2 Qc6 36. h4 Kg7 37. Rb6 Qc5 38. Rb5 Qc6 39. Kh2
Kh6 {With the pawn on b7 vulnerable, the king evacuates the seventh rank.} (
39... Kf7 40. Rdb4 Rb8 41. Rb6 Qc8 42. a6 $18) 40. Rb6 Qc5 41. h5 $1 Qxa5 (
41... Kxh5 42. Rh4+ Kg5 43. f4#) 42. hxg6 hxg6 43. Qb2 f4 44. Rxf4 d4 45. Rh4+
Kg7 46. Rxb7 {1-0 Khalifman,A (2645)-Lukin,A (2425) St Petersburg 1994} (46.
exd4 $18 Qd5 47. Rb5)) 27... d4 (27... Rd6 {does not change much.} 28. a5 a6
29. Qb4 Ba7 30. Rxd5 $1 $18) 28. a5 Rd5 29. Qa4 {defending the pawn on a5.} Bc7
30. Rxd4 $18 *

