{With his last move, 17.Bd4, White has offered the exchange of one or more
minor pieces. The weakness induced by ...f7-f6 makes Black's position delicate.
How would you react?} 17... Bxf3 $1 {This move would have solved most of
Black's problems, requiring a bit of calculation. The main idea is to remove
the blockade on d4 by eliminating an essential defender of that square.} (17...
Bxd4 $6 {In principle, keeping the knight is somewhat better than ...Nxd4, but
the weakness on e6 is not the best solution.} 18. Nxd4 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Rfe8 20.
Kg1 $16) (17... Ba5 $5 {Avoiding the exchange is a reasonable solution, but it
does not free Black from the pressure.} 18. Nh4 Kh8 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Nf5 Qd7
21. g4 $14) (17... Bc7 $2 {The idea of avoiding the exchange at all is not bad,
but this move loses a pawn.} 18. Qxb7 $18) (17... Nxd4 $2 {This move, played
in the game, leads to the knight versus the "not as good as it seems" bishop.
The game continued:} 18. Nxd4 Bxg2 (18... Kh8 19. Bxe4 dxe4 20. Ne6 Rxd1 21.
Rxd1 Rc8 22. Nf4 $16) 19. Kxg2 Qe4+ 20. Kg1 h5 $6 {Black hopes to create
counterplay with ...h5-h4-h3, but his plan is too slow. Larsen, B (2560)
-Bareev,E (2560) Naestved 1988 (1-0, 50). This position is the subject of the
next test.} (20... Rf7 {or}) (20... Rd7 {were preferrble.})) 18. Bxf3 Nxd4 $1 (
18... Bxd4 {loses a pawn without compensation.} 19. Bxd5+ Kh8 20. exd4 $16) 19.
Bxd5+ (19. exd4 Qf7 $14 {yields White only a symbolic advantage. Even if he
wins the pawn on d5 somehow, this will not guarantee him the win at all.})
19... Rxd5 {Continuing the process of simplyfying.} ({Truth said,} 19... Kh8
20. exd4 $14 {does not offer White too many chances, either.}) 20. Rxd4 $1 (20.
Qxd5+ Ne6 $11) (20. exd4 $2 Qf7 $19) 20... Bxd4 21. Qxd5+ Qf7 $1 22. Qxd4 (22.
Qxf7+ Kxf7 23. exd4 Rc8 $11 {Black's activity compensates for the pawn.}) 22...
Qxa2 23. Rc1 $14 {Black has rid himself of the Isolani and White is only
symbolically better, due to the weakness of the black kingside.} *

