{How would you react to Black's kingside ambitions?} 21. Ne2 $1 {The pawn on
d5 is doomed already, since the bishop can not intervene in any way. The
threats are Nf4 and Nc3. Black does not have the time to continue his kingside
plan.} (21. Nb5 {This is as good as the game continuation. White simply wins
the isolated pawn.} Qc4 22. Qxc4 dxc4 23. Nd6 c3 24. bxc3 Rd7 25. Nf5 Rc7 26.
Rd3 {Black's counterplay against the relatively weak pawn is not enough to
level the chances.} Rfc8 27. Rfd1 $1 Bc5 (27... Rxc3 $2 28. Ne7+ $1 $18) (27...
Ba5 28. Rd5 $5 Bxc3 29. Rd7 $18) 28. Rd7 Bf8 $16) (21. Rd2 {Doubling rooks on
the d-file is too slow.} h4 22. Ne2 h3 23. Nf4 g5 24. Rxd5 Rxd5 25. Qxd5+ Qxd5
26. Nxd5 Kf7 27. f4 g4 $14 {Black's huge space advantage on the kingside
ensures him entirely adequate drawing chances.}) (21. h4 $6 {This allow Black
to turn the position double-edged.} g5 $1 $13) 21... Qc4 22. Nf4 $1 {The
correct way of attacking the pawn.} (22. Nc3 $2 Qxb3 23. axb3 d4 $15) 22...
Qxb3 23. axb3 d4 $6 {A desperate attempt or a time trouble blunder?} (23... Kf7
{would have offered some vague hope.} 24. Nxd5 Rd6 25. Rd3 Rfd8 26. Rfd1 g5 $16
) 24. Ne6 dxe3 25. Rxd8 exf2+ 26. Rxf2 Bxd8 27. Nxf8 {and White won, Larsen,B 
(2560) -Bareev,E (2560) Naestved 1988 (1-0, 50).} *

