{We can notice that players either remembered Steinitz's setup once in a while
or simply designed it by themselves. White is well regrouped this time and has
certain attacking chances. Is Black ready to occupy the blocking square, or
should he prepare it still?} 19... Qd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6a6] Before installing a
knight on d5, Black should have activated his queen. Her presence far from the
main theatre of operations is an important difference from the previous games.}
(19... Ned5 $2 {As you will have the occasion to prove it later, the game move
is premature. Kasparian,G-Aramanovich,I Tbilisi 1949 (1-0, 38)}) (19... Nfd5 {
has the same drawbacks as the game move.}) 20. Bc1 Nfd5 {Everything is ready
for this now. I will not reveal the concrete reasons to avoid spoiling the
next test.} (20... Qa6 {is also good, as a direct consequence of the queen's
well-timed activation.}) 21. Rg3 (21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Rg3 {is parried with} Ne7
$11) 21... Nf5 $11 {Black is absolutely safe.} *

