{Why was the occupation of the d5-square premature?} 20. Nxd5 $1 {This is a
good moment for this exchange, because Black cannot keep the piece control on
d5.} (20. Bc1 {The game move allows Black to repair his previous mistake.} Nxc3
$6 {An important concession.} (20... Qd6 $1 {Once again, this manoeuvre would
have maintained Black in the game.} 21. Rg3 (21. Nxd5 Nxd5 22. Bxh6 $2 {
fails to} gxh6 23. Rg3+ Bg7 24. Qg4 Qf8 $19) ({The non forcing} 21. Re1 $5 {
is worth considering.}) 21... Ne7 {We are familiar with this already.} 22. Bb1
Nf5 23. Bxf5 exf5 {White has made certain commitments during his attacking
attempts and the position is double-edged already.} 24. Qd3 (24. Qf3 $6 Rxc3
25. bxc3 Ne4 $15) (24. Bxh6 $2 Rxc3 25. bxc3 Ne4 $17) 24... f4 $5 25. Bxf4 Nh5
26. Rf3 f6 27. Nf7 Nxf4 28. Nxd6 Nxd3 29. Nxc8 Nxb2 30. Rb1 Nc4 31. Nxa7 Nd2
32. Rxb7 Nxf3+ 33. gxf3 Rxd4 $11 {White's extra pawn is more of an insurance
against a disadvantage.}) 21. bxc3 {The structure has changed and the rest of
the tests made out of this game belong to the respective section.} Bd6 {
We have now reached the position examined in another test. Kasparian,
G-Aramanovich,I Tbilisi 1949 (1-0, 38)}) 20... Nxd5 $2 {This desirable move
actually loses, only because the black queen is so passive.} (20... exd5 {
is better, but this leaves White with constant pressure after, say,} 21. Qf3
$14) 21. Bxh6 $1 {With all his pieces ready to take part in the attack, White
can sacrifice already.} gxh6 (21... f6 {This double attack weakens the
kingside even more.} 22. Ng4 $5 gxh6 23. Qxe6+ Bf7 24. Nxf6+ Kg7 25. Qg4+ Kh8 (
25... Kxf6 26. Rf3+ Ke7 27. Re1+ Kd6 28. Rxf7 $18) 26. Bxd5 Rxd5 (26... Bxd5
27. Rg3) 27. Qe4) 22. Rg3+ Kh8 ({With the queen on d6, Black could have
repealed the attack with} 22... Bg7 {, but in this position} 23. Qg4 $18 {
wins, since Black does not have the winning defense...Qf8.}) 23. Bxd5 exd5 24.
Qg4 $18 {mating.} *

