{How would you start the attack?} 22. Ng4 $1 {This is one of the two strongest
moves and the one played in the game. Before transferring the rook to g3,
White prevents ...Bxe5.} (22. Rg3 $6 {is premature as it runs into} Bxe5 $1 {
with double-edged play.} 23. dxe5 Ne4 {Probably the easiest to handle in over
the board play.} (23... Rxd1+ 24. Qxd1 Qxe5 {leads to more complicated
variations.} 25. Bxh6 Nh5 26. Rg5 f5 27. Rxh5 Bxh5 28. Qxh5 gxh6 29. Qg6+ Kf8
30. Bxe6 Rc7 $13) 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Rxg7+ $5 {The best try.} (25. Re3 Nc5 $11)
(25. Qxe4 Rd1+ 26. Kh2 Rxc1 $11 27. Bb1 $6 g6 $15 28. h4 Qd8 29. Bd3 h5) 25...
Kxg7 26. Qh5 Ng5 27. Bf4 {Preventing ...Qxe5.} Qc7 28. h4 Nh7 29. Bb1 Kh8 30.
Bxh7 Kxh7 31. Qxh6+ {with a draw by perpetual.}) (22. f4 $5 $14 {is a good
move, consolidating the knight, which slows down White's attack a bit, by
restricting the bishop on c1.}) (22. Bf4 $1 {[%cal Gd3g3] This is the main
alternative to the game move. White consolidates the knight, without
obstructing his bishop, to prepare Rg3.} Qc7 (22... Nd5 23. Bxd5 exd5 24. Rg3
$18 {yields White a decisive attack.}) 23. Rg3 Kh8 24. Bb1 $16 {Black's king
is in huge danger.}) 22... Nxg4 {Relatively best.} (22... Be7 23. Rg3 $18 {
is just bad for Black.}) (22... Nh7 {You will have the occasion of refuting
this defense in a later test.}) 23. Qxg4 {This position is the subject of the
next test. Kasparian,G-Aramanovich,I Tbilisi 1949 (1-0, 38)} *

