{How should Black parry the threat Bxh6?} 23... Kh7 $1 {This is the only way
to stay alive.} (23... Kf8 $2 {This eliminates a pin, just to fall under a
heavier one.} 24. Rf3 $1 $18 {Black cannot defend e6.} Rc7 25. Qxe6 Re7 26. Qg6
Qc7 27. Qh7 Re2 28. Bb1 Bc6 29. Re3 Rxe3 30. Bxe3 Bd5 31. Re1 f6 32. Bd2 Bxa3
33. Bg6 Bg8 34. Qh8 Bd6 35. Bxh6 gxh6 36. Qxf6+ Bf7 37. Bxf7 Be7 38. Qg6 {
1-0 Kasparian,G-Aramanovich,I Tbilisi 1949}) (23... Kh8 $2 {The king goes to
the right direction... but too far from the pawn on h6.} 24. Qh4 {Threatening
Bxh6.} Kh7 25. Rf3 $18 {Due to the tempo wasted by Black, White has a decisive
attack.}) 24. c4 (24. Qh4 {is answered in the same way.}) (24. Bb1 Qc7 25. Rg3+
f5 $13 {is reasonable for Black.}) ({For the reasons disclosed below, this is
the best way of maintaining the pressure.} 24. Re1 $1 {I have not promoted
this line because of the instructive defensive manoeuvre below.} Qc7 25. c4 b6
26. Bb2 $16) 24... Ba4 $1 {This surprising maneuver solves Black's problems.}
25. Re1 Bc2 $1 26. Rc3 Bg6 $11 (26... Bf5 $11 {is also good.}) *

