{With his last two moves, 19.Nh4 and 20.Rh3, White showed his aggressive
intentions. There is something wrong with his coordination, though. Does this
mean anything?} 20... Be4 $1 {Wells,P This combination, based precisely on
White's lack of coordination, ensures Black at least a clear advantage.} (20...
Ne4 {is less forced than the game move, but should yield Black a small
advantage anyway.} 21. Bd2 Nxd2 22. Qxd2 Nd7 $15 {After exchanging the
dangerous dark-squared bishop, Black can re-activate his knight and retains
pleasant pressure against the central pawns.}) 21. Rxe4 $2 (21. Qb5 {was
relatively better, but this would yield Black a perfect blockade after} a6 22.
Qb3 Bxb1 23. Qxb1 b5 $17) 21... Nxe4 22. Qxe4 {So far so good. White has won
material. What next?} Qxd4 $1 {The point. Suddenly, White's back rank is weak
and the bishops are hanging, too.} 23. Qxd4 (23. Qe1 {is another line showing
White's lack of coordination.} Qd1 24. Kf1 (24. Re3 {is strongest met with the
elegant} Rxc3 $1 $19) 24... Qa4 25. Bd3 Rxd3 (25... g5 $5 {also wins, but
there is no need to weaken the king.}) 26. Rxd3 Qxh4 $19 {With an extra pawn
and the better structure.}) 23... Rxd4 24. Bc2 {Had Jussupow calculated up to
this point, thinking that he has finally retrieved his coordination?} Rxh4 $1 {
If he did, he surely missed this.} 25. Rxh4 Rxc3 26. Be3 Rxc2 $19 {Black has
won two pawns at no compensation for White. Jussupow,A (2640)-Enders,P (2485)
Bremen 1998 (0-1, 58)} *

