{White has a few reasons for being content with this endgame, but Black is not
without trumps. White's structure is imperfect and Black has a knight, able to
compensate for the pawn weaknesses (please refer to the quote from Botvinnik
in the section dedicated to the Isolani). What should Black do now?} 30... Nf6
$1 {This was the only move maintaining equality. Black has two main ideas:
advancing his central pawns and putting the white king under pressure with ...
h4-h3..} (30... Ra8 $2 {This passive move allowed White to take over the
control in Kasparov,G (2830) -Wilson,J (2303) London 2003 (1-0, 56). You will
have the occasion to repeat move by move Kasparov's technical effort in the
next test.}) (30... h3 {The idea of ignoring the threat on a6 is right, but
this ambitious move neglects the central pawns.} 31. Rd1 {[%cal Gg1f1,Ge2g1]
Possibly followed by Kf1 and Ng1} Nf6 32. Rc1 $14 {Black's centre remains
immobile.}) 31. Rxa6 (31. b4 h3 32. Rxa6 Kg7 33. Ra5 Ra8 34. Rxa8 Rxa8 35. Rd2
Ng4 {with excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 31... c5 32. Rd2 Kg7 $11 {
Black is better coordinated and White's extra pawn is irrelevant.} *

