{How should White use the offered tempo?} 31. Kg2 $1 {The king removes the
threat ...h4-h3 and shows that the pawn could become weak after Kh3.} (31. h3 {
This prevents ...h4-h3, but does not put pressure on Black.} Reb8 $14) (31.
Rda4 {This runs into a reasonably good pawn sacrifice.} c5 32. Rxa6 Rxa6 33.
Rxa6 d4 $14) 31... Ke7 32. Rda4 {Now is a good moment for this.} Nb8 33. e4 {
Typical for Kasparov's dynamic and concrete style.} ({The static} 33. b4 Kd6
34. Nd4 $16 {is also strong.}) 33... dxe4 (33... Kd6 34. Nc3 dxe4 35. Nxe4+ Kc7
36. f5 $16) 34. Rxe4+ Kd7 35. Rxe8 {Exchanging Black's only developed piece.}
Kxe8 36. Nd4 Ke7 37. Nf3 {The pawn is suddenly doomed.} (37. f5 $5 g5 38. Re5+
Kf8 {The king needs to prevent ...Re8.} 39. f6 $18) 37... Kd6 38. Ne5 $1 {
The best move, which does not give Black the time to free himself.} (38. Nxh4 {
allows} c5 $16 {followed by ...Nc6.}) 38... Ra7 39. Nc4+ Ke6 40. Kh3 $1 {
Now that the relative danger of ...c6-c5 followed by ...Nc6 has been removed,
WHite can safely win the pawn.} Nd7 41. Kxh4 $18 {On the kingside, White has
an extra pawn. On the other wing, his structure is better. On top, his pieces
are more active than Black's. Kasparov,G (2830)-Wilson,J (2303) London 2003 
(1-0, 56).} *

