{[#] White has two bishops and his kingside pawns are restricting the enemy
knights. His advantage is beyond doubt, but in order to maintain it, planful
play is required. How would you start improving your position?} 20. Nd1 {
The first piece crying out loudly for a placement's improvement was the knight.
} a5 21. Ne3 {The right square, of course. It puts pressure on d5 and might
land on f5 someday.} Re8 22. g4 {Preparing Nf5.} (22. Bh3 {and}) (22. h4 {
were reasonable alternatives.}) 22... a4 $6 (22... Nf8 23. Be5 $16) 23. bxa4 $1
{This looks like a concession, but White had a clear idea.} Bxa4 $6 24. Bf1 $1
$18 {After this bishop comes into play, Black is just lost. He has no play at
all and his kingside is vulnerable.} Nf8 25. Nf5 {Finally.} Qe1 {A desperate
attempt at releasing the pressure.} 26. Bxh6 $1 {Just winning a pawn.} (26.
Qxe1 {also maintains White's advantage, but it does not win anything yet.} Rxe1
27. Kf2 Re8 28. Be5 $5 N8d7 29. Nd6 $18) 26... Qxd2 (26... gxh6 27. Qxh6 Ne6
28. Re3 Qc1 29. Rxe6 $18) 27. Bxd2 {1-0 Marin,M (2583) -Pedersen,N (2431)
Benasque 2009 and White won.} (27. Bxd2 Bd7 28. Ng3 Ne6 29. Be3 Ra8 30. a3 Ra4
31. Ne2 Bb5 (31... b5 32. Rb3 Ne8 33. Kf2 $16 Nd6 $6 34. Nc3 Nxd4 35. Bxd4 Rxd4
36. Ke3 $18) 32. Rc8+ Kh7 33. Nc3 Ba6 34. Nxa4 Bxc8 35. Nxb6 Bb7 36. a4 Nc7 37.
Kf2 Kg8 38. h4 Kf8 39. Bf4 Nfe8 40. Nd7+ Ke7 41. Nc5 Bc6 42. Bxc7 Nxc7 43. a5
Ne8 44. h5 f6 45. Bd3 Nd6 46. Ke3 Nc4+ 47. Bxc4 dxc4 48. Ne4 Kd8 49. Nxf6 {
1-0 Marin,M (2583)-Pedersen,N (2431) Benasque 2009}) *

