{White is more active, but Black is well regrouped, too. Which is the most
promising way of maintaining the initiative.} 28. Re7 $1 {White clears the
e5-square for the queen while also attacking a7. When playing this move, he
had to evaluate the consequences of Black's answer in the game.} (28. Re8 {
For reasons explained below, this is inoffensive.}) 28... Re6 $2 {An excusable
mistake. Black hoped to free his position by means of simplifying.} (28... a5
$6 {allows White to display his plan.} 29. Qe5+ Rf6 (29... Kf8 {loses a pawn.}
30. Re8+ $1 Qxe8 31. Qxd6+ Kg8 32. Qxd5 $18) 30. Rc7 Qd6 {The centralized
queen is too irritating, of course.} (30... Qb5 {runs into} 31. Rc3 $1 Qd7 32.
Rf3 Qe6 33. Rxf6 Qxf6 34. Qxd5 $18) 31. a4 {Turning b6 into a permanent
weakness and putting Black in some sort of Zugzwang..} Qxe5 (31... Kh7 {allows}
32. Rxf7+ $1 $18) (31... Kg8 {yields White a decisive attack after} 32. Rc8+
Kg7 33. Qe8 $18) (31... Qe6 {loses a pawn.} 32. Qxe6 Rxe6 33. Rd7 Rc6 34. Rxd5
Rc3 35. Rb5 Rd3 36. Rxb6 Rxd4 37. Kf3 Rd2 38. Rb5 Kf6 39. Ke4 Rb2 40. Kd4 $18 {
White will soon have two connected passed pawns.}) 32. dxe5 Re6 33. f4 $16 {
With good winning chances.}) (28... Rd7 {yields White a decisive attack.} 29.
Qe5+ Kh7 30. Re8 f6 31. Qb8 $18) (28... a6 $5 {might have been the best
defence. If compared with 28...a6, Black's pawns remain mobile, while the b5
square would not be available to the white rook after winning the d5-pawn.})
29. Qxe6 $1 {Black overlooked this move, simplifying to a won pawn ending. Now
we understand why 28.Re8 would have been weaker.} (29. Rxe6 {does not promise
much:} fxe6 30. Qe5+ Kf7 31. Qh8 Qc2 $11 {Black is ready to deliver a
perpetual check.}) 29... Qxe6 30. Rxe6 fxe6 31. Kf3 Kf7 32. Kf4 Kf6 33. f3 $1 {
This reserve tempo allows White to put Black in Zugzwang.} e5+ (33... Kf7 34.
Ke5 Ke7 {White now has a few winning moves, each requiring a bit of
calculating.} 35. g4 $5 (35. f4 $2 {surprisingly leads to a draw.} a6 36. a3 b5
37. b4 {With this queenside structure, White's attack will develop too slow.}
Kf7 38. Kd6 Kf6 39. Kc6 Kf5 40. Kb6 Ke4 41. Kxa6 Kxd4 42. Kxb5 Ke3 $11) ({
Inserting} 35. a4 a5 {before} 36. f4 {changes the situation radically.} Kf7 37.
Kd6 Kf6 38. Kc6 Kf5 39. Kxb6 Ke4 40. Kc5 $1 Kd3 41. b4 axb4 42. Kxb4 Kxd4 43.
a5 $18) (35. b4 b5 36. g4) 35... g5 {A desperate try.} (35... Kf7 36. g5 Ke7
37. f4 $18 {Another reserve tempo.}) 36. gxh5 ({Only not} 36. hxg5 $4 h4 37.
Kf4 Kf7 $19 {when White is in Zugzwang himself.}) 36... gxh4 37. Kf4 e5+ {
What else?} 38. dxe5 h3 39. Kg3 d4 40. h6 d3 41. h7 d2 42. h8=Q d1=Q 43. Qf6+ {
The least White can do now is exchanging queens and reaching (again) a won
pawn ending.} Kd7 (43... Ke8 44. Qe6+ Kd8 45. Qd6+ {also wins}) 44. Qd6+ Qxd6
45. exd6 Kxd6 46. Kxh3 $18) 34. dxe5+ Ke6 35. g4 {Zugzwang!} d4 (35... g5+ 36.
Kxg5 Kxe5 37. gxh5 $18) 36. gxh5 (36. Ke4 {was also good.} d3 37. Kxd3 g5 38.
gxh5 gxh4 39. h6 Kf7 40. e6+ $1 $18) 36... gxh5 37. Ke4 d3 38. Kxd3 Kxe5 39.
Ke3 Kf5 40. f4 {1-0 Marin,M (2558)-Lianes Garcia,M (2342) Benasque 2018} Kg4
41. Ke4 Kxh4 42. Kf3 $5 $18 {(the most convincing)} *

