{Black had been pushing hard in this endgame with a "daring knight" against a
bad bishop in the previous phase. Things could have gone wrong for him, had
White played accurately. Your move.} 41. hxg3 $1 {Of course, White maintains
the knight imprisoned.} (41. Kxg3 {frees the knight, leading to a symbolically
more pleasant position for Black.} Ne1 42. Bc1 $1 {The only move.} (42. f4 $2
Nd3 43. Ba1 Nc1 $19) (42. Kf2 $2 Nd3+ $19) 42... Nc2 43. Bb2 Ne1 $11) 41... h5
42. f4 $1 {White stabilizes the kingside. The move is obvious but requires
some calculating. In the next sequence, White will have to find a series of
only moves. In more than one moment, all the alternatives lose.} ({The game
went} 42. Ke2 $2 {The decisive mistake. You will have the occasion to punish
this move yourself.}) 42... Kf7 43. Ke2 Kf6 44. Kd2 Kf5 45. Kxc2 Kg4 46. Bc3 $1
{The right way of activating the bishop.} (46. Ba3 {allows Black to ignore the
queenside tension.} Kxg3 47. Bxb4 axb4 48. a5 h4 49. a6 h3 50. a7 h2 51. a8=Q
h1=Q $19 {Black's superior activity and the targets on d4 and f4 yield him a
won position.}) 46... Kxg3 (46... bxc3 {will be examined separately.}) 47. Be1+
$1 {This is the difference concerning 46.Ba3. The bishop returns to life.} Kxf4
48. Kd3 g5 49. Bd2+ Kg4 50. Ke2 $18 {With the threat Bxb4 in the air, Black is
