{Black has certain practical chances with White's kingside pawns on dark
squares. How would you defend with white?} 32. Kg2 $1 {This would have been
the cleares way of achieving a reliable fortress. The paradox is that one move
earlier, White had played Kg2-f3?! The drawish margin is wide enough to allow
White is losing two tempi. The main idea is to prepare f2-f3, preventing the
enemy king's advance.} ({The game went} 32. Bf4 $2 {As strange as it may seem,
this active move loses. The bishop cannot create any threats and will not be
able to prevent Black's progress.} Kf5 {Now and later, the previous exchange
on b3 would not change anything.} (32... axb3 33. axb3 Kf5 $19) 33. Bc7 {
This position is the subject of a later test. Tregubov,P (2556) -Kasimdzhanov,
R (2670) Bastia 2006 (0-1, 47).} (33. bxa4 bxa4 $19)) (32. Ke2 $5 {This should
be good enough for a draw, but requires certain accuracy after} Bd6 (32... Kf5
33. f3 $11)) (32. Ke3 $5 {is similar to 32.Ke2.}) 32... Kf5 33. f3 f6 34. Kf2
g5 35. hxg5 fxg5 36. Be3 $11 {White has little to fear.} *

