{How should White continue?} 33. f4 $1 {The only way of building up the
fortress.} (33. Kf3 Kf5 $19 {is similar to the game (see a later test).}) 33...
Kf5 34. Kf3 Bb4 {White has to make a last "only move" to stay safe.} 35. Be3 $1
{True, not such a hard movie to find. The bishop defends d4 and maintains
reasonable mobility.} (35. Bb2 $2 {places the bishop on a passive square.} Bd2
36. Ke2 (36. Ba1 a3 {immobilizes the bishop, putting White in Zugzwang.}) 36...
Ba5 37. Kf3 axb3 38. axb3 Bb6 39. Bc3 f6 40. Bb2 b4 {Tightening the net around
the bishop.} 41. Ba1 g5 {A good moment for this pawn break, since White will
not have Bc1+ after the general exchanges on g5.} 42. hxg5 fxg5 43. fxg5 Kxg5
44. Bb2 Kf5 45. Ba1 Bd8 {Once again, this works with the bishop far from c1.}
46. Bb2 Bg5 47. Ba1 Bc1 $19) (35. bxa4 $2 {unnecessarily clears the enemy
king's path through b5-c4.} bxa4 36. Be3 Be1 {Keeping the white king busy
defending g3.} 37. Bc1 g6 $5 {Defending the h5-pawn before initiating the
king's march.} 38. Be3 Ke6 {The king will go all the way to c4. The point
behind ...g7-g6 is revealed after} 39. g4 Bxh4 $19) 35... Bc3 36. Bf2 $15 {
With only symbolical advantage to Black.} *

