{Which is the winning idea now?} 33... Ba3 $1 {The only way of preventing the
regrouping Ke3 followed by f2-f3.} (33... axb3 {As mentioned before, the
intermediate exchange on b3 does not change anything.} 34. axb3 {The only
winning idea remains} Ba3 $1 $19) (33... Bb4 $2 {throws the win away.} 34. Ke3
$1 Kg4 35. f3+ Kh3 36. Kf2 $15 {With just a symbolic advantage for Black.} f6 {
does not yield anything.} 37. Bb6 g5 38. hxg5 fxg5 39. bxa4 bxa4 40. Bc7 Bc3
41. Be5 $11 {The black king will not be able to return into the game, nor to
clear the path for the h-pawn.}) 34. Be5 (34. Ke3 {runs into} Bc1+ $1 $19 {
followed by the black king's advance. The bishop was needed precisely on a3.})
34... f6 35. Bc7 g5 $2 {This premature break should have led to a draw.
Besides the intermediate exchange on b3, Black had two winning ideas.} (35...
Bc1 {Preventing Ke3.} 36. Bd6 (36. Bb6 g5 37. hxg5 fxg5 38. Ke2 h4 $19) 36...
g5 37. hxg5 fxg5 38. Be5 g4+ 39. Ke2 Ke4 $19) (35... Bb2 $5 36. Bb6 g5 37. hxg5
fxg5 38. Ke3 Kg4 $19 {WHite misses a tempo for reaching a fortress.} 39. Bc7 h4
40. f3+ Kh3 {With the pawn on d4 hanging, the king cannot go to f2, thus
offering free hands to its rival.}) 36. Bd8 {Keeping the black king busy.} (36.
hxg5 fxg5 37. Be5 {is also good.} Bc1 38. Ke2 Ke4 (38... Kg4 39. f3+ Kh3 40.
Kf2 $11) 39. f3+ Kf5 40. Kf2 $11) 36... axb3 37. axb3 Bb2 {We have reached the
position examined in the next test. Tregubov,P (2556) -Kasimdzhanov,R (2670)
Bastia 2006 (0-1, 47)} *

