{White's advantage is beyond doubt. He is better developed and Black's
kingside is weak. Which is the most effective way of developing White's
initiative?} 22. Nh4 $3 {This surprisingly strong move sets up a few serious
tactical threats in an area where Black's queenside pieces cannot provide
adequate defences.} (22. Re3 {Not a bad move but also not the best. White
prepares to transfer the rook to g3, but this plan is a bit slow.} Nc6 23. Nh4
Kg7 24. Re8 Qd7 $5 (24... Qd6 25. Bf5 $1 $16) 25. Na4 Nd6 $14 {and things are
anything but clear yet.}) 22... f5 {A serious concession, but one of the
relatively safe defences.} (22... Ra6 $2 {allows White revealing his main
threat. You will show it in the next test.}) (22... Kg7 {defends g6, but allows
} 23. Re8 Qd7 24. f4 Nc6 25. Nf5+ $1 gxf5 26. Qg3+ Ng5 27. Re1 $18) (22... Nd6
{is the main alternative to the game continuation, parrying the immediate
threats and avoiding additional weaknesses. The latter does not apply for too
long, though...} 23. Re3 (23. a3 Nc6 24. Nxd5 Nb5 $11) 23... Kg7 24. Rg3 $1 f5
{What else?} 25. Qe5+ Qf6 26. a3 $16) 23. Nf3 $1 $16 {Now that Black has
parried the main threats the knight returns to take the newly weakened
e5-square under control.} ({The game continued} 23. Nf3 Nc6 24. Bd3 Nb4 25. Bb5
Bd7 26. Bxd7 Qxd7 27. a3 Nc6 28. Na4 $16 {1-0 (...58) Chandler,M  (2470)
-Ivanovic,B (2485) Belgrade 1982}) *

