{The absence of the bishop on b7 and the exposed remaining bishop make Black's
position dangerous. How did White gain a clear advantage by force?} 17. Qd2 $1
{A natural, though strong move, attacking d5.} Nb6 {Also natural.} (17... d4 $5
18. exd4 c4 {may work under different circumstances, but Black does not have
compensation for the pawn after} 19. bxc4 Rxc4 20. Qd3 $16) 18. Nb5 {Clearing
the bishop's diagonal with gain of time. We see now that Black's last move has
weakened the defence on f6.} Ne4 $2 {Based on an oversight.} (18... Qd7 {
was the only way to keep fighting in a worse position.} 19. Nxd6 (19. Bxf6 Qxb5
$11) 19... Qxd6 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 21. a4 Red8 22. a5 Na8 23. Rc2 $16) (18... Be7 {
leads to the decisive weakening of the kingside.} 19. Bxf6 gxf6 (19... Bxf6 20.
Nd6 $18) 20. Nh4 $5 $18) 19. Nxd6 Nxd6 20. Rxc5 $1 {Black obviously overlooked
this simple tactical blow.} Rcd8 (20... Rxc5 {runs into} 21. Qd4 {I was
pleased with my forced manoeuvre, of course, but just when writing these lines,
I noticed that I had not invented anything new. More than half a century
earlier, a legendary player executed the same combination.} f6 22. Qxc5 $18 {
Simagin,V-Tipary,L Telegraph 1949 (1-0, 52)}) 21. Qc3 Nf5 22. Nd4 Nxd4 23. Rxd4
f6 24. Rc7 {1-0 Marin,M (2597)-Borgo,G (2419) Bratto 2010} *

