{Black's knight jump to e4 was premature. He is not fully developed yet and,
as we know, White usually benefits from exchanging minor pieces. These general
thoughts suggest that White should have something in the range between a small
and a clear advantage. Does he actually have more than that?} 13. Qc2 $1 {
Apparently a loss of time, this increases the pressure in the centre and
causes Black very serious problems.} (13. Rac1 {is a good developing move,
which does not really punish Black.} Nxc3 14. Bxc3 Re8 $5 $14) 13... f5 {
Consequent, but making things worse.} (13... Nxc3 {runs into} 14. Bxh7+ $1 Kh8
15. Bxc3 g6 {Otherwise, Black would be a pawn down.} 16. Bxg6 fxg6 17. Qxg6 Bf6
(17... c4 18. Ne5 {soon opens the long diagonal anyway.}) 18. Qh5+ Kg8 19. Qg4+
$1 Kh8 {After having transferred the queen to g4 with gain of time, White can
open the centre.} 20. e4 $1 dxe4 21. dxc5 $18 {The knight on d7 is hanging.}) (
13... Ndf6 {was relatively best, but after} 14. dxc5 {Black could not keep his
pawns compact.} Nxc3 (14... Nxc5 15. Bf5 $16) (14... bxc5 $2 15. Bxe4 {wins
material.}) 15. Bxc3 bxc5 $6 (15... Bxc5 16. Qb2 $16 {Both captures with
pieces yield White an insanely pleasant Isolani version.}) 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17.
Rac1 $18 {With a double attack on h7 and c5.}) 14. dxc5 {Clearing the d-file
and finally reaching the genuine Hanging Pawns structure.} bxc5 15. Nxe4 $1 {
The best way of taking advantage of Black's hanging position.} (15. Nxd5 {
yields White "only" a clear advantage.} Bxd5 16. Bxe4 Bxe4 17. Qc4+ Kh8 18. Qe6
Bf6 19. Rxd7 Qb6 $16) 15... fxe4 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Ne5 Bc8 18. Qxe4 Qe8 (18...
Rb8 19. Nc6 $18) 19. Qxa8 $18 {Marin,M (2480)-Pavlov,M (2390) Predeal 1988 
(1-0, 40)} *

