{Something went wrong for Black, who on the next move had been forced to play
28...d4. His knight is passive and his kingside weak. Besides, White has good
control over the central light squares. All these accumulate to a decisive
advantage for White, but surprisngly, he needs a bit of accuracy.} 29. Bxb7 $1
{Before concrete action, White must force the enemy queen to give up the
defence on f6.} (29. Nd5 $2 {The game move throws the whole advantage away.}
Bxd5 30. Bxd5 Rad8 31. Bf3 Nb4 32. Na3 f5 {Apart from the relative kingside
weaknesses, things are excellent for Black, who has more space and some
attacking chances. I offered a draw without realizing that my position was
more pleasant already. ½-½ Yilmaz,M (2616)-Marin,M (2572) Baku 2016}) (29. e3
{The idea is good, but it is better to exchange on b7 first.} Bxg2 30. Kxg2
Qc6+ 31. Kg1 dxe3 32. Nh5 Be7 33. Qe2 exf2+ 34. Qxf2 $16) 29... Qxb7 30. e3 $1
{The key move, eliminating Black's only trump, his central space advantage.}
dxe3 31. fxe3 Qf3 {The best chance.} (31... Bg7 $2 32. Nd6 $18) (31... Qc6 32.
Nd6 $1 Bxd6 33. Qxf6 Rad8 34. Nh5 $18) 32. Qxf6 Qxe3+ 33. Kg2 Qe4+ 34. Kh3 Bg7
(34... Nb4 {runs into} 35. Qg5+ $5 Kh8 36. Nc7 $18) 35. Qg5 (35. Qxa6 $2 {
is wrong for reasons you will explain in the next test.}) (35. Nh5 {is second
best, since it allows Black to improve his position a bit by ridding himself
of the bad bishop.} Bxf6 36. Nxf6+ Kf8 37. Nxe4 Rxe4 $16) 35... Re5 36. Qg4 $18
*

