{White's plan is familiar to us, but his mobilization is by far less advanced
than Black's. How did Black take advantage of this circumstance?} 17... c4 $1 {
Black does not waste time on defending c5 and prepares his queenside attack
with maximal speed.} 18. Nf4 Rfb8 {This regrouping is also familiar to us.} 19.
Rab1 (19. Bf3 {runs into} Ne5 $19) (19. Nxe6 {creates only a relative weakness
on e6, but in general strengthens Black's centre.} fxe6 20. Bg4 Ra6 $1 21. b3 (
21. Qe7 Nf8 $17) (21. Rab1 Qb4 22. Qc3 Qxc3 23. bxc3 Rab6 $19) 21... Qb4 $1 22.
Qxb4 axb4 $17 {With huge queenside pressure.}) 19... Bf5 $1 {Forcing White to
lose some time.} 20. Rbd1 Nf6 21. Rd2 (21. Bf3 {allows Black to simplify to a
very good ending.} Qxb2 22. Qxb2 Rxb2 23. Nxd5 Nxd5 24. Bxd5 (24. Rxd5 Be6 25.
Rc5 Rc8 $1 26. Rxa5 c3 27. Rc1 c2 28. Be4 Rb1 $1 29. Rxb1 cxb1=Q+ 30. Bxb1 Rc1#
) 24... Rc8 25. e4 Be6 $1 26. Bxe6 fxe6 27. a4 c3 28. Rc1 c2 $19) 21... g5 $1
$19 {The same move as played by Jussupow against Karpoiv, but under by far
more favourable circumstances. The knight has to release the pressure on d5.}
22. Nh5 ({The game went} 22. Nxd5 Nxd5 23. Bxc4 (23. Bf3 $2 Bd3) 23... Be6 {
and Black won soon.} 24. Rfd1 Nxe3 25. Qxe3 Bxc4 26. h4 Re8 27. Qg3 Qe7 28. b3
Be6 29. f4 g4 30. h5 Qc5+ 31. Rf2 Bf5 {0-1 Bertok,M-Fischer,R Stockholm 1962.
It is unusual to see Fischer playing the Tartakower Queen's Gamit, but he did
it marvelously.}) 22... Ne4 {With the knight away from f4, the pawn on d5 is
not hanging.} 23. Rc2 Qb4 $19 {The knight on h5 is out of play, while Black's
queenside initiative is decisive.} *

