{White has an active position, but needs to play energetically in order to
maintain his advantage. Your move.} 19. a4 $1 {A very unpleasant move. The
threat is a4-a5, undermining the pawn on d5, while ...a6-a5 is not without
drawbacks.} (19. e4 $2 {This throws the advantage away, as you will show next.
Foisor,O (2420)-Boensch,U (2475) Leipzig 1986 (0-1, 42)}) (19. Qc2 {is not the
best move order.} Kh7 20. a4 Rcd8 $14) 19... c4 (19... a5 20. Qc2 {Threatening
Nxg6.} Kg7 21. Nb5 $18) 20. Qc2 Kg7 (20... Kh7 {Apart from a4-a5, this also
allows} 21. Nf5 $1 gxf5 22. Qxf5+ Kg7 23. Be5 Rfd8 24. Bd4 $1 {White removes
the bishop from the enemy knight's range (...Nbd7) with gain oftime.} a5 25.
Qg4+ Kh7 26. Qf4 Kg7 27. Ne2 $18 {followed by Ng3. Without the insertion of
a2-a4 and ...c5-c4, this combination would only yield a draw by repetition.})
21. a5 $16 {winning d5.} *

